the associated press erroneously reported feb. 25 that pat robertson's campaign asked the south dakota secretary of state's office for a recount of republican votes in tuesday's presidential primary
gordie howie, the candidate's south dakota field director, said robertson's campaign sought information about a possible recount but had not made a request. porcupine caribou herd. ^by lee byrd</note>
the senate energy committee approved 11-8 on thursday a bill that could open up for drilling a potentially oil-rich section of the arctic national wildlife refuge in northeastern alaska
the measure, bitterly contested by environmentalists but eyed by industry as an oil bonanza rivaling the development of prudoe bay, would authorize the interior department to open up 1.5 million acres on the coastal plain of the refuge, which totals 19 million acres
the energy committee's approval followed a lengthy series of mark-up sessions in which various amendments designed to weaken or kill the legislation were turned back
a day earlier, the committee rejected 10-4 an attempt by sen. wyche fowler, d-ga., to force oil companies to prove that exploratory drilling would not prove incompatible with the region's primary purpose as a fish and game refuge
the interior department has estimated that there is a one in five chance that the northern tip of the refuge contains economically recoverable oil. if there is any, the department says, it's 50-50 whether the amount totals more than 3.2 billion barrels, and a 5 percent chance that it totals 9 billion barrels
prudhoe bay contained a little more than 9 billion barrels when it was tapped in 1975. it's now at peak production, 1.8 million barrels a day, and inevitably will start to decline soon
the united states uses about 6.2 billion barrels a year, so 3.2 billion barrels would represent about 188 days' worth
the energy department calls the interior estimates conservative, and the oil industry says the coastal area offers the best drilling prospect left in the united states. the region is within 65 to 100 miles of the alaska pipeline, so extensive work would not be required to bring the oil to market
the bill, backed principally by chairman bennett johnston, d-la., and frank murkowski, r-alaska, faces a difficult floor fight in the senate and even more uncertain chances in the house, where interior chairman morris udall, d-ariz., is a staunch opponent of disturbing the arctic refuge
environmental groups such as the sierra club, the wilderness society and the natural resources defense council are particularly disturbed about the potential effect of oil development on a herd of 180,000 porcupine caribou, whose calving grounds fall within the prime oil area
sen. bill bradley, d-n.j., told the senate committee that ``what is at stake is far more than the well-publicized porcupine (area) caribou (herd). the coastal plain is also vital to polar bears, grizzly bears, wolverines, and muskoxen, the survivors of the ice age. millions of swans, snow geese, northern pintail and other water fowl spend their summers on this stretch of the arctic coast.'' there</head>
midnight was fast approaching as the twin-engine plane flew at treetop level, its lights and radio turned off, into a combat zone in darkest angola
with the small air strip illuminated only by kerosene lanterns set down moments before, the plane landed at the stroke of midnight and out stepped, of all people, former virginia gov. charles s. robb
since leaving office in 1985, robb has become an adventurer of sorts, traveling to many a third world hot spot while attempting at the same time to encourage fellow democrats at home to embrace his cautiously hawkish foreign policy views
robb clearly feels uncomfortable with the ``isolationist'' sentiments of some party leaders and he has been imploring democratic candidates to pursue a more ``traditionalist'' approach to international issues
he would support any party candidate who gets the nomination but in a field dominated by liberals, it is not surprising that robb finds sen. albert gore of tennessee the most ideologically congenial of the lot
robb himself is considered by some a possible candidate for national office one day, but for now his principal short-term ambition is election in november to the virginia senate seat being vacated by paul trible, a republican
if miles traveled are a qualification for election, robb should win in a landslide
he has been within earshot of hostile fire in iraq and along the afghan-pakistan border. his other wanderings seem like a travel agent's dream: japan, korea, the philippines, the soviet union, india, oman, bahrain, kuwait, saudi arabia, israel, nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, panama, australia, new zealand, argentina, chile, brazil, zaire, ivory coast all of western europe and scandinavia. this is a partial list
to understand the stakes involved in a particular area, robb said in a recent interview, there is no substitute for actually being there. no amount of reading or discussion, he said, could prepare him for the visual impact of the israeli-held golan heights and the degree to which israelis in the valley below would be vulnerable if it were returned to its historic owner, syria
to hear robb tell it, few experiences were more rewarding than his visit last fall to angola where the soviet-backed government has been challenged for more than a decade by anti-communist rebels who receive u.s. backing
at the time, the leader of the unita rebel group, jonas savimbi, was directing a military operation in mavinga. a unita pilot flew robb there, shutting off the lights and radio, lest the flight be detected by loyalist forces manning anti-aircraft equipment
robb discussed military tactics with savimbi, drawing on his own combat experience two decades ago in vietnam where he volunteered for service as a young marine officer after marrying lynda johnson, daughter of president lyndon johnson
robb spent five hours with savimbi before flying out in the pre-dawn darkness
his most memorable angolan experience was in jamba, the unita headquarters and stronghold in southeastern angola. there he saw hospitals with operating rooms, a plant where captured soviet tanks were being rebuilt, and a ``most remarkable'' education system involving thousands of children
a prime robb interest these days is the state of the democratic party, which he believes has lost its way in recent years, partly because of too many comfortable assumptions about the intentions of america's adversaries
i spend a lot of time trying to find ways to nudge our party and our presidential candidates ... to take what for me and for many other democrats would be regarded as a more responsible view on foreign policy,'' he said
robb goes to considerable lengths to avoid use of terms like ``conservative'' and ``liberal,'' preferring such words as ``responsible.''
i try not to put things in an ideological or philosophical context because i don't want to be constrained or restricted by a label,'' he said. ``i go to great lengths to avoid being pigeonholed.''
on central america, robb believes the reagan administration has overemphasized the need for military force while too many democrats underemphasize it. he believes united states should support both the central american peace plan and the nicaraguan contras as well
he said the democratic party has come a long way since 1984, a year when he felt that unswerving support for a nuclear freeze was a politically chic stand within the party but not among the public. in the presidential election that year, the democratic ticket carried one state
we're on more responsible ground now. but we haven't moved as far as we should have if we're going to reoccupy the high ground that the party used to be able to occupy in previous decades,'' robb said
