the reagan administration is proposing that states with approved groundwater protection plans be given discretion to permit use of some pesticides that otherwise would be banned
the proposal was unveiled thursday in the form of a draft strategy released for public comment
groundwater provides drinking water for half the u.s. population and for 97 percent of people living in rural areas. epa says it expects to complete a survey in 1990 on the extent of contamination
epa licenses new pesticides, and is gradually re-licensing all the old ones. as it makes those licensing decisions, it tries to take into account the chemical's ability to leach into groundwater _ which can depend on many things, including soil permeability and application method
epa expects to ban the use of some chemicals in specific states or counties, while allowing use in others. the new strategy is designed to allow states facing such bans to overturn them provided they show that groundwater supplies will not be contaminated significantly
john a. moore, epa's assistant administrator for pesticides and toxic substances, said the agency's ``ability to do something at these levels (counties and below) is not good.''
states with plans could employ geological, land use, crop pattern and water data to justify decisions that would run counter to epa determinations
where found appropriate, epa would consider modifying the federal registration to accommodate the state program,'' the agency said
in making decisions, both epa and the states would use current drinking water standards, where they exist, for chemicals that don't cause cancer. for carcinogens, the agency would permit contamination to a level that would mean a one-in-a-million chance of cancer over a lifetime
if there are no drinking water standards _ only six have been established for pesticides, with another 10 in the pipeline _ then epa would determine the permissible pesticide concentration in groundwater supplies
though several other federally mandated environmental programs are run by states _ one example is strip mine reclamation _ moore acknowledged that ``there are no good models'' of states being allowed to make exceptions to federal rules like what epa is proposing for pesticides
he said epa would ``periodically revisit and reassure ourselves that what the state had put together was being maintained,'' moore said
he singled out california, iowa, illinois, wisconsin and florida as states with active pesticide-groundwater programs, generally combining state agriculture, health and environmental protection departments
moore said he expected cooperation from farmers and their trade groups: ``if there's been one area where i haven't had to convince the user community they should pay attention, this is it. it's their wells and their children drinking the water,'' moore said
pesticide contamination of groundwater is a relatively new issue, and as recently as 10 years ago most government officials and scientists believed it didn't happen. they thought the chemicals didn't last long enough or penetrate far enough down
the first serious contamination cases were reported in new york and california in 1979
two years ago, epa said 19 pesticides had been found in groundwater in 24 states; today, said patrick holden, team leader of the groundwater project in epa's pesticides office, 50 to 60 different chemicals have been found in wells in 30 states. iowa has found pesticides in half the wells serving cities
pesticides are not the only contaminants. fertilizers, waste disposal wells and leaking underground tanks all can contribute substantially
epa plans to adopt a groundwater strategy that would require states to classify supplies, known as aquifers, in a three-tier priority system _ high priority protection, drinking water sources, and water needing little protection
many environmentalists object to the plan, saying it would write off a substantial percentage of groundwater supplies
sen. david durenberger, r-minn., on thursday introduced at least the 10th bill this session calling for minimum federal standards for all aquifers
the senator said he would have to study epa's proposal for the states. an aide, jimmie powell, said that ``to the extent you can manage pesticides for their leaching ability, it could be a reasonable proposal'' to let states make detailed, area-specific management decisions along the lines epa is proposing
but rick hind of the u.s. public interest research group said epa's use of a one-in-a-million standard for carcinogens is ``too soft.'' he also said the drinking water standards for non-carcinogens is based ``partly on the cost of cleaning it up'' and thus inappropriate for a strategy of protecting public health
the assembly's action came after delvalle ordered strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega, under u.s. indictment as a drug trafficker, to step down. but the military challenged the order and the man named as new armed forces chief refused to take the job
noriega is regarded as the real power behind the civilian government in panama, headquarters for u.s. military operations in latin america
the national democratic union, 4th graf pvs, a0416
the outlook for u.s. farm exports continues to improve as the soviet union begins a new round of corn purchases
overall, the agriculture department says the value of u.s. agricultural exports will rise to a four-year high of $32.5 billion in the 1988 fiscal year that began oct. 1
spurred by recent heavy sales of grain to the soviet union and china, partly under a special export subsidy program, the new 1988 forecast is up $500 million from $32 billion indicated on dec. 17
steve macdonald of the department's economic research service said the soviet union may account for $1.7 billion of the total export value this year, the most since 1985 when moscow's purchases totaled $2.5 billion. soviet purchases last year were valued at about $700 million
china's u.s. purchases are expected to be around $500 million, more than double the $200 million of 1987, he said
the new export forecast came thursday as the department announced another cash sale of corn to the soviet union, the second in two days
with a shipment value of $32 billion, this year's exports would be up 16 percent from $27.9 billion in 1987 and 24 percent from a decade low of $26.3 billion in 1986. agricultural exports were valued at $31.2 billion in fiscal 1985 and $38 billion in 1984
most of the increase (from the earlier estimate) stems from additional wheat sales under the export enhancement program ,'' the department said. ``since the december forecast, eep offers were announced for 2 million metric tons of wheat to the soviet union and 1.2 million tons to china, among others.''
under the eep arrangement, private exporters get free surplus commodities from the agriculture department as subsidies so they can sell grain and other products overseas at reduced prices
on the basis of actual volume, 1988 exports were indicated at 142.5 million metric tons, up from 141 million forecast in december and 129.2 million tons shipped last year
the u.s. share of the world market, particularly in grains and cotton, is rising,'' officials said in their report. ``relatively low world prices and improved u.s. competitiveness through lower (price support) loan rates, the eep and a lower dollar have reduced production incentives for foreign competitors.''
meanwhile, private exporters reported the sales of 601,600 tons of corn for delivery to the soviet union this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries
on wednesday, the soviets bought 350,000 tons of corn, the first substantial amount since last october. corn sales are not qualified for eep subsidies, however
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 601,600 tons of corn would be about 24 million bushels, having a farm value of around $44 million at recent prices of about $1.82 per bushel
shipments of federally inspected reindeer steaks across the country would be allowed under a proposal being considered by the agriculture department
there is mandatory federal inspection of cattle, hogs, chickens and turkeys at slaughter plants, which allows those carcasses to be shipped across state lines
in addition, regulations permit the voluntary inspection of certain exotic animals slaughtered for human food. those include the american bison, or buffalo, and the cattalo, a cross between cattle and the buffalo
lester m. crawford, head of the department's food safety and inspection service, said thursday producers of exotic animals have asked the inspection list be expanded to include reindeer, elk, deer, antelope and water buffalo
this proposal is a response to their request and could facilitate the sale and export of the carcasses, meat and meat food products from these animals,'' he sad. ``once the animals and products are inspected and passed, they can be sold interstate or exported.''
producers of the animals would pay fees to receive the optional inspection service. crawford said fewer than 2,000 exotic animals are slaughtered annually at the present time and that the slaughter level is not expected to increase much if the exotic list is expanded
by comparison, he said, annual cattle slaughter has been running at more than 32 million head
public comments on the proposal can be sent by april 26 to: linda carey, fsis hearing clerk, room 3168-s, fsis, usda, washington, d.c. 20250
united airlines inc. has paid an $11,000 civil penalty to settle 1987 charges by the agriculture department that it violated federal transportation standards for shipments of live animals
the penalty was assessed by the department in an administrative action stemming from nine shipments of dogs and monkeys in 1985 and 1986. a complaint was filed against united last year by the department's animal and plant health inspection service, which administers the animal welfare act
james w. glosser, acting administrator of the agency, said thursday the complaints alleged that united had accepted dogs in shipping kennels that did not conform to size requirement, and that the airline ``either failed to observe and care for the dogs properly'' or stowed them in cargo space without sufficient ventiliation
two dogs died during shipment and another was killed by highway traffic after it escaped shipment, glosser said. the airline also was cited for having ``allegedly accepted a shipment of 50 monkeys in cages that were not structurally sound'' and had no markings to tell they contained wild animals, he said
glosser said united also consented to an order against future violations of the act and agreed within a year to buy a training film approved by usda and show it to all employees who handle live animal cargoes
michael dukakis, urged by his aides to begin returning campaign fire, says democratic presidential rival richard gephardt ``better watch out'' if he persists with his sharp attacks in the battle for the party's nomination
i've been in negative campaigns before and i can tell you if people want to be negative, i know what to do,'' the massachusetts governor said thursday as he opened a three-day campaign trip through dixie
i hope we don't go down that road,'' he said, adding that negative attacks during the nominating battle would only damage democrats' chances of capturing the white house
dukakis issued his warning one day after gephardt unleashed a stinging attack, the latest in a string that the governor's aides believe may be taking a toll. the missouri congressman said dukakis and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had ``hardly a dime's worth of difference'' on economic issues
gephardt said dukakis' foreign policy experience consisted mostly of ``negotiating with the governor of new hampshire over the use of nuclear power.''
and he summarized dukakis' campaign bitingly, calling him ``the candidate with the most money and the least message.''
gephardt also has attacked dukakis in television commercials
yet with the campaign in an intensive phase leading to the 21 super tuesday primaries and caucuses set for march 8, dukakis so far has declined to respond with anything approaching the vehemence used by gephardt
instead, he has replied with indirect attacks and issued a series of increasingly stern warnings
if people want to get negative, i've had experience with negative campaigns,'' he said at a news conference in boca raton, fla. ``if you've got a record as vulnerable as his is, you'd better watch out, that's all i can say
the massachusetts governor also chided gore and gephardt for ``going at each other'' in a mananer resembling republican presidential rivals george bush and bob dole
i don't think this `prince of darkness' routine is going to sell,'' he said
but some aides say they believe that negative television commercials played a role in gephardt's victory in the south dakota primary on tuesday, a conclusion also reinforced by some public opinion polls
and with the critical southern primaries approaching, the governor is getting advice to respond more sharply to gephardt
we have to knock this negative campaigning out of the box,'' said s. stephen rosenfeld, florida campaign manager for dukakis. ``my own view is that it comes home to roost, but we've got to make it come home to roost (for gephardt) sooner rather than later.''
rosenfeld said he has told dukakis as much and the governor ``made it very clear that it's important to respond.''
but so far, dukakis has passed up every opportunity
when he and gephardt shared a stage to discuss long-term health care before a group of senior citizens, his most biting comment was a mild jab
askdd if he had flip-flopped on the issue, dukakis replied: ``there's the flip-flopper over there. i'm not the flip-flopper.''
a railroad rate case initiated eight years ago by a group of montana farmers may play a pivotal role in the way the interstate commerce commission determines when certain shippers are being overcharged
the case involves ``captive shippers'' who must rely on a single railroad for transporting their goods _ in this case wheat and barley being sent from montana to shipping points along the northwest coast
the icc earlier this month concluded that the burlington northern railroad had overcharged the farmers and directed that the railroad make refunds _ as much as $30 million, according to some estimates _ and use a new method to determine fair rates
the montana ruling, known as the mccarty farms case after one of the farmers, is being appealed by the burlington northern. it may not be settled until it goes to the u.s. supreme court, say both railroad and shipping experts familiar with the case
but if it stands, the case may spawn a new method of determining when captive shippers are being overcharged
the mccarty case is the first attempt to do this in a live case,'' said daniel campbell, the icc's deputy general counsel. ``if we've done it successfully and it's accepted by the courts it has implications for other (captive) shippers.''
in the montana case, the icc sought to establish a shorthand approach to determining whether a shipper is being overcharged by comparing a railroad's revenue to its operating costs
the icc already has used the same method of determining an overcharge in a case involving generators being shipped for westinghouse corp., and shipments of sugar, according to icc officials
but neither the railroads nor groups representing shipping interests are particularly happy about the methods the icc developed in the montana case
it sets up a very nasty test for any future shippers,'' suggested mark cooper, research director for the consumer federation of america, who has studied railroad ratemaking as it applies to captive shippers
cooper said he is concerned that in the montana case the icc decided to use average rates when determining whether the montana farmers were being charged too much
if the same practice is used in other ratemaking cases, shippers who are being charged exceedingly high rates might be denied relief because they are lumped in with other shippers whose rates are lower, suggested cooper
other critics say the montana case exemplifies the problems a shipper faces in challenging railroad rates
the case is an absolute modern horror story,'' maintains robert szabo, the executive director of the consumers union for rail equity. ``it has taken (these farmers) seven years ... and they spent over a million dollars.''
szabo's group, known as cure, has been battling the railroads for years on behalf of primarily coal companies and electric utilities over rates to captive shippers
with the montana case, suggests szabo, the icc has tried to head off continuing criticism in congress that the icc has been moving too slowly to deal with shipper grievances
spokesmen for the association of american railroads declined to comment on the case except to reiterate its position before the icc that it opposed using the new procedure to determine maximum rates and that it did not consider the burlington norther rates excessive
the montana case began in 1980 when richard mccarty, a grain farmer from near plentywood, mont., and a few other farmers filed a class action suit accusing burlington northern of price gouging in shipping crops to west coast markets
a federal judge referred the case to the icc where an administrative law judge ruled in 1981 that the farmers qualified for relief under the staggers act, which deregulated much of the railroad industry in 1980. the icc concluded the case feb. 12
the face had changed and some views were different, but senators might have imagined robert h. bork was back when they held a confirmation hearing for the most controversial judicial nominee before them
bernard siegan, nominee for the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals, spent his confirmation hearing thursday defending what one senator called his ``remarkably extreme views.'' bork did the same during confirmation hearings on his supreme court nomination
and like bork, siegan pledged over and over that he would cast his personal constitutional views aside if confirmed, and follow supreme court precedent
so did bork
the players were the same, too, in the senate judiciary committee hearing room
liberal sens. howard m. metzenbaum, d-ohio, and patrick j. leahy, d-vt., both major opponents of bork, were highly critical of siegan, a 63-year-old professor of constitutional law at the university of san diego
conservative sens. orrin g. hatch, r-utah, and charles grassley, r-iowa, two of bork's most ardent backers, jumped to siegan's defense
and people for the american way, the civil libertian group that ran a controversial anti-bork television spot narrated by gregory peck, promptly issued a news release attacking siegan
siegan, the group said, ``spent the morning distancing himself from his entire body of legal scholarship.''
siegan's views do not always parallel those of bork, but he is just as controversial
he wrote that the supreme court reached the right conclusion in outlawing school segregation but used faulty reasoning. he said prayer in schools could be constitutional, although the supreme court has said otherwise. he gave equal weight to property rights and human rights. and he said the framers of the 14th amendment, which governs due process rights, never intended its scope to be as broad as that defined by the supreme court
leahy _ who conducted the confirmation hearing because committee chairman joseph biden jr., d-del., is recuperating from brain surgery _ said afterward that siegan's almost total lack of experience in the courtroom and his ``remarkably extreme views'' make him ``one of the more difficult ones for the senate to approve.''
the last time you were in federal court i was 12 years old,'' leahy said
asked about siegan's promises to follow supreme court precedent, leahy said, ``there is a feeling there may be a confirmation conversion here, too.''
the senator used the same term during bork's hearing, accusing the nominee of changing many of his controversial positions in order to win confirmation. bork proved to be unconvincing, and the senate rejected his nomination 58-42
in many ways bork would be easier to accept because he had judicial experience and federal court experience,'' leahy said
during the hearing, hatch listed many of siegan's controversial writings, and repeatedly gave the nominee the chance to say he would ``observe the law of the land'' and resign if unable to do so
i hope people will give you a fair shake,'' hatch said
the 9th circuit, on which new supreme court justice anthony kennedy served, covers alaska, arizona, california, hawaii, idaho, montana, nevada, oregon, washington, guam and the northern mariana islands
siegan told the committee: ``there are times i will rule contrary to my own feelings. it would be a direct violation and contrary of my oath to push my position ahead of the supreme court.''
metzenbaum told siegan, ``i'm concerned that if confirmed, you will find a way to implement your views. circuit courts are often the courts of last resort.'' he said there would be a ``great risk'' if the senate confirmed siegan
siegan said his lack of courtroom experience would not be a problem, commenting: ``a circuit court judge is given scholarly duties to see if what the lower court did was right. i have spent 20 years of my life in scholarly activities. even a lawyer with trial experience may not know how to write an opinion.''
the national highway traffic safety board is asking general motors corp. to explain why its engineers withdrew a recommendation that 703,225 cars be recalled because of possible sudden acceleration problems
the center for auto safety, a consumers group often at odds with the automakers and their regulators, contends that the engineers were pressured to change their position. gm has denied the allegation
nhtsa is asking gm to describe the company's product problem evaluation committee in flint, mich., which made the recommendation
a nhtsa letter released thursday also asked gm to state whether the committee memo withdrawing the recall recommendation ``constitutes a legitimate ppec report.''
nhtsa is investigating alleged throttle problems that produce sudden acceleration in the 1986-87 oldsmobile delta 88 and buick lesabre, and the 1987 pontiac bonneville
the agency has received 573 complaints of alleged sudden acceleration in the cars, resulting in reports of 343 accidents, 145 injuries and one death, said joe collins, nhtsa spokesman. none of the reports has been substantiated by the agency, collins said
gm spokesman david hudgens said it was ``preposterous'' to suggest the engineers were pressured
we don't do business that way,'' hudgens said
the automaker was preparing a response to nhtsa, hudgens said. ``in the nhtsa letter and our response, the question of pressure doesn't come up,'' he said
the center for auto safety said the engineers' decision to withdraw their recall recommendation was suspicious because it came just 18 days before gm would have had to tell nhtsa of the recommendation
the timing ``suggests the clear possibility that the gm engineers' change of heart may have been less than voluntary,'' the center said in a petition to nhtsa
nhtsa declined to comment on the gm investigation, citing agency policy
the gm memo, part of the public record of the nhtsa engineering analysis, was in the form of a two-page handwritten note dated oct. 23, 1987, saying, ``withdraw recommendation for lack of data support of a trend or high frequency'' on one page, and, ``withdraw recommendation to conduct field actions on throttle cables on all cars for lack of data to conclude there is a problem'' on the other
the committee on aug. 24, 1987, had recommended a recall. update with white house having no immediate comment on vote to remove delvalle.</note>
the reagan administration on thursday night greeted with caution news that the president of panama has ousted military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said administration officials ``want to reiterate our unqualified support for civilian constitutional rule in panama.''
there is but one legitimate sovereign authority in panama and that is the panamanian people exercising their democratic right to vote and elect their leadership in a free society,'' fitzwater said in a formal statement released not long reports surfaced from panama city saying that president eric arturo delvalle had dismissed noriega
there was no immediate comment from the white house or state department early friday after the panama's legislative assembly removed delvalle and the vice president from office
a senior u.s. official said that as of thursday night, the major unanswered question was whether noriega would attempt to fight his ouster
initial reports indicated that noriega did not intend to go quietly, the official said, citing a television newscast in panama in which a member of the defense forces said that if anyone is removed from power, it should be delvalle
the official, insisting on anonymity, said it was his understanding that col. marcos justine, noriega's designated successor, is almost as tainted by corrupt activities as is noriega
sen. alphonse d'amato, r-n.y., who participated in a congressional investigation of noreiga, said u.s. military intervention might be in order to support panama's civilian government if noriega decides to cling to power or attempts a coup
but he said he has no indication whether the reagan administration might initiate military action against noreiga or act on any request from delvalle
we're not without leverage,'' d'amato said in an interview. ``there are 10,000 u.s. troops under arms in panama'' guarding the panama canal
i am suggesting that there have been times in the past when we have been asked to intervene by a legitimate government,'' d'amato said. ``i don't think we should write off that possibility. that's a very real option.''
at the pentagon, a spokeswoman said the u.s. southern command in panama had issued a ``personnel movement'' alert thursday night as a precaution
capt. nancy laluntas said the command had issued a ``bravo'' alert, which orders american military personnel and dependents to ``decrease their visibility.''
a bravo alert specifies that ``some civil disturbance activity is probable. reduce the amount of time spent in public areas of panama. if you do not live on a defense site or military area of coordination, stay around your residence unless traveling to and from work or conducting personal business in a non-affected area.''
laluntas said there are two higher levels of alert, one which orders travel to be confined to essential business and another which suspends travel
she said the u.s. southern command in panama had received reports of scattered demonstrations in and around panama city
u.s. personnel ... are also being reminded that under the terms of the (panama canal) treaty, we are not to interfere in the internal affairs of panama,'' she said
delvalle's move was applauded on capitol hill, but with some reservation
rep. charles rangel, d-n.y., head of the house select committee on narcotics abuse and control, said he believed the delvalle move was a direct result of noriega's indictment in the united states on drug charges
that was a foreign policy objective, but we used our justice department to do it,'' rangel said. ``that's not the normal way to do things. ... are we going to conduct foreign policy by indictment?''
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., called delvalle's action ``courageous.''
it is constitutional and it deserves the support of freedom-loving people throughout this hemisphere,'' kennedy said. ``there is no doubt about the wishes of the panamanian people: president delvalle must be supported and gen. noreiga must go.''
if gen. noreiga persists in power, he will become an outcast _ now and for all time _ in panama and throughout the world,'' kennedy said
sen. john kerry, d-mass., called the announcement ``very important news'' and said the united states should be prepared to help delvalle
i think we have a number of options,'' said kerry, chairman of a foreign relations subcommittee which held hearings earlier this month on noriega's involvement in drug trafficking
the first (option) for the congress of the united states to immediately move to a full economic embargo of the country. ... hopefully, the business community and others in panama who recognize the impossibility of surviving in that situation and noriega himself will find it impossible for him to govern.''
during a nationally broadcast news conference wednesday night, president reagan, when asked whether the united states would consider dropping the federal indictment if noriega stepped aside, replied:
no, and i'm not going to comment on something of this kind. this man has been indicted by a federal grand jury, and so i'm not going to make any comment of that kind. nor have we made any advances or suggestions of that kind to the government of panama.''
reagan said that ``what we would like to see is a return to democracy and a civilian government in panama, and not this domination by literally a military dictator.''
boredom, peer pressure and bad management create a climate for widespread drug and alcohol use by the nation's railroad workers, two crewmen involved in last year's fatal amtrak crash say
the former conrail workers told the senate commerce committee on thursday of co-workers who consumed as much as a case of beer a day, brought bottles of liquor to work, or used marijuana, cocaine, amphetamines and other drugs
overall, drinking was encouraged on the job, especially when i was hired on,'' said ricky l. gates, who was the engineer of the three connected conrail locomotives that on jan. 4, 1987, collided with a crowded amtrak passenger train
sixteen people were killed and 175 injured in the accident, the worst in amtrak history, which occurred in chase, md
gates, an admitted alcoholic, and brakeman edward w. cromwell have admitted to smoking marijuana in the locomotive cab shortly before the accident
gates was charged with 16 counts of manslaughter but was allowed to plead guilty to just one count in a plea agreement feb. 16
he faces sentencing march 29. cromwell, who testified separately, was prepared to testify in court against gates and was not charged in the disaster
the conrail engines went through a stop signal and into the path of the new york-bound amtrak train. the national transportation safety board has blamed the accident on marijuana use
gates told the panel that he believed 10 percent or 20 percent of rail workers drink or use drugs on duty. cromwell said the figure was more like 40 percent or 50 percent
the two men also said that when they began their railroad careers 14 years ago, as many as 80 percent of their fellow employees used drugs or alcohol during working hours
at times you may be sitting in a caboose for 12 hours without even a wheel turning,'' cromwell said. ``the boredom of the job together with the lack of concern from some supervisors makes it a common thing for some employees to drink or smoke marijuana while on duty.''
gates, 33, said that once ``years ago,'' he was forced to report to work even though he told the official who telephoned him that he was drunk. he said a friend had to drive him to work after he was told that if he did not report, he would be cited for refusin duty
unless a climate is created where it is acceptable to come forward and seek treatment, the employee assistance program (that some railroads have) will not work,'' gates said. ``that climate does not exist in the rail industry.''
daniel w. collins, assistant general secretary of the united transportation union, told the committee that perhaps 10 percent of rail workers on duty or subject to being called in to work are under the influence of drugs or alcohol
he said the estimates that 80 percent of workers used drugs or drank years ago have ``never been true in the history of the industry.''
spokeswoman carol perkins of the american association of railroads said in an interview that rail workers had the same percentage of alcohol or drug use as the rest of society
railroads have improved their policies and are more sensitive to the problem,'' perkins said
the senate has approved a bill that would require several types of drug and alcohol testing for railroad, airline, truck and bus industry workers. the house has yet to approve similar legislation
the most controversial types of testing are examinations of randomly chosen workers
supporters say it is the best way to deter drug and alcohol use. opponents _ led by labor unions and civil liberties groups _ say it could be abused by management officials out to get particular workers, and is an invasion of privacy
the government already has rules allowing some testing of rail workers, but not random tests
state lawmakers say they believe they will be able to approve a holiday to honor slain civil rights leader martin luther king jr. after the impeachment trial of gov. evan mecham
i promised the (acting) governor (rose mofford) that after the trial's over that'll be one of the first things we'll try to do,'' senate government committee chairman john mawhinney said thursday
mecham, who rescinded the state's first king holiday in 1987, goes on trial monday in the senate on a 23-count impeachment, accused of concealing a campaign loan, misusing state funds and trying to thwart an investigation
acting gov. mofford supports a federal-style king holiday, and lawmakers narrowed their focus on thursday when the senate rejected a proposal to have voters decide whether to create a paid king holiday
the vote leaves untouched two other measures more acceptable to supporters of the holiday: a straight, federal-style holiday and a ``cafeteria bill'' that would late state workers pick a certain number of holidays froom a list
the state's republican-controlled legislature killed king holiday proposals for a number of years, citing the estimated $3 million cost of a paid holiday for state employees
then, democrat bruce babbitt, about to launch a presidential campaign, decided in 1986 to end his term as governor by bypassing the legislature and creating a paid king holiday through executive proclamation
mecham, babbitt's successor, promptly rescinded the order in 1987, citing an attorney general's advisory opinion that only lawmakers or voters _ not governors _ could declare such holidays
mecham's decision triggered international boycotts of the state by musicians and convention groups, and the house approved a federal-style king holiday last year, only to see the measure die in committee
house democrats and house republicans are offering different reasons for why a vote on the democratic plan to send $30.5 milllion in aid to the nicaraguan contras was postponed until next week
democrats say they wanted time to explain better how the package differs from a rival republican version. republicans sa the democrats feared the package would have lost if had been voted on thursday, as originally scheduled
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said he planned to bring the measure before the chamber for a vote next thursday, and both sides appeared likely to continue to fine-tune their aid packages to pick up votes
too many members have complained that they don't know what's in it,'' wright said thursday
the democratic version includes some $16 million in food, clothing, shelter and medical aid to the rebels fighting nicaragua's leftist sandinista government, and $14 million to set up a medical aid fund for children who are victims of that country's seven-year civil war
current aid to the rebels, which includes authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons and ammunition, ends feb. 29
but the house gop leader, robert michel of illinois, said the scheduled vote this week was postponed because democrats feared they would lose, the republican package would have been approved, ``and that would have aced out the speaker.''
the $36 million republican plan offered somewhat more aid to the rebels, included non-lethal military items like jeeps and radios, and adopted the democratic plan's call for a ``children's survival fund.''
but the primary difference between the two proposals lay in the conditions they set for the next showdown over a military aid proposal that both sides expect president reagan to offer later this year
democrats want to make any future military aid proposal contingent on a finding by the house intelligence committee sometime after june 1 that the two warring sides in nicaragua have not agreed to a cease-fire because the sandinistas did not make good-faith efforts
if such a determination is made, the new aid package would be designed and controlled by the house democratic leadership. there would be no guarantee that the package would be offered, or if it were, that the senate would be forced to act quickly on it
but the gop version would leave the determination of whether to offer a new aid proposal up to reagan, and would contain much stricter rules to make sure the package would be quickly acted on in both the house and the senate. the president could act anytime after april 15, under this version
rep. tony coelho of california, the chief house democratic vote counter, said failure by congress to pass some form of aid would increase pressure for a vote later in the year on more weapons for the contras
the nation's largest airports would have to install new security systems to screen the movements of airport and airline workers, under regulations the government is drafting, the secretary of transportation says
the secretary, james h. burnley iv, told congress on thursday that the proposed regulations should be ready ``reasonably quickly,'' and would take effect after allowing the airports time to install the equipment
under the new system, employees would carry magnetized identification cards similar to automatic teller cards. computer-controlled gates set up throughout the airports would admit only certain workers during specified hours, and could be programmed to bar admission to people who leave their airport jobs
you can de-program a person out, limiting access to certain areas,'' burnley told the senate transportation appropriations subcommittee
he did not mention a cost or say how many airports would be affected. a similar system is already in use at washington dulles international airport
last dec. 7, a fired usair employee boarded a pacific southwest airlines jet after flashing his expired identification card to airport security workers and shot his former boss and the plane's crew in flight. the aircraft, bound to san francisco from los angeles, crashed in central california, killing all 44 people on board
burnley said he ordered the faa to begin writing the new airport security rule before christmas
in other testimony, the secretary said the faa will not be able to meet the congressionally mandated level of 10,450 fully trained air traffic controllers by sept. 30. instead, he projects that 9,932 so-called full-performance level controllers will be at work at that date
he also said his agency is talking with the air force, which plans to reduce its work force because of budget constraints, about hiring air traffic controllers who lose jobs there
he also repeated the reagan administration's refusal to rehire any of the controllers fired after their 1980 strike, saying, ``they not only broke the law, they left the american people very much in the lurch.''
the government plans to have a total of 15,900 air traffic controllers at work by sept. 30, including trainees and supervisors. it usually takes three to four years for a newly hired controller to reach full-performance level
the pilot of an alaska airlines boeing 727 was forced to take evasive action and dive when an unidentified small aircraft passed 100 feet over the jetliner thursday night, officials said
i don't know the exact distance but it was close. he took evasive action. he dove to avoid collision,'' said lou cancelmi, spokesman for alaska airlines said from seattle, wash. ``the pilot took the plane down to get underneath it.''
the pilot filed a a near-collision report with the federal aviation administration following the 6:36 p.m. incident over this community 35 miles east of los angeles, said dick tornquist, an faa officer in los angeles
a pilot files a near-miss report when he fears his aircraft is in jeopardy,'' the faa official said
the incident occurred as the alaska airlines jetliner was departing ontario airport en route to seattle with 62 passengers and seven crew members aboard, cancelmi said
the boeing 727 was flying at 7,000 feet when the unidentified aircraft passed 100 feet overhead, cancelmi said
the plane landed safely in seattle and no injuries were reported, he added. issues</head>
justice department officials have been directed to ``polarize the debate'' on key legal questions this year including aids, which an internal memo says is ``not a civil rights or privacy issue.''
the document says issues such as aids and drugs should be discussed not as questions of individual rights but as ``public health or safety issues.''
the memo was sent monday to various justice department officials under the initials of william bradford reynolds, the counselor to attorney general edwin meese iii. reynolds also is assistant attorney general in charge of the civil rights division
we must polarize the debate,'' it says. ``we must not seek `consensus,' we must confront. of course, we must confront sensibly, in ways designed to win the debate and further our agenda.''
the memo was adopted from a document assembled several months ago by terry eastland, the department's director of public affairs, who said he wrote it to stimulate discussion on how to approach various justice department issues
the contents of the memo were disclosed in thursday editions of the baltimore sun and subsequently confirmed by eastland
the document recommends that the death penalty be defended as necessary for ``deterrence, retribution and incapacitation (i.e. decapitation).''
eastland said the department is not in favor of decapitation as a method of capital punishment, but that he used the word to make ``incapacitation'' seem ``less abstract and professorial.''
the memo says that ``aids is not a civil rights or privacy issue, but one of public health and safety'' and recommends that the department press lawsuits that seek to counter ``the privacy advocates who challenge aids testing.''
regarding obscenity, it says that the department ``must attack the idea that those trafficking'' in it ``have a right to practice their trade.'' it suggests that public health laws, building codes, and health and safety rules be used to attack obscenity, along with laws making sale of obscene items a crime
entitled ``a strategy for the remaining months,'' the document says the drug issue should be confronted by advocating a ``tough approach'' emphasizing strong law enforcement and drug testing, as opposed to ``the soft, easy way that emphasizes drug treatment and rehabilitation.''
the memo supports construction of more prisons instead of alternatives to imprisonment and says that ``to polarize the issue we must attack those by name (such as sen. paul simon) who take the other approach.'' simon is a democratic presidential candidate
george bush's characterization of republican presidential rival bob dole as a supporter of tax increases is unlikely to work as it did in new hampshire because dole is more vigilant now, political and economics analysts say
larry sabato, a university of virginia political scientist, said bush's new hampshire commercial depicting dole as straddling the tax issue succeeded only because the kansas senator ``chose not to respond to it.''
martin anderson, a domestic policy adviser during president reagan's first term, said the vice president damaged dole's chances in new hampshire with the ad raising doubts about the kansas senator's tax intentions. but anderson also said that dole did himself in by refusing to accept pete du pont's debate challenge to sign a no-tax pledge
economist barry bosworth of the liberal-oriented brookings institution said bush's accusations about dole are specious, but said the vice president adroitly played to an issue of great sensitivity to people worried about their pocketbooks
i think dole has learned from that (new hampshire loss) and you probably won't see this happen again,'' bosworth said in an interview
several economists and political analysts were asked whether bush would be able to campaign successfully in the ensuing months as an opponent of tax increases while characterizing dole as a tax-hike proponent
bush has no record. dole has a record which includes both revenue increases, in concert with the (reagan) administration, and deficit reduction,'' said bob mcintyre of the private group, citizens for tax justice
the question of whether bush will be able to score political points out of the tax issue arose in the wake of the vice president's successful use in new hampshire of a television commercial which raised doubts about dole's tax intentions
in the aftermath of his loss in new hampshire, dole acknowledged that he should have responded immediately to bush's ads. and on thursday, dole announced the departure from his campaign staff of consultants david keene and donald devine
a check of the republican presidential candidates' records shows that while bush succeeded in raising doubts in people's minds about dole's stance on taxes, neither man has a record of unqualified opposition to tax hikes
bush, last november, muted his disagreement with a deficit-reduction package in which president reagan and congressional leaders, including dole, signed a compact aimed at slashing the federal deficit by $76 billion over the next two years, in part with $22 billion in tax increases
bush seemed to dissent when he told a crowd in iowa that while he didn't like the tax hikes envisioned in the package, ``i'll support whatever compromise the president makes.''
bush had slipped a month earlier by launching his presidential campaign with an uncompromising pledge to not raises taxes, only to subsequently leave the door slightly ajar
in an oct. 15 interview on cable news network, bush backtracked from the oct. 12 houston promise
what i have said is, if i were convinced that all spending that could possibly be constrained or cut had taken place, then and only then would i consider a tax increase,'' he said. later the same day, when pressed for an explanation, bush replied, ``i'm not going to raise taxes, period.''
the dole campaign promises to perform some political ``truth squad'' work on bush's commercials during the balance of the campaign, and the bush camp continues to deny that it distorted the senator's position on taxes
but with both dole and bush, the record is full of inconsistencies regarding both general tax increases and the question of imposing an import fee on foreign oil
dole supported the sweeping reduction in tax rates in 1981, but helped enact a $98.3 billion tax hike a year later
during the 1980, bush labeled as ``voodoo economics'' reagan's pledge to restore u.s. military might while cutting taxes and balancing the budget. but the record shows no evidence of a bush dissent from tax increases that reagan has signed in the ensuing years
the record shows that dole supported various deficit-reduction tax hike proposals, including the $98.3 billion package, a $50.6 billion program in 1984 and the $22 billion in hikes contained in a plan reagan agreed to last nov. 20 in the wake of the wall street crash
bosworth said that in times of general economic prosperity, candidates for political office score big points by suggesting an opponent would raise taxes
i think dole has probably learned from this (loss in new hampshire),'' he said. ``it appears republicans voted for bush there because he appeared to be more adamant about not raising taxes than dole was.'' up</head>
senate conferees have stripped lamb import quotas and government payments of $365 million to sugar refiners from a proposed trade bill that lawmakers want to have ready for president reagan by easter
also abandoned thursday was a move to end favorable tariff treatment for romania because of the government's anti-jewish policies. critics said foreign policy issues should be kept out of trade bills
removal of those and other politically sensitive provisions represented a major step for the 1,000-page trade bill as lawmakers began to make the tough, long-delayed decisions needed to get it to the president's desk
the trimming was done in a response by senate finance committee conferees to their counterparts on the house ways and means committee. the house conferees on tuesday produced a wide-ranging proposal to iron out differences between the two rival versions of the bill they have passed
the lamb provision was the only product-specific quota in the legislation. sponsored by sen. max baucus, d-mont., it would have clamped on a quota if imports surged over 110 percent of a formula level based on multiyear averages
the house panel moved earlier to drop the lamb provision, which was contained only in the senate bill
the sugar provision would have meant $365 million in payments to sugar refining companies, mainly to three giants of the industry: amstar sugar corp., imperial sugar co. and savannah food and industries inc
under current law, companies may obtain refunds known as drawbacks on any duties they paid on products they imported as long as the products were re-exported within five years of the original imports
the provision, which was in both versions, would have extended the rules to enable refiners who claim drawbacks on cane sugar imported as early as november 1977
critics said customs records were lacking and there would be a problem with customs fraud. proponents said the measure was a refund that would cost taxpayers little and help maintain sugar industry jobs
this shows that we want a very positive, strong trade bill that opens markets but is in no way protectionist,'' senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said thursday
no fewer than 17 joint committees are negotiating over scores of issues contained in the complex bill, which has been three years in the making. it represents a response to huge trade deficits and joblessness at home caused by competition from imports
the measure aims at streamlining the machinery under which the united states retaliates against unfair practices by trading partners and imposes curbs on imported goods that threaten to injure american industry
among the multitude of issues yet to be resolved is the house-passed gephardt amendment, which would require 10 percent annual rollbacks in ``excess and unwarranted'' japanese surpluses in trade with this country
lawmakers are indicating they may wait to tackle that issue until after the march 8 ``super tuesday'' primaries in which the sponsor, rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., is campaigning for the democratic presidential nomination
house ways and means committee chairman dan rostenkowski, d-illinois, has been saying that gephardt will be among the negotiators when a compromise is reached with the senate, which did not include such a measure in its version
the senate panel's response varied little from what the house outlined in its proposal tuesday
it moved to strike from the bill provisions to step up enforcement of customs fraud laws, which critics called unworkable. it went the house one further in eliminating its own proposal to give private citizens the right to file lawsuits against unfair foreign trade practices
i am impressed with the senate counteroffer,'' rostenkowski said in a statement. ``the house made some painful decisions to drop special interest items in favor of a national trade policy. the senate has upped the ante on that approach.''
u.s. officials will visit portugal next week to talk about giving the portuguese surplus american military equipment as a means of offsetting budget cuts in military aid, the state department says
gen. charles brown, chief of the defense security assistance agency, will head the delegation leaving next monday for portugal to talk about what kind of military equipment the united states could provide
the united states has suggested giving portugal surplus equipment to make up for budget cuts that have forced a reduction in aid below levels promised under a 1983 agreement allowing the u.s. military to use bases in portugal
the announcement thursday came a day after portuguese prime minister anibal cavaco silva met with president reagan to complain about the lower aid levels and call for a formal review of the bases agreement
portugal wants the military bases to continue,'' cavaco silva reiterated in a speech on thursday to the national press club, ``and we don't want to reduce the american facilities in portugal.''
our decision is a result of difference in interpretation of our mutual agreement, and we don't want that this point of friction will continue until 1991,'' he said. ``that is the end of this agreement.''
the agreement, an extension of an original pact stemming from 1951, ``is out of date,'' cavaco silva said
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said u.s. officials were pleased that cavaco silva didn't want a reduction in american military presence in portugal, unlike the insistence of neigboring spanish officials that the united states remove f-16s that had been based in spain
young families with children have suffered the most dramatic income drop since 1970 of any family group in america, while the elderly have seen the sharpest rise, according to a new congressional analysis
the study of family income trends by the congressional budget office found that median income for families with children, in which the head of household was under 25, plummeted 43 percent from 1970 to 1986
for those over 65, including people living alone, income went up more than 50 percent
a republican senator and a democratic congressman independently requested the non-partisan cbo to do a study of family income trends, and each offered his own interpretation of the analysis released thursday
sen. pete domenici, r-n.m., stressed the encouraging cbo finding that overall, american family income has risen 20 percent since 1970. rep. george miller, d-calif., pointed to the plight of low-income families with children
miller also cited cbo's finding that many families increased their incomes over the 16-year period not through higher wages but by adding another wage-earner to the workforce, and with that wage-earner such added costs as child care and commuting
in many families, both parents must now work to maintain the standard of living, which results in increased costs as well as increased income,'' said miller, chairman of the house select committee on children, youth and families
cbo said that the elderly as a group were least buffeted by the swings of the economy, and that rises in their income were due primarily to higher social security payments
among the findings:
_while family income for the elderly grew more than 50 percent, it grew only 26 percent for married couples with children and only 2 percent for single mothers with children. for families head by someone under 25, including those without children, income dropped 20 percent
_income fell 13 percent for low-income single mothers with children, with 20 percent of such families having less than half the cash income needed to live at the poverty level in 1986
_income rose 12 percent to 37 percent for all families with at least one full-time, year-round worker. for families with children and no such worker, it fell 10 percent
domenici, senior republican on the senate budget committee and a member of the national economic commission, said he was not surprised by the negative trends among young and single-parent families. he said any deficit-reduction recommendations would be screened for their impact on those households
however, domenici said cbo might have found more encouraging trends among such families if it had taken into account such non-cash programs as food stamps and the 1986 tax law that took millions of low-income families off the tax rolls
cbo said a lack of family-level data prevented it from including non-cash programs in its analysis. the agency gave similar reasons for not taking into account pre-1981 tax hikes, which reduced disposable income, and said it was impossible to project the net effect of either omission
lawyers for attorney general edwin meese iii say he knew nothing about a plan to use pentagon money to give israel payments to protect a $1 billion iraqi pipeline project
the plan was being promoted by meese's longtime friend, e. robert wallach. wallach's attorney, george g. walker, confirmed the contents of two messages in december 1985 sent by wallach to swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the proposed iraqi project. one contains a reference to meese
wallach was rappaport's attorney
the washington post, which on thursday disclosed the existence of the proposal to use pentagon money, said the december 1985 messages plus another wallach-to-rappaport telex on feb. 3, 1986 show that meese supported the plan and that the late william casey, then cia director, endorsed it
abc news, quoting anonymous sources, reported that under the plan israel would have gotten $400 million in u.s. military aid over four years. the money was to be set aside in a special bank account as construction of the pipeline began, the network said
the attorney general was not involved in any plans to utilize defense department funds for the project, gave no `assurances' about any such plan, and arranged no meeting for that purpose,'' said a statement by nathan lewin, one of meese's lawyers
the attorney general has no recollection of anything being said to him about any such plan,'' lewin added in an interview
meese's involvement with the pipeline project is under criminal investigation by independent counsel james mckay, who is trying to determine whether the attorney general may have violated the foreign corrupt practices act
that act makes it illegal for u.s. citizens, companies or their agents to offer foreign officials ``anything of value'' to influence them and makes the attorney general responsible for filing civil suits to block such payments
federal investigators also are looking at wallach's failure to register as a foreign agent, the washington times reported today. the newspaper quoted justice department officials, who were not identified, as saying the issue could raise conflict-of-interest problems for meese
it said that when wallach went to work as a paid lobbyist for rappaport, he also was acting as an unpaid personal attorney to meese during his confirmation hearings as attorney general
a dec. 16, 1985, message from wallach to rappaport says that ``i have assurance from my friend that if necessary, he will engage new person on project.'' wallach usually called meese ``my friend.''
but walker said that rather than being a reference to meese, the ``he'' referred to in that portion of the telex is someone else, probably national security staff aide david wigg, who would explain the pipeline project in general terms to the new national security adviser, john poindexter. poindexter had taken over the post from robert mcfarlane on dec. 4, 1985
walker said that in 1985, nsc aide wigg came up with the idea of using pentagon money to make payments to israel to ensure that the israelis would not attack the pipeline
wallach sent a dec. 12, 1985 telegram to rappaport relating that wigg was attempting to determine whether or not pentagon financing for the payments could be provided
wallach said ``the capital dod (department of defense) package'' was to be submitted that day by wigg to mcfarlane, who was wrapping up his government employment
on dec. 16, wallach reported in a message to rappaport that at a meeting that day with casey, who was a friend of rappaport's, wigg and wallach reviewed documents relating to the pentagon budget plan
wallach said that casey ``approved the concept with expression as to it being unique in his experience.'' walker said the language stops short of saying casey endorses the plan, and is simply expressing a view about the unique nature of the payment plan
in a feb. 3, 1986 message obtained by the post, wallach tells rappaport meese will contact poindexter to arrange a meeting for wallach, ``if it is necessary to obtain signature of his (poindexter's) superior.''
lewin said meese has no recollection of arranging a meeting for wallach with poindexter nor does he recall being asked to do so. walker said he didn't have a copy of the feb. 3 message and that wallach didn't remember sending one
lewin's statement said meese ``stands by'' a statement he made feb. 1 that ``the sum and substance'' of his involvement with the iraqi pipeline project consisted of referring wallach to mcfarlane in may 1985, referring then-israeli prime minister shimon peres to mcfarlane in october 1985 and discussing the pipeline briefly with peres
the only other involvement, meese said, was having the justice department office of legal counsel consider a request in october 1985 on the legality of using u.s. aid money to israel to help protect the pipeline from israeli attack
a sept. 25, 1985 memo from wallach to meese says that a portion of up to $700 million that would go to israel from the pipeline would be funneled to the israeli labor party
vice president george bush holds a strong lead over his gop rivals among likely south carolina voters, a poll published by the charlotte observer indicated today
coming three days before march 8, super tuesday, when 20 states hold primaries and caucuses, the south carolina primary has assumed strategic importance in the gop sweepstakes, despite its prize of only 37 delegates
the poll indicated bush had the support of 41 percent of those who said they're likely to vote in the south carolina gop primary. trailing were sen. bob dole with 29 percent, former television evangelist pat robertson, 13 percent, and rep. jack kemp of new york, 4 percent. twelve percent were undecided
the poll also indicated bush had the support of most of the younger voters: 61 percent of those 18-24 backed the vice president, as did 45 percent of those from 25-34. but so did 45 percent of those over 65
however, 45 percent of the likely voters _ and 47 percent of republicans _ said they see little difference between bush and dole
the telephone poll, conducted by the market research division of the newspaper, surveyed 687 registered voters who indicated they're likely to participate in the primary. the margin of error was 3.7 percentage points
meanwhile, a third of those polled said the controversy surrounding television evengelist jimmy swaggart has hurt robertson
and robertson, who is counting on support from democrats eligible to vote in the state's ``open'' gop primary, was trailing dole and bush among democratic voters
half the voters said they would feel uncomfortable with a television evangelist as president. and nearly a third said robertson would be hurt by the swaggart affair. but 56 said they didn't believe it would affect robertson
one of the country's most popular tv evangelists, swaggart stepped down this week after allegations that he had been with a new orleans prostitute
this week, robertson lashed out at bush, suggesting that the vice president's campaign had something to do with the timing of the swaggart revelations _ an implication bush called absurd
at the same time, dole was winning the endorsement of _ and stumping the state with _ the state's most revered republican, sen. strom thurmond
after indications that dole would downplay the state, bush supporters say thurmond's backing has raised his stakes. buses</head>
some 4,700 teen-agers will be ousted from the drivers' seats of school buses in north carolina and south carolina under a ruling issued by the labor department
the department, in an effort to crack down on enforcement of child labor laws, announced thursday that 17-year-olds must stop driving school buses in those states after april 1, said department spokesman bob zachariasiewicz
for the past two decades, the department had granted both states annual exemptions from the child labor laws that enabled them to hire the youths
the decision to end the exemptions reflected a failure of the states to comply with more stringent conditions imposed in december on the employment of 17-year-olds, the department said in a statement
in january, a 4-year-old west columbia, s.c., boy was run over and killed by a 17-year-old bus driver who had a previous speeding ticket. no charges were filed against the driver due to confusion over whether he could have seen the child
deputy secretary of labor dennis whitfield informed the two states' governors of the decision thursday
officials from the two states expressed dismay at the ruling
if this in fact comes to pass, it would cause north carolina some very big problems, and we hope the department of labor will send us some bus drivers to go with their order,'' said jim sughrue, a spokesman for gov. jim martin
south carolina gov. carroll campbell said he ``deeply regret(s) the department of labor has seen fit to withdraw south carolina's exemption of 17-year-old bus drivers prior to the end of the school year
but the department's findings that certain school districts were ignoring its guidelines did not help south carolina's position in this matter,'' the governor added
south carolina has 6,000 school bus drivers, of whom 1,200 are 17 years old, said charlie williams, the south carolina superintendent of education. a total of 1,000 young drivers had been fired by december because of bad driving records
north carolina has 13,000 drivers, of whom 3,500 are 17, zachariasiewicz said. in the 1986-87 school year, there were 14,350 drivers, of whom 5,000 were 16 and 17 years old
the department banned school bus driving by 16-year-olds in december, he said
employment of any drivers under 18 after april 1 would result in assessment of monetary penalties and possible court action, the department said
when the states applied for exemptions for the 1987-88 school year, they were instead given extensions until dec. 31, 1987, while they supplied additional data, zachariasiewicz said
in december, the department extended the exemptions through the 1987-88 school year, but three conditions were imposed for the use of 17-year-old drivers: they had to have been trained and started driving school buses on or before aug. 31, 1987; they could not have received a ticket for a moving violation or been involved in an accident for which they were responsible _ in a car or a bus _ during the 1986-87 school year; and they had to be students or high school graduates
investigations by the department of how the states followed these criteria ``revealed widespread non-compliance, particularly employment of 17-year-olds with moving violations on their driving records as student school bus drivers,'' the department statement said
in south carolina, in 14 of 15 school districts investigated, the department found approximately 200 instances of non-compliance,'' the statement said
north carolina had received exemptions since 1967 while south carolina had received them since 1968. opening, sted unchanged for the week. pickup 2nd graf pvs ``the dollar's...''</note>
stock prices closed higher on the tokyo stock exchange friday, with the market's key index posting its 12th consecutive gain, while the u.s. dollar ended the week at 128.35 yen, unchanged from its opening
the dollar's close was 0.45 yen lower than thursday's closing level of 128.80 yen
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues ended the day at 25,165.18, up 64.52 points or 0.25 percent
currency traders attributed the dollar's opening weakness to disappointment that the revised u.s. fourth-quarter gross national product statistics released thursday didn't exceed 5 percent, as some had hoped. the commerce department said the revised growth rate was 4.5 percent
at a press conference friday in tokyo, finance minister kiichi miyazawa said intervention by central banks was not necessary at this time since yen-dollar exchange rates were stable. his remarks appeared to have little influence in the currency market
the tokyo stock exchange's key index rose today for the 12th consecutive trading day, while the dollar declined against the yen to end the week at 128.35 yen
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues rose 64.52 points, or 0.25 percent, in active trading to finish the day at 25,165.18
the investment environment is better now than before because of declining interest rates and the relatively stable market in new york,'' said a senior researcher at nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage, who spoke on condition of anonymity
analysts also said many japanese companies were revising their forecasts for march because of better business performance
on the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 128.35 yen, unchanged from its opening level but down from its 128.80-yen closing thursday. spot turnover totaled $4.5 billion
finance minister kiichi miyazawa told a news conference today that intervention by central banks was not necessary at the present time because of stable yen-dollar exchange rates
the reagan administration is welcoming reports from moscow that a strategic arms agreement could be ready for signing at a may summit, but says it is doubtful such a timetable could be met
we welcome it, if it means the soviets are going to work at the negotiations just as hard as we will,'' an administration official said thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity
and reagan, in an interview thursday with the washington post, expressed hope it could be signed by the end of the year although ``the time is too limited'' to complete work on the treaty by the summit
a senior soviet official in moscow also said thursday he expected a treaty to reduce the superpowers' long-range nuclear weapons stockpile would be ready for signing at the summit meeting, the post said
the official, who was not identified, talked to about 20 foreign reporters at a two-hour meeting. the post was uninvited but said it obtained its account from other reporters
the official also said that reagan will stay in the kremlin during the visit, which should last for about a week and could include other cities besides moscow, according to the account in today's post
the administration is known to completely discount the speculation that reagan would stay in the kremlin
according to administration officials, reagan's expected trip to moscow is likely to mirror in length and style the four-day visit to washington last december by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
the officials said thursday that no dates have been fixed for the president's trip, but that tentative plans continue to be that it will fall sometime from mid- to late-may to early june
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters this week he did not expect a summit date to be set until soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze meets in washington late next month with secretary of state george shultz, who just returned from moscow
gorbachev's visit was confined to washington. in a strict observance of the rule of reciprocity, reagan is expected to remain in moscow
the new york times, in an account of the briefing published in today's editions, said the official indicated the soviet union might drop a key objection to the u.s. development of a space-based missile defense system by permitting the testing of components in space
the discovery of a synthetic peptide that triggers antibodies to neutralize the aids virus in rabbits may eventually help in combating the fatal disease in humans, a chicago researcher says
mark gurney, an assistant professor at the university of chicago, said thursday that the peptides he synthesized imitate part of the hiv virus. the hiv is the virus that causes aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome
the potential is that you could use a peptide to elicit ... the same type of antibodies in man and these would then attack the virus,'' gurney said
peptides are compounds of amino acids, and the ones that gurney made were identical in some ways to a portion of the envelope that surrounds the human immune virus
in the experiments, researchers put the peptides into laboratory rabbits. the immune system of the rabbits produced three antibodies against the peptides
researchers then exposed these antibodies to several strains of the hiv virus in test tubes, and gurney said the hiv virus was neutralized, or prevented from spreading to other cells
the experiment used a peptide that was a chemical mimic of a portion of the hiv envelope that remains unchanged, gurney said. other parts of the virus change frequently
this unchanging portion of the hiv virus does not elicit an antibody response when it is attached to the whole virus for reasons that scientists do not understand, said gurney
he said peptide-antibody response is not well understood now and that experiments in the past have shown that synthetic peptides can trigger undesirable antibodies, only a small number of which will attack the target
until this process is further refined, he said, peptides will not be useful against aids
he said the researchers also are unable to determine precisely how the antibodies created by using the peptide are able to neutralize aids in the test tube
gurney worked on the experiment with david d. ho of the cedars-sinai medical center in los angeles, joan c. kaplan of massachusetts general hospital in boston, and indre e. rackauskas of the university of chicago
a report on the research appears today in science, the journal of the american association for the advancement of science
aids kills by destroying a key part of the human immune system, leaving the body open to infections. aids is spread principally through sexual contact, but also by the shared needles of drug abusers and the use of contaminated blood products in transfusions. infected mothers may also pass the aids virus to their babies while giving birth
as of feb. 15, aids had been diagnosed in 53,814 americans, of whom more than half, or 30,158, have died since 1981, according to the federal centers for disease control. no one is known to have recovered from aids
rock superstar bruce springsteen walked onstage, threw a bouquet of roses into the crowd, stepped up to a microphone and yelled, ``ready for a date?''
nearly 13,000 people, most standing as they would throughout the concert, roared back that they were
springsteen and his 12-piece e street band then went to work, and the boss' nationwide ``tunnel of love'' tour _ his first in nearly 2{ years _ got under way thursday night at the worcester centrum
i'm excited,'' said cynthia swienton of simsbury, conn., standing up in her seat 12 rows from the back of the auditorium. she and her companion, john smedick of torrington, conn., paid $300 for their two tickets
although the concert was sold out, hundreds of people milled around outside before the show began, hoping to buy tickets
according to the worcester telegram newspaper, ticket scalpers' prices were generally between $150 to $225 a ticket, but one unidentified person said he was offered a ticket for $750. tickets were $20 each when first went on sale
ticket scalping is illegal in massachusetts
the crowd was generally orderly outside the centrum, said police lt. paul f. campbell. he said there were a few arrests for unarmed robbery of concert tickets and one man was charged with being a disorderly person after he allegedly spit in the face of a television camerman
police sgt. john r. harrington also said two men, one wielding a crowbar, were arrested for robbing four teen-agers of their tickets before the show began
several celebrities were among the 12,800 people attending the show, including basketball star kevin mchale of the boston celtics and miami steve van zandt, springsteen's lead guitar player until 1981
a lot of the guys (celtics) like springsteen,'' mchale said, taking time to sign autographs while sitting in a middle section of the auditorium. ``the '84 tour, they seemed to be touring a lot of cities that we were playing in. we'd play on one night, they'd come to our game; we'd go to the concert next night. it worked real nice.''
dressed in tight black jeans, black boots, vest and a white shirt buttoned to the neck, springsteen later took off the shirt to reveal a black t-shirt, and his hair was lathered with sweat 3 hours and 25 minutes later
do you want me to get a heart attack? on the first night?'' he asked the crowd before he and the band did a 15-minute encore of such rock favorites as ``devil with a blue dress on,'' ``good golly miss molly'' and ``cc rider.''
he opened the show with ``tunnel of love.''
springsteen, 38, will perform again sunday and monday in worcester before the tour moves on to chapel hill, n.c
although he will have all the functions of president, under panama's constitution solis palma, 71, will have the title minister in charge of the presidency of the republic rather than president
he will fill out the current presidential term, which ends in october 1989. elections are scheduled for may 1989
according to the constitution, selection of a new chief executive goes to the cabinet and the title is changed because the country no longer has a vice president
delvalle was first elected vice president on a ticket with president nicolas ardito barletta and assumed the presidency when ardito barletta stepped down after 11 months in power
panama has been rocked by protests since june, when noriega's recently retired second in command publicly charged the general with illicit activities ranging from drug trafficking to electoral fraud and the assassination of a political opponent
a flight of money from panama followed
today the country is virtually at siege economically by external pressures and tensions,'' delvalle told the nation thursday. ``i have to consider with sadness that many of the successes that had been obtained are vanishing in the past eight months.''
the defense forces have about 15,000 soldiers and police under their command in this nation of 2.2 million people
relations between the united states and panama have deteriorated since the anti-noriega demonstrations broke out last summer
noriega has demanded removal of the southern command, which the pentagon and the white house have rejected, saying american troops are legally in panama and will remain there to protect the canal until it is handed over to panama on dec. 31, 1999
noriega later said he was referring only to the headquarters unit responsible for u.s. strategic military planning. american military sources said that would involve the removal of only about 300 officers and men
during his birthday speech this month, noriega received an ovation when he declared: ``if they want me out, they'll have to kill me.''
the reagan administration looks upon noriega as the main obstacle in its goal of an eventual transition in panama to a truly civilian government
delvalle assumed the presidency in 1985 under circumstances which strongly suggested that noriega forced the ouster of delvalle's predecessor
it was a constitutional succession, but delvalle has been widely perceived as no more than panama's titular head
noriega has maintained that executive authority rests with delvalle and that panama has achieved a full transition to democracy. he says his u.s. critics are campaigning against him with the aim of annulling the panama canal treaties, under which the waterway reverts to panamanian control
u.s. officials said wednesday that delvalle's extensive business interests and family could be threatened if he were to break with noriega. in addition, delvalle's health is said to be tenuous because of a heart operation
however, they said delvalle was increasingly disturbed by his ties to noriega
noriega entered the panamanian national guard in 1962 as a lieutenant after attending a military college in peru on a scholarship. he quickly became acquainted with a rising young officer named omar torrijos
torrijos took power in panama in a 1968 coup. less than a year later he named noriega, then an obscure major in northernmost panama, as his chief of intelligence with the rank of lieutenant colonel
the job put noriega in touch with u.s. intelligence agencies concerned over any potential threats to the panama canal
when torrijos died in an unexplained airplane crash in 1981, noriega began shouldering his way to the top command. he took power in 1983
on an official salary of $60,000 a year, noriega lives in a two-story, colonial-style mansion in an exclusive district of panama city and maintains a fleet of expensive cars. he is reported to own at least a dozen properties, including an apartment in paris and a chateau in the south of france
isolated snow showers lingered in the northeast today and a few light rain showers dampened northern california, but fair weather prevailed across the nation
a weak storm moving across lake ontario was expected to drop 3 to 6 inches of snow on new york state east of the lake, and a snow squall warning was in effect
clouds extended from california to texas and over washington state and oregon. partly cloudy skies prevailed from the great lakes to the middle and northern atlantic coast
today's forecast called for scattered snow showers across eastern upper michigan, the eastern great lakes and upper ohio valley; rain showers over the southern pacific coast and mild weather for most of the nation, with mostly sunny or partly cloudy skies
high temperatures were expected to be in the 50s or 60s across much of the country; the 20s from northern sections of the great lakes through northern and central new england; the 30s and 40s from the eastern dakotas and upper mississippi valley into the ohio valley and the mid-atlantic region; the 70s across southern california and from southern and eastern texas into oklahoma and southwest kansas; and around 80 degrees across the desert southwest
the high for the nation thursday was 88 degrees at palm springs, calif. temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 4 degrees at montpelier, vt., to 68 degrees at phoenix, ariz
other reports:
