actor jimmy stewart drew cheers and tears at a ceremony honoring him for what first lady nancy reagan described as his ``wonderful life.''
your own story could be an entire museum,'' mrs. reagan told stewart and about 1,000 stewart fans at the thursday night ceremony sponsored by the american museum of the moving image, the nation's first large-scale film and television museum, scheduled to open here in may
the first lady also revealed that she developed a crush on stewart after he visited her family in california and entertained them with his guitar
in my teen-age years i had a huge crush on jimmy,'' she said. ``for a 16-year-old to have jimmy stewart for a weekend was too much. i was overcome. i was gone. you know that crush has grown into a real love
i have a twinge of jealousy for those who had the honor to perform with him,'' the former actress added
colleagues such as kirk douglas, richard dreyfuss, brooke shields and janet leigh spoke about how stewart had become as much a source of inspiration as his movies, which include ``it's a wonderful life,'' ``the spirit of st. louis'' and ``mr. smith goes to washington.''
i doubt you know who you really and truly are mr. stewart,'' dreyfuss said. ``you have taught and trained me as an actor. you have inspired me as a storyteller and you have come to personify a part of this nation, to symbolize the american man who is gentle, ironic, self-depreciating, tough and emotional.''
douglas drew chuckles from the audience at the waldorf-astoria hotel ballroom when he said he was in awe of the 79-year-old man who has ``been an inspiration to all of us young actors.''
stewart spoke briefly, praising the museum
i'm really astounded at what all of you have done here to create and bring to reality all you have done in the american museum of the moving image,'' said stewart, whose wife, gloria, and two daughters also attended
the $11.4 million museum will feature exhibits that explore the art, history and technology of all moving image media
the most moving part of the evening occurred when the audience was shown a segment from ``the tonight show'' in which stewart read a poem about his dog bo
although the poem began with comical recollections of the dog, it ended with a tearful stewart describing how the dog died and how he missed having it beside him
miss shields, who was choked up as she started to speak after watching the film clip from the podium, told the audience she too had a dog named bo
u.s. rep. james a. traficant jr., whose avowed campaign for the democratic presidential nomination has yet to take shape, has failed to make the ballot in two more ohio congressional districts
the problems disclosed thursday brought to four the number of ohio districts in which traficant's name will not be on the ballot. ohio has 21 congressional districts
in the sprawling 6th district of southern ohio, traficant needed 150 signatures, and 159 were submitted. every signature was ruled invalid, said nancy stapleton, director of the warren county board of elections
elections officials in the 2nd district in suburban cincinnati said thursday that traficant did not meet petition requirements there, either. traficant already was off the ballot in two other districts
supporters of massachusetts gov. michael dukakis filed petitions containing more than four times the number of signatures needed to get on the april 19 new york presidential primary ballot
thursday was deadline day for the democratic candidates at the state board of elections and, in addition to dukakis, supporters of tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and illinois sen. paul simon also filed petitions to get their candidates spots on new york's statewide ballot
supporters of jesse jackson and missouri rep. richard gephardt had filed earlier in the week
the only one of the six major democratic candidates not to make the board's 5 p.m. deadline for in-person filing, was former colorado sen. gary hart. new york campaign aides were shooting for the midnight thursday deadline for getting a postmark on their petitions
education secretary william j. bennett responded with a stern ``no'' to a columnist's request that cabinet officers rate vice president george bush as to his presidential timber
bennett took umbrage at a request from dale van atta, co-author of the jack anderson column, who sought the impressions of all 34 present and former reagan cabinet members who have served with bush
calling bush ``a mystery to the voters,'' the columnist asked for instances where bush influenced policy decisions or actions, and warned that a failure to reply ``may send a negative message about mr. bush.''
bennett's wrote back that it was ``nonsense'' to call bush a mystery to the voters. he also said he would not violate the confidentiality of cabinet discussions, or ``the president's injunction to all his cabinet members to stay neutral in the presidential race.''
the democratic presidential race in texas is a tight contest, while the republican field still is dominated by vice president george bush, according to a new poll
the poll, conducted for the dallas morning news and the houston chronicle and published thursday, showed jesse jackson with 19 percent, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis with 18 percent, rep. richard gephardt with 15 percent and sen. albert gore jr. with 12 percent of the vote in the texas democratic primary. gary hart had 6 percent and paul simon had 5 percent, while 24 percent were unsure
bush had 60 percent of the support in the texas gop primary, according to the poll. his closest competitor was sen. bob dole, with 15 percent
the poll, conducted by the university of houston's center for public policy, had a margin of error 6 percentage points. it surveyed 294 likely gop voters and 301 likely democratic voters
former ku klux klan leader david duke, a democratic presidential candidate, wants to speak to the oklahoma senate but senate president pro tempore bob cullison doubts duke will get the chance
democrat cullison said a man identifying himself as a representative of duke, one of 12 democrats on the oklahoma primary ballot, came to his office this week and asked if the candidate could address the senate next week
the senate leader said he told the man duke could talk if he could get a senate sponsor and there were no objections
cullison said senate rules require unanimous consent requests before a non-senator can address the legislative body. he said such requests are routinely approved, but he did not think that would be the case for duke
michael dukakis, richard gephardt and jesse jackson had substantial leads over albert gore in florida, according to a mason-dixon opinion research poll conducted for florida news organizations
the poll released thursday showed that 23 percent of the democrats questioned were undecided. dukakis had 23 percent, gephardt 18 percent, jackson 17 percent and gore trailed at 10 percent. gary hart was back at 6 percent, and paul simon had 3 percent
on the republican side, george bush had a huge lead over his challengers in florida at 47 percent. bob dole had 20 percent, while pat robertson had 10 percent. jack kemp was at the back with 3 percent, and 20 percent of florida republicans questioned were undecided
the poll was based on random telephone surveys feb. 19-21 of 843 likely florida voters. the poll was considered accurate within plus or minus 4.4 percentage points for democrats and 5.4 percentage points for republicans
share prices fell in early trading on the london stock exchange today after thursday's drop on wall street
the financial times-stock exchange 100 index was down 8.8 points at 1,773.6 at 9:45 a.m
when the market officially opened at 9 a.m., the index was down 1.3 points at 1,781.1
dealers said prices started to recover near the official opening on continued confidence in the british economy, but fell back shortly afterwards
the early trend followed losses in new york thursday, where the dow jones industrial average fell 22.38 to 2,017.57, and gains in tokyo overnight, where the nikkei index rose 64.52 to 25,165.18. assembly building, sted of presidential palace as sent. picks up 3rd pvs, `delvalle said...'</note>
education minister manuel solis palma was sworn in as panama's new chief of state early friday to replace president eric arturo delvalle, removed from office after he ordered the country's military strongman to step down
legislative assembly president alberto aleman boyd administered the oath of office to palma solis at the assembly building shortly before 4 a.m. est
delvalle said he rejected his removal, which came after the military challenged his order dismissing noriega and the man named as new chief of the defense forces refused to take the job
noriega, who is under u.s. indictment as a drug trafficker, is regarded as the real power behind the civilian government in panama, headquarters for u.s. military operations in latin america
opposition lawmakers did not attend the 10-minute emergency legislative session during which delvalle and vice president roderick esquivel were removed from office. the actions were by unanimous vote of the 38 members of the 67-seat assembly in attendance
the cabinet, which delvalle said he fired today, then named solis palma chief of state to complete delvalle's term. elections are scheduled for may 1989
at his home, delvalle said he fired all 12 cabinet members and called the resolution ``something legally despicable that only fulfills a formality in the mind of those who want to grasp power at any cost
they will not receive acceptance from any country that takes pride in being democratic, '' delvalle said
in washington, white house spokesman bob hall said the white house would have no comment until morning. an official at the state department also had no immediate comment
the national democratic union, which backs the military, holds 45 seats in the assembly. the rest are held by the democratic alliance of the opposition, none of whose members attended the session
in its resolution, the assembly said delvalle did not follow constitutional procedures and laws of the defense forces in removing noriega
in addition, it said, in announcing his decision, delvalle mentioned the u.s. charges against noriega, showing that ``this conduct of the president occurs with the object of permitting the intervention of the government of the united states in the internal affairs of panama.''
it said delvalle's action damaged national sovereignty and endangered the peace and security of the country, also violating the constitution
it said esquivel had abandoned his post sept. 8, 1987, in violation of the constitution
there was no immediate comment from noriega, who has said he is innocent of all charges against him
delvalle said earlier that col. marcos justines, the chief of staff, would replace noriega as head of the defense forces. thursday night, justines said, ``i reject that order.''
the police chief for the defense forces, flanked by colonels and lieutenant colonels at the forces' central garrison, told panamanian tv no officer would replace noriega
he (delvalle) is going first,'' col. leonidas macias said
none of us wants the (panamanian military) command, the commander stays, and we all stay. the president goes.''
justines, also at the garrison, told television reporters: ``we have been conversing with him (delvalle) constantly, and he knows that our position has been that there is too much american interference in this panamanian affair.''
we are not here denying or refusing this post because it's not our place, because we have a commander _ commander noriega,'' justines added
the government's radio nacional called panamanians to a thursday night rally supporting noriega at a downtown park near the national palace, but apparently few people responded. downtown streets were nearly empty
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater had issued a statement in washington thursday saying,``we understand that president delvalle today dismissed gen. noriega from his position as commander of the panama defense forces.''
at this time, we want to reiterate our unqualified support for civilian constitutional rule in panama.''
washington called for noriega's resignation after u.s. grand juries in miami and tampa, fla., indicted him and others on drug trafficking charges feb. 5
the indictments accuse noriega of using his military position to let colombian drug traffickers use panama as a base for smuggling cocaine and marijuana into the united states. the charges said noriega received a healthy kickback from drug profits
the military command late thursday ordered closure of channel 5 television station, owned by delvalle, said an employee who spoke on condition of anonymity for security reasons
the opposition daily la prensa also was closed by military order, according to its news editor, alfredo jimenez. he said an army officer arrived at the newspaper offices at 7:30 p.m. and ``told me we had 10 minutes to vacate the building.''
pentagon spokeswoman capt. nancy laluntas said in washington that the u.s. southern command in panama received reports of scattered demonstrations in and around panama city. she said the command issued a ``bravo'' alert, which orders american military personnel and dependents to ``decrease their visibility.''
the command, initially created to protect the panama canal, has become the center for u.s. military operations in latin america from fighting rebels to drug smugglers. there are 10,000 u.s. soldiers and 20,000 dependents here
delvalle said in a nationally broadcast message thursday that he asked noriega days ago to step down voluntarily so an investigation could begin of charges that he engaged in illicit activities. he said noriega refused
the president said, ``there is no other alternative but the use of the powers that the constitution gives me, to separate gen. noriega from his high command and to encharge the leadership of the institution to the current chief of staff, col. marcos justines.''
some drivers honked their horns shortly after delvalle made his announcement, and some groups could be seen waving white handkerchiefs. both are signs of protest used by noriega's opponents
later, at his home, delvalle told the associated press, ``i am very calm, because i have had to take a very difficult decision, having to do with a person (noriega) with whom i have worked for nearly two years, with a great deal of respect and consideration
however, his little will to take that decision ... which i suggested to him, obligated me to take it for the health of this country.''
about 10 anti-riot police then arrived and remained on guard
in the evening, about 100 people _ relatives, friends and journalists _ gathered at delvalle's home
earlier thursday, roman catholic archbishop marcos gregorio mcgrath visited delvalle and commented, ``it seems to us that we should give our support to president delvalle. it is a step taken after many consultations.''
delvalle smiled when reporters asked if he feared the military would remove him from office. ``if good judgment doesn't prevail, no president has the force to defy the arms that ... we entrusted to them so that they might take care of us,'' he replied
u.s. ambassador arthur davis showed up for a few minutes. ``my presence here is to show my support to the government, because we always have supported the civilian government and we are going to continue doing so,'' he said
asked if the u.s. government would recognize a replacement for delvalle, davis replied: ``we cannot do that.''
panama has, a0878
panama's president risked challenging the authority of gen. manuel antonio noriega because he heard the ``outcry of the people'' against the military strongman, says a leading panamanian exile
the central american nation's legislative assembly removed president eric arturo delvalle and the vice president from office during an emergency session early today
roberto eisenmann, 50-year-old exiled publisher of panama's leading independent newspaper, la prensa, said earlier that either way the power struggle went, ``noriega will lose.''
i don't think he will find any nation that would recognize his government (in the event of a coup),'' said eisenmann, who said his newspaper was shut down thursday by the military
delvalle's decision to challenge noriega was made after seven weeks of negotiations here between the president and half a dozen opposition leaders, participants in the talks told the miami herald in a story published today
the last stage leading to the decision began in early january, when the then-panamanian consul to new york, jose blandon, met with several opposition leaders in the home of former panamanian ambassador and anti-noriega crusader gabriel lewis galindo in the miami suburb of kendall
blandon had just spent 10 hours with delvalle in new york,'' ricardo arias calderon, president of the christian democratic party, told the herald. ``he told us the president was ready to oust noriega, but that he wanted to do that as of aug. 12.''
that date marked the fifth anniversary of noriega's rise to the helm of panama's defense forces
but the opposition politicians told delvalle that if noriega was given that much time, he would be able to regroup
on feb. 16, the opposition counseled the president to go to washington, convene an emergency session of the organization of american states and announce noriega's dismissal, the herald reported
a week ago wednesday, delvalle met with u.s. assistant secretary of state elliott abrams, whom he informed he would fire noriega, but in panama, not in the united states
the thing that worked on him was the enormous outcry of the people,'' eisenmann told abc's ``nightline'' thursday night. ``there was pressure from his family not to go down the tubes with noriega.''
noriega was indicted three weeks ago in tampa and miami on federal charges of aiding drug smugglers, and has been under pressure to step down as military chief
gilbert mallol, who directs the national civic crusade, a panamanian opposition coalition of 192 organizations, predicted thursday during a visit to miami that delvalle's move would force noriega into seizing power and remove the ``facade of democracy.''
mallol, a 32-year-old engineer, lived here in exile after eluding military police and fleeing panama last summer. his group was accused last august of plotting against noriega, but mallol recently had returned to panama
a prosecutor in noriega's drug case said he knew of no u.s. deal to drop charges in order to encourage delvalle to challenge the military leader
richard gregorie, chief assistant u.s. attorney in florida's southern district, said if noriega were to leave panama, ``we would attempt to extradite him like any other dope dealer.''
the feb. 4 indictments charge noriega and 15 others with taking at least $4.6 million in payoffs to protect shipments of colombian cocaine, launder money, supply drug laboratories and shield drug kingpins
the indictment also alleged that noriega was allied with the medellin cartel, the organization reputed to supply much of the cocaine in the united states, and once enlisted the help of cuban leader fidel castro to mediate a dispute with the cartel over drug money
castro, who was named in the indictment but not charged, angrily denied the any role in an interview with nbc news aired thursday night
if noriega is ever brought to trial and convicted of all charges, he could face up to 145 years in prison and fines of more than $1.1 million
cardinal miguel obando y bravo has proposed that a new round of peace talks between the leftist sandinista government and contra rebels be held in guatemala march 10-12
the roman catholic archbishop of managua, who is mediating efforts to establish a cease-fire, suggested the dates thursday in response to a letter from president daniel ortega
he made no reference to ortega's request for three days of negotiations beginning today and did not explain why he was suggesting different dates
obando y bravo suspended the last round of negotiations feb. 18 in guatemala after presenting a proposal for breaking a deadlock that arose in the talks' first hours
deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco accused the cardinal, nicaragua's catholic leader, of breaking off the talks before the government could deliver its formal, conditional acceptance of the proposal
in his letter, obando y bravo asked ortega if the president's letter of tuesday was ``a rejection of the acceptance in principle that your delegation belatedly gave'' to the proposal
there was no immediate response from the government to the march dates or obando y bravo's letter
the cardinal said representatives of the nicaraguan resistance, the umbrella group for the rebels, told him thursday they ``are willing to continue discussing the proposal the mediator made feb. 18 in guatemala.''
the proposal asks the contras to accept a 30-day truce in exchange for four concessions they have long sought from the government _ changes in the draft law, a complete amnesty, an easing of press restrictions and a reopening of talks with the internal political opposition
the cease-fire effort is part of a regional peace plan signed aug. 7 in guatemala by nicaragua, el salvador, honduras, guatemala and costa rica. it also calls for amnesties, democratic reforms and an end to outside aid to insurgencies fighting in the region
the reagan administration has supported the contras' 6{-year-old insurgency, which has claimed about 40,000 lives. but on feb. 3, the u.s. house of representatives turned down a request for an additional $36.2 million in contra aid
employees at the cities service building downtown have received a memo suggesting that their visits to restrooms be wrapped up in 12 minutes _ or they'll be left in the dark
motion sensors that control lights will be installed in the next few weeks in all restrooms of the building occupied by cities service oil and gas corp
the switches will sense motion when people pass and turn on lights. if no motion is detected for 12 minutes, the sensors will extinguish the lights, according to the company memo
a spokesman said the devices have been tested in one men's room in the building and have been found to be effective in reducing use of electricity
the immigration and naturalization service is singing the praises of its amnesty program with a new spanish record, ``amnistia.''
it's a vehicle to get the word across to all the people who haven't applied to let them know that they really should come out of hiding,'' said the author, ins employee art zuniga
his spanish song will be used in a stepped-up campaign the ins is using to lure applicants to its one-year program offering legal residency to certain aliens as the may 4 deadline approaches
zuniga, 38, who grew up in the lower rio grande valley in a family of farm workers and writes songs for a country-and-western band, said he wrote the song because he understands people who come to this country seeking work
well, my friend, the time has come for those who have lived a long time in the country inhabited by americans,'' he sings in spanish. ``recently, a law was passed. ... this opportunity will not come again in your lifetime.''
two of the valley's most popular spanish stations already have agreed to air the song
a strong earthquake was recorded in the southern indian ocean today but there were no reports of damage, the hong kong royal observatory said
the quake was recorded at 2:30 p.m. and registered a preliminary reading of 6.9 on the richter scale, the observatory said
the epicenter was about 1,110 miles east-southeast of the south african port city of durban, it said. the observatory said it had received no reports of tsunamis, or huge waves generated by earthquakes at sea
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. every increase of one number means that the ground motion is 10 times greater
an earthquake registering 7 is capable of widespread, heavy damage in populated areas, but today's quake was centered far from land
a 79-year-old who burst into a board meeting at the retirement home that evicted him and gunned down four former neighbors was in custody today, booked for investigation of attempted murder
apparently, they had a board meeting and one former resident, who was apparently disgruntled, walked into the board room and started shooting'' at the 15 or 16 people gathered there, said police spokesman dee anderson
gunfire from a .22-caliber semiautomatic rifle wounded four people and a fifth person suffered a heart attack in the 11 a.m. attack thursday at the masonic home for the aged, authorities said
the wounded, treated for minor gunshot wounds, were listed in fair condition today at arlington hospital, but the heart attack victim was in critical condition, a hospital spokesman said
the suspect, whose name was not released, had lived at the masonic home for three years, but was evicted in september 1987 for breaking rules, officials said
the man burst into the monthly board meeting with two rifles, one slung around his neck with twine, and opened fire. he fled to a nearby kitchen and surrendered peacefully to police, who booked him on investigative charges of attempted murder
at the arlington villa retirement home, where the suspect has lived since dec. 1, officials expressed shock
he is a good resident, very congenial and sociable,'' said administrator gennie pace
masonic home employees shut out all visitors and referred all questions to board chairman sam hilburn, but refused to say where he could be contacted
a 98-year-old oklahoma law stating that a husband is head of the household and his wife must live where he does is headed toward repeal in the state legislature, but not without debate
the bill to change the 1890 law was approved by the house 67-26 thursday and moves to the senate
i want to bring oklahoma from the 19th century into the 20th century before the 21st century gets here,'' said the bill's sponsor, rep. freddie williams
if the law were enforced, mrs. williams said, an appeals court judge would have to step down from the bench because she lives on one side of the state and and her husband lives on the other
even so, opponents of repeal heatedly argued that the law is based on biblical teachings about the family
i think there should be a difference between a man and a woman, and when we get to where there's not a difference in it, we're going to have all kinds of problems, whether it's war or what it is,'' said rep. bill smith
rep. leonard sullivan contended he had ``never heard any lady'' call for repeal of the law
if it's not broke, don't fix it,'' sullivan said. and ``if it's not being enforced, why worry?''
rep. ken harris, a supporter of the bill, said, ``even having to argue about this bill is a sad, sad commentary.''
mrs. williams and harris pointed out that the law had been declared unconstitutional by a former attorney general
rep. john monks said the attorney general who made the ruling never married and ``never had the responsibility for a family.''
the dollar fell in moderate european trading this morning on indications the u.s. economy is expanding slower than the market expected, dealers said
gold prices were mixed in quiet trading
dealers said economic data released in the past few days showed the american economy slightly less robust than expected, weakening the dollar
the data has made dealers a little more selling oriented,'' said one trader with a u.s. commercial bank in milan
dealers noted the dollar had been moving higher since mid-february, after the report that the u.s. trade deficit narrowed in december for the second consecutive month
but recent economic data disappointed the market, especially thursday's report that the u.s. gross national product grew by 4.5 percent in the fourth quarter, lower than market expectations of a 5 percent rise, dealers said
as a result, traders said, the market feared the u.s. trade gap might not be shrinking quickly enough, eroding sentiment for the dollar
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar closed at 128.35 yen, down from 128.80 yen on thursday. later, in london, it was quoted at 128.45 yen
other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late thursday's rates:
