the president acknowledged, however, that ``mit needs to take a greater part in enabling pluralism. ... i'm not satisifed in the measured levels of black undergrads here nor am i satisfied in the measured levels of black faculty here.''
he agreed to meet with a smaller group in two to three weeks to discuss the demands
earlier this month, students occupied a building at the university of massachusetts for six days to protest racial violence at that campus. the occupation ended feb. 17 when chancellor joseph d. duffey reached agreeement with protesters on such demands as increased resources for third world programs
a music promoter allegedly bribed radio station employees with cash and cocaine to get his records on the air, according to a federal payola indictment, lawyers said
federal agents arrested ralph tashjian, 39, of san mateo and his wife, valerie, in front of their children at their home thursday, said anthony brooklier, the promoter's los angeles attorney
tashjian allegedly paid nearly $42,000 in cash and gave undisclosed quantities of cocaine to three radio station workers from 1980 to 1985 in exchange for air time for his records, brooklier said. the stations were in fresno and el paso, texas
the indictment handed up by a los angeles federal grand jury thursday was announced by brooklier and david kenner, the tashjians' attorneys, who said their clients are innocent
we absolutely deny any wrongdoing on the tashjians' part,'' brooklier said. ``they were arrested at their home, in front of their children, even though we had offered to surrender them (to authorities).''
the indictment charges tashjian with three counts of payola, one count of conspiracy to distribute cocaine, one count of obstruction of justice and three counts of corporate income-tax fraud, brooklier said
mrs. tashjian was arrested for alleged corporate tax evasion. they both face arraignment today in san francisco, brooklier said
federal prosecutors at the justice department's organized crime strike force in los angeles, which is handling the case, withheld announcement of the indictment
tashjian is an associate of joseph isgro, a los angeles-based record promoter who has been investigated by the grand jury but wasn't named in the indictment
tashjian worked out of isgro's los angeles office, but for his own company, ralph tashjian enterprises inc
the payola investigation began in 1986, with reputed organized crime figure salvatore james pisello, 64, of west hollywood, charged in july with three counts of tax evasion. his case is pending
memphis slim, the blues pianist who wrote ``every day i have the blues'' and helped spread blues music throughout the world, died at the age of 72, hospital official said today
an official at necker hospital in paris, speaking on condition of anonymity, said memphis slim, whose real name was peter chatman, died wednesday. the cause of death was not disclosed
memphis slim was born in memphis, tenn., on sept. 3, 1915, and made his name in chicago in the 1930s
he had lived in europe since 1961, mostly in paris where he played frequently at ``les trois maillets'' and other jazz clubs
he was one of the originals,'' said mike zwerin, a paris-based author on jazz and blues music. ``he took blues to the rest of the world.''
a wake, open to the public, was scheduled monday at the hospital, with funeral services planned later in the week in memphis
memphis slim recorded at least 40 albums during his career on many labels, including ``raining the blues'' and ``the bluesman.''
among his songs were ``wish me well,'' ``mother earth'' and ``beer-drinking woman.''
memphis slim was among the most well-traveled bluesmen, attracting international attention with his performance at the 1959 newport festival
he owned a series of rolls-royce cars, and was known for double-parking them outside paris clubs, where he would stop in for an hour or two
the paris daily le monde said friday that memphis slim's music ``always had powerful expression and irresistable subtlety.''
until the 1970s, memphis slim represented blues to europeans,'' zwerin said. ``he was the only blues man they ever saw.''
many american jazz and blues greats moved to europe in the 1950s and 1960s because their music, although created in america, was more popular in the old world than in the new
memphis slim, however, often returned to the united states to play. he was a regular fixture at the chicago blues festival and other blues gatherings. described in a0500, pm-aids antibody. adds 4 grafs at end with more on research. subs 12th graf pvs, `the results ...,' to recast.</note>
a widely used pair of antibiotics prevented a deadly form of pneumonia in a group of 30 aids patients, while more than half of the patients in a similar untreated group came down with it, researchers reported today
this dramatic success in preventing one of the leading causes of death among aids patients is not a cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome, but could prolong the lives of aids sufferers, said the study's principal author, dr. margaret fischl of the university of miami school of medicine
any individual that is symptomatic with hiv (the aids virus) should be considered for intervention with low-dose antibiotics to prevent pneumocystis,'' said fischl. ``it's easily available. it's not expensive.''
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia strikes more than half of aids patients, and ``15 percent to 25 percent of individuals will die with it even when it's recognized and treated,'' she said
in a separate development, the anti-aids drug azt was shown to lower virus levels and improve immune systems in more than two-thirds of 18 otherwise healthy aids carriers, according to a study done at the university of amsterdam, the netherlands
and, a university of chicago researcher announced that he had synthesized a peptide _ a compound of amino acids _ that imitates part of the aids virus and triggered antibodies to neutralize the virus in rabbits
fischl prevented pneumocystis with a pair of sulfa drugs called trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole, marketed under a variety of trade names including bactrim and septra. they are used for kidney infections, bladder infections, traveler's diarrhea and, at high doses, for treatment of pneumocystis in aids victims, she said
after three years, pneumocystis had not struck any of the treated group of 30 patients who had kaposi's sarcoma, a skin cancer, but had not had any of the so-called opportunistic infections _ including pneumocystis _ that strike aids patients, fischl reported
in a control group of 30 untreated aids patients, 16 got pneumocystis, she said. a report of the findings appears today in the journal of the american medical association
when the experiment concluded, 42 percent of the treated group was still alive, compared with only 10 percent of the untreated group, fischl said
that was clear evidence that the preventive treatment was prolonging lives, but exactly how long it might prolong life could not be determined, she said
half of the treated patients suffered from side effects, including nausea, vomiting, itching, redness of the skin and fever
the results of the dutch study on azt, reported in the feb. 20 issue of the lancet, a british medical journal, were described as promising. but they fall short of what doctors would need to recommend that healthy aids virus carriers begin taking azt to prevent aids, dr. samuel broder, the director of aids drug testing at the national cancer institute, said thursday
nevertheless, broder said, it suggests that a recently initiated american study of azt in healthy carriers ``needs to proceed urgently.''
it's very important not to rush out and start using azt in a situation in which its use has not been proven,'' broder said. he noted that azt can have life-threatening side effects
the study found that levels of the aids virus ``declined significantly'' in 13 of 18 men who had longstanding aids virus infections but no symptoms of aids
levels of white blood cells called t4 cells _ which are a necessary component of the immune system and are killed by the aids virus _ rose in 14 of the 18 subjects. no serious side effects were observed, said the study's authors: frank de wolf, jan van der noordaa and others from the university of amsterdam, the netherlands
the aim of such studies is ultimately to determine whether azt might prevent or delay the development of aids in healthy carriers, or reduce its severity
based on their results, the dutch team said ``prevention of more serious hiv-related disease may be feasible.'' hiv, or human immunodeficiency virus, is the virus responsible for aids
enlarged lymph nodes are a common sign of aids infection. the researchers reported ``striking regression of lymph node sizes'' in patients given azt, also known as zidovudine or retrovir
as of feb. 18, 1,158 subjects had been enrolled in a nationwide trial of azt in healthy aids carriers in the united states, said sandra hecker, spokeswoman for the national institute of allergy and infectious diseases in bethesda, md., which is coordinating the trial
the study is aiming for about 1,500 volunteers and is expected to last about three years, she said
in the research by university of chicago assistant professor mark gurney, rabbits given the synthetic peptide produced three antibodies against the compound. scientists then exposed these antibodies to several strains of the hiv virus in test tubes, and gurney said the hiv virus was neutralized, or prevented from spreading to other cells
a report on the research appeared today in science, the journal of the american association for the advancement of science
gurney cautioned that the peptide-antibody response is not well understood now and that experiments in the past have shown that synthetic peptides can trigger undesirable antibodies, only a small number of which will attack the target
until this process is further refined, he said, peptides will not be useful against aids. of number of protesters this morning, students outside holding picket signs, transition. subs 13th graf pvs, `those who...' to include first name for ms. rizvi, whose first reference deleted higher up.</note>
demonstrators continued to occupy the university of dayton president's office early today, demanding an end to central intelligence agency recruiting on campus
brother raymond l. fitz, president of the roman catholic school, met with members of the democratic socialists of america and plowshares for peace in the office for about 90 minutes during the night to hear their demands
about 50 members of the groups took over the office shortly after 10 a.m. thursday, but the number had dwindled to 30 by this morning, university spokeswoman valerie galloway elijah said
she said another eight students were outside holding up signs and a few were standing at the end of a stairwell and blocked by university officials from joining the demonstrators
jon wentz, co-chairman of the democratic socialists of america, described thursday night's meeting as ``very positive. brother fitz was very cooperative with us.''
he said they talked about establishing a forum on the cia and that the students demanded a one-year moratorium on any cia recruitment
we seem to be very confident that we will get that moratorium,'' wentz said. ``we're not going to leave until we are guaranteed there is a moratorium.''
fitz said he would have to talk with his vice presidents and faculty before he could commit the school to a moratorium. he also said he was not yet committed to a forum and expected to meet again with the students later today
fitz would not say whether he would order the students removed
william c. schuerman, dean of the school, met with student representatives for about an hour thursday evening
i think we've been very clear that we're offering the students an opportunity to discuss the issues they're raising,'' schuerman said. ``what we're not prepared to do is to meet the demands they've indicated.''
the cia was recruiting at the nearby kennedy union on campus, but a statement issued by the protesters said they did not appear there because they did not want to infringe on the rights of students to interview with the agency
the students had been told they had to leave by 4:30 p.m. thursday or they would face charges. schuerman said they were allowed to stay past that deadline to avoid provoking them
those who remained at st. mary's hall were charged with disruption under the student conduct code and later would be charged with trespassing under the code, spokeswoman teri rizvi said. penalties could range from a token fine to expulsion, she said
the protesters demanded that if university organizations invite the cia to recruit, even off campus, the school should provide a mandatory course for those seeking cia jobs that would detail alleged atrocities committed by the agency
the chief u.s. delegate to the u.n. human rights commission, former cuban political prisoner armando valladares, today rejected cuban allegations that he lied about being mistreated in cuban prisons
they have had a disinformation campaign against me since before i left prison,'' valladares told a news conference
the cuban government wednesday distributed information in geneva, washington and mexico city saying valladares had been a police officer under the batista government and that he had been arrested and jailed in 1961 because he belonged to a terrorist organization
valladares and the u.s. state department deny that he was a police officer, and maintain that he was arrested and sentenced to 30 years in prison for making anti-communist statements
valladares served 22 years of his sentence before being released after the intervention of french president francois mitterrand
since his release, he has spoken out about what he says are human rights violations in cuba, in particular torture and inhumane treatment of prisoners
valladares told the press conference that the cuban government resorted to personal attacks against him because ``they are not able to deny the accusations'' of human rights violations. he spoke in spanish, and his remarks were translated into english
the cuban deputy foreign minister, raul roa kouri, said at a press conference wednesday that valladares was lying when he said he was mistreated in prison
valladares, asked about kouri's statement, showed reporters scars on his hands which he said were from rat bites, and took one reporter's hand and ran it along his head where he said he had a scar from being beaten
the united states on thursday submitted a resolution for the second year in a row attempting to get the commission to examine alleged human rights violations in cuba
this year's resolution appears to be worded more softly than last year's, which was blocked by one vote, and valladares said he was optimistic that it would pass
prime minister yitzhak shamir today urged secretary of state george p. shultz to move slowly on palestinian self-rule in the violence-torn west bank and gaza strip, informed sources said
shamir told shultz at a two-hour meeting that there should be ``a time of testing'' for up to three years before negotiations are held on a final settlement in the occupied territories, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity
shultz also met with foreign minister shimon peres, leader of the liberal faction of israel's coalition government and shamir's political rival
shultz is promoting a u.s. plan that calls for negotiations on an overall settlement by december. but the sources said he applied ``no pressure whatsoever'' on shamir
israeli soldiers today killed two more palestinians in anti-israel protests in the occupied territories, bringing the death toll in 11 weeks of violence to 67
a u.s. official said today that some palestinians have accepted invitations to talk with shultz, despite a palestine liberation organization ban and death threats. the meeting was set for tonight in east jerusalem, which israel captured from jordan in the 1967 war
the official said 15 moderates had been invited, and a few had agreed to come although he declined to specify the number or identify invitees. he spoke on condition of anonymity
shamir later told reporters his session with shultz was ``very friendly and thorough'' and said they discussed ``the aspirations of all of us for getting peace.''
he said he hoped that the end result would be some ``positive outcomes.''
i think there are many openings,'' said peres, who has previously endorsed most elements of shultz's proposals. ``i think there is a great deal of work to be done.''
shultz said he agreed and added: ``as always it is a great benefit to come and have a good long bull session about it all and hear your views that have been very helpful.''
shultz scheduled two more sessions with shamir on sunday after he will have been to jordan and syria to assess arab positions
in the talks today, sources said shamir reiterated his objections to an international peace conference that would assign an active role to the soviet union
shultz told reporters on his way here wednesday from washington that soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze have voiced interest in such a conference in their meetings in moscow. but shultz said it was ``not a way to go for substantive results.''
shamir's position would keep alive the 1978 camp david formula, which calls for a five-year period to see if the palestinians and israelis can live side-by-side
negotiations on a final settlement would begin after the third year. the options would include statehood or linking the west bank and gaza to jordan in a confederation
but, egypt, jordan and several other countries have told the united states that they rejected negotiations based on the formula. the accords produced the 1979 peace treaty between egypt and israel
jordanian prime minister zaid rifai, who will meet with shultz in amman on saturday, said ``we are against any project that deals with partial solutions, a dividing approach or projects that deal with palestinian autonomy.''
autonomy would mean self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians who live in the west bank and gaza, but they would not have control over their security or conduct foreign relations, two key attributes of statehood
shamir aide yossi ahimeir said ``one shouldn't make a dramatization out of this one meeting. it's part of a process that will continue in washington when the prime minister goes there'' in mid-march
prominent palestinian moderates had said they would not meet with shultz tonight because the united states had not fulfilled a plo demand to consult with palestinians living outside israeli-held territories
they said this was an indication the americans were really seeking to create an alternative palestinian leadership to the plo
i told (shultz) i regret i cannot accept because the palestinian people have decided that we have to have a delegation reflecting the true composition of the palestinian people,'' said al faj newspaper editor hanna siniora, who met with shultz earlier this month in washington
the california supreme court has rejected an appeal by environmentalists and removed a major obstacle to drilling for oil below scenic bluffs on the southern california coast
occidental petroleum corp., which first applied for a permit 18 years ago, can begin exploratory drilling within a few months, unless another court intervenes
the (supreme) court now is less environmentally concerned than it used to be,'' charged roger diamond, a lawyer who represented residents of the los angeles neighborhood challenging the drilling
the court thursday denied a hearing on an appeal of a ruling last november that upheld the city's 1985 approval of the drilling project. justice stanley mosk, whose son, richard, is one of occidental's lawyers, did not participate in the supreme court action
occidental is obviously very pleased,'' said arthur groman, senior member of the company's board of directors
this field, which we think may be as much as 60 million barrels of oil, is a vital resource of the united states,'' he said
diamond, in claiming the court had less concern about the environment than it used to, noted that the court had blocked another version of the palisades project in 1974
the lawyer, also a board member of the environmental group in the case, said opponents will ask a los angeles judge next week to block the drilling while a challenge to the project's coastal commission permit is pending
