the treasurer of the united democratic front today became the last leader of south africa's biggest anti-apartheid organization to be silenced by the state
police came to the house of azhar cachalia this morning and served him with an order prohibiting him from speaking to the press and participating in the front's activities
in the east coast city of durban, 14 white women, members of the volunteer civil rights group black sash, were arrested as demonstrations continued against the new restrictions on major black opposition groups
the move against cachalia means that every national executive of the front group, which represents 600 affiliates with 2 million members, is either in jail, in hiding or restricted by the government
at the university of cape town, 2,000 students and staff gathered to protest the new bans. about half marched around the campus carrying banners and singing ``god bless africa,'' which many south african blacks regard as their national anthem
the rev. allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches, told the gathering that nationwide protests against the government's clampdown must begin immediately
leaders of churches, which like most white opposition groups were not targeted by the government's restrictions, already have called for protest services in nations across the country on sunday
the battle has only just begun,'' boesak said. ``we have decided we will resist. our commitment starts right now.''
when the government prohibited the front and 17 other opposition groups from political activity on wednesday, it also issued restrictive orders against 18 senior black leaders, including front presidents archie gumede and albertina sisulu
mrs. sisulu is the wife of imprisoned african national congress leader walter sisulu
about half of the front's leadership is underground. many others are in detention without charge, awaiting trial or on trial in connection with treason charges
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
in cape town, at least one person died and five were injured during a clash between rival black factions in a squatter camp near crossroads
the fighting between militant youths and the management committee of the ktc squatter camp, both considered anti-apartheid groups, broke out at 3 a.m. with gunfire and stone-throwing, residents told journalists. by 7 a.m. 20 shacks had been burned
police reported one dead and two injured, but residents in the part of the camp controlled by the youths said four people were treated at a hospital for injuries. the argus newspaper reported two deaths
the fighting in the camp began last month and hundreds of shacks have been burned in the feuding reminiscent of the may-june 1986 battles in the crossroads-area squatter camps
in that violence, 70,000 people lost their homes and scores of people died in battles between conservative ``vigilantes'' and the squatter-camp groups
but this year the fighting is between two groups who had fought together against the ``vigilantes'' in 1986, and appears to involve an attempt by the militant youths to gain more power in the administration of the squatter camp
police reported three blacks were killed in violence in two natal province towns, where feuding between supporters of the united democratic front and the zulu political organization, inkatha, has steadily spread from the townships surrounding the provincial capital, pietermaritzburg
more than 400 blacks have died in the past year in the natal fighting. down yet</head>
a 19-year-old woman who has spent a record 488 days in a small wooden box perched atop a telephone pole says she'll remain three-stories high for another month to raise $100,000 for cancer research
i'm not sure what's in store for me, but i'm getting pretty excited,'' mellissa l. sanders said an hour before overtaking a canadian's record at 2 p.m. thursday
miss sanders of tucson, ariz., climbed the pole oct. 26, 1986. last week, she rode out 75 mph winds in her swaying box
the 42-square-foot box doesn't quite have all the comforts of home, but it's almost as well-equipped. she regularly runs up $300 telephone bills, watches television and has a hair dresser who makes box calls. she bathes in a children's plastic pool
her stunt has required commitment and sacrifice, she said
i gave up a good job, visiting with friends, driving my car, walking around and all kinds of things for this,'' she said
she plans to remain in the box another month, hoping a local radio station's support will help her raise the money necessary to meet her goal
i've only raised $6,000 so far. it still needs to grab people's attention,'' said miss sanders, whose sister, rebecca, is a cancer patient who has been in remission four years
if people see it's for a good cause and take two minutes to put some money in an envelope, i could make my goal,'' she said, ``i've seen telethons do it in about five minutes.''
even if miss sanders has not attained her goal when she descends on march 24, her mother, mauri rose sanders, says her daughter is a winner
i'm proud enough to burst. i feel like we both did it,'' said mrs. sanders, who broke a similar record in 1959 by sitting 211 days, 9 hours and 33 minutes above another indianapolis corner in a publicity stunt
indianapolis radio station wzpl-fm has joined the sanders' effort, and morning disc jockey steve stiles says he expects next month's live broadcasts and other planned activities to put the fund-raiser closer to her target
mellissa's commitment has never wavered, but people weren't paying any attention,'' said stiles, who climbed the pole to visit her thursday afternoon
a new law requiring consent of parents or a judge for an unmarried woman under 18 to have an abortion has been effectively blocked from being enforced this year by a ruling of the state supreme court
the law, sponsored by anti-abortion groups, had been barred from taking effect jan. 1 by a judge's order in response to a lawsuit by doctors and family-planning organizations
on thursday, the high court denied the state's request to lift that order in a unanimous decision
the law would make it a crime for a doctor to perform an abortion on an unmarried woman under 18, living at home, who did not have written consent from one parent. as an alternative, the minor could get a ruling from a judge that the abortion was in her best interest or that she was mature enough to make the decision on her own
many other states have similar laws
the lawsuit, filed by medical and family planning organizations, contends the law violates the right to privacy under the state constitution by restricting minors' ability to decide whether to give birth or have an abortion
some minors would be intimidated into bearing unwanted children and others would be delayed in getting abortions, increasing the medical danger, the suit said
the constitutional dispute is far from resolved and could return to the supreme court at a later date. but lawyers in the case say the next legal action is likely to be at least a year away, either in appellate court proceedings or in a superior court trial
until then, minors ``can continue to obtain the health services, including abortions, that they need without the necessity for consent of a third party,'' said abigail english of the national center for youth law, one of the lawyers who filed suit
state officials say some 34,000 women under 18 had abortions in 1985, the latest figures available. under the old law, which remains in effect, a woman of any age can consent to an abortion as long as her doctor concludes she understands the procedure and is consenting voluntarily
attorney general john van de kamp, who personally supports abortion rights but as the state's top law enforcement officer is the lead defendant in the suit, had a low-key response to the court's action, his office said
we don't see this as a significant ruling on the overall merits of the litigation,'' said deputy attorney general allen ashby, press spokesman for van de kamp, who said the attorney general would proceed with an appeal
the state supreme court has permanently removed six judges and barred two others from completing their elected terms because they took cash gifts ranging from $200 to $500 from a union leader
a year ago, the eight judges were suspended from the bench after the allegations of taking cash surfaced during an fbi racketeering investigation of the roofers union
chief justice robert n.c. nix jr. said taking cash from the union affected the judges' impartiality and ordered that the judges' salaries, roughly $80,000 a year, cease immediately
only one judge denied receiving the cash; the others said they considered the money a gift, not a bribe
the judges had collected their salaries and benefits while the pennsylvania judicial inquiry and review board considered the cases. last august, the board recommended removal from the bench
the pennsylvania supreme court, holding that ``a public trust has been betrayed,'' concurred unanimously thursday in a 43-page opinion
district attorney ronald castille hailed the decision
it is a strong message to judges everywhere that this kind of conduct is totally inappropriate. this is an important first step in rebuilding the citizen's confidence (to) get justice back in city hall,'' he said
mark a. aronchick, a lawyer for common pleas judge mary rose fante cunningham who was permanently removed from the bench, said cunningham was ``just saddened about the whole thing.''
james c. schwartzman, a lawyer for common pleas judge michael wallace who was permanently removed, said the penalty was far too severe
stephen p. gallagher, a lawyer for municipal judge thomas dempsey who was barred from completing his term, said he had not talked with his client, ``but i'm sure he'll be unhappy.''
and charles cunningham, a lawyer for common pleas judge william porter who was barred for the rest of his term, said the court had drawn a ``significant distinction'' with its sentence for porter and dempsey, since they will be allowed to try to return to the bench in the future
the case and other bribery scandals, in which three judges have been convicted, have rocked the philadelphia court system in the past year
six other judges, also suspended last year, are under investigation
the eight judges were accused of accepting $200 to $500 from 1983 to 1985 from stephen traitz jr., former leader of roofers union local 30-30b
traitz and 18 other union members were convicted last year of extortion and bribery. they had been accused of trying to bribe more than 50 public officials
the national collegiate athletic association's drug testing program does not violate a student's privacy rights, a federal judge has ruled
u.s. district judge walter mcgovern's decision thursday also upheld the university of washington's right to enforce the drug test program
on the lawsuit brought by cross country and track athlete betsy o'halloran, 19, mcgovern said, ``the invasion of her privacy interest by the specimen collection procedures of the drug-testing program is outweighed'' by the ncaa's interest in protecting student athletes' health, reducing temptations to use drugs and ensuring fair competitions
i think the decision is correct in all particulars and accurately stated the law,'' said jack kitchin, a lawyer for the ncaa in kansas city, mo
the american civil liberties union, which filed the suit on behalf of o'halloran and another athlete who later joined the case, will likely appeal to the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals, said kathleen taylor of the aclu
it's a defeat in a way,'' o'halloran said. ``but i think we've got a great chance in the 9th circuit. i really don't think his arguments are very good.''
o'halloran initially filed suit against the university for its mandatory drug testing program, and a king county superior court judge ruled in july that the university program was a violation of both state and u.s. constitutional privacy rights
but that oral ruling was never formally entered, and the ncaa was ordered to be a defendant in the case, which was then moved to federal court
last month, the university of washington dropped the mandatory aspect of its drug testing program, revising it so that testing was voluntary and required only for those athletes suspected of drug use
the claim against the university program was then dismissed, with the claim against the ncaa program and the university's participation in it remaining
uw athletes are still required to sign a drug testing consent form required by the ncaa. mike lude, the university's athletic director, said o'halloran would be welcomed back if she complies with the ncaa rules and signs a consent form
i will not do that,'' o'halloran said thursday night
under ncaa rules, students must consent to be tested before regular season competition begins, although the random testing would not occur until post-season playoff time
students who refuse to sign are prohibited from regular season competition
o'halloran asked mcgovern to grant her a preliminary injunction allowing her to compete for the women's track team this spring
but mcgovern denied her request, saying any harm done to her by being barred from competition was outweighed by the potentially greater harm to the ncaa if its ``effective regulation of intercollegiate athletics was to be impaired.''
the shiite moslem amal militia today dismissed its security chief in a rift in the forces searching for kidnapped u.s. marine lt. col. william r. higgins in south lebanon
ousted security chief mustafa dirani issued a statement that made no mention of his dismissal, but claimed that higgins and other united nations peacekeeping officials in lebanon were paid by nato to gather information about terrorists
amal said in a terse statement that dirani was ``relieved from his responsibility as head of the central security system.'' it did not elaborate
higgins, 43, was abducted feb. 17 near tyre, 50 miles south of beirut. higgins headed an observer group assigned to the united nations interim force in lebanon, a peacekeeping force in south lebanon
the pro-iranian organization of the oppressed on earth claimed it abducted higgins and alleged he was a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the accusation
higgins is one of nine americans among 25 foreigners missing and believed kidnapped in lebanon
regarding the american officer, i would like to stress that we have confirmed information that nato is seeking to confront what it calls terrorism ... by forming security systems specialized in lebanon to gather information in preparation for acts of piracy in the future,'' dirani said
for this purpose, nato uses some u.n. officers and some unifil officers,'' he said in the handwritten statement
dirani criticized amal for seizing members of the fundamentalist iranian-backed hezbollah, or party of god, in south lebanon during the dragnet for higgins. amal is fighting the iranian-backed hezbollah for control of south lebanon. tyre is an amal stronghold
we denounce the security arrangements that followed the abduction of the american officer,'' dirani said
amal's military commander in tyre, daoud daoud, has been leading a massive search for higgins. his militiamen have rounded up at least 42 hezbollah members
daoud told reporters today that ``we believe higgins is still in the south.'' he made no comment on dirani's allegations
an amal spokesman in beirut said lebanon's senior shiite cleric, sheik mohammed mehdi shamseddine, is involved ``in a quiet effort to release higgins.'' he refused to elaborate and spoke on condition he not be identified
hezbollah, made up of shiite zealots loyal to iran's ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella for pro-iranian factions holding most of the 25 missing foreigners
amal, the main shiite militia led by justice minister nabih berri, is more secular and is backed by syria, the main power broker in lebanon. the two shiite factions have been vying for control of south lebanon
