the nation's roman catholic bishops, who have been asked to make special efforts to help whittle down the vatican's annual budget deficit, have released new detail on the church's worldwide expenses
the record 1986 deficit of $56.7 million included spending of $114 million and income of $57.3 million, said a statement sent to u.s. bishops for use in making fund-raising appeals in their areas. the statement was released thursday
the picture for 1987 looked better at the time church leaders met in rome to discuss the situation last october, according to an accompanying letter to u.s. bishops from leading cardinals
contributions were up for the first nine months of 1987, totaling $35.8 million compared with $32 million for the same period of 1986, said the letter, which was signed by 10 cardinals, including john krol of philadelphia and john o'connor of new york
the letter spoke of ``a heartening response'' to earlier appeals, but it also said the bishops were ``once more invited to continue their generous efforts to make the faithful aware of the holy see's economic problems.''
the biggest 1986 expense by far was for personnel _ $57.9 million, including $50.6 million to pay the vatican's 2,315 employees and $7.3 million in pension payments to 885 retired people
the vatican statement said the next largest expense was $11.7 million for publishing activities, followed by $11 million for expenses on investments
the investment expenses, including management of vatican investments and interest paid to depositors in vatican accounts, left a net income on investments of $17.8 million when deducted from gross investment income of $28.8 million
other expenses included:
_$10.4 million for vatican radio, including $3.9 million for operating costs and $6.5 million for modernization of equipment
_$9.7 million for administrative expenses, ``from the most elementary ones (stationery and printing supplies) to the most complex (consultencies of all sorts).''
_$9.6 million for depreciation and restoration of endowment funds, to help cover the previous year's deficit and to deal with inflation
_$2.1 million for electricity, water, heating and other utilities
_$1.6 million for maintenance work on office buildings and taxes on rented buildings
as for vatican income, investment income was the largest item at $28.8 million, followed by $17.1 million from publishing activities and lesser amounts from other activities
the vatican has been in the red every year since 1979, when it first made financial details public. the deficit at that time was about $20 million
classes were canceled today for nearly 73,000 pupils in ohio's largest school district after teachers rejected a contract offer and set up picket lines
talks were scheduled to resume at 1 p.m. today, according to federal mediator jack buettner
principals and administrative staff will reopen four high schools monday for 3,600 seniors, superintendent alfred tutela said. teachers had planned to strike thursday, but the district declared a snow day and closed all buildings
school officials and cleveland teachers union members declined to discuss the school board's latest offer, which was made at 6:30 a.m. thursday after two days of negotiations
at a regularly scheduled school board meeting thursday evening, mildred madison, board president, said she believed the board had made a fair offer
more than 100 students and teachers attended the meeting, and many were unhappy over negotiating efforts by school officials
it's the students who really need the education here,'' reubin fitzhugh, a senior at cleveland's aviation high school, told the board. ``you have your education. why can't we have ours?''
the school board reportedly has dropped its demand that a mandatory career ladder system be included in the new contract, leaving wages as the major unresolved issue. a career ladder system would have linked teacher advancement and pay raises to performance evaluations
the school board initially offered a one-time 2 percent bonus payment, with further raises contingent on passage of a tax levy. union president eugene kolach said the board had revised its offer to a 2 percent raise retroactive to september, and another 1 percent raise retroactive to jan. 1. a pay raise in the second year would be linked to a levy approval
beginning cleveland teachers are paid $17,600 a year. the average teacher makes $29,000 annually and the highest paid teacher makes just more than $34,600. of the 5,093 union members, 2,559 are classroom teachers
the last teachers strike in the district lasted 11 weeks in 1979
a soldier of fortune magazine ad, subject of a negligence suit that seeks millions of dollars in damages, does not fall under first amendment protection because the ad represents a commercial form of speech, a federal judge says
u.s. district judge david hittner issued the written opinion thursday, elaborating on a pre-trial decision that refused to dismiss the $22.5 million suit filed against the magazine by the family of a texas woman slain in 1985
in an eight-page decision, hittner cited several federal rulings that allowed negligence suits where commercial speech was the issue
according to the judge, the magazine acknowledges that the ad fell into the realm of commercial speech and to allow dismissal of the suit under first amendment grounds ``would afford to commercial speech a broader protection than that given core speech.''
gary black, 18, and marjorie einmann, 64, are suing the self-styled ``journal for professional adventurers'' for running a classified ad that led to the killing of sandra black, gary black's mother and mrs. einmann's daughter
robert black is on texas' death row for paying john wayne hearn $10,000 to kill his wife at her bryan home in february 1985. hearn is serving three life terms in florida for the black slaying and two others in that state
hearn's ad appeared in four issues of the magazine in late 1984, offering services of former marine and vietnam veterans and weapons specialists with jungle warfare expertise for ``high-risk assignments'' in the united states or overseas
attorneys for the magazine do not dispute that the ad brought hearn and black together, but insist that soldier of fortune publisher robert brown had no way of knowing the ad was for illegal activity. brown has testified he would have halted the classified ads for personal services if he had known they were linked to crimes
brown, publisher and founder of the boulder, colo.-based magazine, was expected to return to the stand today as the trial completed a second week. he was called last week as an adverse witness for the plaintiffs and his attorneys reserved cross-examination until later
a former top editor at the magazine testified thursday he favored elimination of classified ads from the publication because they were journalistically unprofessional
william guthrie, now a free-lance writer living in idaho, said the ads continued despite his objections because brown thought they lent an air of mystique to the publication
certain kinds of classified ads appeared to trivialize the magazine,'' said guthrie, who was executive editor before leaving in 1986. ``if soldier of fortune was trying to look like a legitimate military news magazine, to have ads for brass knuckles and so forth seemed inappropriate.''
guthrie said he was not aware that any of the ads may have been linked to criminal activity
a judge dropped contempt-of-court citations against 34 firefighters, but ordered their union to pay a $25,000 fine for a three-day sickout
the president of the union thursday read a letter of apology to the court for not doing more to comply with a back-to-work order issued on the first day of the sickout that eventually involved 110 firefighters
leo j. miller, the president of local 799 of the international association of firefighters, also promised to ``monitor all sick leave that appears to be excessive'' in the future
later, miller said the apology was not an admission that firefighters had participated in any type of job action. job actions by municipal employees are illegal under rhode island law
superior court judge americo campanella told miller he was fining the union ``in order to impress upon you ... the importance of a court order.''
the 34 firefighters failed to appear before campanella on monday afternoon, after they were served notice by the city to appear in court
city labor lawyer vincent ragosta jr. said he was pleased with the ruling, but said the city will press a civil suit to recover $100,000 spent on overtime during the sickout. the fire department kept its night shift on duty throughout the sickout; no major fires occurred during the three days
the city said the firefighters called in sick _ 50 out of 51 on saturday and all 60 on sunday _ to protest what they believed were unilateral changes made in their contract by the city. the walkout ended tuesday
the city has yet to sign the agreement ratified by the union in december, though it has been honoring wage and benefit increases
the dispute, according to fire chief michael f. moise, concerned the union's insistence that rescue truck crews have the highest level of emergency medical technician training
an honors student was fatally stabbed by two teen-agers after a quarrel over a girl, but before the victim died he was able to warn a brother and call his girlfriend, police reported
after the stabbing he called his girlfriend and said, `i probably won't be seeing you again,''' said madison county sheriff bob churchich
christopher a. mcdonald, 18, also was able to tell his father what had happened and to identify his assailants before he died a short time later wednesday at anderson hospital in maryville, police said. an autopsy found he had been stabbed in the chest and the abdomen
the boy's father, gary mcdonald, said his son had been visited a few days earlier by a girl who apparently was a friend of one of the suspects
the elder mcdonald told police that christopher and his 12-year-old brother were home alone when the quarrel and attack occurred. christopher had been on the first floor and the younger brother was upstairs, he said
they threatened to kill our family, but chris stood up to them, and they stabbed him to death,'' gary mcdonald told the st. louis post-dispatch
the younger brother did not hear the fight, but christopher was able to stagger upstairs and warn him to lock his bedroom door, mcdonald said
he said he was returning home when the suspects' car sped out of the driveway ``and almost hit me.''
alec macdonald, 17, of rural edwardsville, and dennis m. miller, 16, of rural worden, were charged thursday with first-degree murder, home invasion and armed violence, said assistant state's attorney randy massey
authorities refused to say which suspect was believed to have stabbed christopher or whether the weapon had been recovered
outnumbered senate republicans held ranks today, scuttling a last-ditch democratic attempt to force a vote on a divisive campaign finance package that kept lawmakers talking for 53 straight hours
the gop victory, capping a sometimes bitter filibuster that included the parliamentary arrest of sen. robert packwood, r-ore., came as the senate voted 53-41 not to invoke cloture, which would have cut off debate and brought the legislation to a vote the majority democrats would win
the cloture attempt failed because at least 60 senators must agree to force a vote. it was the eighth time since june that majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., had lost a cloture motion on campaign spending
the defeat seemingly doomed any chance of congress passing the democratic plan this year to impose voluntary spending limits for senate campaigns. but byrd left the door ajar
we will revisit the issue in one form or another,'' he said before the vote. ``it's not going to go away.''
acting minority leader alan simpson, r-wyo., said the republicans would be waiting
there will be other proposals like this. when they come up, they will be dealt with like this,'' simpson said
this week's struggle centered on a plan advanced by 52 senators, including republicans robert stafford of vermont and john chafee of rhode island, to attack the escalating cost of campaigns by imposing spending limits
limits for a senate general election race would range from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population. in 1986, the average campaign cost $3 million _ up fivefold from 1976 _ with some big state races topping $10 million per candidate
sen. david boren, d-okla., one of the bill's authors, said that to build a $3 million warchest, a senator must raise $10,000 every week from the time he or she arrives in washington until the end of the six-year term
a candidate observing the limit would be eligible for subsidized mailings, rock-bottom radio and tv ad rates and money from the treasury if the opponent exceeded the limit or the candidate was the target of heavy spending by independent groups
the legislation also takes aim at the increasing role of special-interest political action committees, which in 1986 provided over half the campaign money raised by more than 200 house and senate candidates, most of them incumbents. under the plan, pacs could supply no more than 20 percent of the candidate's spending limit
except for stafford and chafee, republicans are having no part of the proposal, which they say would favor democrats and doom them to continued minority status in heavily democratic states, particularly in the south
sen. warren rudman, r-n.h., calls it ``the incumbent protection act'' because, he said, it would hamper challengers with little name recognition or financial resources
everyone in politics knows that with these limits, what we absolutely say to most challengers is, `you've had it,''' rudman said
democrats rejected this argument, saying that the real question was the public perception of senators scurrying for contributions to fuel increasingly expensive campaigns
we have to spend our time running around the country looking for a handout,'' byrd said. ``how can we blame anyone from perceiving us as corrupt? the system is corrupt and we're trying to reform it
the senate should not be owned by an aristocracy of money,'' he said. ``campaign reform gives the little guy an equal share. ... this business of the golden handshake _ nobody likes it. senators don't want to spend all their time going from fund-raiser to fund-raiser with their hand out begging for money.''
republicans were forced into the filibuster at 2 p.m. tuesday when byrd placed the legislation before the senate. within 12 hours, things turned bitter with the parliamentary arrest of sen. robert packwood, r-ore
acting on the orders of democrats, capitol police pushed into his office and carried him feet-first into the chamber, giving byrd the quorum _ at least 51 present members _ he needed to keep the filibuster going
republicans talked of ``banana republic'' tactics. byrd called them ``crybabies'' and castigated them for deserting the chamber en masse in an effort to abort the talkathon
this was a calculated effort to obstruct the senate from doing its work,'' byrd said. ``i was forced to do it (order arrests) to get a majority of the senate present so the senate could do its business.''
byrd forced the filibuster in an effort to get the gop to negotiate. republicans said they were willing to talk about curbing pac money, but they steadfastly drew the line at spending limits
at the start of the filibuster, byrd said he was ready to keep the senate in continuous session through the end of next week
but by midnight wednesday, he and gop leaders had agreed to end the siege thursday evening, let everyone get a night's sleep and return for today's cloture vote
a top uaw official says he will give local unions permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis in an attempt to discourage the company from selling its $1 billion parts-making subsidiary
more than 1,000 angry workers massed outside chrysler headquarters in 20-degree temperatures thursday chanting ``strike! strike!'' to protest the proposed sale of acustar inc., which employs 28,000 workers and represents nearly a fifth of chrysler's worldwide operations
you do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,'' uaw vice president marc stepp told the demonstrators. the rally followed a special meeting of the 140-delegate chrysler bargaining council representing the company's 49 uaw locals
although the union can't legally call a national strike against chrysler over acustar, stepp said he will give local uaw unions permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved issues such as health-and-safety grievances
a series of local strikes at key chrysler plants could shut down the company nationwide
at least seven chrysler locals have voted to seek strike authorization and one, a key 4,000-worker stamping plant in sterling heights, should receive authorization as early as next week, stepp predicted
stepp said the possible acustar sale, which chrysler chairman lee iacocca confirmed in early february, threatens the jobs of all chrysler workers by weakening their bargaining power and reducing work opportunities within the corporation
the council unanimously passed a resolution calling for suspension of all joint labor-management programs that require trust and cooperation, including special team-concept agreements at six plants, unless chrysler decides not to sell acustar
chrysler has begun implementing the so-called modern operating agreements at plants in huntsville, ala., and in indianapolis and newcastle, ind
local union leaders said they immediately will stop attending labor-management plant meetings
similar agreements, in which workers share tasks as part of a team, have not yet taken effect at plants in detroit; newark, del.; and trenton, n.j., stepp said
chrysler has said it may sell acustar because it doesn't want to invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. chrysler already buys 70 percent of its parts from outside sources
workers say they are angry at the possible sale because they made concessions and helped iacocca win loan guarantees from the federal government to rescue the company from the verge of bankruptcy at the beginning of the decade
stepp will lead negotiations with chrysler this summer to replace its contract, which expires sept. 14. stepp said chrysler already has made talks more difficult with its announcement last month that it will close its assembly plant in kenosha, wis., by the end of the year
passengers aboard cruise ships that have passed federal sanitation inspections are less likely to suffer diarrhea during their vacations, federal health officials said
travelers ought to be aware that these are very tough inspections, far tougher than the usual restaurant inspections done ashore,'' said dr. vernon houk, director of the national centers for disease control's center for environmental health
but houk cautioned against reading too much into the inspection reports
the individual traveler should not look at a single inspection report and make that the determinant whether he'll travel on that ship or not,'' he said. ``it seems to me the useful question is, `what is the past history of this ship?'''
cdc researchers said thursday that ``ships that consistently have the highest sanitation scores are less likely to have an outbreak of diarrheal disease than ships with lower average scores.''
on the average, for every 10 million passenger-days _ one passenger, sailing one day _ fewer than two of the ships scoring in the top 20 percent reported diarrhea outbreaks between 1975, when the sanitation program began, and 1985
that compares with outbreaks aboard more than eight of the ships scoring in the bottom 20 percent, the cdc said
the cdc considers an outbreak in progress if 3 percent of the passengers and crew are ill. sanitation inspections monitor water quality, food storage and preparation, potential for food contamination, cleanliness and other matters
the cdc has no power to block a ship from sailing, but does distribute the results of its inspections
the agency also said the percentage of ships passing inspection rose dramatically over the program's first decade, while the number of intestinal illness outbreaks among passengers declined
in 1975, cruise ships reported 7.7 outbreaks of diarrhea for every million passenger-days sailed, houk said. by 1985, the figure dropped to 2.7 outbreaks
this has been a cooperative effort between us and the cruise ship industry, and ... (the study) clearly shows it has been working,'' houk said. ``things are going in the right direction.''
u.s. treasury secretary james a. baker iii said today that he called on the government here to speed up appreciation of its currency to help reduce the growing u.s. trade deficit with south korea
baker said he also discussed other trade issues, including the lifting of a ban on imports of u.s. beef, an easing of restrictions on american cigarettes and protection of u.s. intellectual property rights
baker, who visited south korea for president roh tae-woo's inauguration, said in an airport news conference before leaving that his talks with south korean officials were friendly and useful
baker said south korea's currency, the won, was undervalued against the dollar, but did not say how much it should be revalued. a higher value for the won would make south korean products more expensive and less competitive overseas
south korean officials said baker pointed out that the won's appreciation has been slower than that of the japanese yen and taiwanese dollar, which both gained close to 30 percent against the u.s. dollar last year. the won rose only 8.7 percent
finance ministry officials said they told baker that south korea would actively adjust the won's value by taking into account the value of the dollar on international money markets and the impact on domestic industries
local newspapers reported that baker asked for a 15 percent to 20 percent rise in the won and for south korea to open its stock market to foreign investors
baker said that ``problems have developed that need to be addressed in a spirit of cooperation by the two countries.''
he said the u.s. trade deficit with south korea grew 39 percent last year following a 57 percent increase in 1986, and that it was approximately equal to south korea's entire current account surplus, which hit a record $9.78 billion last year
he said the united states should be given more access to the south korean market because while the u.s. market ``is nearly completely open to korean goods, some of our exporters experience serious impediments to their access to the korean market.'' he cited high tariffs, other trade barriers and an undervalued exchange rate. update with fort sill comment on fatalities and injured from that base, id of dead, later hospital conditions for three men. pickup 18th graf `fort hood...'</note>
an army helicopter nosedived into a cow pasture and skidded about 75 feet before it broke apart in a sheet of fire, killing 10 men and seriously burning eight others, authorities and witnesses said
two soldiers leaped about 35 feet to the ground from the burning twin-rotor ch-47d chinook before it crashed about 50 miles from fort worth on thursday, said state department of public safety sgt. robert rankin. one of the soldiers died
the other soldier said that a fire had broken out at the back of the helicopter based at fort sill, okla., and that those aboard had tried to move to the front to get away from the flames, rankin said
residents raced to the scene, pulling casualties away from the raging grass fire sparked by the crash
some of them were just sitting there screaming,'' said 17-year-old dale christopher, a chico high school student who was among the first on the scene. ``and they kept asking us `help us. help us.' and then we'd say `help is on the way.' that's all we could do for them.''
a three-person team of investigators from the army safety center at fort rucker, ala., was investigating the crash today
the chinook ch-47d has a history of problems and the army grounded its entire fleet of 63 of the big transport helicopters for 1{ months in 1985 after an accident in honduras injured eight soldiers
witnesses said the helicopter was tilted forward at a 45-degree angle, puffing smoke and descending rapidly when it crashed about 3:29 p.m., slicing through a power line
all of a sudden a little thin streak of smoke came out of it and there was a small explosion on the right side underneath it,'' said joe haworth, who was working at a nearby plant. ``then it put out a little more smoke and it flew straight for a ways, then parts went to coming out of it.''
the craft skidded about 75 feet before breaking apart in a sheet of fire, said wendell berry sr., 53, who watched the accident from his home a half-mile away
berry cut the seat belt away from a crewman strapped to the remains of the cockpit
there was only one guy still in the helicopter who was either the pilot or the co-pilot, and he was conscious,'' berry said. ``he was so conscious that when i cut his seatbelt he said, `that feels better _ thanks.'''
jack souther, 54, used a small fire extinguisher from his pickup truck to douse burning bodies. ``the only thing i could do was put the fires out on the bodies. i went from body to body trying to put them out,'' he said
the copter, carrying 13 passengers and five crew members, was returning to fort sill from fort hood in central texas, fort sill spokesman rick brink said
fort sill officials said today that two pilots and a flight engineer from the post were among the 10 killed, and that two of the injured were also from fort sill
fort sill spokesman richard brown identified the three dead as staff sgt. raymond t. hill, 31, of new baltimore, mich.; chief warrant officer 4 ronald w. bender, 40, of rockville center, n.y., and chief warrant officer 4 scott j. temple, 43, of irving, texas. bender was the command pilot and temple was a pilot. hill was a flight engineer
of the 10 dead, six died at the scene, one died in parkland hospital in dallas, one died in bridgeport hospital and another died early today at brooke army medical center in san antonio. another soldier was found dead at the crash site after dark thursday
three soldiers remained hospitalized at parkland memorial hospital this morning, one of them in critical condition with skull fractures and lacerations on his thigh, said spokesman tom geddie. a second was in fair condition with a hip fracture and a third was in good condition with a broken leg and cuts on his face
four soldiers who had been initially taken to parkland late thursday were moved to brooke army medical center in san antonio, but one died shortly after arrival, a spokesman said today
fort hood soldiers paul stroud and calvin turner were in serious condition at harris methodist hospital in fort worth early today, said spokeswoman mandy goad
the ch-47d, which has a troop capacity of 44, is a modernized version of earlier models of the chinook, which was used in vietnam
in the honduras accident, a transmission bearing failed on a ch-47d taxiing to a refueling depot. the failure caused one of the copter's main rotors to stop turning; the other rotor began hitting it and the helicopter tore itself apart
the chinook's main rotors mesh as they turn, and therefore must be synchronized. up 3rd graf pvs, a poll</note>
vice president george bush, during a campaign stop here, said the united states should do ``whatever is necessary, including military force'' to protect american interests in panama
bush stopped short of calling for military intervention in panama in the wake of the ouster of president eric arturo delvalle, saying that the united states' past history of intervention in latin american affairs is ``what's hurting us in some areas now.''
he told the south carolina press association: ``we will do whatever is necessary to protect american interests in panama. we've got treaty interests on the (panama) canal. i don't want to rattle any sabers. ..
but we would obviously as the united states, and i would, reserve the right to do whatever is necessary, including military force, to protect america's sacred interest in that region of the world.''
the vice president, given a strong south carolina lead in a poll published today, was heading for atlanta after a day of campaigning thursday in south carolina, whose republican presidential primary is saturday, march 5
a poll by the charlotte observer indicated bush was the favorite in the state's gop contest, with the support of 41 percent of those likely to vote in the primary
sen. bob dole trailed with 29 percent; former television evangelist pat robertson had 13 percent; and rep. jack kemp had 4 percent. twelve percent were undecided
on thursday, bush seemed to be confidently raising the stakes as he declared, ``south carolina is going to stand alone as the forerunner of who is going to be president, in my view.''
bush traveled by motorcade through the state's northwestern corner, stopping at colleges, technical schools, a high school, popular restaurants and a sidewalk crowd in nearby greenwood
at one of his first stops, bush addressed head-on the issue of the region's major textile industry and the calls by its leaders for limits on foreign imports. textile leaders contend the industry has been damaged by cheap imports and they want legislation imposing limits on foreign products brought into the united states
bush referred to that as a ``pure, all-out'' protectionist policy that may cost three other jobs while saving one. he said existing trade laws are adequate if enforced
that's not the answer,'' bush said. ``the answer is, we can compete if the playing field is level. i will enforce the laws. i will guarantee you that there is every effort made towards fair trade.''
a day earlier rival bob dole campaigned in the state and pledged to support the legislation in the senate _ similar to legislation that president reagan vetoed over textile-state objections two years ago
bush argued that south carolina's economy has been growing and pointed to figures he said show 62,000 new jobs were created in the state last year, including 2,700 in textiles. he contended currency differences with japan are improving and that manufacturing and agricultural imports have climbed recently
we're seeing improvement out there,'' he said
bush cited evidence of economic improvement at most every stop but didn't repeat his opposition to the textile import limits until asked. ``there have got to be some changes before i'd be for it,'' he said
bush rode in his armored limo for most of the day but spent one leg of the trip on a bus with about 40 active supporters from the area
he said that dole's endorsement by sen. strom thurmond ``makes the stakes higher for dole'' in south carolina. thurmond, however, didn't provide enough help to make a difference for his gop primary favorite eight years ago _ texan john connally
bush was accompanied by south carolina gov. carroll a. campbell jr., his state chairman, and national campaign manager lee atwater, a native south carolinian
atwater attached much significance to the state's primary even while arguing bush could withstand a loss here. he said that if robertson fails to beat bush in south carolina he won't win a single state
and atwater said if dole finishes third in south carolina, ``i think he's going to lose every single state on super tuesday'' when 20 states including all the rest of the south hold primaries
the observer's poll, conducted by the newspaper's market research division, surveyed 687 registered voters who indicated they were likely to participate in the primary. the margin of error is 4 percentage points, the newspaper said. to update with gang attack elsewhere.</note>
a member of a street gang opened fire at a member of a rival gang on a crowded city bus, seriously wounding the 15-year-old boy and three other teen-agers, police said
this is every day,'' bystander mary james said at the scene of the shooting spree thursday afternoon. ``i wouldn't mind seeing the national guard around here.''
witnesses aboard the packed southern california rapid transit district bus said two teens on the bus asked passengers if they were members of a rival gang, said police lt. joseph freia
the passengers said they weren't, but one of the two youths pointed to another teen-ager and identified him as a rival gang member, freia said
the youth singled out then pulled a .45-caliber pistol from his waistband and shot the challenger in the chest, said police lt. bruce hagerty
he fired at random and wounded three other 15-year-old boys before he fled on foot into the south central los angeles neighborhood, police said. a search of the neighborhood turned up no suspects, police said
the shooting occurred in an area of the city that is plagued by gang violence and drug dealing. more than 300 gang-related killings occurred in los angeles county last year, many of them in the neighborhoods of south central
on the north side of the city, a man was stabbed in the neck late thursday when he drove his pickup into a residential neighborhood just as a fight between 25 to 50 alleged gang members broke up, said police lt. don brown
a couple of gang members jumped in the back of his truck'' and rode for about half a block, brown said. when the victim stopped his truck, one pulled out a knife and stabbed him in the neck, narrowly missing his jugular vein, officials said. the victim was in stable condition today. no one was arrested
the street violence stirred up political tensions in the city after a 27-year-old long beach woman was gunned down by gangs in the trendy westwood area last month
police chief daryl gates deployed more officers to the area, prompting complaints by residents of the gang-plagued poorer neighborhoods that they don't receive the same attention
