a construction crew working on the grounds of a plutonium-refining plant found an unexploded world war ii bomb in a load of soil they had just dumped onto a truck, officials said
explosives experts safely disarmed the 110-pound u.s.-made bomb after moving it to a wooded area, said christiane kohl, spokeswoman for the hesse state environment ministry
the crew was digging the foundation for a new building at the alkem nuclear-reprocessing facility in hanau, 12 miles east of frankfurt, she said
the excavator's metal shovel scooped up a chunk of earth ``and loaded it onto a truck,'' she said, and the crew then noticed the bomb amid the dirt
work at the scene was halted and police and atomic safety officials were informed, an alkem statement said
detonation experts said there would have been no danger to stored nuclear materials had the bomb gone off'' because of the way the facilities at alkem are constructed, ms. kohl said
the bomb was unearthed about 80 yards from production buildings at the reprocessing facility, she said
manfred popp, state secretary for the hesse environment ministry, said experts will search the grounds for more ordnances before work resumes
the alkem nuclear facility produces radioactive fuel rods for nuclear power plants.   
consumer prices rose a moderate 0.3 percent in january, about the same rate of inflation as through 1987, but a large decline in energy costs cloaked hefty increases in many other areas, the government reported friday
the january increase in the labor department's consumer price index followed a revised december increase of 0.2 percent. the december rise initially been reported as 0.1 percent
the advance was equivalent to an annual inflation rate of 4.2 percent, according to department analysts. that compares to the 4.4 percent actual rate of inflation posted for 1987 and is also in line with the reagan administration's projection of 4.3 percent inflation for 1988
but, while most analysts do not see a major acceleration of inflation this year, january's figures showed particularly steep increases in the category of services
medical care services rose 0.8 percent, its steepest increase in two years. the cost of hospital rooms was up 1.2 percent, physicians' bills were up 1.0 percent
rent costs rose 1.1 per cent, auto insurance prices were up 1.5 percent and entertaintment costs rose 0.9 percent
analysts said that many of the price increases may reflect one-time-only increases timed to coincide with the beginning of the year
but donald ratajczak, a georgia state university economist who specializes in price activity, called the report ``a bit worrisome.''
we didn't expect that much of a rise in services,'' he said. ``it does appear that there was some aggressive pricing going on in january. we should see some calming in february.''
in another economic reports friday:
_the commerce department said americans' personal incomes and consumer spending both rose at moderate rates of 0.3 percent in january, less than half the 0.7 gains both posted in december. economists expect weakening consumer spending this year as the economy slows down
_a real estate trade group said sales of existing homes fell 3.6 percent in january, the third consecutive monthly decline. the national association of realtors said that sales of existing single-family homes were at their slowest pace since june 1985
january's consumer inflation level would have been higher had it not been for the second consecutive monthly decline in energy costs
in fact, subtracting the usually volatile food and energy categories, consumer prices for all other goods and services rose a sharp 0.5 percent in january _ equivalent to about a 6 percent annual inflation rate _ after a 0.2 percent increase in this category in december
overall, energy prices fell 0.7 percent in january after a 0.8 percent drop in december
gasoline prices fell 1.6 percent, heating oil costs were down 0.8 percent, natural gas prices dropped 0.1 percent and electricity charges were down 0.3 percent
food prices, meanwhile, rose but not as much as they had in the previous month _ up 0.3 percent after december's 0.6 percent gain
overall, grocery prices were up 0.2 percent while restaurant meal costs climbed 0.3 percent. after climbing sharply through the fall, the index for fruits and vegetables fell 0.4 percent last month. beef prices were down 1.4 percent, pork prices fell 0.5 percent
poultry prices, however, climbed 1.0 percent while cereal and bakery products rose 1.1 percent
although import prices have been rising recently under the pressure of a weaker u.s. dollar, the january price report did not show much evidence of dollar-related inflation
and, despite the surge in service prices in january, most economists stuck to their predictions of relatively little price acceleration for 1988
there were a lot of price increases that come at the first of the year, but i'm not overly alarmed,'' said lawrence chimerine, chairman of the wefa group, a philadelphia-area forecasting service
services are clearly a major source of inflation. but i think that in the months to come, we'll see less inflation from services and more from import price increases,'' chimerine added
the labor department gave these other specifics of january price behavior
_new automobile prices were down 0.2 percent; used automobile prices fell 0.1 percent
_housing expenses were up 0.4 percent
_apparel costs gained 0.1 percent
_tobacco products rose 2.8 percent
january's increase left the cpi at 115.7, meaning that a selection of goods and services that cost $100 during a 1982-84 base period cost would have $115.70 last month
the department recently abandoned a 1967 base period in favor of the 1982 standard. under that earlier base period, a selection of goods and services costing $100 in that year would have cost $346.70 last month _ which is $1.56 more than the same goods cost in january 1986
the overall index is not adjusted for seasonal variations while other figures in the report are. acceptable</head> house comment.</note>
soviet concerns about president reagan's proposed space-based missile defense system are diminishing, possibly opening the door to wider testing of the ``star wars'' program than moscow previously said it could accept, according to a report published today
in what was described as a highly unusual luncheon in moscow with reporters, a high-ranking soviet official said his country only opposed the deployment of the space-based system and would want assurances that the united states would not use a testing program to disguise actual deployment
in washington, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said, ``if they have new moves or new proposals, we will certainly take a look at them.''
the new york times said the soviet official spoke freely thursday during the meal of caviar and filet mignon with reporters on the condition he not be identified or quoted directly, as senior american government officials often do
the official said technical problems with the system made it unlikely a workable system could be produced by the end of the century
he added that moscow remains committed to a strict interpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty, which includes prohibitions on the development of space-based weapons envisioned under reagan's strategic defense initiative
it was unclear if the new position was a genuine change in soviet policy or merely a hint of possible compromise, the times said
a revised soviet position on testing of components of the system could alleviate one of the main obstacles to completion of a treaty reducing long-range, strategic missiles. with comment from second lawyer, crowe, and edit to conform.</note>
gov. evan mecham's chief attorney has resigned, just days after other lawyers were brought in to handle the governor's impeachment trial opening next week before the state senate
murray miller said today during a brief interview at his office that the decision to withdraw from the case came thursday night. he declined to elaborate on the decision but he said he hoped members of the senate would not suspect he had deceived them
as late as wednesday night, after his appearance before the senate, ``i was fully in charge of the case and defending the governor,'' miller said
i feel uncomfortable that the impeachment court (the senate) may think i knew about the withdrawal at the time i appeared and that i was being deceptive. i want them to be asssured that is totally not the case.''
miller said he thought that washington attorney jerris leonard, hired earlier this week by mecham to be the lead lawyer for the impeachment trial, is now in charge of mecham's case
miller said he did not know whether the new mecham legal team would be able to proceed with the impeachment trial as scheduled monday, but assumed they would if so ordered
my main concern is that the governor gets a fair legal shake,'' said miller
another lawyer hired by mecham this week, thomas crowe, said today that leonard would be at the senate on monday
how ready he'll be i don't know, but he will be there,'' crowe said. he also said the attorneys had not decided whether they would go to court today in an effort to delay the impeachment trial
the arizona daily star of tucson today quoted the governor as saying: ``murray withdrew from the case. we parted friendly, but that's really all. you'll have to ask him why.''
mecham and leonard did not immediately return phone calls this morning
leonard resigned from the washington law firm of manatt, phelps, rothenberg, tunney and evans because of his decision to join mecham's defense, said charles t. manatt, a senior partner in the firm
jerris leonard informed the firm last week that he had been contacted by governor mecham concerning representation,'' manatt said. ``we made it clear that the firm was not interested in representing governor mecham, and mr. leonard informed us that he has resigned from the firm.''
manatt, a former chairman of the democratic national committee, was asked why his firm wasn't interested in being associated with the mecham case. ``lots of reasons, you can well imagine,'' he replied
miller said wednesday he did not know additional attorneys were being hired until leonard walked into his office monday
the beleaguered mecham also faces a may 17 recall election and a march 22 criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
the senate on wednesday refused to delay the impeachment trial. miller said then that he expected to remain the lead attorney until leonard could get acquainted with the case
mecham hired miller on oct. 21, the day it was disclosed that the attorney general's office was investigating mecham's failure to disclose the $350,000 campaign loan made in 1986
on thursday, miller filed a motion asking the state senate to dismiss the impeachment case
lawyers in the case also raised the possibility that the governor would go to state or federal court today in an effort to delay the senate trial. senate counsel john lundin told lawmakers he expected any challenge to be filed in the state supreme court
if mecham's attorneys ask a court to delay the trial, the senate is expected to argue that courts have no jurisdiction over a legislative impeachment
the motion filed thursday said, ``this impeachment article should be dismissed and the governor should be permitted to govern this state as mandated by the will of the people in the last election.''
miller has contended that the republican governor's impeachment trial should be delayed until after his criminal trial, on grounds that the criminal jury would be prejudiced by the publicity surrounding an impeachment trial
mecham was impeached feb. 5 on a 46-16 house vote. several days later the house approved 23 impeachment articles outlining details of three broad charges against the governor: that he concealed the $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership, and tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
miller argued that the claim regarding the alleged death threat was a ``tempest in a teapot'' that had ``given the prosecutors the unbridled license to wildly charge crimes against the governor in a vindictive and persecutorial manner.''
miller said mecham cannot be convicted for allegedly concealing the $350,000 loan because a campaign financial report on which the loan was lumped with other funds was made on dec. 5, 1986, before mecham took office. the state constitution says officials may be impeached only for acts committed while in office, miller said
miller said the $80,000 loan to mecham pontiac violated no laws and was ``nothing short of a prudent investment'' that earned higher interest than the money would have gotten in a bank
a woman has reached a $925,000 settlement of her suit against a hospital and nursing company charging a nurse incorrectly hooked up a pump, causing air pressure that blew a hole in the woman's intestine
juanita johns continues to suffer infections and has a disfiguring scar on her stomach, one of her attorneys, wayne alford, said friday
mrs. johns, 53, reached the settlement this week with university medical center and medical personnel pool of northeast florida inc., which supplied the nurse under a contract with the hospital. mrs. johns' malpractice lawsuit had been scheduled to go to trial next week
mrs. johns was recovering from lung surgery at university hospital in jacksonville last year when her doctor ordered a tube placed down her throat to remove intestinal gas
however, a private-duty nurse attached the tube to the exhaust end of a pump and air was pumped into mrs. johns, blowing a hole in her intestines, her lawyers said
she realized something was wrong when because her stomach started blowing up like a balloon,'' alford said of his client. ``she suffered extreme pain. at that point, she ripped this thing out of her nose and out of her stomach and a doctor later said this ultimately saved her life.''
mrs. johns was rushed into surgery and was in intensive care for eight days
under the agreement, the hospital will pay $150,000 and the nursing pool will pay $775,000, said alford and fellow attorney john kalil. the settlement was reached after a judge ruled that both the hospital and the nursing firm could be held liable. up 1st graf a0627</note>
the national assembly today convened an emergency session and ousted president eric arturo delvalle after he tried to fire the nation's military chief and de facto leader, gen. manuel antonio noriega
in a 10-minute session, 38 legislators voted delvalle out of office and accused him of promoting u.s. interference in domestic affairs by trying to force noriega out
the cabinet immediately named a new chief of state, education minister manuel solis palma, who was sworn in before dawn. devalle called the moves ``legally despicable.''
noriega blamed the upheaval on the united states but said u.s. interests in panama would be safe. he said the events were ``strictly internal.''
in washington, president reagan said the united states does not plan military intervention in panama. ``no, i don't think that's the answer,'' he said when asked
u.s. ambassador arthur davis said the u.s. government would not recognize the replacement for devalle, who had acted to assert civilian control over the government
opposition leaders were meeting today to discuss a possible national strike and the university was closed, but banks and stores opened and there was no sign of unrest
noriega, under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges, said through his miami attorney, ray takiff, ``all american interest in the republic are and shall remain undisturbed and unharmed.''
noriega said he was a friend of the american people, but he denounced u.s. politicans who he said advocate ``hysteria (and) act with a wreckless disregard for the truth.''
in an interview broadcast today by the government's radio nacional, noriega said of the united states: ``they have been using a web that includes psychological warfare ... slander, lies, injury, conjecture, and ... misinformation.''
drivers honked their horns and some waved white handerchiefs immediately after delvalle announced his plan to oust noriega. both have been signs of opposition to noriega, who was the target of nationwide protests and strikes last summer
carlos ernesto gonzales de la lastra, a spokesman for the opposition national civic crusade coalition, said today in a telephone interview, ``the national civic crusade and other opposition leaders are meeting to reach an agreement, with the intention of carrying out a national strike.'' he declined to give more details
officials of the national university of panama closed the school and said it was to prevent disturbances. secondary and primary schools were out for vacation
delvalle called his own ouster ``something legally despicable that only fulfills a formality in the mind of those who want to grasp power at any cost.''
he urged a trade embargo against panama but said he opposed u.s. military intervention
panama, with 2.2 million people, is headquarters for u.s. military operations in latin america
the u.s. southern command has 10,000 troops and 20,000 dependents in panama. the u.s. garrison was on alert and told americans to keep a low profile during any unrest
the white house called for noriega's resignation after his indictment in florida on feb. 5. delvalle's attempt to oust noriega, announced in a nationwide broadcast thursday night, received immediate backing from the united states
but noriega and his supporters moved quickly
the national assembly was called into session, although opposition lawmakers in the 67-member legislature boycotted the 1 a.m. meeting. both delvalle and vice president roderick esquivel were removed from office
noriega, who says he is innocent of all charges, did not comment publicly on the events
delvalle said of his opponents, ``they will not receive acceptance from any country that takes pride in being democratic. i continue to feel that i am president of the republic.''
from his home, delvalle said he asked noriega to ``retire'' as soon as the u.s. indictments were announced, but the general refused
defense forces police chief col. leonidas macias told panamanian television thursday that no officer would replace the general
he (delvalle) is going first,'' said macias, flanked by senior officers at the defense forces' central garrison
delvalle said earlier that col. marcos justines, the chief of staff, would replace noriega. justines refused and told reporters: ``we have been conversing with him (delvalle) constantly, and he knows that our position has been that there is too much american interference in this panamanian affair.''
in its resolution, the national assembly said delvalle violated the law in removing noriega and noted that esquivel had abandoned his post in september without resigning
the resolution said delvalle mentioned u.s. charges against noriega ``with the object of permitting the intervention of the government of the united states in the internal affairs of panama,'' damaging national sovereignty and endangering national security
the u.s. indictments accuse noriega of using his authority to let colombian drug traffickers use panama as a base for smuggling cocaine and marijuana into the united states. the charges said noriega received a healthy kickback from drug profits
later, at his home, the president told the associated press, that he ordered noriega's dismissal ``for the health of this country.''
roman catholic archbishop marcos gregorio mcgrath arrived at the house and pledged support for delvalle
california's ``vehicle of the future'' features a back-seat driver that not only nags but also is capable of slamming on the brakes
a 1977 dodge van equipped with an experimental radar-based ``collision-avoidance'' system was demonstrated thursday at a meeting of the governor's regional transportation management conference
the system has a grill-mounted radar dish and a computer under the dashboard to warn the driver of approaching hazards
john davis, the san diego engineer who invented and sells the system, took the van on a demonstration spin
watch it! watch!'' the computer voice snapped as he drove out of the parking lot
look out! look out!'' it barked as he came too close to a car
fall back! fall back!'' it commanded before finally putting on the brakes
the state has ordered six vehicles equipped with the system, said interim director donald watson of the state transportation department
this system will enable more vehicles to move faster at closer intervals and will substantially increase the capacity of our highways,'' he said
the six experimental trucks and cars will cost about $250,000, he said
vietnam has told the united states that next week it will turn over what the vietnamese say are the remains of 20 american servicemen listed as missing from the indochina war, u.s. government sources said today
richard paul, an aide to sen. frank h. murkowski, r-ala., a member of the senate veteran's affairs committee, said a member of the vietnamese delegation at the united nations told the senator that vietnam had information on, or the actual remains of, 23 servicemen
a reagan administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said vietnam was believed to have 20 remains and information on three others and would provide the bodies and the information on march 2
the official said a u.s. plane would be sent to hanoi and take the remains to the u.s. military's joint casualty resolution center in hawaii for identification
the united states has been urging vietnam to account for the more than 1,700 american servicemen still listed as missing from the indochina war. u.s. government leaders have said vietnam has been withholding information
a leading panamanian dissident said today that ousted president eric arturo delvalle knew in advance his effort to fire military strongman manuel antonio noriega would fail
but jose i. blandon, a former close associate of noriega's, said in an interview that delvalle's bid to depose noriega was but one step in an 18-point plan that is designed to lead to noriega's ouster within three weeks
it is exactly what we thought was going to happen,'' blandon said, referring to delvalle's attempt to replace noriega with the second-ranking officer in panama's defense forces and noriega's decision to ignore the order
early today, the panamian legislature voted to remove delvalle from office and appointed a successor
blandon said that he and about 10 other opposition leaders have joined with delvalle in putting together the plan over the last several weeks
the next steps in the plan, blandon said, include rallying broad international support for delvalle, a general strike in panama and, they hope, an embargo by the united states aimed at crippling panama's economy
these steps, blandon said, ``will leave noriega more isolated than ever'' and force his eventual downfall
blandon said his allies already have been in touch with authorities in the dominican republic to determine whether they would be willing to allow noriega to enter the country if and when he is forced out. he said dominican officials have responded positively to the proposal
one potential obstacle to noriega's acquiescence to this solution is the possibility of his arrest in the dominican republic and his extradition to the united states based on federal drug smuggling indictments against him, blandon said
he said delvalle raised last week with assistant secretary of state elliott abrams the possibility of dropping the u.s. indictments against noriega. he said abrams was unable to make any such commitment and that a final decision on withdrawing the indictments would have to be left either to the justice department or president reagan
in any case, blandon said, the political and economic circumstances in panama are such that it is doubtful that noriega can survive much longer, especially if the united states and latin american countries close ranks behind delvalle
blandon spoke to a reporter at a local hotel where he is under 24-hour guard by u.s. marshals. he was a key witness earlier this month in congressional hearings on noriega's alleged drug smuggling activities and his ties to the cia
as he spoke, blandon frequently referred to a folder outlining the plan to end noriega's domination of panamanian politics and to restore elected civilian rule to the country. the plan was dated feb. 22 but its contents had been agreed to weeks earlier by a broad-based coalition of panamanian opposition leaders, blandon said
an abandoned rum warehouse has become the latest symbol of rebirth in this port city that was founded on cotton, famed for its beatles and devastated by changing times
contractors on wednesday handed over the keys of the old warehouse to sir alan bowness, director of london's tate gallery
on may 24, prince charles, the heir to the throne, will come to the building and open the ``tate in the north,'' the first endeavor by a state museum in britain to show its works on a large scale outside of london
a series of 10-month exhibitions will keep pictures and sculpture circulating to liverpool from the tate's collection of 40,000 works of british and 20th century art
it is a bid to attract another 500,000 visitors a year to liverpool
first to be seen will be surrealist art, the works of american abstract painter mark rothko and british sculpture of the past 20 years
liverpool has had a hard time and it's trying to pull itself up. i hope we can help, not least because i've always felt it was unacceptable that the tate should only be in london,'' bowness told the associated press
it will cost about $17.6 million to convert a warehouse in the albert dock, completed in 1846, to a museum. the dock contains five blocks of five-story, red-brick and cast-iron warehouses surrounding a 7-acre ``courtyard'' of water
the dock area already has a maritime museum and shops. more shops, restaurants and apartments are being created in the warehouses, which have been empty since world war ii when the dock fell into disuse
now the dock buildings are considered so valuable as architectural history that they are state-protected, and liverpool waterfront, stretching 1{ miles along the banks of the one-mile-wide mersey river, is being transformed from dereliction into a major tourist area
more than 50 million pounds ($88 million) has already been sunk into the waterfront and we are sure it is going to be a spectacular success,'' said diana day, publicist for the merseyside development corp
private industry has invested more than $315 million in other liverpool projects
liverpool, with 600,000 people 210 miles northwest of london, is beset by 20 percent unemployment and miles of decaying housing. fifteen million people live within one hour's drive from the city, which was home to the rock group, the beatles
liverpool was once the second port in britain after london and the major port of europe for the atlantic,'' said eric leatherbarrow, spokesman for mersey docks and harbor co
but when britain joined the european economic community trade tilted from here to southeast england, and containerization saw a lot of the old shipping lines disappear
now we are pulling up because european businessmen are realizing that liverpool is still the nearest major port to the united states. shipping companies are coming back and our cargo throughput was up by 1 million tons a year to 11 million tons in 1987.''
to generate interest for the new museum, ``the tate in the north'' has prepared charming and funny posters introducing liverpudlians to the world of modern art
one radio commercial features picasso's ``three dancers.''
a male voice explains the painting as follows:
the bloke on the right was married to the woman on the left who was having an affair with the bloke in the middle who was obsessed with her, only she lost interest so he invited her to a restaurant with some friends, they have a slap-up dinner, then he pulls a gun, fires at her, she ducks, plays doggo, then he shot himself
when his mother heard, she died of shock. you see, paintings talk to you.''
i don't hear nothing,'' a second voice replies. penalty</head> recommending reconsideration of proposed punishment, picking up 8th graf pvs, `swaggart, who ....'</note>
leaders of the assemblies of god said today they have asked church officials in louisiana to reconsider a recommended three-month suspension for fallen tv evangelist jimmy swaggart that hundreds of callers criticized as too lenient
twelve members of the church's highest governing board met for 12 hours at the church's international headquarters in springfield today and thursday to discuss the louisiana district's proposed sanctions against swaggart, who allegedly engaged in voyeurism with a prostitute
officials of swaggart's home district recommended earlier this week that the fiery television evangelist, who confessed to undisclosed moral misconduct, be prohibited from preaching for three months and undergo two years of rehabilitation and counseling
the state recommendation was criticized by many church members as too lenient, and the executive presbytery's move today was an indication the board disagreed with the state district's recommendation
meanwhile, the companion of a prostitute who claims she performed pornographic acts for swaggart for about a year said he was negotiating to sell her story to the mass media
this is a shot for me and a shot for her,'' said john martinez, a carpet cleaner who said he met debra murphree, 28, in west palm beach, fla., about four months ago. ``it's the american way _ see an opportunity and jump on it.''
martinez said he discussed a $100,000 contract to tell ms. murphree' story with the national enquirer and also contacted people magazine, abc-tv's nightline and other media worldwide, the palm beach post reported thursday
enquirer president and editor iain calder confirmed the tabloid was talking with martinez, but would say nothing more
at the end of the assemblies of god meeting here, general superintendent g. raymond carlson said, ``we will not discuss the content of our meeting.'' he said no final decision had been reached on swaggart's punishment and it could be several weeks until one is made
the church constitution provides for the louisiana district to reconsider the case and submit new recommendations to the church headquarters in springfield, where the final decision will be made
carlson made the announcement with seven board members at his side
juleen turnage, a church spokeswoman, said the board met thursday with two representatives of the church's louisiana district _ cecil janway, general superintendent of the state district and a member of the swaggart ministries board, and forrest hall, treasurer of the louisiana district
swaggart, who was not at thursday's meeting, has not made a public appearance since sunday, when he tearfully told his congregation in baton rouge, la., that he had committed an unspecified sin
the evangelist, whose jimmy swaggart world ministries gives $12 million a year to the assemblies of god, has been known for his harsh denunciation of sexual lapses by other preachers, including ptl ministry founder jim bakker
the church's 13-member governing body was considering a recommendation by the louisiana district that swaggart be barred from preaching for three months and undergo counseling during a supervised two-year rehabilitation
mrs. turnage said the international headquarters here has been swamped with up to 300 calls an hour since swaggart's televised confession sunday. about half of the callers complained that the louisiana recommendation was too lenient, she said, while others were generally supportive
mrs. turnage said the two-year rehabilitation is standard, but in cases of moral misconduct on the part of ministers, ``the precedent has always been that for that first year, the minister is barred from preaching.''
under the church constitution, if the executive presbytery decides to toughen up the state district's recommendation, they would send the case back to louisiana for reconsideration
the group had no statement after the meeting thursday, but mrs. turnage said they may release a progress report after more discussion today
we cannot put time and expediency ahead of our constitutional process,'' she said. ``i know that they are really carefully considering everything.''
the church, the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, has been shaken by the swaggart revelations and a sex-and-money scandal that last year cost bakker, another prominent assemblies minister, his ministerial credentials. he had rejected the option of undergoing rehabilitation
evangelist marvin gorman, who claimed swaggart falsely accused him of adultery, for which he was defrocked by the denomination, reportedly gave the church photographs of swaggart entering and leaving a motel room with a prostitute
ms. murphree told wvue-tv of new orleans wednesday that she met with swaggart for about a year at various motels between new orleans and baton rouge to perform pornographic acts, but did not have sexual intercourse with him
ms. murphree has an arrest record in louisiana and florida for prostitution-related offenses. she also is wanted on a drug charge in nashville, tenn., according to police records. ^by reid g. miller</byline>
eric arturo delvalle today insisted he is still president of panama and called for a worldwide trade embargo against his nation and its de factor ruler, gen. manuel antonio noriega
delvalle, ousted by the national assembly today after he tried to fire noriega, said a trade embargo would create economic chaos, ``but we all have to realize that a country has to suffer to rid itself of a dictatorship.''
he said he also he also supports u.s. congressional calls for a halt to commercial airline flights and to free-zone banking transactions between the united states and panama, home of one of the western hemisphere's largest banking centers
delvalle spoke informally to reporters at his home, where he has remained since he announced thursday afternoon he was firing noriega
the assembly is dominated by a coalition of noriega's supporters and its brief, post-midnight session was boycotted by minority opposition members
i am the president of panama this morning,'' delvalle declared, his eyes baggy and red-rimmed from lack of sleep. ``there is no doubt about it. there is no legal power in panamanian laws or the constitution that allows the national assembly'' to dismiss a president
but asked how he intended to exercise the functions of the presidency, delvalle shrugged and replied with a tired smile: ``that's a good question.''
he said he knew that his ``chances were slim'' in calling for noriega's departure because ``never has any president ousted the commander of the defense forces in panama in all our history. it has always been the other way around.''
delvalle said he would take his case to the nation's supreme court, ``where my chances are also very slim, because it also is controlled by gen. noriega.''
the cabinet named education minister manuel solis palma as the new chief of state
meanwhile, a coalition of business, professional, labor and political organization known as the national civic crusade was meeting to consider a call for a nationwide work stoppage
delvalle said he would support ``an indefinite strike'' and called ``the people of panama to unite, all for one and one for all, to struggle for the removal of gen. noriega.''
he said that as soon as u.s. grand jury indictments charging noriega with drug trafficking were announced in miami and tampa, fla., earlier this month, he called noriega and asked him to step down
but he said he didn't think it was advisable.''
i let him consider his answer for a couple of days and then again i requested his own decision to retire, which he didn't accept, and that's why i acted today (thursday.)''
in a telephone interview with ``cbs this morning,'' delvalle said the united states had not pressured him to fire noriega
delvalle, 51, spent most of the evening huddled in a back room with u.s. ambassador arthur davis and his personal advisers
between 30 and 40 people, most of them close friends, listened to radio and television news reports at the delvalle home and he occasionally strolled out to chat with them
asked about the naming of another president, delvalle replied: ``i will fight it out, because there is no reason for me to be removed from my position. i am acting within the laws and the constistution of the country.''
asked what reaction he expected from the international community, delvalle said, ``the reaction of the international community will be against the defense forces.''
asked if he had discussed thursday's action with u.s. assistant secretary of state elliott abrams while in miami last week, delvalle said, ``no, not at all.''
but delvalle said he had a four-hour visit from davis thursday evening and ``received state department support ... stating that they will back me and support my actions.''
he said he did not fear for his safety
delvalle had no political experience before he became vice president in october 1984, after running for the republic party in a coalition with five other parties
he was president and general manager of national sugar, a sugar producing and refining company owned by his family. he studied in the united states
he and his wife mariela diaz have three children
president reagan will nominate karen borlaug phillips, a congressional staff economist, to be a member of the interstate commerce commission, it was announced friday
if confirmed by the senate, she will succeed malcolm m.b. sterrett
since 1987, mrs. phillips has been minority chief economist on the senate finance committee. taxes</head>
taxpayers who underestimated their income-tax withholding this year would be allowed to pay the internal revenue service in installments under legislation introduced friday in the senate
sen. carl levin, d-mich., said broad changes in the income tax law passed in 1986 make it more likely that taxpayers, especially in families with two wage-earners, failed to deduct enough from their paychecks to cover their tax liabilities
the bill, sponsored by levin and sen. steve symms, r-idaho, would allow people who underwithheld to pay off their debt to the irs, with interest, in three payments after april 15
under the present law, taxpayers unable to pay a lump sum by april 15 must negotiate terms with the irs on a case-by-case basis. picks up 9th graf, `austria is ...'</note>
a top socialist minister today reversed his decision to boycott a ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of nazi germany's annexation of austria after president kurt waldheim dropped plans to speak during the event
other socialists hailed the decision of the president, who served as a lieutenant in the german army during world war ii
in a televised interview thursday, waldheim announced he would not give a speech march 11. he said he would give a televised speech march 10
in the interview, waldheim also said he had considered quitting the presidency but had rejected the idea
the announcement on the speech prompted finance minister ferdinand lacina to reverse his decision to boycott the solemn ceremony
lacina, a socialist, said friday that a waldheim speech would have led to ``a renewed polarization'' among austrians and ``criticism coming from other countries.''
heinz fischer, a leader of the socialist party, said waldheim's decision to drop the speech ``will lead to an easing of tensions on march 11.''
waldheim has been surrounded by controversy since march 1986, when it was disclosed that he had served as a lieutenant with the german army in the balkans during world war ii. the united states and put him on a ``watch list'' of undesirable aliens, barring him from entering the united states
in the interview thursday, waldheim said he had a ``clear conscience'' and repeatedly insisted he did nothing wrong
austria is governed by a coalition of socialists and conservatives. waldheim is the ceremonial head of state
the head of the government, chancellor franz vranitzky told abc-tv's ``good morning america'' today that it was up to waldheim to determine whether he should step down
the 69-year-old waldheim said he will address the nation in a televised broadcast on march 10, the eve of the ceremony marking the anschluss, when austria was absorbed into the german reich in 1938. austria was liberated by the allies in the spring of 1945
waldheim opponents had promised to take to the streets in protest if the president went ahead with the talk on march 11 in the hofburg palace
several leading austrian politicians said a waldheim speech was not the way to lead the country into reflecting on its nazi past
there have been calls for waldheim's resignation since march 1986, when austrian and u.s. media and the world jewish congress reported that he served as a lieutenant with the germany army in the occupied balkans during world war ii
the calls intensified after an international historians' commission issued a critical report earlier this month, which left open the question of whether he was guilty of war crimes
if i thought i had done anything false or anything wrong, then i would have taken the consequences,'' waldheim said
in the controversy over waldheim's past, ``taking the consequences'' has come to be synonymous with resignation. waldheim's term is scheduled to end in 1992
waldheim was asked if he had considered quitting
naturally i thought of it,'' he said. ``otherwise i wouldn't be a human being. i'd have to be a piece of wood.''
but he firmly rejected any notion of stepping down. ``my resignation would only make things worse,'' he said
waldheim's decision not to speak at the anschluss commemoration dominated the front pages of newspapers today
waldheim cancels the speech at the remembrance ceremony,'' said the salzburger nachrichten. the conservative newspaper has strongly criticized waldheim for his handling of his wartime past
vienna's kurier tabloid, which also has criticized waldheim, focused on conciliatory remarks he made in the interview
waldheim: i apologize for the misunderstandings,'' the kurier newspaper said in a banner headline
the march 11 speech originally had been planned as a way to avoid a political showdown over whether waldheim would address a joint session of parliament to mark anschluss. angeles-dated item.</note>
a 10-day visit to california by britain's prince andrew and his wife, ``fergie,'' the duchess of york, will be full of public events, but no security problems are expected, a british consulate official says
the couple, scheduled to arrive late this afternoon, will attend exhibitions and concerts that are part of uk@la '88, a three-month-long british arts festival, said angus mackay, the royal visit press officer. they also will attend banquets and visit schools, stores, an aircraft carrier and churches from los angeles to palm springs
when andrew, the third child of queen elizabeth ii, visited los angeles four years ago he was a bachelor naval officer who lived up to a rowdy reputation by playfully turning a paint sprayer on the press corps. since then, he married the former sarah ferguson, who is pregnant, so the current visit promises to be more staid
the first event planned for the royal couple is a welcoming ceremony saturday at los angeles city hall featuring a performance by the rock group los lobos, which gained fame in the movie ``la bamba.'' children</head>
a woman with two small children who is running for election to a judgeship says she's surprised her opponent has made motherhood an issue in their campaign
district judge john mckellips raised the issue at a sheriff's deputies' meeting while comparing his qualifications with mary anne bramblett's
bramblett, an assistant county attorney, has less than six years experience as a lawyer and is seeking to become the county's first female state judge. because there is no republican candidate, the winner of their march 8 democratic primary will capture the 41st district judge's seat
the incumbent judge suggested bramblett and other mothers should stay home with their young children
she had to take some time out for maternity leave to have two small children, so i don't know how much time she's actually spent working as an attorney,'' he added wednesday night
the judge also linked absent mothers to the problem of overcrowded jails and prisons
what do we do (about crowded prisons)? well, we can start in our homes,'' he said. ``mothers can stay home and raise their children during the formative years.''
the judge continued the theme thursday in an interview with the el paso times
no one who will be truthful will deny the importance of a mother being with children during pre-school years,'' he said. ``other persons may try to substitute and mean well, but there's no substitute for a mother's love.''
the judge's views were surprising, bramblett said
everybody got the clear message that (mckellips believes) i am not qualified to be a judge because i'm a woman and a mother,'' said bramblett, whose children are 3 and 4 years old
the judge's comments to the sheriff's deputies association were made in the context of crime rates and the cause of crime, he said
i acknowledge it would have been more correct to have used the term `parent' rather than mother,'' he said in the thursday interview. ``the whole point of this discussion is a breakdown of parental guidance in the home, whether that breakdown is the fault of the mother or the father.''
he said, ``as a district judge, one never has a normal life. to do your job properly requires long hours and extra devotion, and she would have less time as a judge to be with her family than she has had in the past. it appears that mrs. bramblett's personal ambitions are more important to her than the lives of her children.''
it's not true,'' bramblett said. ``i think my children have a very good role model to look up to, both myself and my husband.'' to 24</head>
a man dubbed the ``dapper bandit,'' disguised with sunglasses, wig and fake mustache, robbed two banks in one day to bring his 10-year total in texas to 24, authorities said
in one robbery, the man disarmed an off-duty police officer working as a guard and escaped with the officer's pistol, police said
officials would not disclose the amount taken in the robberies thursday, which came four hours and two miles apart. the well-dresssed robber had been idle since striking a bank in east dallas last september
in addition to the usual disguise, the well-dressed bandit has been known to wear bandages on his face. he has been photographed numerous times by bank cameras and a $25,000 reward has been posted, but there have been no significant leads, police say
the first robbery occurred at first republicbank, said arlington police spokesman dee anderson
we had an off-duty uniformed officer there working security,'' he said. ``he was approached by the suspect, who pulled a gun and ordered him to drop his weapon.''
after picking up officer eddie bell's pistol, the bandit, wearing a gray suit and maroon tie, leaped over the tellers' counter and scooped up money from cash trays, anderson said
bell slipped outside and told passers-by to call police. he ran back in time to see the bandit jump into a car and leave, anderson said
in the second robbery, at landmark bank, the robber pulled a pistol from a leather briefcase, walked around the tellers' counter and took money from both tellers' drawers, anderson said. he fled out a back door and drove away in a different car
police recovered both getaway cars, both of which had been stolen in nearby irving, anderson said
the chief game warden in zimbabwe's state-controlled national parks was convicted friday on charges of fraud and taking bribes from professional hunters
arthur wood was sentenced to five years in jail on the charges of fraud and corruption, in which undervalued permits were issued for hunting trips on state wildlife estates in return for bribes from foreign and local hunters
magistrate billy de beer ruled in harare regional court that wood, 56, defrauded the state of the equivalent of $52,000 by underpricing hunting permits and taling at least $7,100 in bribes. wood denied the charges
a zimbabwe-based professional hunter and safari operator admitted in court he had offered wood money for a hunting permit
here is a chronology of major events in panama leading to the ouster of the civilian president, eric arturo devalle, in a showdown with gen. manuel antonio noriega:
april 18, 1978 _ the u.s. senate ratifies the panama canal treaty, which turns over to panamanian control the 50-mile long waterway and the u.s. military bases on dec. 31, 1999
oct. 1, 1979 _ panama assumes sovereignity over the panama canal zone and is given the right to use portions of the area not needed for its defense
july 31, 1981 _ gen. omar torrijos, head of the defense forces, who came to power in a 1968 coup, dies in a plane crash. two years later gen. manuel antonio noriega emerges as the leader of the defense forces
may 6, 1984 _ nicolas ardito barletta is elected president on the ticket of a military-backed coalition, amid charges of fraud
sep. 27, 1985 _ noriega, chief of the defense forces, and other military leaders force out ardito barletta and replace him with eric arturo delvalle, formerly vice president
june 6, 1987 _ col. roberto diaz herrera, noriega's recently retired second in command, accuses noriega of election fraud, drug trafficking, corruption and involvement in the assassination of political opponents
june 9 _ the national civic crusade is formed, initially by 101 professional, civic, labor and business groups to demand noriega's resignation. small street demonstrations break out, for and against noriega
july 26 _ police close down the newspapers la prensa, extra and el siglo for publishing articles demanding noriega's resignation
july 27 _ police raid the headquarters of the national civic crusade and arrest five leaders. they are later released and flee the country
aug. 31 _ a nationwide strike planned by the opposition fizzles. one man is killed and seven are wounded. demonstrations continue almost daily for about two months
feb. 5, 1988 _ noriega is indicted in courts in miami and tampa, fla., on charges of involvement in drug-trafficking
feb. 17 _ delvalle meets with u.s. assistant secretary of state elliott abrams in miami
feb. 25 _ delvalle announces that he is dismissing noriega as defense chief and replacing him with col. marcos justines, the chief of staff. justines refuses to take the job
feb. 26 _ the national assembly meets in emergency session and votes to oust delvalle. education minister manuel solis palma is named the new head of state and sworn into office
a member of the 1950 brink's robbery gang who seeking a divorce says his wife can have their house, built on land he purchased with some of his share of the $1.2 million heist
vincent costa, 74, told brockton probate court judge summer z. kaplan that he bought the land for $1,800 on nov. 10, 1950
when asked by his lawyer where he got the money, costa replied, ``i got it from the brink's case.''
costa, one of the two surviving members of the 11-member gang, told the judge his share amounted to about $100,000. a son cheated him out of most of it, he said
the jan. 17, 1950, robbery of the brink's counting house in boston's north end was then the largest in u.s. history. none of the money was ever recovered
two of the 11 men involved in the robbery two died before the fbi solved the case in 1956. the remaining nine were sentenced to life in prison, but had their sentences commuted after serving various terms
costa didn't admit his involvement until may 1977, when he and another participant held a news conference to publicize a book and a movie about the robbery
costa told the judge this week he wants his wife of 54 years, nancy, 76, to spend her remaining years in the home. but, he said, he or his estate would be entitled to half of the proceeds whenever the house is sold
the house, now valued at $125,000, is the couple's only asset, her lawyer said
mrs. costa testified she is a devout roman catholic and doesn't believe in divorce but said she won't oppose it. the couple, both of whom have serious medical problems, have five children
the united states said today it continues to recognize eric arturo delvalle as president of panama, even after a parliamentary vote to oust him
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley, reiterating what she termed ``our support for the supremacy of civilian constitutional rule,'' said ``we continue to recognize president delvalle as the president of panama.''
asked to describe the legal grounds for such recognition, she said, ``i don't think it's for us to interpret their constitutional law. we had regarded him as the president, we still regard him as the president.''
she described the situation among panamanian political figures as one of ``a great deal of political maneuvering.''
she said delvalle's decision to fire manuel antonio noriega as the nation's defense chief _ which precipated delvalle's ouster by the assembly _ ``took great courage and we continue with our policy.''
the spokeswoman said delvalle made the decision on his own, though she acknowledged that u.s. officials were in close contact with him. she declined to reveal the substance of the discussions
mrs. oakley also said the united states continues to recognize juan b. sosa as panama's ambassador in washington. sosa has supported delvalle
i informed the state department that i will continue with him,'' sosa said, referring to his support for delvalle
i'm sure they will try to send another ambassador,'' he said, adding that he had asked for continued recognition by the u.s. government
mrs. oakley said elliot abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, met with sosa this morning, but she wouldn't reveal details of the discussion
many people knew that we had been aware of the actions that president delvalle was contemplating doing,'' she said. ``we had been informed that the decision was president delvalle's own to make.''
i'm not going to get into who was behind what; who said what,'' she said. ``this is obviously an unstable period, confused.''
the situation there obviously has to clarify,'' she said
asked if the united states had been in contact with noriega, she said, ``not that i'm aware of.''
pat robertson complains that he is being held to a higher standard than his rivals but the political world is in awe over how he gets away with controversial statements that would sink other presidential hopefuls
the man is tefloned,'' says republican consultant ed mahe. ``he is tefloned so well with his base that he's not taking any hits as a consequence of what he says.''
but mahe and other experts say robertson's controversial pronouncements are likely to sink whatever hopes he holds of winning over enough mainstream support in the republican party to be a serious contender for the presidential nomination at the gop convention in august
ultimately this could be his upending,'' said sociologist anson shupe of indiana, co-author of a forthcoming book, ``televangelism: power and politics in god's country.''
if robertson doesn't make it to the nomination, it won't be because of a lack of money or grassroots organization or definable issues or momentum, it will be because he is so far out in left field with some of these statements that even his followers are embarrassed,'' shupe said
even ronald reagan, who has often stood corrected, ridiculed robertson's claim that his christian broadcasting network had information about the location of hostages in the middle east
isn't it strange that no one in our administration was ever apprised of that?'' asked the president at his news conference wednesday, in a departure from his loyalty to the republican 11th commandment: speak no evil of any republican
robertson said his hostage claim was only a ``throwaway line'' to illustrate a point, but he complained wherever he went that he is being held to an unfair scrutiny
i have been grossly misunderstood and the press has distorted what i've said,'' he said in tulsa, okla
i don't go around with a press person on one side and a lawyer on another and a librarian behind me,'' robertson said. ``i'm not used to having to give 200 answers every time there's one little innocent statement.''
exactly right, mahe said. ``what we have here is a talk-show host who doesn't understand the power of talk; after all, when you're a talk-show host you toss these things out and who cares.''
my guess is that pat is deliberately playing to his south carolina constituency,'' said university of virginia sociologist jeffrey hadden, a student of the television fundamentalist preachers. ``he doesn't care if folks in new york or chicago or los angeles think he's crazy at this point. if he can get the press bashing him a bit, it would help ignite his followers.''
just as robertson weathered the hostage crisis this week, he survived the missile crisis earlier this month
when he claimed there were soviet missiles in cuba, the pentagon denied it, the white house denied it, even fidel castro denied it, and robertson merely shrugged off the outcry, saying he hoped those doing the denying were right
he also suggested he saw the sinister hand of vice president george bush behind the timing of the disclosures of sexual misbehavior by a fellow fundamentalist preacher, jimmy swaggart
and he accused television anchorman tom brokaw of engaging in ``religious bigotry'' when brokaw referred to robertson, a former television evangelist, as a former television evangelist
bush challenged robertson on friday to ``prove it'' about his claim that bush engineered the timing of the swaggart disclosures to hurt robertson's chances in the march 5 south carolina primary. and the vice president said robertson is ``scaring the american people'' with loose talk about missiles
stephen hess, a brookings institution student of the press and politics, said robertson's ability to weather attacks on his credibility _ ``the teflon factor'' _ exists because the press has been easy on him
the media gets tough on people when they become important,'' he said
moreover, said larry sabato, a political scientist at the university of virginia who has followed robertson for decades: ``the other republican candidates are hesitant to attack him. even bush has done so gingerly. the republicans know they need his constituency in the fall; they know these people are easily offended and will stay permanently offended.''
the nation's roman catholic bishops on friday said time was running out for communist authorities to bring sweeping economic and political reforms to poland
among the reforms they called for are constitutional guarantees for private enterprise and the right of workers to form independent trade unions
the bishops also said they viewed with ``seriousness and concern'' the impact of price hikes imposed by the government earlier this month. they said authorities must protect pensioners, invalids and poor families from ``further impoverishment.''
the bishops made their remarks in a communique released after a two-day meeting of the polish episcopate in warsaw presided over by the polish primate, cardinal jozef glemp
the communique reflected growing concern within the influential church about the authorities' slow pace in introducing political and economic reforms announced last fall
the bishops quoted extensively from the recent encyclical issued by pope john paul ii on social action
they cited passages saying that the development and well-being of nations depends on guaranteeing the right to undertake economic initiatives at the expense of bureaucratic state apparatuses, respecting human rights including the freedom to set up trade unions, and reforming unjust political institutions
glemp, in a pastoral letter read aloud in the nation's churches feb. 21, said the many ``shortcomings'' in poland's economic system had embittered and discouraged people, while the government's economic recovery program seemed ``incomprehensible'' and ``inconsistent'' to many poles
the bishops said there had been many official announcements about introducing reforms aimed at allowing more political and economic initiatives. but they had remained ``in the sphere of declarations and discussions.''
administrative practice often goes in the opposite direction, setting a dam for various economic and social initiatives,'' the bishops said. ``time is running out.''
it is only acts that can convince the society about the real wish of reforms in the economic, social and political life,'' they said. ``without them there is a danger of deepening the crisis in our country.''
the bishops said the authorities should make it easier for individuals to set up their own businesses, grant more economic decision-making powers to local governments, and reject ``political criteria'' in the selection of managerial personnel
it is necessary to widen the role of the private sector in the national economy,'' the bishops said
they added that the economic reforms should be accompanied by ``wide reforms ... allowing (the society) to organize independent social associations and workers' representations.''
the government has said its political and economic reform programs advocate many of the same goals supported by the bishops
the outlawed solidarity labor union has called the reforms inadequate because they fail to loosen the communist party's grip on economic and political decision-making powers
president reagan said today the united states does not plan any military intervention in panama and the state department reaffirmed u.s. support for that nation's embattled president
at the white house, reagan was asked about the governmental crisis in panama, where president eric arturo delvalle failed in his attempt to oust gen. manuel antonio noriega, the country's strongman, and was in turn dismissed himself
there are some limits on what we can do, but we are looking at the situation to see if there is anything we can do,'' the president said
when asked if military intervention was planned, he said, ``no, i don't think that's the answer.''
we are not prepared to come up with any answer yet,'' reagan added
when he was asked whether he thought the 10,000 or so u.s. troops in panama were in danger, the president replied, ``no, i do not. i don't think there is any appetite on the part of anyone there, including mr. noriega, to take on our troops.''
separately, the state department said it continues to recognize devalle as panama's president despite an early-morning parliamentary vote to oust him
department spokeswoman phyllis oakley reiterated what she termed ``our support for the supremacy of civilian constitutiona rule,'' and said, ``we continue to recognize president delvalle as the president.''
asked to describe the legal grounds for such recognition, she said, ``i don't think it's for us to interpret their constitutional law. we had regarded him as the president, we still regard him as the president.''
in other developments:
_panama's ambassador to the united states, juan sosa, an ally of delvalle, said he had informed the state department he would stay on, at least for the time being, despite a call from noriega telling sosa he would be replaced
mrs. oakley said the united states does, indeed, continue to recognize sosa
_vice president george bush said in south carolina that the united states should do ``whatever is necessary, including military force'' to protect american interests
bush stopped short of calling for military intervention, saying the united states' history of intervention in latin american affairs is ``what's hurting us in some areas now.''
during a presidential campaign visit to south carolina, he said, ``we will do whatever is necessary to protect american interests in panama. we've got treaty interests on the (panama) canal. i don't want to rattle any sabers. ...''
_defense secretary frank carlucci, interviewed on a u.s. information agency program, also said that ``it would be premature at this time'' to discuss an american military move
_jose i. blandon, a former noriega ally but now a leading panamanian dissident, predicted that noriega would be out of power within three weeks and said delvalle's allies have already asked the dominican republic if it would let noriega live there if and when he is forced out
he said dominican officials have responded positively to the proposal
reagan said the united states did not instigate delvalle's action, but had been ``very much aware of it.''
when asked whether the united states still wants noriega to stand trial on drug trafficking charges on which he was indicted by a federal grand jury in miami, the president said, ``i assume so.''
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said earlier that delvalle had consulted with american officials at the u.s. embassy in panama city
we have had discussions with delvalle over the past several days. we assured him of our position, which is that we would like to see a peaceful transition to civilian rule,'' the spokesman said
asked whether the united states had encouraged delvalle to dismiss noriega, who has been indicted by a federal grand jury in this country on charges of drug trafficking, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater replied:
i can't elaborate on any of the specific conversations. we did not urge him to take this action. he did it on his own. ..
we have a precarious position. yes, we want him (noriega) to stand trial. yes, we want a civilian government in panama. yet, we want to be careful not to unduly intrude upon the affairs of panama.''
another u.s. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the united states would ``take steps'' if americans are endangered in panama
meanwhile, sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., a leading noriega critic, said, ``panamanians will take care of that themselves. just wait and see what happens if and when the united states takes a flatfooted stand and tells the panamanian president, we're with you and we're against him,'' helms said
he said of noreiga: ``he's a bum; he ought to be thrown out.''
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., proposed a trade embargo against the government under the control of military strongman manuel noriega and called for u.s. troops to be put on full alert to protect the panama canal and 50,000 u.s. citizens in the country
fitzwater said no consideration is being given to a trade embargo
delvalle, in a telephone interview with ``cbs this morning,'' indicated he still considers himself president and urged a u.s. trade embargo against his country as ``the only way that we can get rid of the dictators of the americas'' but said he saw no reason for military intervention
the reagan administration on thursday voiced ``unqualified support for civilian constitutional rule'' in panama after delvalle tried to fire noriega as military chief
george bush said friday that republican presidential rival pat robertson should produce evidence to back up rash allegations that the vice president said were ``scaring the american people.''
bush, in a forceful response to the former television evangelist, recounted several allegations that robertson has made against bush and his republican presidential campaign
of each he demanded, ``prove it.''
bush made the remarks in an address to state newspaper editors. he was less direct about robertson moments later in a private meeting with about two dozen fundamentalist church leaders but told them ``i believe in jesus christ as my personal savior.''
i don't like to feel there's a monolith out there'' that will back just one candidate for president, he said
bush and robertson have both targeted south carolina as a crucial battleground in their white house bids, with robertson saying he must win the march 5 primary
a group of 21 congressmen supporting bush flew into south carolina to spend the day campaigning for him as the vice president departed for atlanta after a two-day campaign swing here. appearing with the congressmen, who donned white baseball-style caps bearing the words ``bush '88,'' the vice president said, ``these guys can talk southern.''
south carolina holds its gop primary just three days before the rest of the south votes, and bush forces hope a win here will be a indicator of the super tuesday vote that follows, when one-third of the gop delegates are at stake
answering questions from the south carolina press association, bush was asked about robertson's charges in the state earlier in the week that the bush campaign had engaged in ``sleazy'' campaigning and ``dirty tricks'' against the robertson campaign. he also was asked about robertson's suggestion that bush aides engineered the release of information about the sex scandal involving evangelist jimmy swaggart to embarrass robertson
no,'' bush said. ``if you make such an allegation, the american sense of fair play says, prove it.''
i have something to do with arranging for the assembly of god (church) to bring out information two weeks before the south carolina primary?'' bush asked, referring to the swaggart charge. ``forgive me. prove it. that's all i say.''
bush asked why his questioner was smiling, saying the nature of the allegations by robertson were serious. in recounting them, bush included robertson's claim in a debate in new hampshire two weeks ago that nuclear missiles are hidden in cuba
if you think there's cuban missiles _ scaring the american people _ what's your facts?'' bush said
he also cited robertson's claim in backing out of a debate in dallas last week that questions had been leaked in advance and the audience was stacked against him. ``prove it,'' bush said
bush told the church leaders he had ``respect for life'' and had been frustrated by the administration's lack of success in supporting prayer in public schools
i know we're pluralistic. i also know we're one nation under god. i feel strongly about that,'' bush said. ``... i would not be afraid of asking god's help.''
before the editors, bush cited the developments in panama and said the united states would use military force if necessary to protect u.s. interests in panama following strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega's removal of the nation's president
noriega's gone bad, and he's proven he's trafficked in narcotics,'' bush said. ``... noriega should go and in my view he will go.''
bush referred to the american hostages in lebanon and said a problem in helping recover them has been that ``many of our sources (in lebanon) dried up because of the excessive publicity and exposure'' of the cia in the 1970s. ``that's hurt us very, very badly,'' the former cia director said
singer michael jackson showed a real fondness for flowers, both as decorations and as dinner, when he stayed at a hotel here for two weeks as he rehearsed for his national tour, workers say
jackson last week concluded his secretive rehearsals at the pensacola civic center and kicked off the tour in kansas city this week
during his stay in the presidential suite of the pensacola hilton, workers refused to talk about him, but the wall of silence lifted when he left
michael's chef, damien, visited my flower shop daily, pointed and said, `i'll have that, that and that,''' said gehrig galloway, owner of gehrig's flower shop at the hilton
spray orchids, anthuriam, birds of paradise, calla and ribrum lillies were some of the flowers ordered by damien, a chef from the los angeles hilton who joined the jackson entourage 12 weeks ago
i walked into the kitchen once when damien was cooking,'' said thaisa betts-hester, the hotel's room division manager. ``damien was cooking with an odd-looking flower with brown petals that he kept in a zip-loc bag. i asked him what was in the bag and he said, `flowers
damien ordered about $50 worth of flowers every day, but i don't know if michael ate them all.''
jackson also ordered 32 cases of evian mineral water for drinking and bathing, baby corn, fresh herbs and sun-dried tomatoes from orlando, hotel employees said. he had a portable dance floor installed in his suite's living room and was a polite guest, they said
of the famous people who have stayed at the hotel, including elizabeth taylor and bob hope, jackson ordered the most flowers, galloway said
when michael left, i went up to the presidential suite to collect the vases and they were everywhere, everywhere,'' he said
the entertainer, a vegetarian, ate a normal breakfast of orange juice and toast, but for dinner damien cooked seven different dishes for him so he would have a choice, galloway said. he said some of jackson's favorites were vegetable pizza and meatless mexican and cajun entrees
damien wrote the names of the food on cards and then decorated michael's plates and fruit trays with flowers,'' galloway said
he had a nutritionist with him all the time and what he ate each day depended on his energy output,'' said ken dyer, the hilton's executive chef
while jackson has a reputation for shyness he wasn't totally inhibited, said kathy dyson, the hotel's executive housekeeper
one night, she said, jackson sprayed a can of purple, gooey substance down the hallway of the 14th floor
veteran rocker frank zappa will be made an honorary secretary of state next month for the voter registration drives he stages at his concerts
secretary of state sherrod brown said he would present the grammy nominee with the title when zappa plays in columbus next month
brown, who talked with the singer wednesday night, said workers would have voter registration tables at zappa's march 6 concert at veterans memorial hall. he said he might do the same thing at zappa's concert in cleveland the night before
i don't know a lot of his songs, but i guess he's got a new song out about fundamentalist preachers called `jesus thinks you're a jerk,''' said brown, who confessed to seeing zappa perform as a warm-up act to chuck berry in 1971
zappa, 46, made national news in 1985 as an outspoken critic of the parents music resources center, which wanted to put warning labels on records with sexually explicit lyrics. his album ``jazz from hell'' has been nominated for grammys in jazz and rock instrumental categories
miss maryland-usa, rowann brewer, has been named miss photogenic for the miss usa pageant
ms. brewer, 23, of silver spring, was chosen thursday night by a panel of photographers after the swimsuit and evening gown competitions were taped
photographers said the brown-eyed brunette model was the clear favorite from the moment the 51 contestants began taping ``fun scenes'' around el paso and ciudad juarez, mexico, about two weeks ago
miss usa will be crowned tuesday in the nationally televised contest
britain's princess anne arrived in mozambique on friday for a five-day tour of charity projects run by the save the children fund, of which she is president
the daughter of queen elizabeth ii was greeted at maputo international airport by health minister dr. fernando vaz. the royal entourage then drove to the maputo offices of save the children fund, where the princess was briefed by the charity's field workers
the fund has been working in mozambique for the past four years, concentrating particularly on the central province of zambezia, one of the areas hit hardest by drought and th 12-year-old guerrilla war. in 1987, the fund made about $23 million in aid available for people displaced by the war
princess anne is on a three-nation tour of africa which has already taken her to uganda. she next flies to the east african nation of somalia
comedian george burns will receive an honorary doctor of humanities degree, his first ever, at a special convocation march 31, the university of hartford has announced
the 92-year-old burns has fashioned a career spanning nine decades, but has never been recognized with an honorary degree, the university said thursday
like a superb wine, he has improved remarkably with age,'' said university president stephen j. trachtenberg
fashion designer oleg cassini rode a 10-1 shot to victory at freehold raceway on the second day of his new career as a professional harness racing driver
cassini, 74, the oldest man ever to be given a driving license in harness racing, led wire to wire on hi po bay myst thursday, said track spokeswoman lauren fundler
i feel great,'' cassini said in the winner's circle. ``i am very happy to show everyone that i can be competitive.''
cassini, who said he decided to try his hand at professional racing after doing well in several charity races, was coming off an inauspicious debut on wednesday. he finished last in his first race, was thrown from his sulky in the second race, and a track physician said the designer's blood pressure was too high after the accident to compete in his final race
cassini placed fifth in another outing thursday
hi po bay myst paid $22.20, $13.40 and $7, ms. fundler said
movie producer darryl f. zanuck's daughter has filed a malicious prosecution suit against her late father's mistress, who had contested the movie czar's will
the suit, filed wednesday in indio superior court by darrylin zanuck de pineda, seeks unspecified damages against genevieve gillaizeau, 41, of new york, for alleged malicious prosecution. it also seeks unspecified damages against her attorneys for allegedly failing ``to investigate the facts and law.''
zanuck, a co-founder of the 20th century fox studio, died in 1979. according to court papers, he and ms. gillaizeau were romantically involved from 1965 to 1973 while he was married to virginia fox zanuck
ms. gillaizeau claimed zanuck suffered from alzheimer's disease and was influenced by his family to change his will in october 1973, eliminating her as an heir to his estate, valued at $3.4 million. an earlier will had left her 40 percent of the estate
ms. de pineda's suit claims the former mistress falsely accused her of exerting undue influence on her father to change the 1973 will
zanuck's will was settled jan. 8, after ms. gillaizeau provided that her claim on the estate would be given to yeshiva university in new york. the university received a $50,000 payment
italy's minister of culture says he won't approve construction of a four-lane highway adjacent to pompeii's famous ruins and across the ancient city's unexcavated necropolis
carlo vizzini, whose ministry protects and preserves archaeological sites, said thursday that ``in no case'' will he approve a project ``that not only edges, but minimally touches'' excavations at pompeii
some members of pompeii's city government proposed reducing traffic congestion in the modern city by linking two existing highways with a new one streching a little more than a mile along the famous tourist attraction
opponents argue the exhaust and viabrations will damage the ancient stones, and that the highway will prevent excavation of roman archaeological treasures in the necropolis
the eruption of mount vesuvius in a.d. 79 buried the city of pompeii
guiseppe galasso, a member of parliament from the town of pozzuoli in the shadow of the volcano, calls the highway proposal ``the kiss of death'' for the ruins
britain has agreed to accept a chinese offer of $41.3 million for british assets confiscated after the 1949 communist revolution, less than 8 percent of the sum claimed
foreign office minister timothy eggar told the house of commons on thursday that britain would pay china the equivalent of $3.5 million for property requisitioned by britain during the korean war of 1950-53
britain had originally claimed $840 million for lost assets in china, ranging from a chocolate factory and the shanghai race club to racing saddles, polo sticks, bathing huts and bonds
britain has settled claims against the world's two major communist powers
the soviet union began payment last year of about $81 million on claims originally totaling $1.8 billion from the 1917 revolution
communist bulgaria has agreed to pay britain $1.76 million. claims against albania and east germany are still unsettled
the founder of a boys acrobatic troupe that gained a national audience has been charged with 14 counts of sexual abuse involving youngsters in his organization
robert lee ``flippo'' morris, 35, was indicted wednesday on five counts of aggravated rape, six counts of aggravated sexual battery and three counts of crimes against nature, said district attorney general gary gerbitz
the charges concern nine boys, age 9 to 16, who were members of the flippo morris tumblers, said ardena garth, special child abuse prosecutor for hamilton county
over the years, the tumblers have had as many as 150 members and gained a wide following, performing at school carnivals and during halftime of university of tennessee-chattanooga basketball games. in 1982, they appeared at the knoxville world's fair and on the nbc television program ``real people.''
morris, former director of a city recreation center, started his troupe in 1972 with about 30 boys from chattanooga's inner city. his program has been so highly regarded that hamilton county juvenile court has referred some boys to it and even put some offenders in his custody
an investigation was started when the city received a complaint in july, said ms. garth. when more complaints were made, the tennessee department of human services and gerbitz's office joined the investigation
morris surrendered thursday and was jailed in lieu of $90,000 bond
the environmental protection agency said friday its contractors would begin burning leftover stocks of the banned pesticide ethylene dibromide, edb, in texas next month
the agency paid $2.8 million to buy up 328,000 gallons of edb after banning the pesticide as an emergency action in early 1984. under federal law, epa must pay for stocks of products that cannot be sold because of an emergency ban. there have been only three such actions in the agency's 16-year history of pesticide regulation
epa has stored much of the edb at douglas chemical co. in liberty, mo., and will continue to receive certain forms of the chemical there for transfer to rail cars for shipment to deer park, texas, about 15 miles east of houston
edb formulations containing methyl bromide or chloropicrin will be accepted at the rollins environmental services co. incinerator at deer park. people holding those stocks should get shipping instructions in the next two weeks, epa said
edb is used to kill worms in soil, as a fumigant for grain and fruit and as an additive for leaded gasoline. it causes cancer and birth defects, epa believes
a test burn showed that 99.999 percent of the edb was destroyed by the incinerator, the agency said
rock island has the prettiest privy around
that's the verdict of park maintenance and ground management magazine, which said this city's parks and recreation department built the outstanding outhouse in a nationwide competition
we felt they had an attractive design that fit well in the area,'' erik madisen, magazine editor, said friday in a telephone interview from appleton, wis
not only was it attractive, but it was also economical to build and accessible to the handicapped.''
the $32,000 restroom that made rock island proud is a windowless beauty of graffit-proof silicon-coated brick with ceiling vents which allow sunlight to penetrate
it had a unique design that is substantially vandalproof,'' madisen said. ``that was a big factor. everything, its faucets, fixtures, ceiling and light vents were as vandalproof as you can get.''
madisen said the magazine reviewed 22 public toilets entered from cities across the united states. for winning, the rock island parks agency will receive a plaque at the annual national institute on park and ground management convention
a 19-year-old woman who has spent a record 488 days atop a telephone pole says she's not ready yet to come down from her perch
i've only raised $6,000 so far'' for cancer research, said mellissa l. sanders as she set the record on thursday. ``it still needs to grab people's attention.''
she hopes to remain three-stories high for another month to raise $100,000. her sister, rebecca, is a cancer patient who has been in remission four years
miss sanders, of tucson, ariz., climbed the pole oct. 26, 1986. she is living in a 42-square-foot box that features a telephone, hair dresser and a plastic pool for bathing
if people see it's for a good cause and take two minutes to put some money in an envelope, i could make my goal,'' she said, ``i've seen telethons do it in about five minutes.''
even if miss sanders has not attained her goal when she descends on march 24, her mother, mauri rose sanders, says her daughter is a winner
i'm proud enough to burst. i feel like we both did it,'' said mrs. sanders, who broke a similar record in 1959 by sitting 211 days, 9 hours and 33 minutes above another indianapolis corner in a publicity stunt
the rev. hans upstad and his wife were in the middle of dinner when they were interrupted by a 5-foot-long fugitive from a college exhibit
we were sitting by the table eating our evening meal, and here this snake came crawling over the floor, its red tongue sticking out,'' said upstad. ``what would you think?''
the snake, lucille, and a companion python, mr. twister, were stolen feb. 6 from a live-snake display at concordia college, authorities said thursday
a 17-year-old boy who lived in an apartment across the hall from the upstads later admitted to police he had taken the snakes. mr. twister was recovered from the youth's apartment, but lucille remained at large until she slithered across the upstads' floor late wednesday night
upstad beat the snake with a hoe and later tossed it into a snowbank, but he learned later it was revived after neighbors alerted authorities
the snakes are favorites of concordia biology instructor elinor torstveit. she could not be reached for comment friday, but her husband, olaf, said he and another concordia biology teacher identified lucille for police and returned her to the college thursday
politicians said friday that kurt waldheim's decision not to address the main ceremony will ease tensions when austria marks the 50th anniversary of the anschluss that made it part of nazi germany
two socialist members of the cabinet had said they wouldn't attend the ceremony march ll and two others said they also might stay away if the president spoke
socialist party leaders have said it would be inappropriate for waldheim, who faces unresolved accusations of war crimes, to lead the nation in remembering atrocities of the nazi past. the party is the senior partner in austria's governing coalition
waldheim announced thursday that he was canceling the speech, and said in a television interview later: ``i thought that with this decision, which was my own initiative i might add, i would contribute to the orderly carrying out of the solemn ceremony.''
heinz fischer, socialist floor leader in parliament, said friday that waldheim's decision ``will lead to an easing of tension on march 11'' and it ``certainly was the most reasonable thing'' to do
finance minister ferdinand lacina, also a socialist, withdrew his decision to boycott the march 11 ceremony
in the television interview, waldheim repeated his intention to remain in the presidency, which is largely ceremonial, and insisted that resigning would make matters worse
he also repeated criticism of a report on his wartime activities by an international panel of historians, declaring it ``full of contradictions'' and errneous presumptions
waldhim concealed his world war ii service as a german army lieutenant in the balkans until accusations arose during the presidential campaign in 1986 that he had committed war crimes
the united states put the former u.n. secretary-general on a ``watch list'' of undesirable aliens last year, and in september the government appointed the historians at waldheim's request
they said in their report this month that waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to atrocities, knew of them and did not try to prevent them. the historians said they found no proof that he committed war crimes, but left the question of personal guilt open
the vietnamese government has agreed to repatriate the remains of what it believes may be 20 american servicemen missing from the vietnam war, the pentagon announced friday
the remains will be delivered to u.s. military officials in hanoi on march 2 and transported to the army's central identification laboratory in honolulu, hawaii, for identification, the pentagon said in a statement
the u.s. government appreciates the initiative taken by vietnam to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing humanitarian issue,'' the pentagon said
the upcoming repatriation would be the fourth largest such transfer since the end of the war. the largest occurred in august 1985, when the vietnamese returned 26 remains at once
there are currently 2,404 americans still listed as missing in indochina as a result of the vietnam war, of whom 1,767 are listed as missing in either north or south vietnam. all told, the remains of 152 americans have been repatriated to the united states and subsequently identified by the laboratory since the end of the war
the upcoming transfer would be the third since retired army gen. john vessey traveled to hanoi last august as a special presidential emissary, hoping to step up the process of accounting for missing americans
william harold cox, a federal judge who enraged civil rights advocates with his remarks about blacks but presided over a 1967 trial that convicted eight klansmen of murdering three civil rights workers, has died at the age of 87
cox died of natural causes thursday night at his home here, a family spokesman said
he was a real colorful and effective-type judge who was his own man,'' former gov. bill waller said of cox. ``he was strictly independent in interpreting the law and in carrying out court proceedings as he wanted to do it. he left his mark on the judiciary of our state.''
gov. ray mabus agreed, saying cox ``had an impact on mississippi.''
cox, the son of a sunflower county sheriff, built a successful practice in corporate and civil law before he became a u.s. district court judge in 1961. he was an active judge until july 1983
in the course of his judicial career, cox was attacked by the national assocation for the advancement of colored people and others for his remarks about blacks, segregation and civil rights
during a hearing on a voter discrimination suit in 1964, cox said: ``i don't know who is telling these negroes they can push people around just by getting into a line and acting like a bunch of chimpanzees.''
the remark triggered a demand for his impeachment by u.s. sen. jacob javits, r-n.y., and u.s. rep. peter rodino, d-n.j., but there never was an impeachment proceeding
cox also disdained the civil rights act of 1964 and said in court, ``i don't know anybody down here who don't oppose it.''
when a civil rights attorney complained in 1971 that a decades-old mural behind the bench depicted blacks as serfs to white people, cox retorted loudly, ``well, it will remain in this court whether you like it or not.''
in 1967, cox presided over one of the most famous cases of the decade _ the trial of eight klansmen charged in the 1964 murders of three civil rights workers in philadelphia, miss
after the jury seemed deadlocked for two days, cox ordered them to come up with a verdict. the jury found the eight klansmen guilty
survivors include a son and a daughter
cuban immigrants who commit crimes in the united states can be shipped back to their homeland, even if they have obtained u.s. citizenship, a top immigration and naturalization service official said
the u.s.-cuban immigration agreement reached in november does not limit those eligible for deportation to the 2,500 cuban detainees in federal prisons, ins commissioner alan nelson said thursday
his comments appeared in friday's editions of the miami herald
nelson attended an academic conference in washington, d.c., examining the 1980 mariel boatlift of cubans to the united states and the status of cuban detainees in u.s. prisons
any cuban who commits a crime, whether he is a resident or citizen of the united states, and if the law so sees fit, can be deported,'' nelson said
advocates for cuban prisoners immediately criticized nelson's statements
cuban deportation and what nelson is doing, representing the government's politics, is scandalous and truly unjustifiable,'' said steven donziger, a member of the cuban detainees support coalition in atlanta
the immigration pact with cuba allows the deportation of 2,500 mariel detainees who have committed crimes in the united states. in turn, the united states agreed to allow about 20,000 cubans and 3,000 political prisoners to immigrate every year
news of the agreement triggered riots by cuban detainees at prisons in atlanta and oakdale, la
the pact was aimed at normalizing immigration, nelson said
there would be no purpose in sending 2,500 refugees back now and not be able to deport anyone else in the future for committing crimes,'' he said
the widow of challenger astronaut michael smith cannot sue the government for $1.5 billion in damages because her husband was on military duty when the space shuttle exploded, killing him and six others, a federal judge has ruled
u.s. district judge patricia fawsett cited earlier court decisions holding that military personnel or their dependents could not sue the government for injury or death while on active service
smith, the challenger's pilot, was a navy captain who was assigned to nasa in 1981
smith's death occurred during activity incident to his military service,'' the judge said in removing the federal government as a defendant in the suit filed by jane j. smith
the judge also agreed with government lawyers who argued that military personnel ``receive generous statutory veterans' disability and death benefits.''
mrs. smith's lawyers had argued that her husband was not on regular military assignment and had no military duties at the time of his death
the order, filed this week in u.s. district court in orlando, maintained morton thiokol inc. as the principal defendant in the civil lawsuit. morton thiokol built the solid-fuel booster rocket blamed for the explosion that destroyed the space shuttle on liftoff at cape canaveral on jan. 28, 1986
the shuttle fleet has been grounded since then
the families of the other six victims have accepted financial settlements, four from morton thiokol and the government and two from morton thiokol alone
ms. fawsett also dismissed one count in the smith lawsuit seeking to bar morton thiokol from supplying nasa with any other booster rockets. the court, she said, had no jurisdiction in any of the counts involving the federal government
in a separate action on thursday, the judge denied a request by mrs. smith and her attorneys to transfer her lawsuit from orlando to the federal court in richmond, va. the judge did not explain the order
mrs. smith had sought to move the case because of a heavy caseload in the court system here and because she now lives in virginia beach, va
kerry nesbit, a spokeswoman for mrs. smith's lawyer, william f. maready, said the lawyer was considering appealing the judge's order monday dismissing the federal government from the lawsuit
another defendant named in the smith lawsuit is lawrence b. mulloy, manager of nasa's solid booster rocket program at marshall space flight center at the time of the challenger disaster. federal attorneys have filed a motion seeking his removal from the case, but ms. fawsett has issued no decision
u.s. justice department spokeswoman amy brown said the government contends that mulloy was acting in an official capacity for an agency of the government, and therefore cannot be sued
five wild cougars or mountain lions from texas will be released in a forest in northeastern florida to see if the closely related but endangered florida panther can survive there, wildlife officials said friday
if the re-introduction plan succeeds, the florida panther could be roaming the osceola national forest by the next decade, they said
the big cats will be fitted and radio collars and sterilized before they are released in april or may in the forest north of lake city, said tom logan, chief of the bureau of wildlife research for the florida game and fresh water fish commission
the osceola national forest was selected because of its size, habitat and food base. the surviving population of florida panthers now is largely confined to southern florida in the everglades and big cypress national preserve, although sightings have been reported around lake okeechobee and inland from cape canaveral
it is impossible to use florida panthers for the first phases of the project because only a few dozen of them survive, logan said
we don't have enough to experiment with,'' logan said
after the one-year experiment, the five cougars will be removed from the area and the second phase of the project will begin, with the release of captive-born cougars or hybrid offspring of a florida panther and a cougar
so far, attempts to mate big guy, a florida panther injured several years ago by a car, with female cougars at white oak plantation near yulee have been unsuccessful
he's more aggressive than in past years. we have our fingers crossed,'' said chris belden, an official with the panther project
if the first two phases of the project are successful, the final phase would be the introduction of florida panthers into the area
each phase of the proposed experiment is structured to enable us to identify and deal with any problems that might come up. and the radio collars would enable us to locate and remove any of the cats at any time we believe is necessary,'' logan said
the plan calls for livestock owners to be paid for any losses caused by the cats
wildlife officials said they plan no special hunting season restrictions for the benefit of the cats, but said it is unlikely that people will ever see the animals
they are very reclusive animals and the likelihood of interaction is very, very slim,'' said logan
justice anthony m. kennedy will not take part in the supreme court's deliberations on the constitutionality of a federal law authorizing independent counsels to investigate alleged crimes by government officials, a court spokeswoman said friday
spokeswoman toni house said kennedy, who joined the court on feb. 18, removed himself from consideration of the case without stating a reason
his absence creates the possibility of a 4-4 tie when the court's ruling, expected by july, is announced
if that occurs, the deadlock would have the effect of nullifying the law because it would uphold a decision by the u.s. circuit court of appeals here that declared the statute unconstitutional last month
the appeals court struck down the watergate-era law on grounds that it gives presidential appointment power to the federal courts. the law authorizes a federal court to appoint a special prosecutor when the attorney general recommends an independent investigation of a high-ranking official accused of a crime
the supreme court will hear arguments in the case april 26 in an appeal by independent counsel alexia morrison, who is investigating former justice department official theodore b. olson on charges he lied to congress
the perjury conviction of former white house aide michael k. deaver also could stand or fall depending on the court ruling
kennedy's decision not to take part in the case prompted speculation that he may have been concerned about old ties to president reagan and his aides, including deaver, who have been targets of independent counsel investigations
kennedy did some work for reagan when he was governor of california. at the time, kennedy was a lawyer in sacramento, calif., later to be named a federal appeals court judge there
two other investigations that could be affected by the high court's ruling on the special prosecutor law are a probe of the iran-contra affair and another that resulted in the feb. 11 conviction for illegal lobbying of former white house aide lyn nofziger
but the special prosecutors in both those investigations received parallel authority from attorney general edwin meese iii that could insulate their investigations from the constitutional attack on the independent counsel law. there is uncertainty in both cases because the investigations began before the back-up authority was conferred
a new study shows that sugarbeet production costs in 1984 were lowest in the midwest and highest in some western areas, the agriculture department said friday
the study involved seven regions that produce nearly all the u.s. sugarbeets. about 8,700 farms produce beets in the seven regions. overall, the department's economic research service reported that it cost an average of $30.30 per net ton to produce beets. the range, however, was between $24 and $35 per ton
about 60 percent of the 1984 u.s. sugarbeet crop was produced at a cost below the u.s. average price support of $31.63 per ton,'' the report said. ``the producers received a weighted average price of $33.90 a net ton, ranging from $23.30 in region 3 (colorado, nebraska and southeastern wyoming) to $37.10 in region 6 (eastern idaho).''
most beet producers in region 3 operated at a loss because of the closing of several processing plants by the great western sugar co., the report said
the study of 1984 costs, by region, showed:
_region 1, michigan and ohio, 10.8 percent of the u.s. sugarbeet acreage; government support of $27.79 per net ton; actual price received by growers, $32.95 per ton; average cost of production, $24.02 per ton
_region 2, minnesota and eastern north dakota, 35.2 percent of the u.s. acreage; support of $32.24 per ton; actual price received by growers, $36 per ton; average cost of production, $25.66 per ton
_region 3, colorado, nebraska and souteastern wyoming, 12.8 percent of the acreage; support of $31.23 per ton; actual price received by growers, $23.30 per ton; average cost of production, $28.06 per ton
_region 4, new mexico and texas, was not included in the study
_region 5, montana, northwestern wyoming and northwestern north dakota, 5 percent of the acreage; support of $31.37 per ton; actual price received by growers, $35.40 per ton; average cost of production, $34.26 per ton
_region 6, eastern idaho, 7.4 percent of the acreage; support of $31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $37.10 per ton; average cost of production, $34.87 per ton
_region 7, western idaho and oregon, 6.5 percent of the acreage; support of $31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $36.90 per ton; average cost of production, $34.68 per ton
_region 8, california, 18.8 percent of the acreage; support of $32.98 per ton; actual price received by growers, $35.10 per ton; average cost of production, $34.57 per ton
a former stockbroker was sentenced friday to 120 weekends in jail and fined $10,000 for his role in the insider trading scandal that involved a wall street journal reporter
peter brant also was placed on probation for five years and ordered to do 750 hours of community service. u.s. district judge charles e. stewart did not say what the community service would be
brant, 35, a former broker at kidder peabody &amp; co., pleaded guilty in 1984 to conspiracy and securities fraud. he admitted his part in a scheme to trade stock in 24 companies on the basis of information that was to appear in the journal's ``heard on the street'' column
the material brant received came from r. foster winans, a journal reporter who wrote the column. during a five-month period, the scheme netted almost $700,000, of which winans got $31,000 and brant got most of the rest
winans, whose mail, wire and securities fraud convictions were upheld by the u.s. supreme court last november, is serving an 18-month sentence. brant's sentencing was delayed pending the high court decision and because of his cooperation in other cases
brant's lawyer, stephen weiner, pleaded for leniency, asking stewart to consider ``the brutal price already paid'' by his client. brant, who now works for a telecommunications company in west palm beach, fla., has agreed to stay out of the securities business for life
the judge said he found the defendant ``at least as guilty as mr. winans and perhaps more so.''
stewart could have sentenced brant to 15 years in prison and fined him $30,000, but he took into account assistant u.s. attorney carl loewenson's request that he consider brant's cooperation in prosecuting two major criminal cases
one case loewenson referred to was the prosecutions of winans, winans' roommate david carpenter, and former kidder peabody broker kenneth p. felis who had roles in the wall street journal trading scheme
felis is serving six months of weekends and carpenter was placed on probation and directed to do community service
the second case involved former lawyer david w.c. clark, convicted last november of embezzling more than $3.7 million from clients from 1980 to 1984
clark, who died of chronic alcoholism a few days before he was to be sentenced, used the embezzled funds to trade securities based on the insider information brant passed on to him from the journal column
a plea of innocent to three misdemeanor counts of vehicular manslaughter was entered friday for the driver of a runaway bus that killed three people and injured 15
salvador orogo was at the wheel of a commuter bus on jan. 19 when it pulled out of a terminal during rush hour and plowed through a crosswalk filled with pedestrians
defense attorney gilbert eisenberg entered the pleas for orogo, 53, who was not in court. he is free on $10,000 bail
orogo surrendered thursday after an arrest warrant was issued. district attorney arlo smith said charges were filed when ``it was determined that the cause of the incident was negligent operation of the bus by orogo.''
orogo said after the crash that his accelerator had jammed and his brakes had failed, but investigators said the bus showed no mechanical defects
authorities said there was no justification for felony charges in the case because there was no allegation that alcohol or drugs played a role
michael dukakis jabbed gingerly at richard gephardt on trade and taxes friday, saying the 1981 tax cut his democratic presidential rival voted for was ``one of the biggest mistakes in recent american history.''
dukakis refrained from directly attacking gephardt as he pressed his campaign for southern support in the multi-state primaries and caucuses on march 8
no culprits,'' the massachusetts governor said with a smile after delivering his speech to an overflow crowd at the lyndon johnson school of public affairs without uttering gephardt's name. ``just good, strong, positive efforts to get this country moving again.''
dukakis devoted much of his speech to his campaign message of ``good jobs and real opportunity'' for all, with special emphasis on the need for education and research. ``it's going to take hard workers, not high rollers, to get america moving again,'' he said
he spoke as he moved through a three-day southern swing in advance of the march 8 primaries, most of which will be in southern or border states. aides said he has begun airing television commercials in targeted areas of florida and texas, as well as in the baltimore area
if gephardt's name was not mentioned, dukakis' meaning was clear when he said in his speech that ``building walls around america'' was a mistake. ``we tried that 60 years ago and it gave us the worst depression in our history,'' he said
gephardt favors trade legislation that would give the president authority to retaliate against trading partners that failed to open up their markets
the missouri congressman also voted for the 1981 reaganomics tax cut, which passed with substantial help from southern democrats in the house
in seven years that one mistake transformed our nation from the world's largest creditor into the world's largest debtor,'' dukakis said
reaganomics isn't an economic theory; it's theft from our children,'' he said. ``it's a felony against the future and it has played the hard-working, tax-paying families of middle america for fools.''
the governor's speech reflected at least a temporary decision to remain above the fray in an increasingly fierce rhetorical battle. gephardt sharply attacked dukakis earlier this week and the governor said on thursday his rival ``better watch out'' if he persisted
in his speech, dukakis said he has no ``southern strategy'' for the primaries on march 8. ``the people of texas and florida and virginia aren't voting for a zip code. they're voting for a president of the united states,'' he said
but at the same time the massachusetts governor sought to re-establish a political bond created 28 years ago when john kennedy and lyndon johnson were on the winning ticket in the national election
together, john kennedy and lyndon johnson inspired a whole generation,'' he said. ``ten months ago, in the spirit of jfk and lbj, we launched a campaign for the future of america.''
u.s. companies surveyed by the government reported a loss of $23.8 billion in 1986 because of foreign piracy of u.s. patents, trademarks and copyrights, according to a u.s. international trade commission study released friday
the itc said actual losses are much greater because not all companies filled out questionaires on the subject
the commission said it received responses from 431 companies. the questionaire was sent to 736 u.s. companies, including all those on the fortune 500 list
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said that the annual drain on u.s. companies because of ``inadequate protection of intellectual property'' actually may run as high as $43 billion to $61 billion
the failure of our trading partners to provide effective protection for intellectual property is a severe and growing problem that distorts trade,'' yeutter told a news conference called to release the study
the report came in advance of discussions next week in geneva on developing a new international code to protect patents, trademarks and copyrights. the talks are being held under the auspices of the 95-nation general agreement on tariffs and trade (gatt), which is at work on a new set of global trade rules
the united states is seeking much tighter protection for intellectual property rights and unified standards
industries hardest hit by intellecutal-property piracy include sceintific, medical and photographic equipment, computers and software, electronics, entertainment, motor vehicles and pharmaceuticals, yeutter said
nations cited most frequently as having inadequate protection of intellecutal property included mexico, brazil, taiwan, korean and japan
however, yeutter declined to single out any particular country as the worst offender, telling reporters ``it's not just developing countries. there is ample opportunity to improve among most of the nations of the world.''
piracy of u.s. movies and musical recordings is a major problem area, the study said
jack valenti, president of the motion picture association of america, told the news conference: ``piracy is a toxic waste ... it is life threatening. it is a global war and we are fighting it on every front.''
the commission, which undertook the study at yeutter's request, said its figures represent only a partial approximation of u.s. losses from piracy
the data collected by the commission's questionaire cannot be projected to u.s. industry as a whole with any statistical validity,'' the report said. ``the universe of all u.s. businesses is unknown (and) those companies responding do not represent a random sample.'' udf official operating freely, sted not in hiding. ^by david crary</note>
police on friday arrested 14 white women protesting the crackdown on black opposition groups, and authorities silenced the last high-ranking united democratic front official who was operating freely
at the university of cape town, 2,000 students and staff assembled to denounce the government's bans on political activity by the udf, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition, and 17 other groups
the battle has only just begun,'' said the rev. allan boesak, one of the udf's founders, at the campus rally. ``we have decided we will resist. our commitment starts right now.''
the 14 members of black sash civil rights group were arrested as they carried placards in durban. they were taken to police headquarters, told they were being charged with participating in illegal gathering, then released
azhar cachalia, treasurer of the united democratic front, was served with a restriction order prohibiting him from speaking to the press, publishing any statement or participating in activities of the udf or other anti-apartheid organizations
cachalia had been the only udf executive committee member not in hiding, in custody or restricted from udf activities. the 5-year-old coalition has 600 affiliates with about 2 million members
the government wednesday banned the udf and 17 other opposition groups from political activity, and issued restrictive orders against 18 senior black leaders, including udf co-presidents archie gumede and albertina sisulu
also on friday, the pietermaritzburg chamber of commerce met with law and order minister adriaan vlok to discuss the feuding between udf supporters and members of the zulu political organization, inkatha. more than 400 people have been killed in the past year in fighting between the groups for control of black areas in natal province
with the udf banned from all activity, and its leaders restricted, observers predicted the violence would continue and inkatha would have an advantage
chamber of commerce manager paul van uytrecht was quoted friday as saying that peace talks sponsored by his group could not proceed
inkatha, with an estimated 1.5 million members, was not affected by the new bans
the kwazulu homeland assembly, headed by inkatha president mangosuthu buthelezi, condemned the restrictions. but at the same time, it asked the government to give the homeland's pro-inkatha police force jurisdiction over all natal townships
the weekly mail, a newspaper the government has threatened with closure, quoted an unidentified udf representative friday as saying the crackdown ``simply gives buthelezi a free hand to gain control of the whole of natal.''
musa zondi, an inkatha delegate at the chamber of commerce peace talks, said the restrictions ``dash all hopes for the talks. the udf is a crucial element in the search for peace.''
police said three blacks were killed in violence in natal late thursday, but gave no details
at the ktc squatter camp near cape town, rival black factions shot at each other and burned shacks early friday, resulting in at least one death and five injuries, police and witnesses said
the fighting was between militant youths and the squatter camp management committee, both considered anti-apartheid groups. about 20 shacks were burned during the battle
the fighting in the camp began last month, and hundreds of shacks have been burned. in 1986, 70,000 people in the area lost their homes and scores of people died in battles between conservative ``vigilantes'' and the squatter-camp groups
this year the fighting is between two groups who fought together against the ``vigilantes'' in 1986, and appears to involve an attempt by the militant youths to gain more power in the administration of the squatter camp
prime minister yitzhak shamir urged secretary of state george shultz to move slowly on palestinian self-rule, and 15 prominent arabs didn't show up for a meeting friday night to which shultz had invited them
shultz went to a hotel in arab east jerusalem, stood in the floodlit courtyard and read a statement suggesting the palestinians were fearful of working with the united states
peacemaking is difficult,'' he read. ``peace has its enemies, but peace is a necessary ingredient to a decent life. even small steps toward peace can be significant in moving beyond distrust and hatred.''
shultz is here pursuing new american proposals for middle east peace
the no-show was not new for him. a group of palestinians also refused to meet him in jerusalem during a visit last october
in the statement he read friday night against a backdrop of moslem evening prayers in the distance, shultz still pursued the goal of bringing palestinians into middle east peace talks
opportunity knocks loudly on your door,'' he read out in the hotel courtyard. ``now is the time to get to work. we have a workable plan, and we are ready to commit our efforts to it. the time is right, together, to make decisions of historic proportions.''
earlier friday, several palestinians issued statements saying they would not attend the meeting. the palestine liberation organization had told palestinians from the west bank and gaza strip, where riots began more than 11 weeks ago, not to meet with shultz in jerusalem
mr. shultz seems to be trying to make a political statement by insisting on a meeting here: that the palestinian problem is in the context of civil, religious and perhaps economic rights,'' said sari nusseibeh, a professor at bir zeit university in the west bank
by saying i will not attend, i'm saying this is wrong. the problem is one of the national rights of the palestinians.''
hanna siniora, editor of the newspaper al fajr, said he told shultz ``i regret i cannot accept because the palestinian people have decided that we have to have a delegation reflecting the true composition of the palestinian people.'' siniora conferred with the secretary earlier this month in washington
shultz met on friday with the three principal members of israel's coalition government _ shamir, foreign minister shimon peres and defense minister yitzhak rabin
he put ``no pressure whatsoever on shamir,'' an israeli official said, on condition of anonymity. the official said shamir urged shultz to move slowly on self-rule in the west bank and gaza strip
during a two-hour meeting, shamir told shultz there should be ``a time of testing'' of up to three years before negotiations on a final settlement in the occupied territories, the official said. the american plan calls for negotiaitons on an overall settlement by december
the attempt by shamir to keep alive the 1978 camp david formula for interim palestinian self-rule puts shultz in the middle, between israel and the arabs. egypt and jordan have declared the process out of date
shamir also insisted that palestinian ``autonomy,'' which would involve some self-rule but not statehood, not be ``accelerated'' because of the current violence, the israeli official said
peres, shamir's partner and rival in the ``national unity'' coalition, said he found shultz ``open-minded and very attentive, looking for fresh ideas and information.''
he brought workable proposals,'' the foreign minister said.``we have some workable proposals, and for that reason we have started to work.''
rabin, the defense minister, said arab demonstrators should have ``no illusion that by force they can change the position of israel.''
a solution is possible only through negotiations involving palestinians who live in the west bank and gaza, along with jordan and israel, he said
he told reporters: ``they are going to suffer more than anybody else by the violence. ... by military means we can achieve tranquility, but not a solution.''
peres and rabin represent the center-left labor party, which for 20 years has proposed that israel yield some of the occupied territory as part of an overall peace settlement. shamir and his conservative likud bloc oppose trading land for peace, which shultz has suggested
shultz flies to amman on saturday to meet with prime minister zaid rifai of jordan, then to damascus to see the syrian president, hafez assad
he also will travel to cairo during his five-day shuttle, for which jerusalem is the base. assault</head>
a young white man sentenced earlier this week to work for the naacp by a judge who hoped to end a ``cycle of hate'' faced new charges of ethnic intimidation friday for allegedly punching and shouting slurs at a pregnant woman
it's very disappointing,'' cook county circuit judge stuart nudelman said of the new charges against james kalafut jr., 21. ``i've done these type of community-service sentences before and they've been successful
unfortunately, perhaps this one may not be. that remains to be seen.''
kalafut was back in nudelman's court friday to face charges of ethnic intimidation, battery and violation of his court-supervised sentence, accused of punching a pregnant woman in the stomach and shouting ethnic slurs at her
the woman has an hispanic surname
kalafut had pleaded guilty tuesday to ethnic intimidation and aggravated assault for an aug. 16, 1987, incident in which a group of whites brandishing baseball bats, hurling bottles and shouting racial slurs chased two blacks from their neighborhood
nudelman said kalafut had been ``taught to hate blacks'' and sentenced him to perform 200 hours of community service for the national association for the advancement of colored people. he also sentenced the young man to one year of court supervision
the judge said he imposed the sentence in an effort ``to stop the cycle of hate.'' however, the sentencing plan was put on hold and will be set aside if kalafut is convicted on the new charges, the judge said
nudelman said friday that if the younger kalafut is found guilty of the new charges, ``the young man unfortunately will be in a position where he may need an alternative form of punishment, such as some time in the county jail.''
defense attorney barry silver said kalafut had met with naacp officials and worked out a plan to collect and distribute clothing to poor families and victims of house fires
the judge transferred the two new charges to judge leo holt, saying, ``it wouldn't be fair for me to hear them.'' a trial before holt was tentatively scheduled for march 28
silver said the new charges were trumped up and said he believes kalafut was framed because of his guilty plea and sentence in the earlier incident
i interviewed two witnesses who tell me he never touched the girl,'' who lived nearby, silver said. ``i'm told there has been bad feelings between the families for quite some time.''
the charges stem from an argument late wednesday in front of the kalafut home between virginia flores, 27, who is 4{ months pregnant, and kenneth kolokowski, 25
the couple said kalafut came out of his house, yelled at them and then got into a struggle with kolokowski, said police officer al murphy
kalafut then allegedly punched ms. flores in the stomach and shouted an ethnic slur, murphy quoted the couple as saying
the defendant apparently considers ms. flores to be of hispanic origin, although ms. flores told police she is primarily of irish heritage with some indian background, murphy said
she suffered minor injuries but her fetus was not harmed, said a spokesman for holy cross hospital, where she was treated and released
the couple also told police the defendant's father, james kalafut sr., 45, came out of the house during the confrontation wearing pajama bottoms and exposed himself, murphy said
silver said friday the allegation was false
the elder kalafut, charged with ethnic intimidation and battery, faces an april 14 court hearing
kalafut's teen-age brother, larry, was sentenced last march to six years in prison for firebombing the home of a black family who moved into gage park, a predominantly white neighborhood
nicaragua came out in support of panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega on friday in the showdown over the leadership of the central american nation
venezuela backed eric arturo delvalle, who was removed from office early friday by legislators a few hours after he ordered noriega to step down
in cartagena, colombia, the foreign ministers of eight other latin american nations attending a regional meeting stayed non-committal, saying they were studying the situation
in bogota, ex-presidents alfonso lopez michelsen of colombia, daniel oduber of costa rica and carlos andres perez of venezuela said they had agreed earlier with noriega on a plan for the ``democratization'' of panama under which they said noriega would promise to retire as armed forces commander to allow free elections next year
but the three former leaders said the events in panama had aggravated the situation in the country
in managua, nicaraguan president daniel ortega offered his support to noriega and accused the u.s. government of trying to destroy the nation's sovereignty, the government-owned sandinista newspaper reported friday
the president of nicaragua assured gen. noriega that the panamanian people, facing threats, blackmail and the danger of american troop intervention, could count on the militant and combative solidarity of the people of sandino,'' a government communique printed in the newspaper said
the sandinista communique said ortega spoke with noriega on the telephone thursday night and offered ``unconditional solidarity in these moments when the american government is trying to kill the spirit of torrijos to save the sovereignty of panama.''
brig. gen. omar torrijos, the nationalist leader who staged a 1968 coup, became a national hero by working out the transfer to panama in 1999 of the american-built panama canal. he died in a plane crash in 1981
the sandinista links with torrijos and the panamanian government go back to before the 1978-79 revolutionary war in nicaragua. torrijos' government sent combatants and arms to the leftist sandinistas, who overthrew anastasio somoza
weeks after noriega's problems broke out last june, ortega flew to panama as a show of support. ortega said the united states was engaged in a conspiracy to break the 1977 canal treaties
the eight latin american foreign ministers attending the meeting in colombia discussed the events in panama at the request of panamaian foreign minister jorge abadia
we are being informed about developments in panama,'' said colombian foreign minister julio londono paredes, but he declined to make any further comment
abadia had asked thursday that his fellow ministers of argentina, brazil, colombia, mexico, peru, uruguay and venezuela should offer their solidarity to panama against ``a worldwide disinformation campaign.''
abadia told them that drug-dealing charges against noriega ``do not correspond with the facts in panama'' and he denounced ``maneuvers'' by the united states to keep its troops in control of the panama canal beyond the year 1999, when a treaty stipulates that panama will take over control of the waterway
abadia returned hurriedly to panama on friday
venezuelan foreign minister german nava carrillo said in cartagena that his government supports ``the democracy, sovereignty and independence of panama'' but warned that ``the military forces should be subject and obedient to civilian power.''
in caracas, the venezuelan government expressed support for delvalle's decision to oust noriega and called on the central american nation's armed forces to respect such a decision
the venezuelan government reaffirms its unequivocal position on the respect that the military forces in panama owe to the civilian power, as dictated by the panama's constitution,'' said a communique issued thursday night by the miraflores government palace
the venezuelan government expresses categorically its support to all the efforts aimed at strenthening the panamanian democratic process,'' the brief communique said
a rookie policeman was killed in his patrol car friday by three point-blank shots to the head in what the police commissioner said was an assassination meant to intimidate a crime witness
officer edward byrne, 22, was shot as he sat in a marked patrol car in queens, guarding the home of a threatened witness in a drug case. the house had been firebombed twice, allegedly by dealers
two men drove up to the patrol car at 3:30 a.m. one man got out and fired up to five shots into the patrol car, said police commissioner benjamin ward
the gunman had approached the car ``in a way not likely to alarm the police officer that anything was amiss, and then when he was so close that he could not miss, and moving so rapidly that the police officer would not be able to respond defensively, fired into the car,'' the commissioner said
byrne was the first officer killed in the line of duty this year, said police spokesman sgt. peter sweeney. three city police officers and one transit police officer were killed in 1987
ward acknowledged that the shooting could have been an act of random violence, but said ``it smacks more of a deliberate assassination attempt.''
he described the shooting as ``an attempt to intimidate not just that witness but all of you, and all of the people of this city and this country to say that if you cooperate with criminal justice something is going to happen to you.''
the resident of the house is a witness in impending cases against area drug dealers
the house was firebombed twice in november by drug dealers who believed the man had complained to police about drug dealing on his street, police said
southeast queens has become a hub of crack trafficking and drug-related violence in the last two years. many shootings in the area are the result of constant turf wars between drug cartels, ward said
authorities assigned a 24-hour police guard to the house after the firebombings. ward said the witness has also received other threats against his life for cooperating with authorities
he said assigning a single officer was standard practice. the patrol car was provided for the officer's convenience because of the weather
ward said having two officers in the patrol car would not make a difference in officers' safety ``if an assassin decides to arrive.''
byrne was single and was a second generation police officer; his father, matthew byrne, headed the department's legal bureau from 1972 to 1976
a state judge friday formally dismissed 22-year-old triple murder charges against rubin ``hurricane'' carter a week after prosecutors said they would not seek a third trial of the former boxer
i'm joyous with the result and deeply satisfied that justice finally has been done and the charges dismissed,'' said carter's attorney, myron beldock, after superior court judge ralph v. martin signed the order dismissing the indictment against carter and john artis
carter had served 19 years in prison before a federal judge in 1985 voided his second conviction and ordered his release on grounds that the conviction was tainted by racial bias and the witholding of information from the defense
carter, who has been living in seclusion, could not be reached for comment. beldock would not release his telephone number or whereabouts, but said his client would meet with reporters monday
prosecutors had said dismissal of the charges was justified because of the passage of time since the 1966 killings, problems finding witnesses, court decisions descrediting previous testimony and the burden posed by a third prosecution
they also cited the time served in prison by the defendants. artis, who was paroled in 1981, is serving a six-year term on an unrelated drug conviction
carter and artis were convicted in 1967, but given a new trial in 1976 after two witnesses recanted. they were convicted again, and the verdicts were upheld by the state supreme court
the federal judge's decision releasing carter from prison was upheld by an appellate court, and the u.s. supreme court refused to accept an appeal by prosecutors
carter, 50, and artis, 41, had been accused of killing a bartender and two patrons of a paterson bar. the victims were white; and the gunmen, like carter and artis, were black
hours earlier, a black paterson bartender had been shot to death by a white man. prosecutors theorized that the later killings were in retaliation
celebrities such as muhammed ali and actress ellen burstyn took up carter's cause, viewing him as a symbol of racial injustice. bob dylan wrote and sang ``hurricane,'' a ballad about the boxer's case
americans' incomes rose 0.3 percent in january, a moderate increase that matched the gain in consumer spending during the month, the government reported friday
the commerce department said that incomes and spending both rose 0.3 percent, following identical 0.7 percent advances in both categories during december
the gains were taken as positive signs that consumer spending, while not growing as briskly as it did during the early years of the economic recovery, will at least expand enough this year to keep the economy out of a recession
consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity, is being closely monitored following the october stock market collapse
these figures support our impression that the economy will slow down this year but continue to move ahead,'' said roger brinner, an economist with data resources inc. of lexington, mass
consumer spending, after adjusting for inflation, fell at an annual rate of 3.1 percent in the fourth quarter, the biggest decline in more than seven years. brinner predicted that much of this decline would be reversed in the current january-march quarter, in part, because auto sales have rebounded
wages and salaries, the key component of the income category, increased $12.4 billion in january, more than double the $5.6 billion december increase. this gain included a $2 billion increase in payrolls at manufacturing companies, which followed a $1.1 billion december increase
allen sinai, chief economist for the boston co., said the rise in incomes, while below previous months, was still strong enough to support further increases in spending. he noted that incomes in manufucturing have risen 4.7 percent in the past 12 months, compared to growth of just 1.8 percent in the previous 12 months
we have a picture of a consumer with adequate income growth who has become a bit more cautious and is more likely to save, but is not going to stop spending and drive the economy into a recession,'' sinai said
americans' savings rate, savings as a percent of disposable income, rose to 4.7 percent in january, 0.3 percentage point higher than the december level
the 0.3 percent increase in spending reflected an annual rate of increase of $10 billion with almost all of the strength coming in the services category
purchases of durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, edged up $200 million compared to a $12.3 billion december advance. purchases of non-durable goods fell $700 million in contrast to an increase of $5.3 billion in december
the services category, which includes housing expenses, shot up at an annual rate of $10.6 billion in january, much faster than the $4.2 billion december rise. some analysts said this reflected in large part a big jump in inflation in the services sector during the month
in a separate report friday, the labor department said that medical care services rose 0.8 percent, the steepest increase in two years, while rental costs and other service charges also posted big gains
in january and december, personal income was affected by a variety of special factors, including pay raises for federal employees, cost-of-living adjustments for social security recipients and swings in farm subsidy payments
farm incomes fell $10.5 billion in january, erasing a $10.4 billion december increase. excluding the big swings in government subsidies, farm incomes would have increased $500 million in janaury following a $1.5 billion december decline
after-tax incomes rose 0.6 percent in january following a 0.7 percent december increase
panama's ambassador to washington said he refused an order friday by military strong man miguel antonio noriega to resign and would continue to serve as envoy under u.s.-recognized president eric arturo delvalle
ambassador juan sosa also said a u.s. trade embargo might be necessary to depose noriega and acknowledged that delvalle has no support in the military
sosa declared his support for delvalle hours before the state department said it would continue to recognize him even though he was ousted by panama's national assembly after he tried to fire noriega as military chief
department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said the u.s. government still considered sosa panama's legal ambassador
sosa said at a news conference that he expects noriega to appoint a rival ambassador, but he said later that he would retain his office with the full backing of his embassy staff in washington
sosa said he had not contacted other panamanian envoys around the world and did not know whether others would support delvalle
he said, however, he expects official recognition of delvalle's government from several other countries
the envoy said he told noriega in a telephone call friday that as a member of delvalle's republican party, he still considered him president of the country. noriega asked for his resignation and he refused, sosa said
he noted that as ambassador for four months he had opposed economic sanctions against panama, ``but there are some times in the history of nations when economic sanctions (are needed) to get the country back on track.''
we certainly hope that not only the u. s. but the whole hemisphere will support panama and if necessary apply economic sanctions to help panama get back onto the road of democracy,'' sosa said
he said, however, delvalle would not support u.s. military intervention
sosa said he did not expect reprisals against the 50,000 u.s. citizens in panama and predicted the crisis could be resolved by peaceful means
he denied that u.s. pressure had led to delvalle's attempt to depose noriega, saying it is a ``step that has been taken consciously and courageously'' without anyone else's help
asked if there were any signs of support for delvalle in the military, sosa said, ``the national defense forces are very united. there might be dissent, but i don't know of it.''
we do not have any military support. we only have the weapon of being right,'' he said
a former morton thiokol engineer who tried to stop the fatal launch of the space shuttle challenger says another shuttle disaster is possible because what he feels is a poor redesign job
the shuttle's return flight is not going to be a safe one,'' roger boisjoly told student engineers thursday during a speech on professional ethics in oklahoma city
morton thiokol managers, not engineers, directed the effort to redesign new booster joint seals, and the result is ``an incredibly lousy design,'' he said. the new seals are no better than the old ones, he added
company spokesman rocky raab was out of his office in brigham city, utah, on friday and could not be reached for comment
boisjoly was considered morton thiokol's expert on the booster rocket joint seals. he warned nasa officials not to launch the challenger on jan. 28, 1986, when below-freezing temperatures beset the kennedy space center
the shuttle exploded when o-ring seals on its solid fuel booster joints failed and allowed gases to escape the booster and ignite the massive fuel tank. the seven astronauts were killed
the next space launch is tentatively set for august. boisjoly said he wouldn't fly on it, and wouldn't advise anyone else to
boisjoly has filed two federal lawsuits against morton thiokol inc. he took a long-term disability leave from the chicago-based company, saying he suffered depression and post-traumatic stress following the explosion
he contends the company hurt his reputation by portraying him as a disgruntled employee after he testified before the rogers commission, which investigated the challenger explosion
boisjoly contends in another suit that morton thiokol and the national aeronautics and space administration conspired to ensure that the company would be the sole supplier of solid-rocket motors
the lawsuits also charge that morton thiokol falsely certified the safety of its o-rings
the fbi is conducting a criminal investigation of fraud allegations made by morton thiokol employees. but the justice department has declined to enter the case
a top soviet official went on armenian radio and television friday and read a plea by mikhail s. gorbachev for an end to unrest by protesters demanding land from a neighboring republic
armenian activists speaking by telephone from yerevan described an increased presence by the red army, including paratroopers armed with clubs
the 15-minute unprecented speech, broadcast at 11 a.m., blasted from speakers throughout yerevan, the capital of armenia. demonstrators crowding the streets heard it read over tv monitors placed outside by government officials
reports from yerevan late friday indicated that the thousands of demonstrators began dispersing several hours after the broadcast. a witness said the protesters only began heading home after the armenian communist party central committee agreed to ask the soviet central committee to reconsider the request for land
another witness said 1,500 soviet paratroopers had been flown into yerevan around midnight thursday and were ferried in a 40-vehicle motorcade to the dynamo sports hall and other locations around the republic's capital
they came with full equipment, including clubs,'' said paruyr ayrikyan, an armenian activist
for the past week, unsanctioned mass demonstrations have rocked yerevan. protesters are demanding that nagorno-karabakh, an autonomous region of the neighboring republic of azerbaidzhan, be made part of armenia
protests also were reported earlier in the week in nagorno-karabakh where more than 80 percent of the 157,000 residents are armenians
the armenian national committee, an anti-communist group based in athens, greece, claimed that azerbaidjanis killed more than 70 armenians in the disputed region
a 17-year-old resident of nagorno-karabakh said thursday that virtually the entire armenian population of the region demonstrated daily in the main city, stepanakert, since feb. 13
tass reported that soviet officials said there were some ``victims'' in those protests but said there were no deaths
in his speech, gorbachev appealed to the people of armenia and azerbaidzhan to show ``civic maturity and restraint,'' the official tass news agency reported
he said the central committee will meet to examine relations among the country's more than 100 ethnic groups, tass said
in a late night dispatch, tass reported that gorbachev acknowledged ``there are unresolved problems in the life of soviet society, but the fomenting of strife and mistrust among peoples only hinders their resolution.''
one witness said the demonstrators did not begin dispersing immediately after hearing the address, read by politburo member vladimir i. dolgikh
they began leaving a few hours later, after learning that the armenian central committee had requested the national central committee to reconsider the annexation proposal, said the witness, a 40-year-old armenian woman reached in yerevan by phone friday night
a hotel worker said the demonstrators planned no more protests until after march 23 when a decision on the dispute is expected from the armenian central committee
there is no disorder. everyone is working again,'' said the employee of the yerevan hotel who spoke on condition of anonymity
asked how the demonstrators reacted to gorbachev's speech, valery aidinyan, chief of the propaganda department at the yerevan communist party newspaper kommunist, said: ``they took it with good feelings. it had a calm tone, and was warm, without the usual rhetoric.''
earlier friday, sergei grigoryants, a dissident of armenian origin, estimated that more than 1 million people were in yerevan's streets friday morning
columns are marching along the major streets, and there is a sea of banners,'' he said
gevorg mirozyan, an editor at the armenian state broadcasting authority gostelradio, put the number of demonstrators at more than a million
aidinyan said his crowd size estimate was in the range of tens of thousands or hundreds of thousands
there has been no official estimate of the number of demonstrators, and the government has barred foreign reporters from traveling to armenia
aidinyan said factories and public transportation, reported earlier to have been closed by a strike in support of the protesters, had returned to normal
late friday, tass issued the first official confirmation of labor disruption
a number of industrial enterprises in yerevan have been in a fever of late as people were leaving their workplaces to take part in demonstrations and meetings in connection with the events in nagorny-karabakh,'' the news agency reported, quoting an armenian central committee member identified only as s. petrosyan
armenia is the smallest of the 15 soviet republics in area, and has 3.4 million inhabitants. by annexing nagorno-karabakh, which at 1,760 square miles is smaller than delaware, armenia's area would increase by 14 percent, and its population by 4 percent
the protests test gorbachev's campaign for greater democratization and openness, and his personal appeal showed how seriously the kremlin leadership regards the situation. gorbachev has said relations among the soviet union's nationalities are the country's greatest problem
grigoryants said protesters carried signs linking their actions with gorbachev's policies of ``glasnost,'' or openness, and ``perestroika,'' his broad plan for rebuilding soviet society
the speech marked the first time gorbachev has personally intervened in a nationalities dispute
even in december 1986, when rioting broke out in the central asian republic of kazakhstan, killing three and injuring hundreds, gorbachev did not surface
president reagan is nominating frank degeorge to be inspector general at the commerce department, the white house announced friday
degeorge, if confirmed by the senate, will succeed sherman maxwell funk in the job
reagan also announced his intention to nominate robert h. brumley ii to be general counsel of the commerce department, succeeding douglas a. riggs
since 1982, degeorge has been deputy inspector general at the commerce department. before that he was associate deputy administrator for administration at the veterans administration from 191-82
degeorge, 58, graduated from la salle college in 1951 and completed graduate studies at the university of delaware in 1955
brumley since 1985 has been deputy general counsel at the commerce department, and before that was a special assistant to the general counsel and had been in private practice of law from 1979-83
brumley, 39, is a graduate of east tennessee state university and the university of tennessee college of law
soon it will be all right for american hunters to bring foreign-bagged wild pheasant and grouse home for cooking, the agriculture department said friday
that is, so long as the birds have been eviscerated and their heads and feet removed, said james w. glosser, acting administrator of the department's animal and plant health inspection service. the new rule takes effect march 28
previously, such game birds had to be cooked before being brought into the united states to prevent the introduction of poultry diseases. glosser said the agency has determined that wild pheasant and grouse carcasses are not threats if they are first trimmed of innards, heads and feet
about 300 to 400 american hunters annually have been returning with cooked fowl shot in foreign countries, he said
health and human service secretary otis r. bowen on friday announced the formation of a federal task force to focus on aids among children
the purpose of the initiative is to cut across agency lines, ensuring that we provide not only the best medical response but also the best use of our social programs on behalf of these children and their families,'' bowen said at the latest in a series of department briefings on aids
dr. antonia c. novello of the national institute of child health and human development heads the newly designated pediatric hiv infection working group, which includes representatives from five agencies within the sprawling hhs department
bowen cited emerging evidence that the deadly disease affects children somewhat differently than adults as justification for designating the special task force
he said the working group ``will help carry out the agenda set last year at the surgeon general's workshop on children with hiv infection and their families.''
bowen noted that many agencies within hhs have already been working on special problems associated with aids among children. he cited as an example a plan by the health resources and services administration to spend $4.4 million this year on demonstration programs for innovative ways of caring for children with aids
he also said the office for human development services ``will be funding projects to improve recruitment of foster parents and to provide supportive services for natural and foster families'' of children with aids
there are just over 1,000 officially reported aids cases among people under 18 years old, but bowen said that is projected to increase to 3,000 in three years
moreover, he added, ``we believe that for every one child who meets the definition for aids itself, at least another two are hiv infected and the number of probably higher. by 1991, we expect that there will be some 10,000 to 20,000 hiv-infected children in the united states.''
existing evidence suggests that most children infected with the virus eventually develop the disease itself
two independent music promoters, a former radio executive and a promoter's wife were indicted on bribery, tax evasion or other charges stemming from a two-year-old payola investigation, federal officials said friday
one promoter used cocaine as well as cash to bribe radio station employees to play his records, according to the indictment
the independent promoters were acting on behalf of virtually all record companies in this country,'' u.s. attorney robert bonner said at a news conference after the indictments were unsealed
however, bonner said there was no evidence the record companies were aware of any bribery, or payola as it's called in the industry
the investigation was continuing with help from authorities in half a dozen cities, bonner said, but he declined to say whether additional indictments were expected
federal agents arrested promoter ralph tashjian, 39, of san mateo and his wife, valerie, at their home thursday, even though their attorneys had offered to surrender them to authorities, said anthony brooklier, the promoter's lawyer
tashjian is accused of three counts of payola, one count of conspiracy to distribute cocaine, one count of obstruction of justice and three counts of corporate income-tax fraud, brooklier said
tashjian allegedly paid nearly $42,000 in cash and gave undisclosed quantities of cocaine to three radio station workers from 1980 to 1985 in exchange for air time for his records
the charges against him, handed up by a los angeles federal grand jury thursday, were denied by the tashjians' attorneys
mrs. tashjian was arrested for alleged corporate tax evasion
a second indictment announced friday by bonner charged independent promoter william craig, 42, of scottsdale, ariz., also known as william craighead, with willfully aiding in the preparation of false federal tax returns and attempting to evade individual income tax
it also charges craighead with making illegal payments to three radio stations to ensure that certain records were played on the air
the third indictment charged george wilson crowell, also known as george wilson, 59, former vice president and general manager of radio station kiqq in los angeles, with willful failure to file federal income tax returns for 1984, 1985 and 1986
craig faces 18 years in prison and fines of $1.64 million if convicted. the charges against tashjian carry penalties of up to 23 years and $1.53 million in fines; mrs. tashjian, 15 years and $1.5 million; and crowell, three years and $75,000, bonner said
the payola investigation began in 1986. alleged organized crime figure salvatore james pisello, 64, of west hollywood, was charged last july with three counts of tax evasion. his case is pending in los angeles federal court
panama's president eric arturo delvalle knew in advance that his attempted firing of gen. manuel antonio noriega would fail but is confident that planned steps would lead to noriega's downfall within three weeks, a panamaniam dissident said friday
jose i. blandon, a onetime noreiga associate, said in an interview that delvalle has devised an 18-point plan for the ouster of the military strong man, and his unsuccessful bid to replace him was but one element
it is exactly what we thought was going to happen,'' blandon said, referring to delvalle's bid to install the second-ranking officer in panama's defense forces as commander on thursday and noriega's decision to ignore the order
hours later, the panamanian national assembly, dominated by noriega allies, voted to oust delvalle and replace him with the education minister. but delvalle said he still regards himself as president
blandon said other elements in the effort to topple noriega include a general strike, the rallying of international support for delvalle and the consent of the dominican republic to give noriega a safe haven if and when he flees panama
delvalle received a boost friday when the state department announced that it continues to recognize him as president. blandon said he expects similar support from many latin american democracies
the reagan administration has been increasingly hostile to noriega, especially since his indictment on drug-smuggling charges by federal grand juries in florida three weeks ago
other aspects of the anti-noriega plot, blandon said, include a purging of panama's defense forces, leading to the ouster of six majors he said are involved in drug trafficking and eight colonels who are serving in violation of rules requiring retirement after 25 years' service
if noriega leaves, col. elias castillo, the third-ranking member of the defense forces, would take command. blandon said castillo is a military professional, is untainted by corruption and leads a modest middle-class existence that contrasts sharply with the opulent life styles of some of noriega's close military associates
castillo is ``not involved in drugs and he's clean,'' blandon said. ``he's a good soldier. he does not have political ambitions.''
with u.s. marshals deployed nearby, blandon sat in a local hotel suite and outlined how he, delvalle and a group of other opposition leaders have been planning to restore civilian rule in panama
noriega once looked on blandon as a close confidante, but the two had a falling out last fall after blandon told the military chieftain that panama's crisis can only be solved if he steps down
blandon is under u.s. government protection because of testimony he gave outlining noriega's alleged drug-smuggling activities and his ties with the cia, among other issues
during his 90-minute conversation with a reporter, blandon perused a document he said was an 18-point plan for restoring civilian supremacy in panama. it was dated feb. 22, but blandon said the essentials of the plan had been worked out by himself, delvalle and opposition leaders weeks earlier
blandon said that during a meeting in miami last week, delvalle asked assistant secretary of state elliott abrams if it would be possible to drop the indictments against noriega
abrams replied that it would be legally possible but that any such decision would have to be made by either the justice department or president reagan, blandon said
withdrawal of the indictments presumably would leave noriega free to seek a safe haven outside panama without fear of u.s. extradition. but blandon said the administration has given no indication it would agree to lift the indictments
he said authorities in the dominican republic, where noriega has a son-in-law, have agreed to allow him and five to seven associates into the country should he be forced out. noriega has been informed of this development, he said
but if the indictments remain in place, noriega would be subject to u.s. extradition under a treaty with the dominican republic
still, blandon said he was confident that noriega's days as defense chief are numbered, particularly if there is widespread adherence to a scheduled call for a general strike and if the united states imposes an economic embargo against panama
he said alaskan oil is shipped through a panamanian pipeline for eventual delivery to u.s. east coast ports. an embargo would prevent continued use of the pipeline by american companies, depriving panama of millions of dollars of badly needed revenue and aggravating what he described as the country's acute financial crisis
cotton use by u.s. textile mills is at the highest level since the early 1970s, the agriculture department said friday
in the 1987 marketing year that ended last july 31, nearly 7.5 million bales of cotton were used by mills, up from 6.4 million in 1986. as it looks now, 1988 mill use is headed for another gain to around 7.8 million bales
but imports of cotton textiles also are up, totaling an equivalent of 4.9 million bales in 1987, a 22 percent increase from 1986, the department's economic research service said
meanwhile, u.s. exports of raw cotton are expected to be around 7 million bales in the 1988 marketing year, an increase of 300,000 bales from 1987, the agency said in its new outlook report
based on jan. 1 indications, the 1987 cotton harvest _ which goes into the overall supply for the 1988 marketing year _ is expected to yield 14.7 million bales, up from 9.7 million bales in 1986
cotton prices moved up last year because of the tighter supply and rising demand. the u.s. spot price, for example, rose above 77 cents per pound, the report said. but since last august prices have dropped by 17 to 20 cents
the larger-than-expected 1987 u.s. crop, the potential for increased acreage and production in 1988, and concern about the economy's performance have pressured prices lower this season,'' the report said
democratic presidential condidate jesse jackson campaigned in georgia on friday, visiting the legislature, cajoling atlanta attorneys to help the poor and picking up an endorsement from amy carter
jackson, as he has done at other stops across the south, reminded members of the georgia general assembly of his southern roots
i am one of you,'' he said in remarks to the state senate. ``i worked hard to make the new south new _ now, lets make the new south better
i am my party's conscience. by july, with your help, i want to be its candidate.''
appearing with jackson in the capitol rotunda was miss carter, the daughter of former president jimmy carter, who said she was endorsing the civil rights leader and 1984 democratic candidate because of his ``pro-people'' stands
i have discussed this with my father, but you'll have to ask him how he feels about it, not me,'' miss carter told the marietta daily journal
the former president, a ``superdelegate'' to the democrats' national convention in atlanta this summer, remains uncommitted, according to aides at the carter presidential center
jackson will be back in georgia on saturday for a debate with the other democratic hopefuls at the georgia world congress center, sponsored by the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution
in a speech friday to members of the atlanta bar association, jackson asked the lawyers for help in assuring all americans equal access to the judicial system
we have a whole body of people denied equal protection under the law'' because president reagan has cut funding for legal help for the poor and the nation's lawyers have failed to fill in the gap, jackson said
in response to a question about his religion and the presidency, the baptist minister vowed to keep church and state separate if he is elected
but, he said, ``we should not keep morality and state separate. ... we must bring our values to high office. ... i'm not ashamed of the gospel. that which makes us feed the hungry and clothe the naked ... we must never apologize for that.''
the air force said friday it had launched an environmental impact study of bases that could be used as garrisons for rail-mounted mx nuclear missiles
in conducting the study, the service said it would review a number of deployment alternatives, including the fielding of 100 mx missiles on rail cars instead of just 50 missiles
defense secretary frank c. carlucci disclosed recently the administration would like to move the 50 mx missiles that congress already has approved for silo basing to rail cars along with a new batch of 50 missiles
congress has yet to approve any type of mobile deployment for the 10-warhead mx, but it has provided research-and-development funding since president reagan unveiled the idea in december 1986
the air force announced a year ago it had selected f.e. warren air force base in wyoming to become the main operating base for any rail-mounted mx missiles and 10 other bases for consideration as additional ``rail garrisons.''
the service said friday that list had not changed, and that special ``meetings to identify environmental issues'' would be scheduled soon for residents living near each of those 11 bases
besides f.e. warren, the list includes blytheville air force base, ark.; little rock air force base, ark.; whiteman air force base, mo.; barksdale air force base, la.; dyess air force base, texas; fairchild air force base, wash.; grand forks air force base, n.d.; minot air force base, n.d.; malstrom air force base, mont., and wurtsmith air force base, mich
the air force said it hoped to complete the impact study by late this year and make the final selection of home bases
the air force envisions either 25 or 50 six-car trains, with each train carrying two mx missiles. each garrison could house four, five or six trains
the missiles would be carried in specially modified cargo cars, made to look like a regular boxcar. to launch the missile, the top of the box car would open outward, allowing the missile to be erected into a vertical position and fired
the trains would remain inside the heavily guarded garrisons during peacetime, but could disperse onto the regular commercial rail system in the event of an emergency. the pentagon's goal would be to have a mobile target that the soviet union could not destroy
the air force says it has made no decision on how many rail garrison bases it needs out of the list of 10 besides f.e. warren
the air force, which calls the mx the peacekeeper missile, said, ``the proposed action is to deploy a total of 50 peacekeeper missiles on 25 air force trains with two missiles per train. but an alternative action is to deploy 100 peacekeeper missiles on 50 trains.''
three companies accused of selling thousands of pounds of non-kosher poultry as kosher to customers in up to 22 states have agreed in a legal settlement to get out of the kosher business, officials said friday
we wanted to make sure something like this never happened again,'' said rabbi victor segal, president of goldman-segal kosher caterers of chicago, which had accused the three companies of fraud in a federal lawsuit. ``it was a nightmare.''
segal said it was the largest case of fraud involving mislabeling of kosher foods, and potentially affected jewish families in 22 states where the companies' kosher poultry products were sold
jewish religious law restricts the type of meats that can be eaten and mandates a ritual for butchering the meats and removing as much blood as possible to make them kosher. ``the process is lengthy and more expensive,'' segal said
in mid-december, segal's catering company sued the chicago-based companies _ united poultry inc., aspen foods inc. and shelat kosher foods inc. _ and two of their officers in federal court, accusing them of false advertising, fraud and deceptive trade practices. the catering company had bought kosher poultry products from united poultry, segal said
a month earlier, the illinois attorney general had filed a state lawsuit against the companies, as well as sheldon terman, president of the three firms, and michael terman, the companies' secretary, for allegedly mislabeling their products as kosher
cook county circuit judge anthony scotillo ordered a nationwide recall on nov. 5 of up to 376,000 pounds of poultry processed by shelat kosher foods and sold under the shelat label
the judge also issued a temporary injunction shutting down shelat, a meat-processing firm that made specialty kosher poultry products such as chicken kiev
on nov. 24, shelat admitted selling non-kosher poultry as kosher in a court-issued consent decree and was permanently closed, said william sullivan, chief of the attorney general's consumer protection division
the attorney general's office estimated that shelat made about $250,000 profit from selling cheaper non-kosher poultry at the higher kosher prices
but segal said his catering company was more concerned about the possible violations of jewish religious law. ``the mental anguish that we had from the possibility of having defiled dishes and ovens and flatware was awful,'' he said
the company also was ordered to pay $250,000 in restitution and fines, and its president, sheldon terman, was ordered to sell his stock in united poultry, a company that distributed shelat's products and other kosher foods
under friday's settlement, united poultry, which still was distributing other kosher poultry products, must stop selling all kosher foods by no later than sept. 1, and the other two companies are also ordered out of the kosher business, segal said
it also specifies a monetary settlement which may not be disclosed under terms of the settlement, segal said
we have no complaints about the settlement,'' said harvey silets, an attorney representing the companies and the termans. ``we've agreed to it. this is merely a continuation of the matter that was initiated by the attorney general.''
silets said the company officers accused in the suit would not be available for comment
shelat bought poultry from kosher butchering houses and then processed it to make specialty items, such as boneless chicken breasts stuffed with rice, segal said
but a new employee at shelat noticed that the company was sending out more kosher-labeled products than the amount of kosher-slaughtered chicken it received, segal said
a surprise inspection by the union of orthodox jewish congregations found that shelat employees were placing the union's kosher labels on poultry that was not kosher, segal said
milk production last year declined 1 percent to less than 142.5 billion pounds from a revised 1986 record of 143.8 billion pounds, the agriculture department said friday
previously, usda had estimated 1987 milk output at about 142.9 billion pounds and the 1986 record at 144.1 billion
the new estimates were in a monthly report on milk production, which showed january output running about 3 percent above a year ago in the major dairy states
department economists say 1988 milk production is expected to rise by 1 percent to 3 percent, which could push output for the year to another record level
an appeals court on friday freed on bail 20 british soccer fans charged with manslaughter in riots that killed 39 people at a 1985 championship match
the court ruled that despite the charges, the setting of bail was sufficient to assure their appearance at a trial, a court official said. he spoke on condition he not be identified by name
no date for the trial has been set
the 20 were among 25 fans of the british soccer team fc liverpool who had been extradited to belgium last september to be tried in connection with the riots at heysel
earlier this month, a lower court had set bails ranging from $1,430 to $5,715. five of the defendants had been released earlier to await trial
the 25 fans were arrested in britain after video tapes and photographs indicated they had been involved in the riots, which occurred before the european champions' cup final between liverpool and juiventus turin of italy on may 29, 1985
british supporters charged rival fans in an adjacent stand, causing panic. thirty-nine people, most of them italians, were trampled to death during the retreat from the violence
the foreign ministers of six balkan nations pledged friday to resolve ethnic disputes in their region following a meeting that included the rare participation of albania
the ministers ended their first post-war meeting by adopting a communique in which they also pledged to boost economic cooperation. participating in the conference were yugoslavia, albania, greece, turkey, romania and bulgaria
relations among nearly all the balkan nations are marked by ethnic tensions. albanian and yugoslav relations have been strained over the ethnic albanian minority in the southern yugoslav province of kosovo
the three-day conference was the highest-level meeting of balkan states since world war ii, and the first international conference outside the united nations to be attended by an albanian foreign minister
it was also the first visit to yugoslavia by an albanian foreign minister since belgrade broke with the soviet bloc in 1948. albania broke with the bloc in 1960
albania has been moving toward contact with other nations since the death in 1985 of its longtime leader enver hoxha, who kept albania virtually isolated from the rest of the world
the adoption of the final document was delayed 9o-minutes after albania raised objections to some aspects of the text. as the host country, yugoslavia drafted the final document
albanian foreign minister reis malile and his yugoslav counterpart budimir loncar left the conference hall to discuss the disputed paragraphs
loncar, asked what albania had objected to, said that it involved ``only a sequence of words and paragraphs.'' he refused to be more specific
the communique adopted by the conference encouraged more frequent meetings among the balkan leaders. the foreign ministers agreed to meet ``periodically,'' but did not set a date for their next conference
addressing the minority issue, the communique stated that ethnic minorities ``should be a factor of cohesion, stability, friendly relations and cooperation.''
the communique also emphasized the ``humanitarian aspect of cooperation,'' an apparent reference to concerns of some states over human rights abuses regarding their ethnic minorities in neighboring countries
bulgaria began a campaign in 1984 to change the names of its estimated 1 million-strong ethnic turkish minority. the campaign was first reported by turkish newspapers and later confirmed by western diplomats in sofia and amnesty international, the london-based human rights organization
albania has also accused yugoslavia of discriminating against its ethnic albanian minority, and greece has in the past expressed concern about the greek minority in albania. mission</head>
the united nations prepared friday for an emergency session of the general assembly next week to consider u.s. plans to close the u.n. observer mission of the palestine liberation organization
the session by the 159-nation group begins monday and is expected to last at least three days
the dispute began after the u.s. congress voted and president reagan approved an order last december to shut the plo mission in new york effective march 22
following the congressional action the general assembly voted overwhelmingly to urge the united states to abide by its treaty obligations and leave the mission alone
the united nations resolution said the u.s. law violated the 1947 headquarters agreement, which obliges the united states to allow u.n. missions to operate
both the plo and arab league previously said they might seek to move the general assembly from new york to geneva if the plo office is closed. they also have said they could seek a ruling by the world court in the hague
the united nations was awaiting word from u.s. attorney general edwin meese iii on whether he would implement the law and close the mission. in the past, he has said he intends to enforce the law
in washington, u.s. ambassador vernon a. walters, america's permanent u.n. representative, told congressmen thursday he was ``not optimistic about the outcome'' of the session
he made the comment after testifying that if the united states continues to default on its u.n. budget dues, now $252.8 million in arrears, it will lose influence and prestige in the international body
a draft resolution approved friday by the arab league states that the united states is legally obliged to let the plo operate its observer mission and calls the u.s. legislation ``a blatant violation'' of the headquarters agreement
last year, the state department closed the plo information center in washington, the only other plo office in the united states
the headquarters agreement provides for binding arbitration of disputes between the united states and the united nations. u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar has invoked the arbitration clause of the treaty, but said the united states had not agreed to arbitration.  
an internal revenue service agent and a former agent have been charged in a sting operation in which $300 million of purported drug money was to be laundered and brought into the united states, federal prosecutors said friday
william parramore, 52, of union city, an irs employee for 20 years, and harold brown, 33, of albany, ga., who resigned from an irs office in san mateo last year, were among four men charged after an internal investigation that began in seattle, said u.s. attorney joseph russoniello
the investigation last month when ray wilford, 26, of des moines, wash., told a government informant posing as a cocaine dealer that he had an uncle who worked for the irs and could help launder money, said irs internal security investigator michael charland in a statement filed in federal court
wilford later identified the uncle as parramore, a revenue officer group manager in the hayward irs office, charland said
the informant told parramore at an electronically recorded meeting jan. 14 that he had $300 million in panama and hong kong banks and wanted to bring it into the united states without trouble, charland said
he said parramore agreed to help in exchange for 10 percent of the money, and proposed setting up a corporation to launder the funds, which were to be moved in amounts of $500,000. wilford and his cousin, terrance wilford, 25, of seattle, were to receive $50,000, charland said
parramore and ray wilford referred the informant to brown, who in a recorded feb. 5 meeting proposed a plan to move money into the united states by setting up three businesses in the san francisco bay area that would be financed through loans from foreign banks, charland said
he said the informant and an undercover irs agent rejected the proposal, and that brown promised to work on a new plan
all four men are charged with conspiracy to commit tax fraud, punishable by up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine
parramore was arrested at his home friday, and the wilfords were arrested in seattle, russoniello said. brown is being sought. 02-26 0693</first>
the romanian government, apparently weary of white house and congressional demands for a better human rights performance, has renounced american trade benefits given to communist countries with good emigration policies, u.s. officials said friday
as a result, romania could lose up to $250 million in commerce with the united states, according to romanian figures
state department spokesman phyllis oakley said romania informed the united states through diplomatic channels that it had decided to ``renounce'' the trade concessions, therefore subjecting romanian goods to higher tariffs as of july 2
romania also will lose eligibility for u.s. government-supported export credits through the commodity credit corp. or the export-import bank, mrs. oakley said
the announcement reflected a growing deterioration of relations between the united states and romanian leader nicolae ceausescu, who has been wooed by u.s. administrations in the past because of his relatively independent line from moscow
deputy secretary of state john c. whitehead, who met ceausescu in bucharest three weeks ago, informed the romanian leader of u.s. dissatisfaction with human rights policies. whitehead later told reporters that ceausescu's replied, in essence: stop meddling in romania's internal affairs
starting in 1975, presidents ford, carter and reagan scrutinized romania's emigration policies and repeatedly asked congress to waive a rule preventing state-economy countries from receiving ``most-favored-nation status'' _ the right to lower tariffs. congress has gone along
under the jackson-vanik amendment, designed to spur the soviet union and its allies to permit high levels of emigration by jews and other ethnic groups, countries that satisfy that human right are eligible for the trade benefit on an annually renewable basis
among soviet bloc countries, only romania, poland and hungary have been recipients
despite friday's announcement, mrs. oakley said romania ``stated to us that it will continue to allow emigration for family reunification purposes, without relation to economic ties with the united states. we welcome this.''
she said romania had also expressed a desire to continue to work for better relations
according to her figures, u.s. exports to romania are worth $200 million annually, of which half are agriculture products. ``the competitiveness of these exports will suffer,'' she acknowledged. ``we think trade will likely shrink.''
romania exported goods worth $775 million to the united states last year, the spokeswoman said. she said romania estimates that its loss of most-favored nation status will cost up to $250 million in lost exports
in recent years, u.s. diplomats have conferred with the ceausescu government on steps romania would be expected to take to win president reagan's approval of a waiver of the jackson-vanik rules
romania traditionally had satisfied those expectations enough to win a presidential waiver and approval by congress, but in recent years, members of congress increasingly have questioned whether romanian compliance met the requirements
many members, notably sen. paul trible, r-va., asserted that romania's continued discrimination against religious minorities and its overall supression of free speech, political opposition and other freedoms warranted cancellation of the trade benefits
they also rejected arguments by reagan and other presidents that the benefits encouraged romania to continue such non-moscow policies as recognition of israel and non-participation in warsaw pact military maneuvers
whitehead said after returning from bucharest that the administration had not decided whether to ask congress to give romania the trade benefits this year. even if it made such a request, there were no assurances congress would grant it, he said
stripping romania of its most favored nation status has been under consideration by house-senate negotiators working on new trade legislation
rep. christopher smith, r-n.j., a sponsor of the trade-benefit cutoff, said of ceausescu's action, ``i think he has done this to pre-empt the annual scrutiny of romania's human rights record, which is deplorable.''
smith said that during a recent visit to bucharest he detected ``a hardened attitude.''
he's cutting off his nose to spite his face,'' smith said of ceausescu. ```we don't want to end the relationship. we just want them to stop the trashing of human rights.''
congressional foes of panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega urged the reagan administration on friday to impose an immediate and total trade embargo to force him from power
some said the administration should not rule out _ at least as an option _ the use of military force to oust noriega, the general who heads panama's defense forces
noriega was indicted in the united states recently on charges of taking millions of dolllars to turn panama into a haven for drugs and the profits they generate
others said the united states should press the issue at the organization for american states and seek the widest possible consensus in the western hemisphere for noriega's removal and for the restoration of democracy in panama
but senate majority leader robert c. byrd of west virginia said the united states needs to ``keep cool''as it reviews its options in dealing with noreiga, especially in light of the continuing u.s. need to protect free passage through the panama canal
there was almost universal rejection on capitol hill of noriega's claim that the united states is attempting to use corruption charges against him to renege on the u.s. committment to turn the canal over to panama by the year 2000
that statement by gen. noriega is piffle, pap, and political flim flam intended to preserve his own interests,'' byrd told reporters
that is an absolute and total and complete fabrication,'' said sen. david boren, d-okla. ``... it's the old trick of when you get caught with your hand in the till, of trying to raise some red herring to draw attention from yourself ...''
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said he spoke to panamanian president eric arturo delvalle by telephone at midday on friday
he said to me he would be fully supportive of a trade embargo,'' d'amato told reporters. ``that would be the kind of decisive action the united states should follow through on.''
d'amato said that while he does not believe the united states should now intervene militarily, ``we should not preclude military action if that is necessary to protect the vital interests of the united states.''
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., said the united states should press the organization of american states (oas) to accept the credentials of a new ambassador sent by devalle and cancel the credentials of noriega's ambassador
he said that would make clear where the democracies of the hemisphere stand on the matter
the action that the oas takes will speak volumes about whether that is a meaningful organization or whether it should not be taken seriously,'' kennedy said
sen. john kerry, d-mass., who heads a senate foreign relations committee investigation into noriega's alleged links to narcotics racketeering and money laundering, said the united states should consider suspending landing rights for panamanaian aircraft and stop the export of u.s. technology to that country
but he said that because panama uses u.s. currency as legal tender, the most telling step would be to suspend the transfer of u.s. dollars to and from panama
sen. alan simpson, r-wyo., the senate's deputy gop leader, called for a bipartisan movement to deal ``with a squirrel like noriega who's got his mailed fist on the levers of the locks of the canal.''
i think you will find noriega will leave once the united states makes a flat-footed stand,'' said sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., a leading critic both of noriega and of the treaties which call for the canal to be turned over to panama in the year 2000
just embargo panama,'' helms said. confession</head>
federal prosecutors said friday they intended to appeal a judge's ruling that the fbi illegally obtained a confession from a lebanese hijacking suspect who is scheduled to go to trial next month
assistant u.s. attorney ramsey johnson said prosecutors had asked solicitor general charles fried to approve an appeal of u.s. district judge barrington parker's order suppressing the confession of fawaz younis
parker ruled earlier this week that the fbi illegally interrogated younis over a four-day period on a navy vessel after the suspect was lured onto an fbi-chartered yacht off cyprus and arrested last sept. 13
younis is scheduled to go on trial march 22 on charges he led the june 11, 1985, hijacking of a royal jordanian airliner carrying three americans
the plane was blown up at beirut international airport the next day after the passengers and crew were taken off the aircraft
parker ruled that the fbi should have provided younis with an attorney for the interrogation, which occurred on board a navy munitions boat that slowly steamed from cyprus to a rendezvous with an aircraft carrier, from which younis was flown to washington
the judge found that younis, whose wrists were fractured when he was grabbed by fbi agents and slammed to the deck of the yacht, was in no physical condition to freely waive his fifth amendment right against self-incrimination before he was interrogated
the judge was sharply critical of the fbi's arrest and interrogation, saying the only reason the fbi kept younis aboard the ship for four days was to extract a confession
an appeal of parker's order could delay the proceeding if the u.s. circuit court of appeals agrees to take the case and does not make a ruling before the trial date. time</head> grafs, bgng: sen. george, to include mitchell comments and clarify filibuster background</note>
the senate refused on friday for the eighth time in a year to allow a floor vote on a democratic proposal to limit campaign spending, but supporters and republican foes agreed that the battle wasn't over
a move by majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., to halt debate failed again on a 53-41 roll call after 53 hours of round-the-clock filibustering led by republicans. the bill was promptly shelved, probably for the rest of the year
the democrats thus fell seven votes short of the necessary 60-vote majority required to invoke cloture, or to gag debate, even though democrats got the votes of republicans john chafee of rhode island, robert stafford of vermont and nancy landon kassebaum of kansas
democratic leaders of the fight to curb the escalating costs of senate campaigning _ which averaged $3 million per candidate in 1986 _ said they were ``disappointed but not downhearted'' by their latest setback
they claimed enough votes to pass the bill by a simple majority if the cloture petition had succeeded. but byrd declared that the campaign finance issue ``will not be swept under the rug.''
sen. david boren, d-okla., said, ``this is not the end of the fight for campaign reform; this is but the beginning.'' and assistant gop leader alan k. simpson of wyoming agreed
we've sliced the snake into seven sections and today we'll lop off the head, for the eighth time, but it will rise again from the sand,'' simpson said
by all accounts, the bill was killed by unwavering republican opposition to a provision that would have given senate candidates incentives to limit voluntarily their spending in general election campaigns starting in 1990. the ceilings would have ranged from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on the size of a state's population
under the bill, special-interest political action committees could have supplied no more than 20 percent of a participating candidate's funds. in 1986, these pacs accounted for more than half the campaign money spent by more than 200 house and senate candidates, most of them incumbents
republicans complained, as sen. mitch mcconnell of entucky put it, that ``the bill was crafted to aid the democrats at the expense of republicans,'' especially by limiting funds available to gop candidates challenging democratic incumbents in larger states
boren and other democrats denied such an aim, but gop senators remained convinced that the bill would serve to perpetuate democratic control of the senate, which they seized in 1986
mcconnell said republicans would never accept campaign spending limits. ``we didn't do it today,'' he said. ``we won't do it ever.''
but the issue, which sen. james exon, d-neb., called ``a ticking time bomb out there,'' was clearly far from dead. ``we will revisit the issue in one form or another,'' byrd said. ``it's not going to go away.''
the majority leader suggested that one option might be a proposed constitutional amendment, which reportedly has some bipartisan support, that would seek to override a supreme court ruling against mandatory limits on congressional campaign spending
but simpson warned that republicans would be waiting. ``i know there will be some more proposals like this, and when they come up, they'll be dealt with like this,'' he said
the latest senate battle over campaign spending followed a record seven cloture attempts by the democratic leadership last year, all of them in vain. wound up with a fusillade of floor rhetoric
in a futile appeal for votes to halt the debate, byrd asked his colleagues whether the senate ``is going to become the fortress of special interests and the citadel of men of wealth.''
sen. george mitchell, d-maine, said the republicans ``have made a miscalculation of historic proportions'' because incumbents tend to spend more on senate campaigns than their challengers
unless gop senators agree to spending limits, mitchell said, ``it is possible there will be a republican minority in the senate for the rest of this century.''
republicans began filibustering tuesday afternoon in an effort to block a vote on the bill, which the democrats were virtually certain to win. byrd responded by ordering non-stop debate in an effort to wear the republicans down and focus attention on their stalling tactics
things turned nasty early wednesday when senators _ nearly all of them democrats _ approved a byrd motion to have absentee republicans arrested and returned to the chamber
plainclothes capitol police seized sen. robert packwood, r-ore., in his office and carried him feet-first into the senate chamber, giving byrd the quorum of 51 senators that he needed to keep the filibuster alive
these were the top developments involving panama on friday:
panama city, panama _ gen. manuel antonio noriega accused the united states of instigating the effort to end his military rule
president eric arturo delvalle, ousted by the legislature after trying to fire noriega thursday, insisted he was still the president of panama and called for a worldwide trade embargo against his country
the defense forces, meanwhile, closed the headquarters of two opposition groups
washington _ president reagan said he has no plan to intervene militarily in panama, and the state department said the united states will continue to recognize delvalle as president
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the united states wanted to see noriega stand trial on the drug charges for which he was indicted in florida, and wants panama to have a civilian government, but ``we want to be careful not to unduly intrude upon the affairs of panama.''
vice president george bush said the united states will do ``whatever is necessary'' to protect its vital interests, but reagan said he detected no ``appetite on the part of anyone there, including mr. noriega, to take on our troops.''
washington _ sen. alfonse m. d'amato, r-n.y., advocated a trade embargo to press noriega to step down while sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., called noriega ``a bum'' who ``ought to be thrown out.'' senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., said the united states ``ought to keep cool'' and give the panamanian people ample time to decide noriega's fate
washington _ jose i. blandon, a onetime associate of noriega, said delvalle anticipated that his attempted firing of noriega would fail but is confident that planned steps will lead to noriega's downfall within three weeks
washington _ panama's ambassador to washington, juan sosa, said he refused an order friday by noriega to resign and would continue to serve as envoy under delvalle. sosa said a u.s. trade embargo might be necessary to depose noriega and acknowledged that delvalle has no support in the military
gov. mario cuomo on friday criticized lawyers for a black teen-ager who says she was assaulted by six white men, accusing the lawyers of ``making up conditions'' that have blocked her testimony
a lawyer for tawana brawley said cuomo's remarks were ``down in the gutter.''
meanwhile, an aunt of miss brawley's aunt was quoted in a newspaper interview as saying the girl hadn't even talked about the case with the lawyers who have refused to allow her to cooperate with investigators
miss brawley, 16, was reported missing for four days in november. she was found wrapped in a plastic garbage bag and covered with feces, with racial epithets scrawled on her body. she has said one of the men who assaulted her flashed a police badge and had a holster
she and her family, of wappinger's falls north of new york city, have refused to be questioned on the advice of attorneys c. vernon mason and alton maddox jr. of new york city, who have pressed for a special prosecutor acceptable to them
they said they had reasons they could not cooperate. ... it's clear now they don't really,'' cuomo said, referring to the lawyers. ``these conditions obviously don't mean anything. they keep making up new conditions. what has become more and more apparent is they simply don't want to cooperate for reasons that i don't understand.''
cuomo said he was willing to do anything to help move the case along, including meeting with miss brawley if her lawyers and the special state prosecutor he appointed thought that might help. her lawyers have rejected that idea
at a news conference in newburgh on friday, mason blasted cuomo's remarks and compared new york to ``mississippi circa 1954.''
i shudder to think how he would deal with gorbachev. i shudder to think how he would deal with the world's problems. i shudder to think of how he would deal with leading the nation,'' mason said, referring to speculation about cuomo as a potential presidential candidate
he renewed his demand for a new and permanent special state prosecutor for racial crimes to replace cuomo's selection for the brawley case, state attorney general robert abrams
mason said that if cuomo didn't replace abrams, he would turn to federal authorities for help
mason and the rev. al sharpton said a mass rally against racism is planned for saturday in newburgh and neighboring poughkeepsie
cuomo stood behind abrams, and rejected mason's claim that the attorney general was unable to handle the investigation
abrams told an albany news conference that he was pressing ahead with the investigation. miss brawley's cooperation is ``critically important'' to the investigation, he said, but he refused to say the case couldn't be solved without her help
the middletown times herald record quoted juanita brawley, who helped raise tawana for eight years and who has spent time with the girl since her attack, as saying she is the only one who knows enough about the incident to keep the lawyers and the girl's mother informed
i know a few things that no one else knows,'' the girl's aunt said during an interview at her home. she said of maddox, ``he has not talked to tawana. he does not need to talk to tawana.'' she did not elaborate
i'm not going to address it or dignify it,'' mason said when asked about the report
miss brawley has refused to talk to investigators since shortly after she was found. the dutchess county district attorney and a special local prosecutor both withdrew from the case for unspecified conflicts of interest
miss brawley's supporters, without providing specific evidence, have charged that local law enforcement officials were somehow involved in the attack
john macgregor, great britain's minister of agriculture, will meet with u.s. officials and farmers during a visit next month, the agriculture department said friday
deputy secretary peter c. myers said macgregor will be here march 10-16 and will also visit st. louis and memphis, tenn., where the briton ``hopes to meet with small groups of farmers and agricultural leaders to learn more about u.s. agriculture,'' myers said
the cia official who established a secret supply network for nicaragua's contra rebels has resigned to go into private business, becoming at least the fourth agency official involved in the iran-contra affair to leave his job
alan fiers, a veteran agent who was chief of the agency's central american task force, has resigned effective march 4, bill baker, the agency's spokesman, said friday
fiers was one of several cia officials involved in the iran-contra affair who was reprimanded last year by cia director william webster because of his role and his failure to inform congress about the activity
despite that disciplinary action, fiers had continued to handle central american matters and had briefed members of congress as part of the reagan administration's efforts to win renewed military aid for the contras
it was his personal decision to leave,'' said baker, who called fiers ``a solid guy'' and confirmed that he had turned down a job as a cia station chief in an unspecified foreign country. ``he said he has other options and is going to take them. alan had a full career here, and he knew it.''
baker also said the agency is annoyed at elliott abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, who also was involved in the administration's clandestine plan to aid the contras at a time when congress had prohibited such aid
abrams, quoted in friday's new york times, said fiers' treatment by the cia ``would send exactly the wrong signal to young officers at the agency.''
abrams was quoted as saying the handling of fiers case ``says, `don't get involved in controversial programs because you will end up being punished for it.''' he added: ``he has made a great contribution to our interests in central america and it is an injustice that he is not being rewarded for it.''
baker said the agency will complain directly to abrams about what he called the impropriety of the remarks
we're very angry at elliott abrams,'' he said. ``it's none of his business to making comments about case officers and their futures.''
fiers, a former ohio state football player, spent nearly 21 years in the cia after joining in june 1967. at age 48, fiers was two years short of reaching the cia's early retirement age and collecting a substantial pension, said one associate, who spoke on condition of anonymity
webster reprimanded fiers late last year after an internal probe of the agency's involvement in the secret sale of u.s. weapons to iran and the diversion of profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels. the reprimand meant fiers could not be promoted for at least two years, and he apparently saw his career at the agency stalled, the source said
after that same investigation, webster reportedly fired two officials _ the former station chief in costa rica, joe fernandez, and the chief of a large agency base at aguacate, honduras. and clair george, chief of the agency's clandestine service who was criticized for his role in the affair, retired at the end of last year
during closed-door testimony before the congressional iran-contra committees, fiers acknowledged that he had withheld information from congress about the resupply effort, saying: ``so long as others who knew the details, as much as i, were keeping their silence on that, i was going to keep my silence.''
fiers remains under investigation as part of the investigation by the government's independent counsel, lawrence e. walsh, into the iran-contra scandal
the cia has never disclosed fiers' name or position, but some details of his background and career are known. he served as an intelligence officer in pakistan and later as station chief in saudi arabia, which was enlisted by the reagan administration to provide $32 million in covert funding for the contras
fiers played right end and tackle under the legendary ohio state football coach woody hayes from 1958 to 1960. he was a biological sciences major
at the cia, fiers was credited for skillful work in setting up a system to make airdrops of supplies to the rebels fighting the leftist sandinista government
a pleasure voyage around central america turned into a seagoing nightmare when passengers encountered poor food, a mutinous crew and fistfights, authorities say
the cruise brochure had promised passengers a ``friendly, attentive crew'' and a chance to meet new friends around the pool, or in the lounge or casino
on friday, the last 90 passengers aboard the cruise ship galaxy got off the boat in panama city, panama, without completing the last leg of the trip between acapulco and cancun, mexico, said ron dusek, spokesman for the texas attorney general's office
texas attorney general jim mattox had filed suit wednesday against golden cruisetours inc. of san antonio, which booked the cruise, and two of its subsidiaries and the companies' owners
mattox alleged that cruise customers were bilked of hundreds of thousands of dollars when their trips were canceled and their money not refunded. the pleasure cruises were advertised in an austin newspaper and 51 other newspapers across the country, mattox said
the galaxy is owned by global cruises, a panamanian company owned by the same people at golden gruisetours, said dusek
telephone calls placed friday to golden cruisetours' office in san antonio went unanswered
the galaxy cruise began feb. 11 in acapulco. eighty-seven of the 250 passengers refused to go on the cruise because the food was cold and the air conditioning broken, officials said
the next day, the crew mutinied, according to the u.s. state department. more passengers left the ship feb. 18, before the ship left from punta renas, costa rica
during a docking in costa rica, about 50 mutineers were removed from the ship. that led to a dock rally sponsored by a local workers' union which refused to supply replacement labor
when the ship docked in panama city, the last 90 passengers on the cruise disembarked, according to dusek, who said he did not know where the ship was
passenger sarita anderson described an unsettling scene aboard ship during a docking in guatemala
as we started into the lounge, there was a fight going on,'' she told the houston chronicle. ``it was something to do with work schedules.''
the english-speaking honduran crew supervisor was arguing with the ship's staff chief, yelling that the mexican crew members, kitchen help and cabin boys, who had been hired only days earlier in acapulco, were being worked too hard, ms. anderson said
the two men then began a bloody fight, she said. with woman, set for 6 p.m. est</note>
the prostitute who claims to have posed nude for evangelist jimmy swaggart failed a lie detector test, a national tabloid reported friday
the national enquirer said debra murphree voluntarily took the polygraph test it arranged, adding that it was administered by a expert with 15 years' experience with the new york city police department
the tabloid said in a news release that its expert concluded murphree failed to tell the truth on all key questions relating to her statements
however, the statement did not say what the questions were and gave no other details
murphree saus she performed pornographic acts for swaggart for about a year but never had sex with him
after allegations of misconduct arose, swaggart made a tearful public confession of sin and faces a three-month suspension from preaching recommended by the louisiana assemblies of god hierarchy
john martinez, a companion of murphree, told the palm beach post that murphree visited swaggart weekly for a year in new orleans-area hotel rooms at $50 per meeting
martinez is now peddling ms. murphree's story. ``this is a shot for me and a shot for her,'' he said wednesday. ``it's the american way _ see an opportunity and jump on it.''
martinez says he talked with the national enquirer about a $100,000 contract for murphree's story and also contacted other media
i don't want to see her end up with nothing and on the streets,'' martinez, 28, said in a telphone interview thursday. ``she's not after the money, but i'm looking out after her future.''
enquirer president and editor iain calder said the tabloid was talking with martinez, but would say nothing more
teachers in the state's largest school district walked picket lines for a second day friday as negotiators continued to search for ways end their strike and resume classes for 73,000 students
adminstrators planned to teach classes for 3,600 seniors starting monday if the walkout continued
the cleveland teachers union went on strike thursday after rejecting the school board's latest contract proposal. negotiations resumed friday afternoon under the guidance of a federal mediator
i'm hopeful, and the parties seem resolved to try to make a deal this weekend,'' said craig m. brown, the school district's chief negotiator
said richard farmer, the union's strike coordinator:``we would hope they sit at the table until it's resolved. we don't want a long strike.''
the district canceled classes friday because of the strike by the 5,093-member union. schools were closed thursday because of bad weather, although other area school systems remained open
the closure was viewed as an effort by school administrators to give negotiators in marathon talks more time to reach a settlement
schools spokesman john m. hairston said the school board planned to seek a court order to limit the number of pickets at the district's buildings because of problems friday. at lincoln-west high school, pickets prevented adminstrators from entering the building to prepare for classes for seniors at that school monday, he said
the school board had offered a three-year package with a 3 percent pay raise retroactive to sept. 1, and 5 percent increases the next two years contingent on passage of a tax levy and a voluntary ``career ladder'' in the third year, which would link pay raises to performance evaluations
the school board also offered a one-year contract with a 3 percent raise
cleveland teacher salaries range from $17,600 to $37,450, depending on education and experience. the average teacher makes $29,000 annually
a wild miss usa pageant took a turn for the wilder friday when an animal-rights activist disrupted a news conference by co-host alan thicke
thicke, star of abc's ``growing pains'' and host of the saturday morning children's show ``animal crack-ups,'' replaced bob barker as the pageant's host after barker resigned last month to protest the giving away of fur coats as prizes
it was just one in a series of bumps on the way to tuesday's nationally televised beauty contest
miss minnesota-usa and her runner-up dropped out after it was disclosed they had been arrested on shoplifting charges. another contestant is awaiting trial on drunken-driving charges
and thursday night, thicke's co-host, actress tracy scoggins, was attacked in a hotel elevator. she suffered bruises but no other injuries and a suspect was charged with attempted sexual assault
miss usa will be awarded cash and prizes including a full-length mink coat and a mink jacket. the furs are worth $15,000
the las cruces, n.m., and el paso chapters of sangre de cristo animal rights plan to picket the el paso convention center during the pageant to protest the fur prizes. the activists say fur farming and trapping are cruel activities that should be stopped
bob young, the picket organizer and president of the group's las cruces chapter, has criticized thicke for what he calls his hypocrisy in hosting the pageant. thicke ends each ``animal crack-ups'' show with the admonishment: ``here's hoping you will be kind to animals.''
thicke seemed eager to address the charges at friday's news conference. he said he prefers to work within the system instead of causing ``more abrasion in what is potentially a conflictive issue.''
referring to the pickets, thicke said: ``i invite those people to join any one of the eight groups that i am involved with and do some of the things that we do, such as meet with lobbyists and legislators.''
at that point, young stepped in front of thicke and held up a poster of a raccoon caught in a leg trap
do your eight groups go along with this?'' young said, holding up the poster
i'm addressing all of that, sir,'' thicke said
your eight groups _ i'd like to know what those groups are, and if they go along with this,'' young said
i'm sure they would be happy to give you an opportunity to speak when i'm done,'' thicke said. ``as mr. reagan once said, i paid for this microphone.''
he did not name the eight groups
thicke said he investigated the suppliers of the pageant's furs before deciding to do the show to make sure they conformed with u.s. animal-treatment standards
pageant officials clearly were angry about the interruption, but declined comment. ^ap news analysis</head>
although president eric arturo delvalle could not dismiss the general who really runs the country, his attempt will make it harder for other latin american nations to support panama's government
since that has long been a goal of gen. manuel antonio noriega's opponents, leading panamanian dissidents and the u.s. state department were quick to cheer delvalle's seemingly quixotic move
its practical result was that noriega stayed in his post as military commander and the national legislature dismissed delvalle, althoguh he refused to relinquish the office and the united states supported him
delvalle's order to noriega had the futility of tilting at windmills because he had no way to back it up. noriega, not the civilian president, controls panama's army, police, legislature, and even the game wardens
it came as no surprise, therefore, that the commander of the national police and the army's chief of staff quickly sided with the general against the president
so, too, did the national assembly, which is dominated by a coalition of noriega followers. in a 10-minute meeting early friday, it fired delvalle and vice president roderick esquivel
delvalle said the assembly's action was unconstiutional, but his only weapon against it is public opinion
panama's latin american neighbors have been slow to condemn noriega despite widespread allegations of involvement in drug trafficking and other forms of corruption, even murder. the general has denied all the charges
noriega has drawn the united states as a straw man, accusing it of trying to oust him and renege on a 1976 treaty turning the panama canal to panama at the turn of the century. delvalle took that stance himself before the change of heart
latin american governments are reluctant to side with the united states in any dispute involving a neighbor, if only to pacify their own large numbers of left-leaning voters
but the spectacle of a legally sitting president firing his top general, but being fired himself by the general's henchmen, is not likely to sit well
this will isolate the government, no doubt,'' said mario luis del valle, vice president of the panama banking association and a member of the national civic crusade, which began clamoring for noriega's ouster last june
the civic crusade, a loose coalition of business, professional, labor and political groups, has been trying for months to convince other latin american nations that panama's government is not legitimate
aurelio barria, president of the chamber of commerce and industry and an opposition leader, has carried that message personally to the presidents of at least half a dozen latin american nations
barria has obtained little support until now but the president, or ex-president, predicted that soon would change
i think it will be another blow against noriega and also against panama, which has had a terrible track record in recent years,'' delvalle said of his unsuccessful dismissal of the general. ``i expect that the majority of the nations of this hemisphere will be very reluctant to have relations with panama.''
editor's note: reid g. miller is roving correspondent in central america for the associated press. he has been based in san jose, costa rica, since january 1984
the league of women voters has rescheduled the march 5 debate among republican presidential candidates in nashville, tenn., to march 6 to avoid a conflict with the march 5 south carolina primary, a league spokeswoman said friday
the new schedule means the gop debate will be on the same day as a previously scheduled democratic debate sponsored by the league
we thought it would be better for the candidates if we scheduled the debate on sunday rather than on the day of the primary,'' said league spokeswoman janice kaplan
carole bucy, president of the league of women voters in nashville, said vice president george bush and sen bob dole of kansas had sent word they could not participate march 5 because of the conflict with the south carolina primary
ms. kaplan said rep. jack kemp of new york is the only candidate so far to accept the league's invitation for the gop debate march 6. she said all six major contenders have agreed to participate in the democratic debate
however, spokesmen for the campaigns of missouri rep. richard gephardt and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis said they have not yet given a final commitment to join the league debate
the republican debate will begin at 2 p.m. est, while the democrats' debate will start at 5 p.m. both of the debates will last an hour and will be at the tennessee performing arts center
new york gov. mario cuomo said friday he wants no part of any brokered democratic national convention, either as the presidential candidate or a kingmaker in selection of the party's nominee
he said he still didn't believe there will be a deadlocked convention when the democrats gather in atlanta in july
cuomo, who announced a year ago that he wouldn't seek the democratic nomination, has since refused to rule out accepting a convention draft
his comments came as he prepared for trips during the next few days to north carolina and texas, two of the march 8 super tuesday primary states
i would have no role,'' said cuomo of any brokered convention. ``they (the announced candidates) would confine themselves to people who were candidates and talk to one another.''
cuomo did say the possibility of a brokered convention came up in telephone conversations he had this week with, among others, former arizona gov. bruce babbitt and illinois sen. paul simon. babbitt has quit the race for the presidential nomination while simon has cut back on his campaigning to concentrate on his home state's march 15 primary
i just asked them how they thought it would come out,'' said cuomo. ``they said it looks now like it's open.''
cuomo said that in discussing the situation, neither simon nor babbitt had asked if cuomo might become a candidate at a brokered convention. ``they know i'm not interested. they know i'm out of this thing,'' said cuomo
cuomo repeated his view that a deadlocked convention ``is the worst thing that could happen to the democrats'' because it would hurt them in the november election
was it coincidence that cuomo was heading south just before the super tuesday voting? ``oh, no, that's a plan,'' he joked. ``you see, i'm going to be march 1 in texas and if it really goes well, then march 2 i'm going to announce i'm running.''
organizers said a march and rally saturday for the homeless, designed to make their plight an issue in the presidential campaign, is expected to draw democratic candidates along with up to 10,000 participants
the march coincides with debates by democratic and republican presidential contenders saturday and sunday at the georgia world congress center. the debates are sponsored by the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution
organizers said democrats jesse jackson, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, sens. albert gore of tennessee and paul simon of illinois, rep. richard gephardt of missouri and former sen. gary hart of colorado
keith summa, a project coordinator with the national coalition of the homeless, said no republican candidates agreed to attend
