young arabs went from weekly moslem prayers to street war with israeli soldiers friday, and four palestinians were killed in melees that swept the occupied territories
u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz met with israeli leaders to explore new peace proposals in the second day of his mission to the middle east
friday's dead included a 12-year-old boy accidentally hit by a piece of concrete thrown by protesters outside a gaza strip mosque, the army said. hospital officials said israeli gunfire wounded 11 arabs
the army reported the arrests of four soldiers on charges of beating and kicking two young palestinians who had been detained, as shown in footage taken thursday in nablus by a cbs news crew
we were shocked and couldn't say a word after we saw this film,'' said maj. gen. amram mitzna, the army's west bank commander
mitzna said he suspended the unit's deputy commander, a captain, and ordered the two arabs released
before the violence friday, u.n. figures listed 65 arabs killed by gunfire and beatings since riots began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip. hundreds have been wounded
shultz is on a five-day mission to israel and arab countries with new u.s. proposals for stopping the violence and reviving arab-israeli peace talks
he met separately friday with prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres, partners and rivals in the tenuous ``national unity'' coalition
the u.s. plan calls for immediate talks on palestinian self-rule and negotiations by december on the final status of the west bank and gaza, which israel captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
israeli sources said privately that shamir asked shultz to move slowly, recommending a three-year ``time of testing'' before negotiations on a final settlement
fifteen prominent palestinians refused to meet with shultz in jerusalem
leaflets signed by the ``united nationalist leadership for the uprising'' exhorted arabs to street protests this weekend as an accompaniment to the shultz visit
haaretz said syrian-backed al quds radio announced plans for six weeks of violent protest and strikes. the newspaper said arabs were using firebombs more frequently and suspected collaborators were being targeted for attack
a west bank palestinian accused of collaborating with the israelis was hanged by his fellow villagers wednesday
israel stationed 1,500 extra police in jerusalem, doubling the force, brought in soldiers to help with security during the shultz visit and put army units on alert throughout the occupied territories
it did not stop violence on the moslem sabbath, sometimes instigated by prayer leaders
thank god we are still alive to fight our enemy israel,'' a masked prayer leader told worshipers at nasr mosque in the west bank city of nablus
this is the time that we have to use to launch a holy war. we have already paid a very high price, and we have to be willing to pay more.''
in gaza's jabaliya refugee camp, the body of iyad al ashqar, 12, was brought to a u.n. clinic after a clash at al qassam mosque
according to the army, a military doctor said the boy died from a gash on the head inflicted by a chunk of concrete. initial army reports gave the cause of death as gunfire
hospital officials in jabaliya said a woman was wounded by gunfire and 20 arabs were treated for injuries caused by beatings or tear gas
ahmed attallah, a witness, said soldiers broke into the mosque and took 30 people away after palestinians inside began shouting ``allahu akhbar!'' (god is great)
at hebron, south of jerusalem, hundreds of worshipers streamed from a mosque chanting and throwing stones, and soldiers opened fire when tear gas and rubber bullets did not disperse the crowd, an army spokesman said.
arab reports said fuad shaarawi, 47, was killed but conflicted on the cause of death. the army said it was not clear whether he was shot or died of tear-gas inhalation
razk daraghmen, 55, bled to death after being shot in the right thigh during a protest in toubas, a the west bank village, hospital officials said
a palestinian was killed as a result of disturbances in al arub, south of bethlehem, the army reported. hospital officials and the arab-run palestine press service said israeli soldiers shot hassan abu kheiran, 22, in the chest
three arabs were wounded in jenin, also in the west bank, after 3,000 arabs staged a march that led to a clash with soldiers. arabs threw stones and glass bottles and troops fired tear gas, rubber bullets and live amunition, witnesses reported
panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega said friday he's still a friend of the united states and u.s. interests in his country ``shall remain intact, undisturbed and unharmed'' despite a leadership struggle there
noreiga's statement was issued by his miami attorneys after panama's legislative assembly removed the president and vice president early friday. the president had tried to remove noriega
these events are strictly internal to panama,'' noriega said
his attorneys declined to speculate as to whether noriega would step down
our roles here are as lawyers, not as foreign policy or domestic policy advisors,'' said neal sonnett, who read noriega's statement at a news conference
conditions in panama, as we understand it, are calm,'' sonnett said. ``that's a domestic political situation that's going on down there.''
noriega was indicted three weeks ago by federal grand juries in miami and tampa on charges of allowing drug traffickers to use his country as a base for smuggling into the united states
sonnett said he last spoke with noriega about 10 days ago. friday's statement was issued after consultation between noriega's advisers and his defense team in miami, sonnett said
all american interests in the republic are and shall remain intact, undisturbed and unharmed,'' the statement said. ``the general reiterates that he is now, and has always been, a friend of the united states of america. those american politicians who have suggested otherwise, and who advocate hysteria, act with a reckless disregard for the truth.''
panama's legislative assembly removed president eric arturo delvalle and the vice president from office during an emergency session. its action followed delvalle's order that noriega step down
hours after delvalle's announcement thursday, roberto eisenmann, exiled publisher of panama's leading independent newspaper, la prensa, received word that soldiers had again closed the newspaper. it was closed down last year for six months, reopening in january
richard gregorie, chief assistant u.s. attorney in florida's southern district, has said that if noriega were to leave panama, ``we would attempt to extradite him like any other dope dealer.''
if noriega were tried and convicted of all charges, he could face up to 145 years in prison and fines of more than $1.1 million
president reagan on friday announced his intention to nominate robert l. pettit to be associate deputy secretary of transportation, succeeding jennifer lynn dorn
since 1986, pettit has been a partner with the law firm of wiley, rein &amp; fielding in washington. before that, he was senior legal adviser to mary dawson, a member of the federal communications commission, from 1982-86, and an associate with the law firm of fletcher, heald &amp; holdreth, from 1978-82
pettit, a 35-year-old native of springfield, mo., graduated from the university of missouri in 1974 and duke university school of law in 1977
the sky was clear over much of the nation friday as two large areas of high pressure over the rockies and the southeast swept most clouds away
there were only a few areas of spotty precipitation
light snow or flurries extended across eastern upper michigan, northern new england, and western and upstate new york
isolated showers dampened arizona, new mexico, western texas and northwestern washington state
southwesterly wind of 15 to 25 mph with gusts around 35 mph blew up the middle mississippi valley as far as southern michigan, carrying warm air into the region and pushing temperatures into the 40s or 50s
the temperature hit 71 as far north as emporia, kan
temperatures were mostly in the 20s across western and northern pennsylvania, new york state and northern new england, and a freeze warning was issued overnight over parts of northeastern and north-central florida
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 16 degrees at gunnison, colo., to 83 at palm springs, calif., and gila bend, ariz. the low for the day was 17 below zero at gunnison
for saturday, snow was forecast from the upper ohio valley through new jersey and new england. scattered showers were forecast over california, and from southern texas across the central gulf coast region
highs in the 20s, 30s and 40s were predicted from north dakota across the northeastern quarter of the country; in the 40s in the mountains of colorado and western wyoming; in the 70s across the southern plains, louisiana and southern florida; in the 70s and low 80s over much of california and the desert southwest, and in the 50s or 60s over much of the rest of the nation
eric arturo delvalle, called a puppet of gen. manuel antonio noriega a few days ago, may have lost the presidency but he has gained respect
after 2{ years in the obscurity of panama's presidency, he went on television thursday and ordered noriega, the man who is really in charge of the country, to leave his post as military commander
on one side of the contest was a man with high political office but no power, on the other a man with no political office but control of the army, navy, air force, police and national legislature
a colonel delvalle appointed to succed noriega declined the job. other officers rallied around their boss. the national assembly convened for 10 minutes, long enough to declare delvalle an ex-president
the legislature's action was unconstitutional, delvalle said, and the united states continued to recognize him as president, but it was clear that he had lost
delvalle, 51, was the fifth president in six years of a nation whose presidents serve at the pleasure of the military. he said he would take his case to the supreme court, but acknowledged that his chances there were ``very slim because it also is controlled by general noriega.''
even so, he refused to relinquish the office. ``i am the president of panama this morning,'' he said friday
by friday afternoon, the two remaining numbers to the five-line telephone system to delvalle's residence were answered by a recording: ``because of damage to the system, the number you have dialed is being repaired.'' the other three lines were cut thursday night
delvalle was vice president in the fall of 1985. noriega moved him up after dismissing president nicolas ardito barletta for recommending an independent investigation into the death of one of the general's leading opponents, hugo spadafora
the dead man's relatives claim noriega was behind the killing. spadafora's headless body was found stuffed in a canvas u.s. mail bag in costa rica
he had been threatening to offer proof of noriega's involvement in drug trafficking, the same charge on which two federal grand juries in florida indicted the general earlier this month
before becoming vice president in the 1984 election that opponents claim was rigged, delvalle had not held public office. he had spent most of most of his time since graduating from lousiana state university running a family sugar mill
when asked friday whether he regretted getting into politics, he said:
no, not at all. i think when you have an opportunity to serve your country and you believe you can, you have to take the risks involved
i discussed it fully with my family before running for vice president and we knew it would be a difficult task. but i thought that i could help and maybe i could make the difference.''
he shrugged and added: ``i couldn't.''
just last month, retired gen. ruben d. paredes had urged delvalle to act. the former panamanian military commander said the president should ``look at the tomb of his father, be a man and do his part to tell noriega'' it was time to go
the leader of a puerto rican independence group and three sympathizers who plotted to spring him from prison with rockets, grenade and a helicopter were sentenced to prison terms of up to 15 years friday
those who take up the sword, die by the sword,'' u.s. district judge william hart said in sentencing faln leader oscar lopez and the others
lopez, 45, drew 15 years in prison for masterminding the scheme to free himself and another inmate from the federal prison at leavenworth, kan., in 1986. the fbi infiltrated the plot almost from the beginning and broke it up
lopez's co-defendants received prison terms ranging from three to five years
the conduct which has brought the defendants to this court is not their political beliefs,'' the judge said
in this country political beliefs are protected by the constitution, but by planning a prison escape with explosives, such conduct goes beyond that protection.''
lopez was convicted of conspiracy in december along with grailing brown, a fellow inmate and murderer; dora garcia, lopez's former sister-in-law, and jaime delgado, a counselor at northeastern illinois university
prosecutors said the group conspired to use rockets, hand grenades and a helicopter to free lopez, who was serving a 55-year sentence for a 1981 seditious-conspiracy conviction. he was transferred to another prison
brown was sentenced to five years in prison; delgado, 34, received four years, and garcia, 37, three years. lopez had faced a maximum of 25 years in prison, ms. garcia and delgado faced 15 years each and brown five
defense attorneys had denied their clients engaged in violent acts
lopez views himself as a freedom fighter above the law,'' assistant u.s. attorney daniel gillogly told the judge. ``he provided the leadership and the direction of the conspiracy.''
lopez ``believes human life is expendable,'' said assistant u.s. attorney deborah devaney
lopez said friday that authorities and inmates at leavenworth had made threats against his life
i do not deny that i love my people,'' he told the judge. ``i love my country puerto rico. i will do anything necessary _ when an injustice is committed _ to fight it.''
hart had planned to sentence the defendants at a closed hearing in the federal metropolitan correctional center because of outbursts by puerto rican activists at the defendants' trial, but later decided to do it in open court
ms. garcia made a plea for leniency friday, but ms. devaney dismissed her contention that she is ``generous and loving.''
what compassion did she show for the guards at leavenworth who were going to be riddled with bullets?'' the prosecutor asked
faln is a spanish acronym for armed forces for national liberation. the group seeks independence for puerto rico. it has been linked to more than 100 bombings or planned bombings since 1974 in chicago, new york and elsewhere
authorities say at least six people have died and 100 have been injured in faln violence in the united states
following are questions and answers about panama's importance to the united states and the dispute over the leadership of gen. manuel antonio noriega:
q. why is panama important to the united states?
a. panama is vital to the united states, both because of the panama canal, linking the atlantic and pacific oceans, and its strategic location
access to the s-shaped country is critical to control of the sea lanes in the caribbean as well as of links to south america and the far east. from panama, forces can be quickly deployed to central and south american points
q. is it that vital?
a. yes. the united states helped create panama by recognizing its independence when it seceded from colombia on nov. 3, 1903, and deployed the u.s. navy to deter colombia from reconquering it. the united states financed and built the canal, owned it and ran it as a wholly-owned u.s. government company until president jimmy carter and panamanian leader omar torrijos signed treaties in 1977 that would hand ownership to panama
q. what is the canal's status now?
a. panama owns the canal, which is administered by a joint u.s.-panamanian commission. complete administration, control and defense of the waterway will be handed over to the panamanians by the year 2000
the carter-torrijos treaties also abolished the panama canal zone, a 10-mile strip of land flanking the waterway that had been u.s. territory. u.s. military forces in the southern command are allowed to remain in forts and bases to defend the zone
q. what does the southern command do?
a. the u.s. southern command has about 10,000 officers and servicemen and coordinates all u.s. military activity from south of the u.s.-mexico border to tierra del fuego, in argentina, and antarctica. among other tasks, it does contingency planning for the defense of latin america, including training of latin american troops in anti-guerrilla warfare. part of that is carried out under provisions of the 1947 inter-american defense treaty
q. will the united states turn the canal over to panama?
a. it has to, if the treaties are to be respected, although at the time carter signed the accords now president ronald reagan and other conservatives in the republican party opposed the move
q. could current troubles affect operation of the canal?
a. since the unrest started last june, there has been no disruption in operation of the canal. officials say there is no cause for concern
q. why is the united states opposed to noriega's continued leadership?
a. he had been considered useful at times in some intelligence operations, but the mounting controversy over his purported involvement in illicit activities from drug trafficking to the assassination of political opponents has lost him credibility in washington
his presence also runs counter to the trend toward civilian governments in latin america
the united states wants a functioning democracy in place when the canal is turned over to panama to help ensure its security. noriega maintains democracy already exists
q. how was president eric arturo delvalle ousted?
a. delvalle fired noriega thursday evening. hours later the legislature, dominated by noriega supporters, deposed delvalle in a 10-minute session. it claimed he acted unconstitutionally in firing noriega. the officer corps stood by noriega
q. have relations between panama and the united state been strained before?
a. yes, several times. the last big confrontation was jan. 9, 1964, when students rioted in a dispute over flying the panamanian flag alongside the stars and stripes in the canal zone. this led to disputes over the then- existing treaties governing the zone, and eventually to the carter-torrijos negotiations
q. when did present tensions start?
a. last june, after noriega's recently retired second in command, col. roberto diaz herrera, went public with charges of illicit activities. the allegations had circulated for a long time, but were never on record before from one of noriega's associates
noriega denies the allegations and blames u.s. rightists who oppose turning the canal over to panama for provoking the problems. benefit</head>
state republican party officials revised their feb. 18 presidential straw poll numbers thursday after turning up 1,276 uncounted ballots, including some taken home by a precinct meeting captain the night of the poll
after the revision, vice president george bush remained the winner with 27 percent. but the undecided vote _ listed as 23 percent previously _ was revised downward to 22 percent. kansas sen. bob dole, whose original tally was 22 percent, had 23 percent after the revision
rep. jack kemp moved ahead of former television evangelist pat robertson, who dropped two points to 13 percent as kemp rose one point to 14 percent
the remaining 1 percent went to former delaware gov. pete du pont and former secretary of state alexander haig, both of whom have dropped out of the race
the final numbers are: bush, 1,672; dole, 1,480; undecided, 1,391; kemp, 875; robertson, 846; du pont, 42; haig, 8
while the numbers and percentages changed slightly and robertson's official tally slipped below that of kemp, robertson supporters were still claiming victory by combining undecided ballots and votes for their candidate
steve wark, robertson coordinator in nevada, has said most of the undecided votes were cast by robertson supporters as part of a strategy to control later voting for delegates to upcoming county conventions
asked what happened on the night of the straw poll, state gop chairwoman sally vitkus-mckinney said, ``i really don't know.''
hal steiner, state party vice-chairman who was in charge of the ballot counting, said part of the problem was the number of precinct captains involved in the counting process. he said there were 50 captains in clark county alone under pressure to get the numbers in quickly
asked about the fact that only 82 percent of the vote was in while party leaders were claiming 100 percent, steiner added, ``in the scurry of things, it's hard to tell an exact percentage.''
ambassador vernon a. walters said thursday the united states must pay the huge arrears in its share of the u.n. budget or lose prestige and influence in the world body
if the united states intends to use the united nations as an important tool of foreign policy in afghanistan, the middle east and the iran-iraq war, then ``we must treat it as a serious institution,'' he said
walters, permanent u.s. representative at the united nations, addressed the joint human rights and international organizations subcommittees of the house foreign affairs committee in washington on thursday. his testimony was made available by the u.s. mission
america, the largest u.n. contributor, now owes $252 million in regular budget assessments for several years. the annual u.n. budget is about $800 million, of which the united states is expected to pay about 25 percent
western sources said thursday that if congress continues to withhold u.n. dues, the embarrassed administration may seek a reduction of its budget contribution to the 159-member organization. no decision has been made
the sources spoke on the condition of anonymity
the united states has been withholding some of its dues since 1985 in an effort to push for reforms in the united nations, which u.s. officials viewed as inefficient and biased against the united states
u.s. delinquency in its payments and its efforts to close the u.n. mission of the palestine liberation organization have tarnished america's image in the organization. the general assembly reconvenes monday in an emergency session on the plo dispute
we cannot continue to neglect our financial commitments to the united nations and then expect that our opinions, policies and positions will carry their former weight in the world body,'' walters said
the u.n. is not a perfect organization, politically or administratively, from the u.s. perspective, nor will it ever be. after all, the world is hardly a perfect place ... we must work to improve the way the u.n. serves our needs.''
he and the reagan administration have been urging congress to restore full u.s. funding for the united nations, about $212 million annually
the united states said that, as the largest donor, it should have a greater voice in how its money was spent. under the one-nation-one-vote rule, developing countries were dictating how u.s. funds were spent and voting expenditures the united states opposed
a policy of consensus was instituted, in effect giving the united states veto power, but it broke down in the general assembly session
u.n. member countries understood that this budget reform would be followed by a return by the u.s. to full payment of our assessment,'' walters testified
he said implementation of the reforms was mixed and a key u.n. committee last year was unable to agree on a budget ceiling and contingency fund, as sought by the united states
but he said u.s. failure to pay even half of its u.n. dues last year ``made other countries unwilling to move the new (budget reform) process forward.''
the initial shock of u.s. withholding created the impetus for reform, walters said, ``but reforms are unlikely to take full effect in an organization paralyzed by financial instability.'' also calling for strike, more u.s. reporters turned back, other details. no pickup</note>
ousted president eric arturo delvalle called friday night for a national strike to show that panamanians repudiate the leadership of gen. manuel antonio noriega
the general accused the united states of instigating delvalle's failed effort on thursday to end his military rule and said washington waged a campaign of ``psychological warfare'' against him
noriega addressed a rally of his supporters friday night and said panamanians who consider ``betrayal, because they are born traitors, meet a bad end here.''
up to 10,000 people attended the rally at the central garrison of the defense forces
the noriega-dominated national assembly turned delvalle out of office in a 10-minute session early friday after the president tried to fire the armed forces chief following noriega's indictment in the united states as a drug trafficker
noriega has denied all accusations against him
the legislature named manuel solis palma, the education minister, as new president, but delvalle insisted to reporters he was still president
in washington, the state department said it still recognized delvalle as panama's president
delvalle told reporters friday night, ``i don't have a seat of government, nor military support, but i do have two million panamanians who are tired ... of living under a regime that one man has governed capriciously, and because of that i call for national resistance to paralyze the entire country starting monday.''
the opposition national civic crusade on friday evening called for a ``progressive, nationwide strike'' starting immediately
aurelio barrilla, president of the panamanian chamber of commerce and industry, one of the groups in the coalition, said the crusade was seeking ``total paralysis'' of the country by early next week
however, only one of several strikes called last summer by the coalition of about 200 organizations was notably successful, and the government has shut down opposition newspapers, radio and television stations, limiting the crusade's ability to spread its message
in his address at the central garrison rally, noriega said, ``the defense forces offer subordination, total support and our cooperation to the new president, our best efforts to be able to reach presidential elections in may 1989.''
panama is not a tribe,'' he said. ``the americans who live in panama should sleep easy, because this people is not a tribe, it is a healthy people.''
panama, a nation of 2.2 million people, is headquarters for u.s. military programs in latin america with the u.s. southern command that has 10,000 military personnel and their 20,000 dependents in panama
after the rally, noriega walked with his supporters to the presidential offices about a mile away
throughout the day there were fewer vehicles and people on the streets, but panama city was calm and businesses operated normally
delvalle said the protest strike would be peaceful, saying, ``i don't pretend to be the leader of the resistance. i pretend to be the president who returns to the presidency.'' he also urged a worldwide trade embargo against panama
he called solis palma ``an opportunistic politician.''
delvalle's bid to remove noriega as head of panama's 15,000-member defense forces was thwarted thursday night when the military closed ranks around the general and said no officer would replace him
president reagan said the united states was not behind delvalle's attempt to get rid of noriega but was ``very much aware of it.'' he said there were no plans for military intervention
the white house called on noriega to resign after he was indicted feb. 5 in florida on drug trafficking charges. noriega was accused of using his authority to let colombian drug traffickers utilize panama as a base for smuggling cocaine and marijuana into the united states. the charges said noriega received kickbacks from drug profits
soldiers on friday surrounded and closed the chamber of commerce building, headquarters for the national civic crusade
opponents of noriega met elsewhere to discuss actions to protest his rule
police closed the offices of the christian democratic party, whose president, ricardo arias calderon, has been a leader of the crusade movement
arias calderon and a miami herald reporter, andres oppenheimer, were detained for two hours thursday night when they arrived on a commercial flight from miami. oppenheimer was released but arias calderon was put on a flight to costa rica
panamanian authorities refused entry to three american journalists when they tried to land early friday in a charter plane from costa rica
miami herald central america correspondent sam dillon, washington post correspondent julia preston and john siceloff, a nicaragua-based producer for nbc-tv returned to costa rica
the rally was noriega's first appearance in public since delvalle acted. in an interview broadcast by the government's radio nacional earlier friday, he said of the united states: ``they have been using a web that includes psychological warfare ... slander, lies, injury, conjecture, and ... misinformation.''
asked if there was u.s. involvement in delvalle's attempt to oust him, noriega said: ``totally, they have maintained a web.''
he said delvalle ``is in his home, with his family, without any problem.''
relations between the reagan administration and noriega have deteriorated since june, when opposition leaders launched a campaign of strikes and protests in panama to force the general out
protests began after noriega's former second in command, retired col. roberto diaz herrera, accused noriega of drug trafficking, fraud and assassinating political opponents
noriega issued a statement through his attorneys in miami in which he denounced u.s. politicians he said advocate ``hysteria (and) act with a reckless disregard for the truth.''
the statement also said, ``all american interests in the republic are and shall remain undisturbed and unharmed.'' it added ``these events are strictly internal to panama
the panama canal operated normally friday
american military personnel were on alert and civilians were told to keep a low profile
the white house immediately offered its support after delvalle announced his intention to oust noriega, but noriega and his supporters moved quickly against delvalle
solis palma, 71, will fill out the current presidential term, which ends in october 1989
the national assembly removed both delvalle and vice president roderick esquivel from office, saying delvalle violated the law in trying to fire noriega
the soviet union will have its first international art auction in july when sotheby's holds a sale of contemporary soviet works, the american-owned auction house and soviet officials announced friday
about 100 paintings by more than 20 contemporary soviet painters, including some previously ``unofficial'' artists, will go on the block july 7 at the international trade center in moscow, said lord gowrie. he is a former british arts minister and now chairman of the world's largest auctioneering company
i hope this will be the first of a series of auctions. ... we chose sotheby's because they have an international name,'' sergei popov, a senior official in the soviet ministry of culture, told reporters at the news conference at sotheby's headquarters
it will be the soviets' first international auction since the 1917 revolution that brought the communists to power
asked if the auctioned works would be by unofficial artists as well as those whose work is approved by the soviet union of artists, popov replied: ``there are no longer any unofficial artists. for the past three years there have been no restrictions on any style or tendency in art.''
popov said that when the works in the sale are given preview exhibitions in new york, zurich, london and paris ``you will see that all tendencies that flourish in the west are present in our art, and some are perhaps better developed with us.''
gowrie said the soviets placed no restrictions on what could be sold
we have chosen what to sell and in the main they will be artists whose works are already well known in the west and of interest to collectors,'' he said
simon de pury, sotheby's managing director in europe, said, ``a large number of the artists represented in the sale were until recently regarded as unofficial artists.''
among the contemporary artists with works in the sale are iliya kabakov, ivan tschuikov and vadim zakharov. there will also be some russian avant garde paintings of the 1910-1932 period
gowrie said prices should range from about $3,500 to $35,000 and will have to be paid for in british pounds
he said sotheby's expects the sale total to be ``well over half a million pounds ($880,000) and the bulk of the money, after the normal commissions, will go to the artists.'' he would not disclose sotheby's commissions
popov said the soviet government agreed to the auction because previous art sales to the west, which started in 1967, were done through an export trade body
that's not a very good way of entering the art market and this auction will help to establish prices on the international art market and allow soviet artists to receive the bulk of the proceeds,'' popov said
asked if the auction didn't run contrary to marxist principles, gowrie said: ``we had a good response from the artists themselves and i don't think 19th century philosophers were consulted.''
popov said, ``what's un-marxist about selling soviet art works so they become better known all over the world?''
a defense contractor executive who lost his job after criticizing the pentagon's budget priorities filed suit thursday against the former secretary of the navy and three others, accusing them of having him fired
the suit by dr. lawrence j. korb, filed in u.s. district court here, requests a jury trial and asks for a minimum of $500,000 in compensatory damages as well as punitive damages for violating his first amendment right of free speech
the suit names as plaintiffs former navy secretary john f. lehman jr.; a former top aide, melvyn r. paisley; assistant navy secretary everett pyatt, and carl m. smith, a staffer with the senate armed services committee
the lawsuit alleges the four men, by complaining directly or indirectly to korb's bosses at the raytheon co., ``intended to and did penalize dr. korb for exercising the right of free speech guaranteed to him by the first amendment of the constitution ....''
as a direct and proximate result of the defendants' acts, dr. korb has sustained and will continue to sustain substantial monetary losses and has suffered and will continue to suffer mental and emotional pain, anguish and humiliation,'' the suit says
the suit was filed on korb's behalf by the american civil liberties union, which in 1986 had asked then-defense secretary caspar w. weinberger to fire lehman and his aides for their conduct
weinberger instead admonished the three
efforts to contact lehman and the other defendants thursday were unsuccessful
korb, who worked for weinberger for four years as the pentagon's assistant defense secretary for manpower, joined raytheon _ a major navy contractor _ as a washington vice president in 1985. with the company's permission, he also joined the committee for national security, a bipartisan group that seeks to encourage informed debate on national security issues
in february 1986, korb appeared with other group members at a press conference and suggested the pentagon could maintain its strength with a smaller budget than that requested by president reagan
following the news conference, raytheon received phone calls and letters from paisley and pyatt
the two lehman deputies have acknowledged calling raytheon and suggesting korb be told to stop speaking out against the president's budget. the pentagon's inspector general, in an earlier investigation, concluded lehman had not directed pyatt and paisley to call raytheon but clearly supported his deputies' actions
korb's suit says raytheon also was contacted about the same time by smith, a senate committee staffer who oversaw missile budgets affecting raytheon
on information and belief, defendant smith told them that unless raytheon silenced or removed dr. korb, he (smith) would no longer meet with anyone from raytheon's washington office,'' the suit says
in direct and immediate reaction to the angry complaints and explicit and implicit threats made by defendants lehman, pyatt, paisley and smith, raytheon terminated dr. korb as vice president in charge of its washington operations.''
korb is now the dean of the university of pittsburgh's graduate school of public and international affairs
the suit filed thursday is similar to one filed in december by korb against raytheon. ratheon has responded that it didn't fire korb, but offered him a transfer to another job that he declined to accept. korb has said he considered the offered job would have been a demotion. correcting from edward vii to edward viii. picks up 9th graf pvs, the new ...</note>
a 52-year-old surveyor has inherited 30 farms and the entire village of southwick, including two pubs, two churches, a post office and 67 houses from a distant relative he hardly knew, it was reported friday
robin thistlethwayte said he was astonished when he was told that eva borthwick-norton, who died last week at the age of 96, left him her 7,500-acre estate in hampshire, about 60 miles southwest of london near england's south coast
although i had only met her a handful of times i think she must have felt i was the best person to leave it to,'' thistlethwayte was quoted as saying in today's times of london
i have a lot of experience in running agricultural estates with traditional standards of farming and i intend to continue with the traditions as far as is possible in the 20th century,'' he said
the 300 residents of the pastoral village, nestling under the slope of nearby portsdown hill, appeared delighted with her decision
it seems she made sure the village will be preserved as it is, which is wonderful news,'' valerie church, who runs the red lion pub was quoted as telling the today newspaper
the estate had been in the thistlethwayte family for 250 years until lt. col. evelyn thistlethwayte left it to his nephew, hugh borthwick, in 1943. following his death in 1950, his widow took over its management
mrs. borthwick-norton, a socialite who was friends with wallis simpson, the american divorcee who forced the abdication of king edward viii, had no children, and apparently decided to return the estate to the thistlethwayte family
the new owner, who lives in banbury near oxford, said he plans to move to the village with his wife and three children. with dole quotes</note>
president reagan said friday he has no plan to intervene militarily in panama, as u.s. officials scrambled to assess ``a precarious position'' brought on in part by federal drug-smuggling indictments of strong man gen. manuel antonio noriega
but the state department said the united states will continue to recognize eric arturo delvalle as president of panama, despite a parliamentary vote to oust him and replace him with manuel solis palma, who has been education minister
the national assembly moved against delvalle after he tried to dismiss noriega, who was indicted by federal grand juries in miami and tampa, fla., earlier this month
amid the continuing political instability, vice president george bush said the united states should do ``whatever is necessary'' to protect american interests in the central american country, which include the militarily and economically vital panama canal
noriega's gone bad, and he's proven he's trafficked in narcotics,'' bush said. ``... noriega should go and in my view he will go.''
reagan said he didn't think there was ``any appetite on the part of anyone there, including mr. noriega, to take on our troops.''
responding to questions during a picture-taking session with southern republican party leaders, the president said the united states did not instigate delvalle's move thursday. but he also said u.s. officials had been ``very much aware of it.''
asked whether the united states was contemplating military intervention there, the president replied, ``no, i don't think that's an answer.'' he declined to discuss other alternatives, saying: ``we're not prepared to come up with any answers as yet.''
reagan said he thought ``there are some limits on what we can do,'' but that ``we're looking at that situation, and our people are meeting on it to see if there's anything we can do.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said earlier there was no administration interest in a proposal by sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., to impose trade sanctions against panama
late friday, following a series of meetings involving national security officials, fitzwater issued a statement saying that ``we condemn all efforts to perpetuate military rule in panama, including efforts to remove president delvalle from office.''
the statement said ``we have also initiated a series of consultations to learn the views of other countries in in the hemisphere with regard to this situation.''
bush, campaigning to succeed reagan, seemed to take a harder line during a talk to a greenville, s.c., audience
he told the south carolina press association: ``we will do whatever is necessary to protect american interests in panama. we've got treaty interests on the (panama) canal. i don't want to rattle any sabers ....''
but we would obviously as the united states, and i would, reserve the right to do whatever is necessary, including military force, to protect america's sacred interest in that region of the world,'' bush said
he stopped short of calling for military intervention, however, saying the united states' past history of intervention in latin american affairs is ``what's hurting us in some areas now.'' some 10,000 american troops are stationed in panama
one of bush's rivals for the republican nomination, senate minority leader bob dole of kansas, said during a campaign stop in st. louis that, ``the united states has had enough of noriega and will have nothing to do with any phony civilian, noriega-puppet government.''
dole warned the panamian strong man: ``if you think you can put the heat on us by meddling around with the canal _ we will do whatever is necessary, including the use of military force, to protect our security interests and the lives of american citizens.''
from capitol hill, the administration got conflicting advice on how to handle the situation
senate democrats urged caution, while d'amato advocated the trade embargo and sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., called noriega ``a bum'' and said ``he ought to be thrown out.''
senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., said the united states ``ought to keep cool'' and ``make haste slowly'' to give the panamanian people ample time to decide noriega's fate
sen. david boren, d-okla., chairman of the senate intelligence committee, said washington should proceed with ``great caution,'' in consultation with neighboring nations, to protect u.s. national interests in panama
rep. dante fascell, chairman of the house foreign affairs committee, said the united states should strongly support delvalle and that other nations in the region should do the same
fascell, d-fla., said the united states should increase diplomatic pressure immediately, and added: ``at this point, we certainly should be reviewing our options in the economic area.''
fitzwater confirmed that delvalle had held talks at the u.s. embassy in panama city before moving to oust noriega on thursday, but he denied that the administration had lent any encouragement to the panamanian president
there's not a lot that we can say about impressions,'' the spokesman said. ``the united states has a large interest there, obviously. but we have tried to walk the line between what's appropriate and what's not appropriate.''
we have a precarious position,'' fitzwater added. ``yes, we want him (noriega) to stand trial (on the miami indictment). yes, we want civilian government in panama. but we want to be careful not to unduly intrude upon the affairs of panama.''
at the state department, spokeswoman phyllis oakley reiterated what she termed ``our support for the supremacy of civilian constitutional rule'' and said ``we continue to recognize president delvalle as the president of panama.''
asked to describe the legal grounds for such recognition, she said, ``i don't think it's for us to interpret their constitutional law. we had regarded him as the president, we still regard him as the president.''
mrs. oakley also said the united states continues to recognize juan b. sosa as panama's ambassador in washington. sosa has supported delvalle, and he said he planned to remain in his post, although noriega told him by telephone friday morning that he would be replaced
mrs. oakley said elliott abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs met with sosa on friday, but she wouldn't reveal details of the discussion
asked if the united states had been in contact with noriega, she said, ``not that i'm aware of.''
many people knew that we had been aware of the actions that president delvalle was contemplating doing,'' the spokeswoman said. ``we had been informed that the decision was president delvalle's own to make.''
reagan canceled a scheduled weekend visit to his camp david, md., mountaintop retreat, but fitzwater said it was because of a scheduled social event at the white house on sunday afternoon and not because of the panamanian crisis
fitzwater said that while delvalle had been in contact with state department officials before thursday's ill-fated attempt to oust noriega, ``we did not urge him to take this action. he did it on his own.''
the spokesman also said he saw no immediate need for any dramatic moves by the united states to protect citizens and military forces in panama
panamanian authorities advise us there is no threat to americans in that country,'' he said. move up reference to car stopped in intersection. picks up 2nd graf pvs, `evans and ...'</note>
a woman out looking for a policeman to shoot stopped in an intersection and waited friday for one to find her, then smiled as she fired point-blank into the officer's chest, police said
officer buddy evans, who had approached the car at 5 a.m. because it appeared stranded, was saved by his bullet-proof vest, said police spokesman dee anderson
evans and another officer managed to subdue the woman, who was sitting on the passenger side of an idling station wagon, he said
she has given us information that this was premeditated. she was driving around looking for a police officer to shoot for some time, then she decided to stop and let the officer come to her,'' he said
she turned around and smiled and then shot him,'' he said
the woman, pamela diane takhar, 33, was arrested for investigation of attempted capital murder and was held in arlington city jail on $250,000 bail, anderson said
officers said the woman was ``not real lucid or coherent,'' said anderson
she thought by shooting a policeman and being put in jail, she would be an example to other people not to do it,'' anderson said
officers said evans was taken to arlington memorial hospital for an examination and was released. starting</head> presided ...' to delete extraneous `delay' and restore dropped `in.'</note>
arizona's supreme court on friday refused to delay the start of gov. evan mecham's immpeachment trial on monday but did not rule out blocking the proceedings later
the ruling came in an emergency session during which the governor's lawyers cited danger to his constitutional rights and the justices expressed concern about breaching the separation of judicial and legislative powers
the high court said it would decide on tuesday _ one day after the senate trial is to begin _ whether to issue an injunction against it
in another development, mecham's chief attorney has withdrawn from mecham's case
thomas crowe, another attorney for the first-term republican, had told the high court that mecham's rights would be violated if an impeachment trial were held before related criminal charges were heard in court
but john lundin, representing the senate, told the justices they were ``being asked to enter an arena that has never been entered into by any court in this nation'' and suggested they refrain from breaking such new ground
the justices indicated by questions that they were reluctant to interfere with legislative matters in light of the state constitution's separation of powers
i don't think one can say that fundamental rights of fair play don't apply to impeachment proceedings. but who decides what is fair play? isn't it the senate that decides what the rules are?'' said vice chief justice stanley feldman
feldman said he believed that the framers of the constitution ``wanted to keep us out of'' matters involving legislative bodies
feldman presided in place of chief justice frank x. gordon, who has removed himself from such matters because he will preside over the impeachment trial
meanwhile, the arizona civil liberties union filed a friend-of-the-court brief arguing that mecham's right to a fair trial on criminal charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan would be violated if the senate proceeding were held first
we are taking no position on the impeachment,'' said aclu lawyer alice bendheim. ``but we are asking that the state supreme court ensure that governor mecham gets due process.''
senators, who previously delayed the trial's start a week, refused earlier this week to give crowe and washington attorney jerris leonard more time to prepare the governor's defense
mecham was impeached feb. 5 on a 46-14 house vote. several days later the house approved 23 impeachment articles, the equivalent of an indictment in a criminal case. they outlined details of three broad charges against the first-term republican: that he concealed a $350,000 loan to his 1986 campaign, misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership, and tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
murray miller, who has represented mecham since october, withdrew from the case abruptly, saying friday that he decided late thursday night to drop out
he said leonard was now in charge of the defense. but he expressed uncertainty at whether leonard, who was hired by the governor tuesday, could be prepared to proceed on monday
however, leonard said, ``i think evan mecham is entitled to the best representation he can get. i don't say this braggadociously at all, but if he feels he wants me, he should be entitled to have the lawyer of his choice.''
miller declined to elaborate on his reasons for bowing out but he said he hoped senators would not suspect he had deceived them about his role in the case. as late as wednesday night, he said,``i was fully in charge of the case and defending the governor.''
senate majority leader robert usdane, a republican, said he suspected the change of lawyers was planned and was a delaying tactic by mecham
anything to try and tie this thing up until may 17th,'' he said, referring to the date when the republican governor faces a recall election. ``we are not going to do that.''
senate minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, said, ``i see no reason to delay.''
i think it is absolutely disgusting and an outrage...,'' said assistant minority leader lela alston. ``i think it's part of the governor's strategy to continue delays.''
miller, denying any devious actions, said, ``my main concern is that the governor gets a fair legal shake.''
mecham did not immediately return a telephone call friday from the associated press, but the arizona daily star of tucson on friday quoted him as saying: ``murray withdrew from the case. we parted friendly, but that's really all. you'll have to ask him why.''
impeachment prosecutor william french said miller will be required to submit a motion on monday seeking senate permission to withdraw from the case. french said he may oppose the motion if he believes miller's withdrawal might be used for a later claim that the new attorneys did not have time to prepare for the trial
leonard was in his office but sent word through a secretary that he was too busy to talk to a reporter who visited his office friday
leonard has resigned from the washington law firm of manatt, phelps, rothenberg, tunney and evans because of his decision to represent mecham, said charles t. manatt, a senior partner in the firm
jerris leonard informed the firm last week that he had been contacted by governor mecham concerning representation,'' said manatt. ``we made it clear that the firm was not interested in representing governor mecham, and mr. leonard informed us that he has resigned from the firm.''
manatt, a former chairman of the democratic national committee, was asked why his firm wasn't interested in being associated with the mecham case. ``lots of reasons, you can well imagine,'' he replied
the beleaguered mecham also faces a a march 22 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan. miller has dropped out of that case too
miller had repeatedly pleaded to have the criminal trial heard first, contending that widely publicized senate proceedings would prejudice potential jurors
senators have voiced suspicions that mecham wanted to fight for his job in the recall election before the senate trial because the senate has the power to bar him from ever holding public office again if he is convicted. released, statements by opposition and government, other detail. no pickup</note>
government officials said 2,134 prisoners were released saturday and 5,100 others had their prison terms reduced or civic rights restored under a ``grand amnesty.''
the officials said 125 political dissidents were among those freed and 1,606 dissidents were among those granted other forms of leniency. the rest were common criminals
it was the first public gesture of conciliation by the government of president roh-tae-woo, who was installed thursday in the first peaceful transfer of power since south korea's independence in 1948
culture and information minister chung han-mo announced the amnesty friday. he said it was meant to promote ``national harmony and restore public confidence'' in the roh government
the political opposition and dissidents, however, said the amnesty was not enough and expressed regret that many leading dissidents were not included
the divided opposition agreed friday to join ranks after months of bitter squabbling. the two parties decided to unite to oppose the roh government in upcoming national assembly elections
the rival opposition leaders issued a joint announcement saying, ``we have agreed to form a new integrated party by the end of next week.''
the agreement calls for kim young-sam's reunification democratic party and the kim dae-jung's party for peace and democracy to merge into a new opposition party, to be named later
in a news conference saturday, kim dae-jung called for ``total'' amnesty. he complained that the number of political prisoners released constituted a small portion of the total of 1,300 political detainees. he called on the government to free all but those who profess themselves to be communists
lee ton-myung, a leading dissident and human rights lawyer, said the amnesty was ``a sham'' and showed roh was ``the extension of his authoritarian predecessor chun doo-hwan.''
prosecution authorities claimed that 276 political detainees remain _ 216 awaiting trial and 60 serving sentences but considered unrepentant, involved in serious crimes such as murder or arson. the prosecution hinted that some of those awaiting trial might be freed later when judicial processes are completed
among released political prisoners were seven student leaders involved in seizing the u.s. cultural center in seoul in may 1985
some prominent dissidents, including the rev. moon ik-hwan and poet ko eun, who were already out of jail, had their civic rights restored
meanwhile, several major questions remained unanswered about the opposition merger, including power distribution, the two parties have been bitter rivals and their past unification attempts have failed
the division was formed after both kim young-sam and kim dae-jung insisted on running in the dec. 16 presidential election. the two kims, who split the oppostion vote, lost to roh, the ruling party candidate
roh was elected with 36.6 percent of the vote. friday.</note>
the hierarchy of jimmy swaggart's church said friday it will ask church officials in louisiana to reconsider their proposed three-month suspension of the tv evangelist accused of sexual misconduct
g. raymond carlson, general superintendent of the springfield-based assemblies of god, refused to say what penalty the church recommended instead
however, the church's executive presbytery had met here to consider a tougher penalty after many members called the church headquarters to complain that the suspension of the fire-and-brimstone evangelist too lenient
cbs reported friday that the assemblies of god told louisiana leaders to order swaggart, who tearfully confessed to unspecified sins from his pulpit sunday, to step down a year. the network cited no sources for the report
assemblies of god spokeswoman juleen turnage late friday said she did not know what the church had recommended and could not confirm the report. louisiana district superintendent cecil janway was not home friday night, said his wife
carlson announced the decision after 11 hours of discussion over two days with other members of the executive presbytery. other board members refused comment friday
the home district of the baton rouge, la., evangelist recommended earlier this week that swaggart be barred from preaching for three months and undergo two years of rehabiliation and counseling
once the louisiana district has reviewed the swaggart case, the executive presbytery will take it up again, carlson said. ``a final decision on these matters could be several days or weeks away,'' carlson said
although swaggart and church officials never specified the evangelist's sin, an admitted prostitute said in interviews this week that she had performed lewd acts for swaggart for about a year
church officials say no other minister accused of moral misconduct has been allowed to return to preaching in so short a time as three months and questions were raised about the financial support the louisiana district receives from jimmy swaggart world ministries
two officials of the state district _ general superintendent cecil janway, also a member of swaggart's evangelical enterprise, and forrest hall, the treasurer _ met with the executive presbytery on thursday. louisiana district officials had no comment friday
turnage said earlier that if the executive presbytery disagreed with the louisiana district's recommendations, it would pass on its concerns to the lower body and ask officials in louisiana to reconsider
mrs. turnage said the church's constitution made the disciplinary process a lengthy one. she said this has been frustrating for church members, who have flooded headquarters with calls expressing their concern
it just continues to hang there in the forefront of everyone's mind,'' she said
mrs. turnage added that officials want to conclude the matter as soon as possible, ``and get out of the public spotlight.''
it is the second time in a year that the assemblies of god, the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, considered disciplinary measures against a prominent minister caught in a scandal. last year, ptl founder jim bakker lost his assemblies credentials after it was disclosed that he had had sex with a woman other than his wife and then tried to pay her to keep silent. bakker rejected a rehabilitation proposal
swaggart, who reaches around the world with broadcast sermons and contributes $12 million a year to the foreign missions programs of the assemblies of god, stepped down from his pulpit sunday after confessing to an undisclosed sin
he has not appeared in public since then and was not at the closed meetings here
mrs. turnage said the swaggart case is the most complex ever for the executive presbytery because of the many facets of swaggart's ministry
swaggart records gospel albums, bible study tapes and television tapes and takes his ministry abroad
the problem, according to mrs. turnage, is deciding ``what is preaching.''
`in the past, preaching meant going into the pulpit,'' she said. but with swaggart, ``is his singing going to be considered preaching? i don't know.''
the federal communications commission voted thursday to explore the possibility of creating a national radio channel with a single entity guiding the operations of the channel on a nationwide basis
such a channel could be carved from a new set of am broadcasting services in the 1605 to 1705 kilohertz range at the upper edge of the am band. these frequencies could accommodate about 10 channels in a band for which receivers are not yet available
the fcc voted to open its fourth inquiry on the expanded band to get comment on this proposal and others on use of the new channels, in preparation for an international telecommunications union conference in june where the issue will be discussed. the itu, a unit of the united nations, coordinates use of the electromagnetic spectrum
the fcc said that while it is keeping open the option of licensing the additional channels in its traditional way, it also said it will explore ``national licensing'' of frequencies in the expanded band
under this approach, a single entity would be able to guide the development of a channel on a nationwide basis. such a national licensee could operate the stations itself or could lease the frequency to others,'' the fcc said
the commission said such a concept could have several advantages, including economies of scale
commissioner patricia diaz dennis said that while the idea was ``creative,'' it would face a number of regulatory hurdles, including the commission's multiple ownership rules
the senate on thursday approved president reagan's nominations for three u.s. district court judges and four federal prosecutors
the nominations were approved by voice vote shortly after the senate ended a continuous 53-hour filibuster over campaign finance legislation
approved were:
_malcolm j. howard as a judge of the u.s. district court for the eastern district of north carolina
_stephen m. reasoner as a judge of the u.s. district court for the eastern district of arkansas
_rudy lozano as a judge of the u.s. district court for the northern district of indiana
_john e. fryatt to be the u.s. attorney for the eastern district of wisconsin
_patrick j. fiedler to be the u.s. attorney for the western district of wisconsin
_edgar w. ennis jr. to be the u.s. attorney for the middle district of georgia
_charles a. banks to be the u.s. attorney for the eastern district of arkansas
afghanistan's communist government said thursday a guerrilla proposal for an interim government while soviet troops withdraw was a ``hysterical'' dream, but a u.s. envoy called it a good idea
undersecretary of state michael armacost, visiting pakistan, said the plan announced this week by the seven-party guerrilla alliance was a ``very welcome step toward the resolution of the afghan problem.''
the alliance, led by yunis khalis and based in pakistan, proposes an executive council of all seven guerrilla leaders to preside over a 28-member cabinet of rebels, afghan refugees and ``moslems presently living in kabul.''
soviet military forces entered afghanistan in december 1979 and an estimated 115,000 now are in the country helping fight the guerrillas
about 3.5 million afghans have fled to neighboring pakistan. most live in border cities and camps that serve as bases and supply points for the guerrillas
thursday's editions of the afghan communist party newspaper anis said the plan ``resembles more a hysterical and disturbed dream,'' kabul radio reported
it is clear that this void and unfounded plan has no legitimacy and therefore is unacceptable,'' the paper said, adding that the insurgent proposal was like the ``story of sharing the wolf's prey.''
the radio also broadcast a foreign ministry statement that ``there is only one legal government in afghanistan, which has been recognized by 80 countries in the world.''
armacost arrived wednesday to discuss progress toward soviet withdrawal. he met with president mohammed zia ul-haq, and a u.s. embassy official said he also had ``frank and open'' discussions with leaders of the moslem guerrillas
mikhail s. gorbachev said feb. 8 that soviet troops will start pulling out may 15 if u.n.-sponsored talks in geneva between afghanistan and pakistan bring a settlement by march 15, and complete the withdrawal in 10 months. the talks are to resume wednesday
pakistan demands a military settlement be accompanied by a political one to ensure transitional stability. washington, which supports the guerrillas, has devoted most of its effort to obtaining a withdrawal
leftist guerrillas called an end to their transportation ban thursday. at least three civilians were killed and eight wounded during the three days it lasted, police said
the guerrillas announced monday on their clandestine radio venceremos that all vehicles defying the ban risked attack
police said guerrillas damaged four vehicles and a gasoline station during the ban
the five leftist guerrilla groups which form the farabundo marti national liberation front denied responsibility for civilian casualties in a statement broadcast over radio venceremos
they blamed the u.s.-supported government of president jose napoleon duarte, saying the dead and injured were part of ``an orchestrated campaign ... with the brutal intention of incriminating'' the guerrillas for civilian casualties
the broadcast claimed the guerrillas sabotaged 30 electrical distribution structures and killed or wounded 45 soldiers during the transport ban
a land mine exploded thursday as an army patrol sought to dismantle a barricade on the pan american highway, wounding five farmers and one soldier, according to judicial sources in ilobasco, about 35 miles northeast of the capital
city and rural traffic returned to normal thursday. dozens of trucks, waiting at the guatemalan and honduran borders until the ban ended, entered el salvador, customs and migration officials said
police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said earlier this week that three workers were killed and five wounded when guerrillas attacked a bus on a highway 10 miles northeast of san salvador
police reported that in another incident, on the south side of the capital, three civilians were injured when suspected guerrillas ordered passengers off a minibus defying the ban and then tossed a grenade into it
the rebels have called transportation bans regularly as part of their economic sabotage campaign during the 8-year-old civil war
a gunman wounded four people on a crowded city bus and fled thursday in an outbreak of the gang violence gripping south central los angeles, police said
gang challenges were shouted back and forth on the bus before the assailant shot one gang member in the chest with a .45-caliber automatic handgun, said lt. bruce hagerty. ``then he shot indiscriminately,'' hagerty added
three of the victims were teen-agers and one was an adult, police said. two of the wounded were believed to be gang members, said police lt. fred nixon
two 15-year-old boys were taken to martin luther king jr. medical center, one in guarded condition with a chest wound, the other in serious condition with a wound in the lower abdomen, said spokeswoman paula wauls
a 15-year-old boy was in stable condition at california medical center with a gunshot wound to the upper thigh, said hospital spokeswoman jane twomey
the condition of the wounded adult was not immediately known
the shooting occurred in an area of the city plagued by gang violence. more than 300 gang-related killings occurred in los angeles county last year, many of them in the neighborhoods of south central
about 200 people gathered near the shooting scene. ``this is every day,'' said mary james, a bystander. ``i wouldn't mind seeing the national guard around here.''
earlier this week county supervisor kenneth hahn suggested national guardsmen be used to quell the gang violence. sheriff sherman block said people wouldn't like the idea of troops in the street
a major obstacle to oil and gas drilling below the scenic bluffs at pacific palisades on the los angeles coast was removed thursday when the state supreme court rejected an appeal by environmentalists
the unanimous vote of the six justices participating clears the way for occidental petroleum corp., which first applied for a permit in 1970, to begin exploratory drilling within a few months unless another court intervenes
occidental is obviously very pleased,'' said arthur groman, senior member of the company's board. ``this field, which we think may be as much as 60 million barrels of oil, is a vital resource of the united states.''
attorney roger diamond, who represented two residents challenging the drilling and is a board member the environmental group no oil inc., said opponents will ask a los angeles judge next week to block the drilling while a challenge to the project's coastal commission permit is pending
the (supreme) court now is less environmentally concerned than it used to be,'' said diamond, noting that the court had blocked a version of the palisades project in 1974
the court refused to hear an appeal of a lower-court ruling upholding the city's 1985 approval of the drilling project. justice stanley mosk, whose son, richard, is one of occidental's lawyers, did not participate in the ruling
occidental plans to seek quick city approval of a water drainage system to stabilize the cliffs, site of a destructive 1957 landslide. drilling could then begin
opponents suffered a setback monday when a los angeles city council panel voted 3-2 against withdrawing city approval of the project
occidental has estimated that 25 million to 60 million barrels of oil and 50 billion to 120 billion cubic feet of natural gas can be found 10,000 feet below ground at the site. opponents have called the estimates inflated and speculative
the arizona senate on thursday rejected a proposal to let voters decide whether to create a holiday honoring the rev. martin luther king jr
the 15-12 vote against a referendum clears the way for the legislature to decide the matter for itself
the republican-controlled legislature has killed such holiday proposals for many years, citing the cost of another paid holiday for state workers
but democratic gov. bruce babbitt ended his term in 1986 by creating a paid holiday by executive proclamation in honor of the slain civil rights leader
babbitt's successor, republican evan mecham, rescinded the order in 1987, triggering international boycotts of the state by musicians and convention groups
