_ best classical performance _ instrumental soloist or solists (with orchestra): elmar oliveira (leonard slatkin cond. st. louis symphony), ``barber: violin concerto, op. 14''; murray perahia (bernard haitink cond. concertgebouw orchestra), ``beethoven: piano concerto no. 5 in e flat (emperor)''; wynton marsalis (donald hunsberger cond. eastman wind ensemble), ``carnaval (works by arban, clarke, levy, paganini, rimsky-korsakov, bellstedt''; dale clevenger (franz lizst chamber orchestra), ``mozart: horn concertos no. 1-4, rondo, fragment''; itzhak perlman (james levine cond. vienna philharmonic), ``mozart: violin concertos nos. 2 in d@4 in d.''
_ best classical performance _ instrumental soloist or soloists (without orchestra): andras schiff, piano, ``bach: the well-tempered clavier, book 2''; murray perahia, ``beethoven: piano sonatas no. 17, op. 31@18, op. 31@26, op. 81a''; vladimir horowitz, piano, ``horowitz in moscow''; itzhak perlman, violin (samuel sanders, accomp.), ``kreisler: my favorite kreisler''; peter serkin, piano, ``stravinsky: wolpe: lieberson (stravinsky: serenade in a &amp; sonata@wolpe: form iv: broken sequences, pastorale, passacaglia@lieberson: bagatelles)
_ best chamber music performance (instrumental or vocal): itzhak perlman, lynn harrell &amp; vladimir ashkenazy, ``beethoven: the complete piano trios''; murray perahia &amp; members of the amadeus quartet, ``brahms: piano quartet no. 1 in g minor''; beaux arts trio, ``dvorak: piano trio in e minor (dumky)@ mendelssohn: piano trio in d minor''; jean-pierre rampal, isaac stern, salvatore accardo, mstislav rostropovich, ``mozart: the flute quartets (k. 285, 285a, 285b, 298)''; kronos quartet, ``white man sleeps (music by volans, ives, hassell, coleman, johnston, bartok).''
_ best classical vocal soloist performance: marni nixon (keith clark cond. members of the pacific symphony orchestra), ``copland: eight poems of emily dickinson''; kathleen battle (james levine, accomp.), ``kathleen battle _ salzburg recital (faure, handel, mendelssohn, mozart, purcell, strauss, spirituals)''; elly ameling (rudolf jansen, accomp.), ``soiree francaise (debussy, faure, poulenc, franck, canteloube, roussel, chausson, messiaen, etc.)''; jessye norman (geoffrey parson, accomp.), ``(r.) strauss: lieder including `malven'''; arleen augur (the yale cellos of aldo parisot), ``villa-lobos: bachianas brasileiras no. 5 (for soprano &amp; orchestra of violincellos).''
_ best contemporary composition: john adams, ``adams: the chairman dances''; milton babbit, ``babbit: piano concerto''; krzysztof penderecki, ``penderecki: cello concerto no. 2''; joseph schwantner, ``schwantner: a sudden rainbow''; roger sessions, ``sessions: symphony no. 5''; michael tippitt, ``tippitt: the mask of time.''
_ best engineered recording, classical: beethoven: symphony no. 9 in d minor (sir georg solti cond. chicago symphony orchestra; solos), john pellowe, engineer; faure: requiem, op. 48@durufle: requiem, op. 9 (robert shaw cond. atlanta symphony orchestra &amp; chorus; solos), jack renner, engineer; hindemith: when lilacs last in the dooryard bloom'd (a requeim for those we love) (robert shaw cond. atlanta symphony orchestra & chorus; solos), jack renner, engineer; horowitz in moscow (vladimir horowitz), thomas frost, engineer; tchaikovsky: 1812 overture@romeo &amp; juliet@the nutcracker suite (sir georg solti cond. chicago symphony orchestra), john pellowe, engineer
_ classical producer of the year: steven epstein; thomas frost; michael haas; jay david saks; robert woods
the u.s. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent annual rate from october through december, the fastest pace in almost two years, the government said
the growth in the gross national product was revised thursday up from an original estimate of 4.2 percent made a month ago
three-fourths of the growth last quarter came from a buildup of business inventories which was occurring at the same time that consumer spending was plunging 3.1 percent
getty petroleum corp. has joined the brewing contest over texaco inc., announcing it has bought $14 million worth of texaco stock and is seeking to acquire more
getty petroleum, which sprang from texaco's 1984 takeover of getty oil co., said thursday it would ask the federal trade commission to let it buy more than $15 million of texaco's stock
takeover strategist carl c. icahn, texaco's biggest shareholder, is attempting to win five seats on the company's board of directors. fellow takeover artist t. boone pickens has disclosed plans to acquire a major texaco stake and says he supports icahn's move
afg industries inc., which has made unsuccessful bids for two other companies in recent years, has agreed to be taken private by its chairman in a $940.5 million plan
the board of afg, one of north america's leading glassmakers, said thursday it had signed a definitive agreement to support clarity holdings corp. offer to pay $33 a share for 94 percent of its common shares, or $883.4 million
clarity, headed by afg founder r.d. hubbard, would acquire the rest of the stock for $33 a share in preferred stock or a combination of cash and stock for a total of about $57.1 million
campeau corp. has increased its hostile tender offer for federated department stores inc. to $66 a share from $61, and said it would consider sweetening the bid again if necessary
the move thursday by campeau _ which previously had offered $66 a share, about $5.84 billion, only as part of a negotiated merger agreement _ came as federated's board of directors met to consider campeau's offers and its own takeover alternatives
usg corp. is keeping quiet about a texas partnership's $1.96 billion takeover offer for the nation's largest producer of gypsum
at this time, we have nothing to say on any aspect of this,'' paul colitti, a spokesman for chicago-based usg, said thursday
the group led by oilmen cyril wagner jr. and jack e. brown said wednesday it would pay $42 a share in cash for at least 21.5 million common shares, or less than half the total shares outstanding. the group said it would exchange securities for the rest of the stock
northwest airlines and flight attendants were bargaining to avert a weekend strike, but a union representing the workers said a walkout appeared likely
there's a 100 percent chance of a strike,'' william genoese, director of the international brotherhood of teamsters airline division, said thursday. ``as far as i'm concerned we're on a collision course with northwest airlines to strike.''
flight attendants were preparing to strike at midnight tonight if an agreement wasn't reached
chrysler corp.'s possible sale of its parts-making division prompted demonstrations outside corporate headquarters by hundreds of angry workers shouting for a strike
you do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,'' united auto workers union vice president marc stepp told more than 1,000 workers who marched thursday in windy, 20-degree weather for more than two hours
chrysler says it is considering selling its 28,000-worker, $1 billion acustar inc. parts-making subsidiary. stepp said the sale threatens the job security of all chrysler workers
the railroad industry is riddled with workers who drink large amounts of beer or use marijuana and other drugs on the job, according to two conrail crewmen involved in last year's fatal amtrak crash
engineer ricky l. gates told a senate committee thursday that he believed 10 percent or 20 percent of rail workers drink or use drugs on duty. brakeman edward w. cromwell guessed the figure was more like 40 percent or 50 percent
the two men told the senate commerce committee that when they began their railroad careers 14 years ago, up to 80 percent of their fellow employees used drugs or alcohol during working hours
bank of new york co. has tightened the noose around irving bank corp., winning government approval to proceed with its $1.08 billion hostile bid and moving to oust the rival's directors if they don't capitulate
the federal reserve board and new york state banking board concluded thursday that a shotgun marriage of the two large new york banks wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's biggest financial center
the approvals were significant because they could signal more hostile takeover attempts of banks, which have been rare
the federal communications commission has signaled to foreign governments that the united states remains concerned about markets that have been closed or severely limited to u.s. telecommunications manufacturers
the fcc stopped short thursday of taking action that would reciprocally exclude or limit foreign-owned companies from participating in the u.s. market
however, chairman dennis r. patrick said such measures ``are still very much open, very much alive'' at the commission
the british government said it would proceed with the huge privatization of the state-owned electricity industry of england and wales, which is expected to raise $47.5 billion
the complicated sale, which the cabinet approved thursday, is expected to take two or three years and would be the biggest of the government's privatizations since prime minister margaret thatcher came to power in 1979
stock prices fell thursday as an afternoon selling wave wiped out strong early gains. the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up about 27 points at its midsession high, closed down 22.38 at 2,017.57
the dollar was mixed in narrow trading. gold prices edged higher in new york after falling sharply in europe
bond prices fell after a volatile session
coffee futures prices fell sharply, reversing a five-month trend on speculation that a tight supply situation may soon ease
crude oil prices have dipped below $16 for the first time since december, reflecting worries about overproduction and higher inventories
on the new york mercantile exchange thursday, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, closed at $15.92 per 42-gallon barrel, down 54 cents from wednesday
it was the first time the near-month crude contract closed below $16 since dec. 21, when it settled at $15.16
among march contracts for refined products, wholesale heating oil closed at 45.22 cents a gallon, down 1.18 cents from wednesday, while unleaded gasoline settled at 45.37 cents per gallon, 0.98 cent lower
analysts said technical factors and a report showing larger-than-expected u.s. inventories helped to send prices lower thursday
the catalyst of the decline was a federal energy information administration report, issued wednesday night, that showed u.s. crude inventories up by 8.5 million barrels last week, said william byers, an analyst at bear, stearns &amp; co
that figure, much greater than the 1.88 million-barrel increase reported tuesday by the american petroleum institute, a washington-based trade organization, shook the market, which was already edgy over continuing reports of growing production and inventories
the market's confidence was shaken further when the near-month crude contract broke below $16.37 in early trading. that had been viewed as an important support level on the, they said
declining prices on the london oil market overnight also contributed to the tone of thursday's market in new york, said donald morton, vice president for energy futures at the boston office of prudential-bache securities, inc
psychology in the market was already very weak, very negative,'' he said. ``so it gave ground and just broke. it seemed like everyone lined up on the sell side all day long.''
but behind the recent trend lay one underlying cause, he said: ``there weren't any new rumors. there weren't any new reasons. there weren't any new excuses. it was the same old reason: oversupply.''
three years ago today, american tourists were flaunting dollars in paris and tokyo while bargain-priced west german cars rolled off arriving cargo ships
feb. 26, 1985, marked the dollar's highest point of the 1980s _ a level that economists say will probably never be seen again
the strong dollar made americans rich in the eyes of the world, but contributed to a huge trade deficit and damage to american industries unable to compete with a flood of inexpensive imports
since then the dollar has lost roughly half its value against the currencies of japan, west germany and some other trading partners
against the japanese yen, for example, the dollar has fallen from a little more than 260 yen to a little less than 130
the dollar has fallen less against the currencies of canada, south korea and taiwan, though, and is actually stronger now against the currencies of mexico and brazil
the cheaper dollar has brought about an export boom and the trade deficit has begun to shrink, although more slowly than almost anyone had predicted
meanwhile, the dollar has flattened out in recent months, pinched between speculators who expect it to rebound and others who say it has further to drop
the dollar's stability makes for boredom at the banks and securities firms that specialize in trading currencies, where volatility is crucial to lock in profits
this week has been about the deadest it's been,'' james hohorst, managing director for foreign exchange at manufacturers hanover trust co., said thursday
currency traders are confident that the action will pick up, though, because governments can't agree on the coordination of economic policies that would allow for stable exchange rates
hohorst, 33, recalls once worrying about whether to commit his life to trading currencies because of the danger that governments would agree on fixed exchange rates
but then i realized fixed exchange rates would depend on responsible governments,'' he said. ``so i stopped worrying about it.''
car bombs, corporate spies, hijackings everywhere: the headlines are enough to make a millionaire shake in his guccis
they're also causing ceos, sheiks and stars from kenny rogers to michael jackson to seek out a host of high-tech security devices that would turn 007's head
are you bugged?'' asks the poster at the front desk of ccs communication control inc., where specialties include briefcases stuffed with telephone scramblers, wiretap detectors and ``bug alerts'' disguised as watches
the shah of iran once hired the company to build a limousine with an ``armageddon device'' to explode unless disarmed, a pop-out motorcycle in the trunk and other james bond-like features
the makers of ``miami vice'' have rented night-vision scopes, debuggers and long-distance microphones and occasionally call up to consult for the sake of realism, said tom salway, head of the ccs beverly hills office
salway is reluctant to discuss celebrity purchases in detail, but he outlines a few: singer kenny rogers stopped by for a bulletproof briefcase, actor roddy mcdowall bought a disguised tape-recording system and representatives of superstar eccentric michael jackson often drop in
they're always checking up on what's available,'' he said
when the company began nearly two decades ago, it sold only a few wiretap and hidden microphone detectors. now about 300 products are offered, salway said
among the items available for heads of state and corporations, security forces, private eyes, gadget-lovers and the merely paranoid:
_``supercars'' that spew tear gas and oil slicks. occupants breathe bottled oxygen, fire weapons through portholes in armor, and navigate through smoke and the dark with an infrared system
_letter bomb detectors, in case enemies use the mail
_more than a dozen bullet-resistant vests, shirts, coats and jackets. sales soared after recent reports of random freeway shootings, salway said
_video cameras disguised in books, bamboo stalks and clocks
_a voice ``microtremor'' detector advertised as a portable lie detector that ``can help determine ... if your friends are really your friends.''
salway said insurance companies use it to help determine if claimed losses are real
producers for entertainer joan rivers' talk show approached ccs about using the tremor detector to catch guests in lies, but she was replaced as permanent host of the fox broadcasting co. show last may before she could
it would have been so much fun,'' miss rivers said recently. ``it would have been the kind of thing i do.''
but most seek out high-tech security for deadly serious reasons
probably there's been more corporate interest in anti-terrorism in the last year or two than there has been in the 25 years i have been in the business,'' said philip w. little, president of west coast detectives
little, a former sheriff's deputy who opened his own private-eye business in 1971 and bought west coast detectives in 1977, says west coast doubled in size in 1986 and grew substantially in 1987. ``and it's all related to anti-terrorism.''
he tells stars and chief executive officers that terrorist groups have moved from the mideast and europe to latin america, and the united states is the next stop
little said clients include ``television and movie studios, oil, finance, electronics, aerospace, every manufacturing concern you can imagine.''
west coast detective's anti-terrorist division tries to do for private companies and people what the secret service does for the president, little said. many clients are americans traveling abroad
in southern california, protecting the homes of high-profile business people and entertainers, especially those with children, is a major part of the business
they have such a high profile that they feel they must take action _ they know you or anyone can find out where they are if you want to,'' little said
infrared cameras that see in the dark, alarms throughout the house, and ``panic buttons'' in the bedroom are part of a typical setup. perimeters of celebrity properties typically have visible but well-dressed guards
very professional, an executive look,'' little said. ``so you don't create fear in the minds of children or a wife _ you don't want to so overdo the threat that you create paranoia.''
little and salway said many corporate chiefs are worried more by devious employees or snoopers from the competition or the government than by terrorism
bug-detector business boomed after the arrest of stock speculator ivan boesky in the wall street insider trading scandal and reports that boesky, cooperating with investigators, had allowed his business conversations to be recorded, salway said
bank of new york co. has tightened the noose around irving bank corp., winning government approval to proceed with its $1.08 billion hostile bid and moving to oust the rival's directors if they don't capitulate
the federal reserve board and new york state banking board concluded thursday that a shotgun marriage of the two large new york banks wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's biggest financial center
the approvals were significant because they could signal more hostile takeover attempts of banks, which have been rare
irving officials could not be reached thursday night, but earlier they vowed to fight the takeover regardless of the government's decision. though irving's defenses have shrunk, the battle is expected to intensify
after a meeting that lasted well into thursday night, the fed's governors unanimously sanctioned the bank of new york's takeover attempt in a 58-page order
while noting the difference between friendly and hostile takeovers, the central bank said federal law ``does not draw any distinction between acquisitions that are agreed to between the parties and those where, as here, there is no agreement.''
as a condition, however, the fed requested the bank of new york to finance the $264 million cash portion of the proposed takeover by selling additional stock, partly because of concerns that such a depletion of capital would weaken it financially
bank of new york executives, who have been maneuvering to acquire irving for months, expressed delight with the fed's approval and said they were confident the condition could be met
we intend to proceed with our offer as expeditiously as possible,'' said owen brady, a bank of new york spokesman. ``we again invite the board of directors of irving to reconsider their position, sit down and talk to us, and discuss ways in which the transaction can be concluded on a negotiated basis.''
the bank of new york also said that as an irving shareholder with an approximate 4.83 percent stake, it would nominate 16 people for election to irving's board at the annual shareholders meeting april 21. the move was seen as another strategy to pressure irving into agreeing to a takeover
earlier thursday, the bank of new york won approval from the state banking board, which regulates many of the nation's biggest banks
jill m. considine, board superintendent, said a combination of the two banks met all state requirements, wouldn't hurt competition and would benefit the public with a wider range of services
such a merger would create the nation's 12th largest bank holding company, with assets totaling around $41.7 billion
despite bank of new york's successes thursday, analysts said it still faced a battle for control of irving
there's no reason to think they could strike a deal with bank of new york. chances are slim,'' said rosemarie conforte, a banking analyst with moody's investors service. ``their goal is to remain independent or maybe combine with somebody else they feel makes more sense, although i don't know who that is.''
shareholders of both banks would have to approve the merger, and bank of new york shareholders might react unhappily at the prospect of an additional stock issue that could dilute the value of their holdings
in composite new york stock exchange trading thursday, irving stock jumped $3 a share to $53.50. bank of new york fell 12{ cents to $29.50
in an effort to bolster its takeover defenses and place stock in friendly hands, irving announced tuesday that 15 investors were issued $100.1 million worth of cumulative convertible preferred stock, which have expanded voting rights and other entitlements that could foil a hostile bid
earlier this month, irving's board rejected as inadequate bank of new york's revised offer to pay $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of irving's roughly 18.1 million common shares outstanding. that amounts to about $60 per share, or $1.08 billion
bank of new york initially offered to pay $80 in cash and securities for irving last september. it reduced the offer twice after the october stock market crash
gasoline retailer getty petroleum corp., cousin of a texaco inc. takeover four years ago that later would bring texaco to its knees, has now joined the contest for buying chunks of the troubled oil giant
getty announced thursday that it has bought $14 million worth of texaco shares and is seeking government permission to acquire more
the jericho, n.y.-based company, born of texaco's 1984 takeover of getty oil co., said it would ask the federal trade commission to let it buy more than $15 million of texaco's stock, in accordance with government regulations
getty is the third party holding _ or in the process of lining up _ a large block of texaco stock. but analysts said getty was not large enough to harbor any notions of swallowing texaco
rosario ilacqua, an industry analyst at nikko securities co. international inc., said ``$15 million is peanuts'' when it takes $42 million to buy roughtly 1 million of texaco's 243 million shares
he suggested getty might be hoping to make money on its stock, or perhaps negotiate its holding into some texaco assets in the future _ either with the company or some other party or parties
george friesen, who watches oil companies for the dean witter reynolds inc. securities firm, also held that view
i suspect we'll have a number of smaller predators circling the prey and relying on the bigger predators to do the job for them,'' he said. ``i can't imagine getty becoming a big player.''
last friday, t. boone pickens, a takeover strategist who controls mesa limited partnership, an oil and gas concern, also expressed interest in buying texaco shares. he joined fellow raider carl c. icahn, texaco's biggest shareholder
getty spokesman stephen salzman said that his company had not been in contact with either icahn or pickens and was unwilling to say if it would join icahn's effort to gain a greater voice in running texaco
in late trading on the new york stock exchange thursday, texaco stock stood at at $42.87{ per share, up 62{ cents
we believe that texaco is an excellent company which is substantially undervalued,'' leo leibowitz, getty's president, said in a statement. ``we are purchasing shares of texaco for investment purchases at this time.''
getty is one of the nation's largest independent marketers of gasoline and refined products, doing business in 11 states in the northeast and mid-atlantic regions. getty was known as power test corp. until january 1985, when it acquired getty oil's retail operation and the getty name
getty's interest in texaco coincides with texaco's effort to exit the refuge of federal bankruptcy court, sought nearly a year ago because of a $10.53 billion judgment held against it by pennzoil co
the judgment stemmed from a houston jury's ruling that texaco had illegally interfered with move by pennzoil to acquire getty oil and bought getty itself
in december, texaco agreed to pay pennzoil $3 billion in cash to settle the dispute as part of an overall plan to reorganize and emerge from bankruptcy
shareholders are voting whether to approve that plan, with the results due to be announced at a march 22 hearing in u.s. bankruptcy court in white plains, n.y., texaco's corporate home
the judge who heard the pennzoil-texaco case is listed in an attorney's directory as having a law degree, but the judge only has an undergraduate degree
solomon casseb jr., 72, a prominent san antonio attorney, garnered national renown after presiding over the controversial $10.53 billion judgment that a houston jury ordered texaco to pay pennzoil in 1985, the biggest civil damage award in history
casseb does not have a law degree, although the authoritative 102-year-old martindale-hubbell law directory lists casseb as having a law degree from the university of texas
it is legal to practice law or sit on the bench in texas without having a law degree because during an earlier era it was possible to pass the texas bar exam and become a licensed atorney without having graduated law school
larry fitzgerald, a spokesman for the state bar of texas, said that casseb was a member in good standing
we have absolutely no reason at all to say anything is wrong at this point,'' fitzgerald said. ``as far as state bar of texas is concerned, the man is a licensed attorney, passed the law exam and never had a grievance against him.''
richard pizzi, a spokesman for martindale-hubbell, said thursday that the company has two casseb application forms on microfiche, one from 1938 and the other from 1974. the original application forms for inclusion in the directory were destroyed years ago, pizzi said
pizzi said the 1974 application form is illegible, but the 1938 form listed casseb as receiving a bachelor of arts degree from st. mary's in 1936 and a ``bachelor of law'' degree from ut in 1938
the application has casseb's name typed in the signature line, but it is not signed, pizzi said
we don't require a signature and we don't require a certification. we rely on the representation of the attorney,'' pizzi said. ``about the law degree, i don't know if he said it, but whoever filled in the form said it.''
records show that casseb attended st. mary's university in san antonio as an undergraduate pre-law student from 1932 to 1935, said registrar spokeswoman helen garza
casseb then went to the university of texas at austin law school for three years, but did not receive a degree, dean susana aleman said
instead, casseb applied his law school credit to his bachelor of arts degree, which he received from st. mary's in 1938
casseb was hearing a civil case in laredo on thursday and did not return telephone calls to the associated press. attorneys for texaco and pennzoil also did not return calls
the united auto workers union is stepping up pressure aimed at discouraging chrysler corp. from selling its $1 billion acustar inc. parts-making arm
more than 1,000 angry workers gathered outside chrysler headquarters in below-freezing temperatures thursday chanting ``strike! strike!'' to protest the proposed sale of the 28,000-worker subsidiary, which represents nearly a fifth of chrysler's worldwide operations
you do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,'' uaw vice president marc stepp told the demonstrators, which followed a special meeting of the 140-delegate chrysler bargaining council representing the company's 49 uaw locals
although the union can't legally call a national strike against chrysler over acustar, stepp said he will give local uaw unions permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved issues such as health-and-safety grievances
a series of local strikes at key chrysler plants could shut down the company nationwide just as easily
at least seven chrysler locals have voted to seek strike authorization and one, a key 4,000-worker stamping plant in sterling heights, should receive authorization as early as next week, stepp predicted
acustar, which has plants in mexico and canada as well as the united states, represents nearly a fifth of chrysler's worldwide operations, already the leanest among the big three u.s. automakers
chrysler has said it may sell acustar because it doesn't want to invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. chrysler already buys 70 percent of its parts elsewhere
the potential sale of acustar would generate funds for future investments but the primary reason we would sell acustar is because, long-term, we want to concentrate our resources on new product and powertrains rather than components,'' the company said in a statement
acustar's best chance to progress may be to operate as an independent company free to pursue business opportunities beyond chrysler,'' the statement said
workers say they are angry at the possible sale because they made concessions and helped chairman lee iacocca win loan guarantees from the federal government to rescue the company from the verge of bankruptcy at the beginning of the decade
four u.s. congressional bank investigators cut short a trip to switzerland after being warned that some of their alleged activity could constitute economic espionage, swiss authorities said friday
switzerland had allowed the staffers from the house committee on energy and commerce to hold talks earlier this month with authorities and banks about swiss rules on judicial assistance and insider trading probes, foreign ministry official alexei lautenberg said
the visit followed signing of a swiss-u.s. agreement designed to speed up cooperation in such cases last november. the committee oversees the u.s. securities and exchange commission
several days into the visit, a geneva bank alerted swiss authorities that the u.s. investigators allegedly overstepped their mandate, demanding details on a possible swiss link to a major insider trading case involving wall street dealer dennis levine, lautenberg said
he said authorities warned the congress staffers about swiss laws on economic espionage and banking secrecy and told them a swiss official would accompany them for their remaining interviews. thereupon the u.s. investigators left abruptly
switzerland's ambassador in washington, klaus jacobi, meanwhile has tried to smooth the affair in talks with rep. john dingell, a michigan democrat who heads the committee
bern and washington had lengthy diplomatic rows over exchange of information in the dennis levine case and another u.s. probe in the early 1980s involving marc rich, a commodities trader now based in switzerland
consumer prices in the 12 nations of the european economic community edged up on average 0.2 percent in january from december and 3 percent from the year-earlier month, the eec statistical office eurostat reported friday
the eec's year-to-year inflation rate of 3 percent in january compares with 3.2 percent in december
eurostat said the steepest price increases were recorded in italy (0.5 percent), denmark (0.5 percent), spain (0.6 percent) and portugal (1 percent)
west germany, france and luxembourg reported moderate increases of 0.2 percent or less, while prices in britain remained unchanged
according to eurostat, january prices declined in three countries, including the netherlands (0.8 percent), belgium (0.1 percent) and greece (0.2 percent)
the eec price index weighs the proportion of each country in the total consumption, and does not necessarily coincide with inflation figures from individual member states
consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in january as the year began with a moderate dose of inflation, the government reported today. higher grocery prices partially offset declines in energy costs
the increase in the labor department's consumer price index was equivalant to an annual rate of inflation of 4.2 percent, compared to the 4.4 percent rise for all of 1987
last month's increase was larger than the 0.2 percent rise in december and matched november's 0.3 percent rise. december's increase was revised from the previously reported 0.1 percent
pacing the january increase were widespread gains across a range of goods and services. energy prices, however, supplied a major dampening on the overall rate by plunging 0.7 percent after a 0.8 percent drop in the preceding month
gasoline prices fell 1.6 percent; heating oil costs were down 0.8 percent. the price of natural gas and electricity, combined, fell 0.3 percent
food prices rose 0.3 percent, down from december's 0.6 percent gain. pacing last month's rise were jumps in prices for poultry, eggs and bakery products. meat, fruit and vegetable prices declined
subtracting the usually volative food and energy categories, consumer prices for all other goods and services rose a sharp 0.5 percent in january after a 0.2 percent increase in december
january's report underscored forecasts by many analysts that any significant change in the inflation rate was unlikely this year
the underlying rate of inflation looks to be 3 percent to 4 percent,'' said allen sinai, chief economist for the boston company economic advisers. ``the question mark is on the energy price side.''
the reagan administration has predicted an inflation rate of 4.3 percent this year
energy prices, which tumbled in 1986, partially rebounded through 1987. but more recently oil prices again have been falling, recently dipping below $17-a-barrel on the spot market from the $18-a-barrel prices that prevailed in december and from prices of around $19 a barrel in november
while petroleum prices have fallen recently, anlaysts also said they expected to see a rise in natural gas costs
energy prices may continue to soften through late spring, providing continuing offsets to food prices, which are expected to remain on an upward path,'' said donald ratajczak, a georgia state university economist who specializes in prices
supply shortages and weather and crop infestation problems, particularly in california and arizona, have pushed up food prices in recent months. after climbing through the fall, fruit and vegetable prices fell 0.4 percent last month
beef prices were down 1.4 percent while pork priced declined 0.5 percent. poultry prices, however, climbed 1.0 percent, their first increase since august. cereal and bakery product prices rose 1.1 percent
overall, grocery prices were up 0.2 percent while restaurant meal costs climbed 0.3 percent
the labor department gave these other specifics of january price behavior
_new automobile prices were down 0.2 percent; used automobile prices fell 0.1 percent
_housing expenses were up 0.4 percent
_apparel costs gained 0.1 percent
_medical care expenses rose 0.8 percent, its largest increase in two years
_entertainment costs gained 0.9 percent
january's increase left the cpi at 115.7, meaning that a selection of goods and services that cost $100 during a 1982-84 base period cost would have $115.70 last month
the department recently abandoned a 1967 base period in favor of the 1982 standard. under that base period, a selection of goods and services costing $100 in that year would have cost $346.70 last month
using either base number, the gain from january 1986 would have been $1.56
the overall index is not adjusted for seasonal variations; other figures in the report are
the major source of inflation in the months ahead likely is to come from higher import prices resulting from declines in the foreign exchange value of the dollar
the dollar is now worth only half of its 1985-value against japanese and key european currencies. these exchange rate changes have begun to show up in the form of higher import prices for a wide variety of goods. at the same time, u.s. items are becoming less expensive abroad
the weaker dollar is expected to help trim the nation's huge trade deficit, although higher priced foreign goods might be the price americans will have to pay for more trade balance
still, ``there is too much slack in the u.s. economy and too much slack in the world economy'' to worry about steep inflation as a result of higher import prices, said jay goldinger, chief economist for capital insight, a los angeles bond brokerage
many economists say this slackness is illustrated by a recent slowdown in consumer spending _ a slowdown that will keep inflationary pressures at a minimum. consumer spending dropped 3.1 percent in the fourth quarter of 1987, the steepest plunge in more than seven years, the commerce department reported on thursday
while most private economists deem a major bout of new inflation unlikely, federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan suggested earlier this week that chances of a resurging inflation and of a recession are now roughly equal
the companion producer price index, which only includes domestically produced items and does not cover imports or services, showed a 0.4 percent rise in wholesale prices in january
a ``broad-scale consumption tax of some sort'' may be the best medicine for the nation's economic woes, former federal reserve board head paul volcker says
i don't think we are approaching doomsday,'' he said, speaking thursday before a seminar held by the national association of industrial and office parks. ``i do not think we face inevitable recession or inevitable inflation or a combination of the two.''
i think we are in control of our destiny, but i don't think we can take the future for granted,'' he said
new york stock traders blamed volcker's remarks for helping kill a morning stock rally thursday, although he has publicly advocated tax increases before
to alleviate the nation's trade deficit, foreign debts and declining dollar, volcker said, ``we need to start with the federal budget deficit.''
i think there's some amount of wishful thinking about the budget deficit,'' he said. ``i'd like to think we can solve it all by a little spending restraint, but i don't think that's possible
certain elements of spending are going to increase, and you know it,'' he said
a combination of spending cuts and tax increases are needed to cure the deficit, he said
the newly reformed income tax structure should be left alone and ``given a chance to work,'' volcker said. instead, he recommended a ``consumption tax'' to raise revenue
as an example, volcker cited ``a very sizeable increase in the gasoline tax, which by world standards is relatively low. is it really so impossible to add 10 or 15 cents to the gasoline tax?''
i do not think this problem is insoluble,'' volcker said of the budget deficit. ``i think it's quite readily soluble.''
at a press conference after his speech, volcker said the ``political pressure'' of this year's presidential campaign is discouraging a meaningful discussion on the nation's large budget and trade deficits
the tendency in democracies is to wait for a crisis,'' volcker said in his speech. ``it is terribly important that we put a sense of reality in this situation and ... get this issue before the american public in a way that the political campaign does not undermine.''
both the federal government and american businesses must wean themselves away from their dependence on foreign capital, volcker said
people are not going to lend us money indefinitely to finance the deficit,'' he said
the european economic community said friday it has authorized spain to cut the imports of japanese cars and trucks to 2,000 units through much of this year
the eec executive commission, which granted the authorization, said the move was needed to protect spain's fledgling car industry from non-community imports coming largely from japan
citing spanish figures, the commission said car and truck imports to spain rose to nearly 400,000 units in 1987 from 70,190 in 1985, an increase of over 435 percent. of the 1987 total, 11,582 cars and trucks were imported from non-community countries
in spain, the share of domestically produced cars fell to 64.8 percent from 89.4 percent over the same three-year perid, the commission said
separately, willy de clercq, the top eec trade official, said the commission wants to conclude an agreement with japan to hold imports, mainly cars, to around 10 percent of the community market
he said in a speech to french businessmen in lille thursday that japan sold 1.18 million cars in the eec last year. this represents about 11 percent of the european car market
de clercq said the arrangements would be ``transitional'' to give the community's car industry time to restructure
the commission has been under pressure from automakers to impose eec-wide limits on japanese car sales following a surge in the imports in the first five months of 1987
the eec car industry has also expressed fear that the community's plan to abolish all internal borders and create one integrated market by 1992 will lead to a flood of japanese imports
japanese car imports are currently subject to a variety of national rules ranging from no restrictions in west germany to strict numerical limitations in italy and spain
any national curbs, however, must be approved by the eec commission
in his speech, de clercq urged japan to open its market to european car exports in order to boost europeans' market share to 5 percent from its current level of 2.7 percent
he said eec car makers sold 87,000 vehicles in japan last year
a commission official, who declined to be identified, said there are no negotiations under way at present on limiting car imports. ``there are continuing contacts, however,'' the official said
now that more and more people are investing on an international scale, many wall streeters these days are teaching themselves to think in foreign currencies
the exercise is relatively simple, nothing like having to learn a whole new language. and it seems a logical way to try to understand what has motivated foreign investors operating in this country in the recent past, and what they might do in the future
the dollar, of course, has taken a drastic drop since the mid-1980s against important foreign currencies
in early 1985, a dollar could be exchanged for more than 250 japanese yen. recently, it was worth about 129 yen. similarly, the exchange rate has fallen from more than 3 west german marks per dollar to about 1.7
to understand the kind of impact such wide swings can have on financial decisions and distort the way they are perceived, burton siegel, chief investment officer at drexel burnham lambert inc., speaks of the ``dave righetti effect.''
as followers of the sports pages know, righetti is a standout pitcher for the new york yankees who was offered, and decided not to accept, a deal to play in japan under a two-year contract that would pay him something on the order of $10 million
even in these days of boxcar-number sports salaries, the figure was regarded as mindboggling
but as siegel points out: ``in currency-adjusted terms, the offer was handsome, but not quite as expensive to the japanese as it first appears. indeed, when adjusted for the yen-dollar relationship, the proposal was in line with salaries being paid to top players in the united states
the same analyses can be applied to recent auctions of fine art in which japanese and euopean collectors-investors bid up dollar prices.''
what does all this mean for other businesses and the stock and bond markets?
if the dollar is going to keep dropping in foreign exchange, it would be a negative for foreign investors, reducing or eliminating the return they realize from investments denominated in dollars
but if the dollar is perceived as fundamentally cheap, the story could well be very different
says siegel: ``foreign corporations may be especially attracted to the opportunity to acquire existing u.s.-based operating assets. this avoids the delay of starting from scratch and can sometimes be done at lower cost
this may be especially appealing to foreign companies interested in handling u.s.-produced goods through their own international distribution systems
foreign companies anxious to increase or maintain their market share in the u.s. may also be attracted to the ability to produce in the now cost-competitive u.s.''
thinking in yen or marks yields another interesting point: when stated in those currencies, standard &amp; poor's 500-stock composite index is now substantially below where it stood at the beginning of 1985
thus, from a foreign investors' viewpoint, wall street has been experiencing a bear market for more than three years
there is a danger in carrying this kind of analysis too far. to illustrate that, greg smith, an analyst at prudential-bache securities, recently suggested a remedy if a friend or relative remarks that you seem to have put on weight lately: ``tell them that in yen, you have actually lost five pounds.''
the stock market edged upward today, steadying after thursday's late selloff
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.65 to 2,021.22 in the first half hour of trading
gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 602 up, 459 down and 432 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 25.32 million shares as of 10 a.m. on wall street
analysts said many traders were disappointed at the market's inability to surpass its early-january highs, as measured by the dow jones industrial average
the average seemed to be headed for into new-high territory for the year thursday morning, but the advance gave way to selling
while evidence continues to accumulate that the economy hasn't yet suffered any severe effects from last fall's market crash, brokers say confidence remains fragile
the labor department's report this morning that the consumer price index rose 0.3 percent in january was in line with advance estimates, and had little evidence impact on the market
