consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in january, matching 0.3 percent increases in american's personal incomes and consumer spending for the same month, the government reported today
the rise in the labor department's consumer price index was larger than the 0.2 percent rise in december and matched november's 0.3 percent rise. the gain in december was revised from the previously reported 0.1 percent
pacing the january increase in consumer prices were widespread gains across a range of goods and services, including a 0.3 percent gain in food prices
energy prices, however, fell 0.7 percent after a 0.8 percent drop in the preceding month, the report said
the overall increase in january prices was equivalent to an annual rate of inflation of 4.2 percent, compared with the 4.4 percent rise for all of 1987
the january gains reported by the commerce department in personal income and consumer spending were less than half the gains posted in december
the department said the 0.3 percent seasonally adjusted increase in incomes followed a 0.7 percent rise in december and was the slowest income gain since a 0.4 percent decline in november
the 0.3 percent rise in spending represented a slowdown from a 0.7 percent december advance. spending had risen 0.5 percent in november after falling 0.7 percent in october, reflecting a decline in auto purchases that month
the reports came a day after the government reported that economic expansion at the end of 1987 reached the fastest level in almost two years
the commerce department's announcement thursday that the economy grew at a 4.5 percent annual rate in the last three months of last year initially rallied wall street but stocks later fell sharply. bond prices and the dollar also fell
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up about 27 points at its midsession high, closed with a 22.38-point loss at 2,017.57, most of it in the last hour of trading
there is a considerable amount of confusion in the financial markets'' about the strength of the economy, said jack barbanel, senior vice president at gruntal &amp; co. in new york
the growth in the gross national product, the broadest measure of the economy, was revised up from an original estimate of 4.2 percent made a month ago
the reagan administration said the growth rate showed the economic recovery, now in its sixth year, a record for peacetime, was suffering no ill effects from the october stock market collapse. however, private economists said they were still concerned about the one-sided nature of the growth
the rapid expansion in the fourth quarter occured without a pickup in inflation. a price index tied to the gnp rose at an annual rate of 3.7 percent from october through december, little changed from a 3.4 percent increase in the third quarter
three-fourths of the growth last quarter came from a buildup of business inventories, occurring at the same time that consumer spending was plunging 3.1 percent, the biggest spending drop in more than seven years
the last such sharp drop in consumer spending occurred in 1980 during the recession that year which helped doom president jimmy carter's re-election bid
some analysts said the revisions made in the new gnp report made them more confident that a recession can be avoided. others said they were encouraged because the report showed that consumer spending, while falling sharply, was not as weak as previously believed. the report also increased the estimate of business investment spending, another area of expected strength
the fourth-quarter gain boosted growth for the year to 3.9 percent, when measured from the end of 1986, up slightly from the 3.8 percent estimate made a month ago. growth when all four quarters of the year are averaged together showed a 2.9 percent increase in 1987, the same as 1986
northwest airlines and its flight attendants are on a ``collision course'' and a strike by the attendants appears to be imminent, according to a teamsters union official
several dozen flight attendants demonstrated thursday night outside the eagan, minn., home of northwest chief executive officer steven rothmeier. the home was watched by private guards and eagan police
mr. rothmeier has been traveling around the circuit all of this week, visiting all of our flight attendant bases; we thought it was only polite to return the favor,'' flight attendant dottie malinski told wcco-tv
it was not known if rothmeier was home at the time
talks continued thursday as flight attendants prepared to walk off their jobs at 11:01 cst tonight
there's a 100 percent chance of a strike,'' william genoese, director of the teamsters' airline division, said at a morning news conference thursday. ``as far as i'm concerned we're on a collision course with northwest airlines to strike.''
but redmond tyler, a spokesman for the airline, said progress was being made on some of the major contract issues. the two sides have been meeting steadily since tuesday at northwest's headquarters in eagan with the assistance of a federal mediator, tyler said thursday
seniority wage scales, pensions and work rules are among the major issues in the dispute. former republic airlines flight attendants have been working under their old contract since northwest acquired republic in 1986. the company is trying to bring the workers under one contract
we believe we're making substantial progress at the bargaining table,'' tyler said. ``we're not jimmy the greek, but we continue to believe that we will get this resolved without a strike.''
flight attendants have voted overwhelmingly to strike if a contract agreement isn't reached by the 11 p.m. cst deadline. the national president of the international association of machinists has vowed his union's support, but the telegram that contains the message stops short of saying machinists would honor picket lines
officials at national and local iam offices did not return a reporter's phone calls thursday
tyler said the machinists are under a contract that forbids them to strike in sympathy with another union. ``we expect our machinists to honor their contract,'' he said
pilots are barred from sympathy strikes under provisions of the railway labor act, tyler said
asked if those workers would be locked out if they walk off their jobs in sympathy with the flight attendants, tyler said, ``we won't address that because we don't want to play that `what if?' game.''
genoese said flight attendants would have the full backing of the international teamsters, which could result in delays of supply shipments from truckers
we're putting all our power together in the next 24 hours,'' genoese said. ``we would like to put them (northwest) at 10 to 20 percent'' of operations if there is a strike
genoese said he is hopeful that pilots would honor picket lines, but jim halverson of the air line pilots association said pilots would not decide until today
tyler said the airline is armed with about 2,000 management workers who are certified as flight attendants to step in if the 6,700 union flight attendants strike
the machinists union represents about 20,000 airline mechanics, baggage handlers, aircraft cleaners, ticket and reservation agents and clerical workers at northwest
genoese said thursday the teamsters are researching the possibilities of an employee-led leveraged buyout of northwest and other airlines to protect the long-term interests of workers
he said his union has talked with salomon brothers inc. and other wall street investment firms to consider financing arrangements. however, robert salomon, managing director and chief spokesman of the firm, said he is unaware of any contact between the teamsters and his company on the issue
genoese said discussions of a possible leveraged buyout of northwest could help the bargaining position of flight attendants, but he said the talk was not a ploy
