chrysler corp. hopes to add passenger cars to the line of jeeps it already produces in china, a top official of the automaker said friday
gerald greenwald, head of the chrysler motors division of chrysler corp., said in an interview that his company was negotiating with first automotive works of changchun, in northeast china, to produce upscale autos for use as official cars and taxis
first automotive hopes to begin construction by the end of the year on a plant that initially would produce 30,000 cars a year, with potential capacity of 150,000, greenwald said
if successful, chrysler would be the first american automaker to set up passsenger car production in china, and the third foreign company. peugeot has a small joint venture in canton, and volkswagen produces about 10,000 vehicles a year at its shanghai plant
china produced about 400,000 motor vehicles last year, almost all trucks and buses. only about 20,000 passenger cars were built
chrysler inherited a stake in china last year when it took over american motors corp., which produces cherokee jeeps as part of a joint venture known as beijing jeep co
beijing jeep has had a rocky road since it began as a much-heralded sino-american joint venture in 1984. two years ago, the plant shut down for two months because it ran out of foreign currency to import the parts it needed to stay in operation. the chinese government finally agreed to provide financial support after exacting promises that the plant would use more domestically produced components
greenwald said that currently about 18 percent of parts are made locally. he said the process to increase the local percentage will take years, but that eventually, as production climbs from the current 4,000 vehicles a year to 30,000-40,000 vehicles, localization of parts could top 50 percent
we have an excellent start with the two projects'' with beijin jeep and first automotive, greenwald said. ``we want to move ahead at a faster pace.''
greenwald said he did not know what other companies were bidding for the passenger-car contract, but chrysler is thought to have an edge because it signed a deal with first automotive last july to supply technology for four-cylinder engines to the company. the chinese company is to produce 150,000 engines under the initial stage of the agreement with chrysler
at the end of last year, the chinese government sent a high-level delegation to the united states to seek a partner in a major auto production joint venture. chrysler is believed to have an advantage because of its previous activities in china, although general motors corp. sold an engine assembly line to china last month in what it said was a first step toward eventual co-production
greenwald said the 2.2-liter engine to be produced in changchun could be used in first automotive's envisioned car, giving the company a needed boost in its drive to cut back on foreign currency spending by relying on domestically produced parts
the bad news has been pouring in from all sides recently for eastman kodak co. as rivals, partners, judges and financial analysts take turns bashing the company
a questioned merger ... bam! battery troubles ... pow! the potential for a whopping damage award to polaroid corp. ... sock! a downgraded bond rating ... boom!
it seems like kodak can't do anything right,'' said robert maney, a local stock analyst with prudential bache securities inc. ``every time they get one thing cleared up, another thing comes along and hits them on the head like a hammer.''
things had been looking up for the photographic and chemical giant, which announced record sales and tripled profits for 1987, after two years of cost cutting and restructuring
but just two months into 1988, triumph has turned to trouble
we don't see it that way,'' countered kodak spokesman henry kaska. ``it's just coincidence that all these things have come together at the same time.''
kodak's woes began jan. 22, a friday, with the company's surprise announcment of a $5.1 billion effort to acquire sterling drug inc., maker of such products as bayer aspirin and lysol disinfectant and prescription drugs
stock analysts criticized the deal as being too expensive and several stopped recommending kodak's stock
four weeks later, on feb. 19, another friday, kodak found out that polaroid corp. wanted a federal judge to award $5.7 billion in damages for kodak's violation of instant photography patents, several times earlier estimates
kodak officials called polaroid's estimate ``ridiculously inflated.''
the same day, kodak announced that it had determined its innovative 9-volt lithium battery, which was supposed to have a shelf life of 10 years, doesn't last that long
that revelation prompted black &amp; decker corp., which sold two lines of mini-flashlights with the lithium cells included, to pull the products from the shelves immediately
we can't very well continue to be associated with something like this,'' said barbara lucas, a spokeswoman for the baltimore-based company
last monday, a federal judge in fort worth, texas, put kodak's planned joint venture with fuqua industries inc. on hold, ruling that a tiny photofinishing competitor, phototron corp. of san bernardino, calif., had grounds for an antitrust lawsuit
the venture with colorcraft corp., a fuqua subsidiary, would create the nation's largest wholesale photofinishing operation with potential control of up to 80 percent of the market, according to claims by phototron that are disputed by kodak
moody's investors service lowered its rating of kodak and sterling senior debt three levels, from aa2 to a2, the lowest rating kodak has ever had, according to john dean, a moody's analyst
the service's highest rating is aaa, followed by aa1, and aa2
standard &amp; poor's corp. disappointed kodak by lowering its ratings even further
on thursday, kodak officials held a special meeting with stock analysts in new york in an effort to stop the flow of bad news about the company and put an end to the storm cloud that seems to be hovering over its sterling deal
kay whitmore, kodak's president, told analysts that they had lowered their profit expectations too much because of the sterling deal and that kodak earnings will meet or exceed profit estimates made at the start of the year, which ranged from $4 to $4.40 a share
several analysts had dropped their estimates down to $3.75 before the kodak meeting. in 1987, kodak had profits of $3.52 a share
things went about as positive as could have been expected,'' eugene glazer, an analyst with dean witter reynolds, said about thursday's meeting. ``considering that virtually everyone went in with a negative attitude, i think it's still negative, but not as negative.''
peter enderlin, a stock analyst for smith barney, harris upham, said kodak offered a convincing case for the various cost savings and reductions inherent in the sterling deal
the meeting did not, however, prompt either analyst to start recommending the purchase of kodak stock again. kodak's stock edged up just 62{ cents a share to $42 a share, compared to $49.12{ just before the sterling announcement
kaska, who is kodak's chief spokesman, said that while the recent rash of troubles had kept him busy, they were really nothing more than ``temporary setbacks.''
he said the sterling acquisition will prove over time to be good deal, the lithium battery shortcoming will be corrected in a few weeks, the polaroid damage estimate is absurd, the phototron lawsuit will be thrown out on appeal and the bond rating is not so bad
the company has a bright future. period,'' kaska said
maney said he has been getting many calls from kodak investors in rochester who are disturbed by the flurry of bad news, but his advice to them is to buy more kodak stock
this has not changed my opinion that kodak is still a great buy. you just have to have patience,'' he said
in other business and economic news this past week:
_federal reserve chairman alan greenspan criticized a top treasury official's attempt to influence fed policy. he also said in congressional testimony that the risk of a recession is as great as the risk of renewed inflation, but neither is imminent
_the u.s. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent annual rate from october through december, the fastest pace in almost two years, the government said. the growth in the gross national product was revised from an original estimate of 4.2 percent made a month ago
_the government said consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in january, matching 0.3 percent increases in american's personal incomes and consumer spending for the same month
_orders to u.s. factories for ``big-ticket'' durable goods fell 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year, the government said
_the nation's trade deficit shrank in the final quarter of 1987 as exports climbed, the commerce department said. the deficit's decline to $40.2 billion on a balance-of-payments basis marked the first quarterly improvement since the spring of 1986
_the federal government reported a rare $16.09 billion surplus for january, primarily because social security checks for january were mailed early
_sales of existing homes fell 3.6 percent in january, the third consecutive monthly decline, the national association of realtors said
_new american car and truck sales rose 14.5 percent in mid-february from the comparable period a year ago. general motors corp. said it planned to rehire 8,600 workers at four u.s. and canadian assembly plants because of rising demand and shrinking inventories
_the oil, chemical and atomic workers union rejected a merger with the united mine workers union after private talks in denver
_campeau corp. and federated department stores inc. said they were negotiating a $68-per-share, $6.1 billion cash proposal to merge the two retail companies
_l.f. rothschild holdings inc., an investment firm staggered by october's stock market crash, said it will merge with a subsidiary of franklin savings corp., a financial services company based in ottawa, kan
_santa fe southern pacific corp. rejected an offer from dissident investor henley group inc. to buy $780 million of new santa fe stock. santa fe said it would pursue a financial restructuring
_new england electric system, a massachusetts electric holding company, began talks aimed at taking over ailing public service company of new hampshire, except for its 36 percent share of the stalled seabrook nuclear plant
_black &amp; decker corp. sweetened a hostile bid for american standard inc. a second time, raising its offer to $68 from $65 per share and promising court action to block the target's recapitalization plan
_afg industries inc., one of north america' leading glassmakers, agreed to be taken private by its chairman in a $940.5 million plan
_bank of new york co. tightened the noose around irving bank corp., winning government approval to proceed with its $1.08 billion hostile bid and seeking to oust the rival's directors if they don't capitulate
_texaco inc. agreed to pay $1.25 billion to the government to settle claims it overcharged customers for oil during the 1973-81 period of price controls. meanwhile, getty petroleum corp. announced it has bought $14 million worth of texaco stock and was seeking to acquire more
_a federal judge ruled occidental chemical corp. was liable for the estimated $250 million cost of cleaning up the love canal landfill that became synonymous with environmental disaster
_the pentagon said mcdonnell douglas corp. surpassed two competitors last year to reclaim the title of largest u.s. defense contractor. mcdonnell douglas jumped past general dynamics corp. and general electric co. to win the top ranking for fiscal 1987
