share prices dropped on the london stock exchange friday as investor sentiment turned sour and trading volume thinned
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was down 15.9 points, or 0.9 percent, at 1,766.5 at the close. the index's low for the trading session was 17.8 points down
volume fell to a light 350.2 million shares from 510.1 million on thursday
a strong rally earlier this week seemed to run out of steam as the index approached strong technical resistance at the 1,800-point level, dealers said
in addition, losses on wall street thursday and sharp declines on the london stock futures market took their toll on british stocks, they said
it's amazing how quickly confidence can change, showing we're still very nervous'' in the wake of october's stock crash, one dealer said
however, the market still views the british economy as sound, and a string of company earnings results this week indicated that corporate profits are being maintained despite the crash, dealers said
the government will announce by march 4 its response to foreign banks' secret bids for bonds offered by mexico in an innovative plan to reduce its $105 billion in foreign debt, the treasury department said
mexico's approximately 560 creditor banks had until 4 p.m. est friday to submit their sealed bids under the plan, devised by the mexican and u.s. governments
new york-based j.p. morgan &amp; co., exchange agent for the deal, refused to disclose details of the bids
over the next week, mexican officials will consider how much debt would be cleared and service cost reductions in determining whether to accept each bid, the treasury department said in a statement
the plan involves exchanging some of the debt mexico owes foreign commercial bankers for new, 20-year bonds to be issued by the government
the bonds, backed by $10 billion worth of special u.s. treasury securities, will carry a higher interest rate than mexico is paying on the old debt
mexico's potential savings ``will be in proportion to the offers that are accepted,'' the department said in a statement carried by the government newspaper el nacional
in addition to the bond scheme, the government ``will present other options and programs'' to its creditors to reduce the country's debt burden, the treasury statement added
it refused to predict how much principal and interest the government might save under the bond program, saying each bank bid must be analyzed first. but mexican officials previously have warned that if the offers are not attractive enough, they may reject all of them
participating banks sought to get as much money as they could for their old loans, while mexico wants to buy the debt cheaply
most analysts expected bidders to offer discounts of between 30 cents and 40 cents to the dollar. mexican debt paper sold for 48 cents to the dollar in early february
observers doubted the government could market the entire $10 billion package. mexican officials, they said, would consider at least $3 billion in securities sales to be acceptable
the treasury department said that at the least, the mexican bond scheme had achieved a ``formal recognition'' by mexican creditors of the difference between the debt's book value and that commanded on secondary markets
