for the fifth time since the october stock market crash, a stock specialist firm has agreed to give up its role as a market maker in a new york stock exchange issue, the exchange said friday
the nyse said wagner, stott &amp; co. had voluntarily withdrawn as the specialist in the stock of carter-wallace inc., a drug and consumer products company based in new york
the exchange said in a news release that the stock would be reallocated to another specialist firm march 10
catherine maroney, a nyse spokeswoman, said the exchange would not disclose the reason for the reallocation. the press release said the exchange had been reviewing the performance by wagner stott on oct. 20, the day after the historic market collapse
the nyse is investigating several cases in which its 53 specialists failed to maintain orderly trading in stocks they controlld. the specialist firms control the rights to market certain issues and are required to keep order by setting opening prices and covering trades when there are too few buyers or sellers
previously, spear, leeds &amp; kellogg surrendered its franchise in j.p. morgan &amp; co. stock; m.j. meehan &amp; co. withdrew its rights to gould inc.; lawrence, o'donnell &amp; co. gave up neiman-marcus group inc.; and labranche &amp; co. agreed to drop e.f. hutton group inc. and a.g. edwards inc
the dollar slipped friday against most major currencies in quiet trading on the world's foreign-exchange markets
gold prices resumed their recent decline in new york, falling to their lowest level since april 1987 in moderate volume. republic national bank of new york quoted a late bid price for gold of $429.50 a troy ounce, down from $433 late thursday
the dollar slipped in asia and europe, reflecting lingering disappointment over thursday's report that the u.s. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent pace in the fourth quarter when some traders had expected a 5 percent rise
but dealers in europe said expectations that central banks might intervene to support the dollar prevented it from falling even lower
john hazelton, a vice president for institutional sales at manufacturers hanover trust co., said the dollar traded in a very narrow range in the united states with professional traders accounting for the bulk of the activity
they are about the only ones involved in the market,'' he said. ``there has been very little corporate or institutional business. it's mostly traders in the various banks.''
he said the market shrugged off the latest government reports on the u.s. economy, which said friday that personal income, consumer prices and consumer spending each rose 0.3 percent in january. the increases were within expectations
we are in a quiet period for the currencies,'' hazelton said
in tokyo, the dollar fell to 128.35 japanese yen from 128.80 yen on thursday. later in london, the dollar fell to 128.24 yen. in new york, the dollar edged down to 128.37 yen from 128.425 yen late thursday
in london, the british pound rose to $1.7715 from $1.7665 late thursday. in new york, the pound rose to $1.7715 from $1.76725 late thursday
