the champion spark plug co. announced friday that nearly 20 percent of its 1,700 production workers nationwide will be laid off because of overcapacity in the auto parts industry
the bulk of the cuts, which will begin march 22 and will be phased in over the next four months, are being made at the plant here
the layoffs come just one month after workers at four u.s. champion plants approved a new four-year contract that includes a provision that the company try to increase production at two of its domestic plants
we explored every alternative to reducing the labor force. even though the numbers are regrettable, it was the only way we could keep a significant number of manufacturing presence in toledo,'' said william walker, champion's industrial relations director
there is clearly too much capacity in the auto parts industry, and we have elected to balance production rather than close and consolidate plants,'' he said
a total of 243 toledo workers _ 119 people from the aviation products group and 124 from automotive operations _ will lose their jobs, the company said. champion currently employs about 800 production workers in toledo
an additional 63 people will be laid off at the company's three other u.s. manufacturing facilities, including 13 at the detroit; 20 at cambridge, ohio; and 30 at burlington, iowa
walker said uaw leaders were aware of the overcapacity situation when they agreed to a new national contract last month, which covers about 1,700 workers at the u.s. champion plants
we informed them of the possible consequences to champion; specifically, that about 200 workers might be laid off in the coming months. as a result, it was a recognized fact in the negotiations and led to a major effort on the part of the company and the uaw to assure those who were laid off that they would receive benefits,'' walker said
rodney smith, international representative for the uaw, said he was disappointed with champion's decision
it's bad news for us, that's for sure,'' he said
walker said the effect of the toledo layoffs could be lessened by normal attrition through the retirement of 60 to 70 production workers
he also said the company is reducing its toledo aviation division because it is trying to balance production between toledo and liberty, s.c, a non-union plant
bond prices rose in thin trading friday, supported partly by indications of continued moderate inflation
the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose by nearly } point, or $7.50 per $1,000 in face value, with its yield declining to 8.36 percent from 8.42 percent late thursday
analysts said that after a busy morning session market activity quieted for the rest of the day, with price movements occurring in very thin trading
helping to tug prices higher was the labor department report that its consumer price index rose 0.3 percent in january, a pace generally expected by the market, analysts said. the monthly rate translated into a moderate 4.2 percent annual rate, compared with 4.4 percent in 1987
high inflation erodes returns on fixed-income securities such as bonds and reduces their attractiveness as investments
in addition to the cpi report, the commodity research bureau futures index of 21 commodities fell a sharp 1.42 to 224.26. many market participants consider the index a reflection of inflationary expectations, with a decline thought to signal lower near-term inflation
furthering such sentiments were additional declines in crude oil prices. the april contract for west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, fell 14 cents to $15.78 per 42-gallon barrel on the new york mercantile exchange, its lowest since late december
otherwise, analysts said, many market participants were limiting their activity in the absence of major new economic news. many are waiting for next friday's u.s. unemployment report for february before taking major investment positions
the economy still seems to be moving at a decent clip and no one has any strong convictions in either direction to buy or sell, so the market waffles in a narrow trading range,'' said elizabeth reiners, a vice president of money market research at dean witter reynolds inc
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term governments rose [ point, intermediate maturities rose in the range of 3-16 point to 15-32 point and 20-year issues rose { point, according to the investment firm salomon brothers inc
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.32 to 113.71. the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, rose 3.46 to 1,189.35
in corporate trading, industrials rose { point and utilities rose ] point, according to salomon brothers. trading was light
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.09 to 284.57
among tax-exempt municipal bonds, general obligations and dollar bonds were unchanged in light trading
yields on three-month treasury bills were down 4 basis points to 5.59 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills fell 3 basis points to 5.76 percent and one-year bills were off 4 basis points to 6.19 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 6 9-16 percent, unchanged from late thursday
the federal communications commission signaled a tougher stance thursday on minority hiring, putting conditions on license renewals of 11 southern television stations with affirmative action efforts it found defective
the action, the first since the fcc revised its equal employment opportunity guidelines last year, shows that ``we mean business,'' said commissioner patricia diaz dennis
the fcc renewed the stations' licenses but said they must report periodically to the agency on efforts to recruit, hire and promote qualified women and minorities
the commission will monitor the stations' efforts and if unsatisfied, could conduct an investigation. if the fcc still is unsatisfied with a station's equal employment opportunity efforts, it could take steps to revoke the station's license
the national black media coalition had asked the fcc to deny license renewals to 19 tv stations because of what the group called deficient affirmative action efforts
pluria marshall, coalition chairman, said that while he was disappointed the commission did not take stronger action, it was ``a step in the right direction.''
the fcc requires all tv and radio stations to have plans describing their efforts to find, hire and promote qualified women, blacks and other minorities. the plans are reviewed at the time of license renewal, every five years for tv stations and every seven for radio stations
in revising its equal employment opportunity guidelines last year, the fcc required more detailed reporting by stations and put stronger emphasis on evaluation of a station's overall employment efforts, rather than focusing on the the number of minorities and women employed
with the revision, the fcc also decided to scrutinize all plans. previously, the agency looked closely at plans of stations where minority employment was less than 50 percent of the minority population of the work force in the station's area
one of the stations cited, wtwc-tv in tallahassee, fla., had more minority employees than required by the fcc parity guidelines, but the commission said ``merely meeting or exceeding these guidelines is not a `safe harbor.'''
the number of minorities and women that a station employs is important and continues to be a factor which we consider,'' said fcc chairman dennis r. patrick
we will not use numbers as a strict quota below which a broadcaster will necessarily fail in their eeo program if they are making aggressive and adequate efforts to correct the problem,'' he said. ``but nor will numbers be used as a `safe harbor' above which broadcasters will necessarily be found to be in compliance
the simple lesson is that all broadcasters must have in place an affirmative action program which puts them in a position to identify and recruit and retain qualified minorities and women,'' he said
besides wtwc, the stations required to submit further reports to the fcc are: wnct-tv, greenville, n.c.; wunc-tv, chapel hill, n.c.; wtkk-tv, manassas, va.; wtgl-tv, cocoa, fla.; wxel-tv, west palm beach, fla.; wnft-tv, jacksonville, fla.; kets-tv, little rock, ark.; wlpb-tv, baton rouge, la.; wyes-tv, new orleans, la.; and wjtc-tv, pensacola, fla
all stations in a block of states come up for renewal in the same year. price.</note>
after a month of public discord, campeau corp. and federated department stores inc. announced friday they had opened negotiations on a $6.1 billion merger agreement
federated's board of directors, which met in regular session thursday, authorized the merger talks, in which campeau proposes to pay $68 in cash for each share of federated
the proposal, which followed campeau's pledge to sell off its brooks brothers division to help finance the merger, is to be presented to the federated board monday, the companies said in their joint announcement
no assurance can be given that a definitive agreement will be reached,'' the companies said
it was the first sign of a softening in campeau's month-long, increasingly hostile campaign to buy federated. the cincinnati-based federated had $11 billion in sales last year. the toronto-based campeau, a development company, bought allied stores corp. in december 1986
sixty-eight dollars per share is a good price. the shareholders should be happy,'' said monroe h. greenstein, an analyst with the bear stearns firm in new york city
federated stock rose $1.50 to $64.50 a share in late new york stock exchange trading friday
the merger proposal is separate from campeau's latest hostile takeover offer, its $66-per-share tender bid made thursday, campeau spokeswoman joele frank said friday in new york city. that offer was improved from a previous $61-per-share proposal
federated has 90.4 million common shares and equivalents outstanding. in addition to acquiring the company's 88.5 million outstanding shares, campeau would pay about $100 million to buy up outstanding federated stock options
what's new about this is that negotiations are under way and that the price has been agreed on,'' ms. frank said
greenstein predicted that campeau corp. would _ if it buys federated _ sell off some federated holdings, including non-department store assets and underperforming department store groups
greenstein said those groups might include i. magnin in san francisco, lazarus in cincinnati and abraham &amp; straus in new york. ``all these have been known to be under-performers in recent years,'' he said
thursday, the canadian company increased its tender offer to federated from $61 to $66 per share and said it would consider making a higher bid if necessary. campeau has been bidding to buy federated since jan. 25
federated's board said friday it has deferred until 11:59 p.m. est monday implementation of a ``poison pill'' shareholder rights measure designed to make a takeover of federated more difficult. the board said it could later decide to further delay the measure's implementation
federated has rejected previous campeau takeover bids, questioning whether campeau had obtained the necessary financing. campeau chairman robert campeau says he has the financing and would be willing to match offers by other bidders for federated
campeau said thursday it would raise a substantial amount of equity for its proposed buyout by selling the brooks brothers division of its allied stores corp. unit to britain's marks and spencer plc for $770 million. the brooks brothers sale was conditioned on campeau acquiring federated
the brooks brothers sale also could preempt antitrust concerns raised by sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, in connection with the proposed federated acquisition. metzenbaum is concerned that a campeau purchase of federated could hurt competition in some u.s. markets, such as new york and miami, where both allied and federated operate stores
federated's board has previously rejected offers of $66 and $47 per share. the company has been considering alternatives, such as selling some of its non-department store assets or having management buy the company and convert it to private ownership
federated operates 650 stores nationwide. its holdings include the new york chains bloomingdale's and abraham and straus, filene's of boston, burdines of miami, rich's in atlanta, bullock's and bullocks wilshire in los angeles, i. magnin in san francisco and lazarus in cincinnati
dart group corp. announced friday that it passed another hurdle in its attempt to oust the board of directors of stop &amp; shop cos. inc. in its $1.03 billion hostile takeover bid for the supermarket chain
dart said its 95 percent-owned affiliate, jefferson partnership, submitted to stop &amp; shop applications from holders of more than 10 percent of stop &amp; shop's outstanding shares calling for a special shareholders meeting on march 30, according to dart spokesman stanley rubenstein
dart says the meeting, which is being demanded under massachusetts' business corporation law, is to consider replacing stop &amp; shop's board with jefferson's nominees and adopting related resolutions
stop &amp; shop spokeswoman aileen gorman declined to comment on dart's latest announcement
stop &amp; shop, based in braintree, mass., on feb. 12 filed a federal suit to block dart's $37-a-share offer. stop &amp; shop claimed that dart failed to register as an investment company with the federal securities and exchange commission and failed to disclose details of its past takeover attempts
dart responded with a countersuit, claiming that stop &amp; shop illegally withheld corporate information. u.s. district judge rya zobel ruled dart must file its claim in norfolk superior court in massachusetts
as of wednesday, jefferson partnership had acquired more than 73,000 shares of stop &amp; shop, about 2.7 percent of the company's outstanding shares
stop &amp; shop operates 113 stop &amp; shop supermarkets and 169 bradlees discount department stores from maine to north carolina
speculation mounted friday that stop &amp; shop could soon be sold to an outside bidder
one union representing stop &amp; shop workers said thursday it wanted to be included in any sale negotiations, said robert petronella, international vice president and new england regional director for the united food and commercial workers union, which represents about 20,000 stop &amp; shop employees
recently, ufcw union leaders agreed to take a strike vote if there was not a new contract for stop &amp; shop employees by march 6
dart, based in landover, owns crown books and trak auto parts. it has mounted other hostile takeover attempts targeting retail chain dayton hudson corp., safeway co. and supermarkets general. acquiring federated; brooks brothers is owned by campeau, not federated; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, campeau and federated ...</note>
marks and spencer plc, where prime minister margaret thatcher shops, is poised to establish a major u.s. beachhead with its planned purchase of the preppy clothier brooks brothers
marks and sparks,'' as the 550-store chain is affectionately known among rhyme-loving londoners, has been seeking to expand in the united states for more than a year as part of its strategy of becoming a global retailer
marks and spencer announced thursday it had agreed in principle to buy brooks brothers for $770 million from campeau corp., the canadian retailing and real estate company, if campeau acquired federated department stores inc. of cincinnati
campeau and federated disclosed friday they were negotiating a $6.1 billion merger but said there was no guarantee they would reach a definitive merger agreement. federated already has rejected several lower offers from campeau
marks and spencer has grown in 104 years from a market stall to a favorite store of the average briton. it's also where mrs. thatcher buys her underwear because, she says, it is well made
the retailer hopes to get brooks brothers' flagship store on new york city's madison avenue, its 46 other u.s. stores and 12 joint-venture outlets in japan
british retailers have boomed in recent years on strong spending by consumers and their increased use of credit. this has prompted some retailers to ponder expansion outside britain, which they now see as too small a market
marks and spencer needs to become a global retailer and to a certain extent hey do need to get into the u.s. market to fulfill that ambition,'' said charles allen, an industry consultant with the investment firm wood mackenzie and co
other british retailers that have expanded into the united states by acquisition or opening of new stores include storehouse plc, owner of the conran's home furnishing stores, dixons group plc, owner of the silo electric appliance chain, and the jeweler ratners plc
but reaction to marks and spencer's plans were mixed in the city, london's financial district
marks and spencer fell 4.5 pence, about 8 cents at current exchange rtes, to 176 pence, or $3.12, a share late friday on the london stock exchange after falling the same amount on thursday
analysts agreed the retailer should target the united states but were divided about whether the acquisition of brooks brothers was the right choice and whether marks and spencer agreed to pay too high a price
some also expressed concern that marks and spencer was establishing its beachhead in a portion of the u.s. market that might be softening
wood mackenzie's allen said the company agreed too quickly to something that wasn't a sure deal
marks and spencer's pre-tax profit growth will slow to 5 percent from 10 percent in its new fiscal year beginning april 3 because of the acquisition, allen predicted
but paul backhouse, a retail analyst with the investment firm morgan grenfell and co., said: ``this is a long-term move for marks and spencer.''
analysts also noted that although many foreigners view the u.s market as uniform, it has regional differences that make marketing products challenging
marks and spencer stated thursday: ``the acquisition of brooks brothers would represent a substantial opportunity for marks and spencer to enter the u.s. retail clothing market through a major long-established business with a high reputation for quality.''
marks and spencer said it wants to use its retailing expertise to boost brooks brothers' business
brooks brothers and marks and spencer are similar in that they both sell durable, quality merchandise under their own brand name and they stick with classic designs
but there are some big differences. brooks brothers caters to a small clientele of the well-to-do; marks and spencer markets huge volumes to the middle class
marks and spencer also sells more than clothes. it sells food under its st. michael brand name, and home furnishings
marks and spencer ventured into the u.s. market last year by opening four women's clothing stores in upstate new york under the name d'allaird's
a marks and spencer spokeswoman, who did not want to be named, declined to detail how the stores were faring but said the company remained optimistic about their prospects
marks and spencer has had mixed results with its efforts to expand into other foreign countries
profits for its 11 stores in the rest of europe jumped 25 percent in its most recent fiscal year. but in canada, where it operates 260 stores, its profit sank 61 percent
the company plans to open a store under its own name in hong kong in may
marks and spencer's pre-tax profit jumped 18 percent to 432 million pounds, about $765 million, in the year ended march 1987 on a 13.5 percent revenue gain to 4.2 billion pounds, $7.4 billion
montgomery ward &amp; co., bolstering its move to promote itself as a specialty retailer, announced on friday a realignment of field office management to create several new specialist merchandising positions
the move will create a 20 percent increase in employees, while some current employees will lose their jobs, said spokesman charles thorne. he did not have exact numbers on how many employees will be cut
under the realignment, the chicago-based retailer will close two of its six territorial management offices, one in los angeles and one in kansas city, leaving offices representing the north, south, east and west, thorne said
the new merchandising experts will be spread out primarily at 23 offices throughout the country, with an aim to bring the managers closer to the stores they serve, he said
each of montgomery ward's four major specialty merchandising categories _ electric avenue, auto express, home ideas, and apparel _ will have its own field organization under the realignment
every full-line store features each of the four categories of merchandise, thorne said
as a result, montgomery ward will begin to compete as a specialty retailer right down to the point of sale, as is done by the best specialists in the industry,'' said bernard f. brennan, president and chief executive officer
the new organization will create 10 merchandise director positions, one additional apparel vice president and 115 district merchandise manager positions, the company said in a statement
the district managers will be deployed in the field and are responsible for implementing merchandising and sales training programs at the store level,'' the statement said
the field officers currently in charge of the retailer's territorial offices will concentrate on operations, customer service and other similar responsibilities, thorne said
now, our territorial offices can concentrate their entire effort on sevring customers, while a new group of managers has the task of moving our specialty merchandising strategy ahead,'' brennan said
the move will increase the retailer's field employees to more than 180, he said
the company is in the process of identifying candidates for the new positions, brennan said, adding that they will come from within as well as outside the organization
montgomery ward, a subsidiary of new york-based mobil corp., operates a chain of 316 stores in 39 states. for 1987, sales increased 6 percent to $4.6 billion. earnings rose 23 percent to $130 million in 1987, the second consecutive year of record earnings, the retailer said. documents</head>
manville corp. said friday it will make available at a denver storage facility more than 16 million asbestos-related documents to those involved in resolving health claims against the company
billions of dollars worth of asbestos-related lawsuits drove manville into chapter 11 reorganization. the denver-based company's reorganization plan has been confirmed, but it cannot emerge from bankruptcy until all appeals have been exhausted, and one currently is pending
manville said in a prepared statement that the repository, which is believed to be the most comprehensive of its kind, will be established in cooperation with the manville personal injury settlement trust, the committees representing asbestos health claimants and other interested parties
manville officials said the repository should be operational in six weeks, and access guidelines will be provided
the documents were produced from 1983 through 1986 in two widely publicized manville lawsuits against 29 insurance carriers and the u.s. government. the company said some documents support claims that manville knew or should have known before 1964 that some employees and customers were at risk because of exposure to high levels of asbestos
manville has agreed to pay $2.5 billion over a 28-year period, including $615 million in insurance proceeds, into the personal injury settlement trust when the chapter 11 plan is completed. the company also will give the trust 50 percent of its common stock and convertible preferred stock for use if needed. the trust also will share in manville profits as long as necessary to pay off the claims
japanese share prices posted modest gains at the start of half-day trading in tokyo saturday following an overnight rise on wall street, and analysts predicted a 13th consecutive day of gains in a market intent on recouping its losses after the october crash
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which gained 64.52 points friday for the 12th straight trading day, gained another 5.74 points, or 0.02 percent, in the first 15 minutes of trading to rise to 25,170.92
it's the 13th day of straight gains and the market is definitely headed for a rally ... it's 100 percent sure,'' said a trader with nikko securities, one of japan's four largest brokerages
the index stood at 25,746.56 points just before the mid-october crash when it lost nearly 4,000 points in one trading day. it was the largest single day drop for the nikkei
the trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said tokyo trading opened on a positive note, taking the lead from moderate gains in new york friday, and then shot up by some 40 points by mid-morning
trading companies and supermarket issues were winners, he said
other notables included precision machine makers such as as olympus and ricoh, as well as pulp and paper, transportation and nonferrous metals
the tokyo foreign-exchange market is closed on saturdays
